#. Paragraph 51
#: sentence:57
msgid "Foreword"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 52
#: sentence:58
msgid ""
"Many of you will pick up this book because you know Bill Thetford by "
"reputation or as a co-scribe of A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 52
#: sentence:59
msgid "Others may find it simply because you are meant to do so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 52
#: sentence:60
msgid ""
"Because of her close personal relationship with Bill during his years in "
"California, and her clear and eloquent voice, we know of no better person to"
" offer insight into Bill’s life than our good friend Carol Howe."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 53
#: sentence:61
msgid ""
"My journey (Jerry) with Bill and Carol began in 1978 when she first visited "
"Tiburon in the fall of that year."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 53
#: sentence:62
msgid "I was still practicing psychiatry and Bill was new in town."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 53
#: sentence:63
msgid ""
"I could tell after the first time all of us were together that he was "
"impressed with her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 53
#: sentence:64
msgid ""
"I was not surprised when he started visiting her in Denver and know that "
"being there was a kind of escape for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 53
#: sentence:65
msgid ""
"I (Diane) met Carol in 1982 when she was in Tiburon and also recognized that"
" she and Bill had a unique relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 53
#: sentence:66
msgid ""
"Little did any of us know at that time all the ways our lives would be "
"intertwined over the years or just where our work would take us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 54
#: sentence:67
msgid ""
"This book is not simply a biography, but a body of work that integrates the "
"facts of Bill’s life with Course teachings and the personal reflections of "
"more than thirty friends in a way that creates a unique and meaningful "
"experience for the reader."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 54
#: sentence:68
msgid ""
"Bill was a man of opposites and contradictions who did not fall neatly into "
"categories."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 54
#: sentence:69
msgid ""
"He was also a very private person and in reading Carol’s account of his "
"life, we discovered many things about him that we did not know despite our "
"close friendship and all the years we spent together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 54
#: sentence:70
msgid "That was a heart-warming experience for us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 54
#: sentence:71
msgid ""
"As those of us who were there in the beginning of ACIM history continue to "
"age, there is a sense of urgency to put our experiences and insights on "
"paper so that others may learn from them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 54
#: sentence:72
msgid "We are grateful Carol has chosen to do so in regard to Bill’s life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 55
#: sentence:73
msgid ""
"After reading this book, we found it hard to imagine incorporating so many "
"details about Bill into one document."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 55
#: sentence:74
msgid ""
"Carol has accurately expressed the impressions and impact that Bill had on "
"the many of us who loved and appreciated him so deeply."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 55
#: sentence:75
msgid ""
"In many ways, it is a love story about Bill and his many friends, from "
"comfortable close associates to casual acquaintances, whose insights and "
"experiences with him are included throughout."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 55
#: sentence:76
msgid ""
"It’s also a love story about Bill and the Course and, finally, about Bill "
"and God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:77
msgid ""
"The offering of this book about Bill’s transformation is a gift for those "
"who choose peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:78
msgid ""
"Many of us feel a need to own our thoughts and attitudes, heal our split "
"minds, and thereby heal the world we see."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:79
msgid ""
"We take an important step in our journey when we become aware that it’s only"
" our own thoughts that hurt us and offer forgiveness instead."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:80
msgid ""
"Bill’s story is one of giant steps taken through willingness to forgive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:81
msgid ""
"Bill was a partner in the original transcription of A Course In Miracles and"
" a true practitioner of its teachings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:82
msgid ""
"One of his favorite phrases was “celestial amnesia” and he suggested we all "
"practice forgetting everything unloving about our past."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 56
#: sentence:83
msgid ""
"His continual practice of forgiveness, his kind presence, and wonderful "
"sense of humor all led to his ultimate release."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 57
#: sentence:84
msgid ""
"Carol’s love for Bill and the Course shines deeply in every line she has "
"written here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 57
#: sentence:85
msgid ""
"With this book, she brings a balanced perspective about his life so others "
"can have a better sense of what motivated him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 57
#: sentence:86
msgid ""
"It is a window into his heart and soul, a gift of love she has created for "
"us all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 57
#: sentence:87
msgid ""
"We feel certain that Bill is blessing her with his wit and smiles wherever "
"she goes, with every Course workshop she teaches, and with every word she "
"has written within this book."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 57
#: sentence:88
msgid ""
"We are grateful that you, the reader, have chosen to share in this love as "
"well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 58
#: sentence:89
msgid "With boundless love and peace,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 59
#: sentence:90
msgid "Jerry Jampolsky, M.D. and Diane Cirincione, Ph.D."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 60
#: sentence:91
msgid "Preface"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 61
#: sentence:92
msgid ""
"In a few short years all who knew Bill Thetford personally will have exited "
"the world stage."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 61
#: sentence:93
msgid ""
"It would be unconscionable for this first generation of A Course In Miracles"
" students, those who were Bill’s friends, to leave without recording our "
"collective witnessing of his transformation.[1] Humanity expends much time "
"and treasure seeking any scrap of information about the teachers, "
"philosophers, and avatars who have gone before, lighting the path for us "
"throughout all cultures and ages."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 61
#: sentence:94
msgid "Bill was such a light."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 62
#: sentence:95
msgid "Drs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 62
#: sentence:96
msgid ""
"William Thetford and Helen Schucman were professors of medical psychology at"
" Columbia University’s College of Physicians and Surgeons in New York, "
"eminent in their field and known for their research into personality theory."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 62
#: sentence:97
msgid ""
"The preface to A Course In Miracles states that the scribes’ names do not "
"matter and, therefore, are not listed on the cover."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 62
#: sentence:98
msgid ""
"True though that may be, as the Course continues to become more widely "
"recognized for the life-changing curriculum it proposes, more people are "
"interested in knowing about these two who considered themselves most "
"unlikely candidates for the job."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 63
#: sentence:99
msgid ""
"In beginning this project, I originally intended to simply write about my "
"own personal memories and recollections of Bill, perhaps with input from my "
"family and some friends in Denver who also knew and loved him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 63
#: sentence:100
msgid ""
"The writing project took on a life of its own, however, and grew to include "
"recollections from a number of his close friends, as well as input from "
"archival records."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 63
#: sentence:101
msgid ""
"In time, even though we are never objective about anyone and see them "
"through our own individual filters, a common view of Bill emerged—and what a"
" picture!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 64
#: sentence:102
msgid ""
"In some extant publications on ACIM and from information on the "
"Internet—some incomplete or actually incorrect—Bill’s role often seems "
"marginalized as the typist or as Helen’s helper."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 64
#: sentence:103
msgid ""
"In most of these accounts, one does not begin to fathom Bill’s presence, his"
" greatest contribution."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 64
#: sentence:104
msgid ""
"As for A Course In Miracles, his gifts were twofold: as Helen’s unwavering "
"partner and co-scribe and as its most dedicated and accomplished "
"practitioner."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 65
#: sentence:105
msgid ""
"The Course lays out a specific plan to liberate our happiness and peace of "
"mind, and Bill’s commitment to it personified the process of forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 65
#: sentence:106
msgid ""
"For more than ten years, a number of people had the good fortune of watching"
" a master teacher in the making, as Bill’s ego steadily dissolved and his "
"gracious presence—the same presence that exists in all of us—became ever "
"more radiant and unencumbered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 65
#: sentence:107
msgid ""
"My intention is to pay homage to Bill for the gifts he gave us, to provide a"
" more complete portrayal of his life, and to show how his awakening process "
"can illuminate our own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 66
#: sentence:108
msgid ""
"[1]A Course In Miracles is a self-study course in three parts: a text, a "
"workbook, and a manual for teachers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 66
#: sentence:109
msgid ""
"Its basic hypothesis is that we are conditioned from birth to a limited way "
"of perceiving and our “understanding” of life is a product of past "
"conditioning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 66
#: sentence:110
msgid ""
"Practicing the workbook lessons undoes our negative, unhelpful, inaccurate "
"view of people, situations, and events, resulting in a different perception "
"of the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 66
#: sentence:111
msgid ""
"As Course practice proceeds, the fearful ideas we have learned are "
"systematically replaced with an alternative viewpoint—happier, more "
"spiritual, and all-encompassing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 66
#: sentence:112
msgid ""
"Later lessons are designed to evoke a direct spiritual experience and "
"greater love for self and others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 67
#: sentence:113
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:114
msgid ""
"And thus are two sons made, and both appear to walk this earth without a "
"meeting place and no encounter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:115
msgid "One do you perceive outside yourself, your own beloved son."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:116
msgid ""
"The other rests within, his Father’s Son, within your brother as he is in "
"you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:117
msgid ""
"Their difference does not lie in how they look, nor where they go, nor even "
"what they do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:118
msgid "They have a different purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:119
msgid ""
"It is this that joins them to their like, and separates each from all "
"aspects with a different purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:120
msgid "The Son of God retains his Father’s will."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 68
#: sentence:121
msgid "The son of man perceives an alien will and wishes it were so.[1]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 69
#: sentence:122
msgid ""
"And so begins Bill’s tale, like ours, a double story, a parallel story."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 69
#: sentence:123
msgid ""
"On the one hand, “our own beloved son,” the ego mind—the sense of a personal"
" self that presumes it is in charge, alone, and always wanting "
"something—develops slowly as we “mature,” striving endlessly for security "
"and recognition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 69
#: sentence:124
msgid ""
"Our initial purpose is to protect and promote this “son,” and Bill certainly"
" did that with complete dedication in his earlier days."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 70
#: sentence:125
msgid ""
"Simultaneously, however, the eternal spiritual presence, the I AM, is always"
" moving deep within the psyche, knocking at the door of awareness to be "
"acknowledged as what we are at the most fundamental level."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 70
#: sentence:126
msgid ""
"Thus, “divine discontent” or “spiritual deprivation,” to use Mother Teresa’s"
" phrase, becomes more pronounced as our worldly goals and our budding "
"spiritual inclinations begin to clash."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 70
#: sentence:127
msgid ""
"Consolidating our lives under the guidance of one thought system rather than"
" two and adopting a single purpose of forgiveness allow the discomfort and "
"uncertainty to diminish and finally disappear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 70
#: sentence:128
msgid ""
"Ultimately we awaken and recognize we are forever our “Father’s Son.” As we "
"shall see, by the end of his life, Bill had accomplished this mission."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 71
#: sentence:129
msgid ""
"Like most people, Bill presumed he was organizing his life according to his "
"personal priorities, but as I assembled the details of his life, it became "
"clear he was being led inexorably, step by step, to his own awakening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 71
#: sentence:130
msgid ""
"His personal story, with its trials and triumphs, waxes, wanes, and finally "
"closes, but not before he demonstrates how to lay aside the quest for the "
"“best of both worlds”—that unsatisfactory mix of love and fear—to pursue the"
" single goal of peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 71
#: sentence:131
msgid ""
"He also makes it clear that you can be “in the world but not of it” and "
"accomplish the only feat that really matters—waking up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 72
#: sentence:132
msgid ""
"Bill was a shy and private man, and all those who knew him are very clear "
"that he would not and did not seek publicity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 72
#: sentence:133
msgid ""
"Once A Course In Miracles became the centerpiece of his life, he always "
"preferred to focus on its teachings and not on his personal life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 72
#: sentence:134
msgid ""
"In any biography about him, he would want the transformation of his personal"
" life to be “exhibit A” of what is possible when one chooses to practice the"
" Course teachings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 72
#: sentence:135
msgid ""
"Therefore, in order for his life to illustrate some of its major principles "
"in action, this biography provides some details about his “time and space” "
"history."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 72
#: sentence:136
msgid ""
"His life is representative of everyone’s, and the steps he took reveal those"
" we must take, if we would be healed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 72
#: sentence:137
msgid ""
"This document is less a traditional biography than a guidebook for learning "
"to leave grievances behind, replacing them with grace and peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:138
msgid ""
"Of all forms of recognition, Bill most objected to being sanctified or put "
"on a pedestal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:139
msgid "In the early days, some ACIM teachers were inclined to do just that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:140
msgid ""
"He used to laugh about his response to situations where he thought he had "
"been unduly elevated, saying, “When they started that, I’d just have to "
"smoke cigarettes and say ‘shit’!” Now, he would want people to know his "
"shortcomings and not evade issues he found challenging."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:141
msgid ""
"Although he insisted on seeing himself as ordinary, most of his friends did "
"not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:142
msgid ""
"Therefore, to honor what would certainly be Bill’s request, I present him "
"here as a beloved equal, a dear friend, and unwitting mentor to so many."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:143
msgid "One wonders if he ever totally realized how greatly he touched others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 73
#: sentence:144
msgid ""
"In discussing this gift with him, in true egalitarian fashion he would ask "
"us to apply that same question to our own lives. And so we should."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 74
#: sentence:145
msgid ""
"It is, of course, unnecessary to know anything about Bill Thetford and Helen"
" Schucman to benefit from the lessons of A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 74
#: sentence:146
msgid ""
"Some students are unaware of his existence and others may not be "
"particularly interested."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 74
#: sentence:147
msgid ""
"However, many are curious about the daily life, habits, and interests of the"
" two persons who made available one of the world’s most important "
"psychospiritual works."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 74
#: sentence:148
msgid ""
"For those who are not curious about the particulars of Bill’s life, there "
"are suggestions throughout this book that can help ease the burdens we often"
" carry and move us toward a happier, more lighthearted experience of life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 75
#: sentence:149
msgid ""
"One time years ago, when Bill was at my home in Denver, he indicated that he"
" felt we were to do some work together, but at the time neither of us could "
"imagine what that would be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 75
#: sentence:150
msgid "ACIM was still fairly new, so more writing didn’t seem called for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 75
#: sentence:151
msgid ""
"With his extreme introversion and my general extroversion, a project "
"suitable to our different modes of being in the world seemed a mystery, so "
"we agreed to wait and see what would happen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 75
#: sentence:152
msgid ""
"Years later, in the days after Bill’s passing, I felt the mantle being "
"passed to the next generation, so to speak, and that it was imperative for "
"those of us drawn to the Course to increase our dedication to “walking the "
"talk.” I spent a great deal of time contemplating my experiences with him "
"and presumed the obvious, that our “project,” whatever it might be, would "
"still happen even though we were on different sides of the “veil.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 76
#: sentence:153
msgid ""
"During his ten years in California, the last chapter of his life, Bill often"
" told the stories of his youth, his career path, and the circumstances "
"surrounding the scribing of the Course, almost always with a humorous twist."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 76
#: sentence:154
msgid ""
"He used to say he would probably tell those stories until he was finally "
"comfortable with them, as if telling and retelling them was a sort of soul-"
"liberating confession."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 76
#: sentence:155
msgid ""
"In particular, he often commented that if we thought studying and practicing"
" the Course was difficult, we should have experienced the complications of "
"scribing it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 76
#: sentence:156
msgid ""
"Therefore, we will read his tales from our current vantage point, which "
"allows a more fleshed-out picture of him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 76
#: sentence:157
msgid ""
"I have also included firsthand accounts of his impact on those who knew him,"
" the healings that occurred for so many, as well as my own experience of a "
"precious friendship with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 77
#: sentence:158
msgid ""
"I have gathered information about Bill before his last ten years from "
"secondhand sources—persons who knew him in his earlier days, archival "
"records, and from Bill’s own writings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 77
#: sentence:159
msgid ""
"In addition to his many academic publications (see Appendix Two), he wrote "
"an autobiographical essay when he was fifteen for a school assignment and an"
" unpublished autobiography, originally created through a series of taped "
"interviews with Frances Vaughan in 1982, now held under copyright by the "
"Foundation for Inner Peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 77
#: sentence:160
msgid ""
"Although he could report what he did and what was important to him, he could"
" not accurately portray his life as others experienced him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 77
#: sentence:161
msgid ""
"Therefore, those who interacted with him must say what that was like for us "
"because his legacy is too important not to share."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 78
#: sentence:162
msgid ""
"In addition, as I spoke with old friends who were also some of Bill’s "
"closest companions, we reaped an unexpected dividend."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 78
#: sentence:163
msgid ""
"We are coming back together with renewed appreciation for and delight in one"
" another’s friendship and company—and probably a common wish that we all had"
" used tape recorders back then, not realizing the import of what we were "
"witnessing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 78
#: sentence:164
msgid ""
"Now with this book, I hope to honor him, not to put him on that pedestal he "
"abhorred or make him “special,” but to allow him to be helpful still to "
"anyone drawn to his presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 78
#: sentence:165
msgid ""
"I have to believe Bill, wearing a big smile, is at the heart of this "
"process."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 78
#: sentence:166
msgid ""
"His energy was so present during this writing that I believe this is truly "
"our joint project, offered to you with happy memories and many blessings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 79
#: sentence:167
msgid "[1]A Course In Miracles Text, 517."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 80
#: sentence:168
msgid "Part I"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 81
#: sentence:169
msgid "Childhood through retirement"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 82
#: sentence:170
msgid "Chapter 1"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 83
#: sentence:171
msgid ""
"Many students of A Course In Miracles are familiar with the oft-quoted "
"statement,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 84
#: sentence:172
msgid ""
"Into eternity, where all is one, there crept a tiny, mad idea, at which the "
"Son of God remembered not to laugh."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 84
#: sentence:173
msgid ""
"In his forgetting did the thought become a serious idea, and possible of "
"both accomplishment and real effects."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 84
#: sentence:174
msgid ""
"Together, we can laugh them both away, and understand that time cannot "
"intrude upon eternity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 84
#: sentence:175
msgid ""
"It is a joke to think that time can come to circumvent eternity, which means"
" there is no time.[1]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 85
#: sentence:176
msgid ""
"If ever there was one who learned to joke about the absurdity of the human "
"condition, it was Bill Thetford."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 85
#: sentence:177
msgid ""
"He was graced with a superb sense of humor, delighting in the antics, large "
"and small, of both himself and his fellow human beings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 85
#: sentence:178
msgid ""
"A prayer in the liturgy of the Episcopal Church begins, “Almighty God, unto "
"whom all hearts are open, all desires known, and from whom no secrets are "
"hid, . . .” Bill was a mortal version of that omniscience; for him his "
"fellow man was deeply transparent, an open book—and often a comic book."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 85
#: sentence:179
msgid ""
"His lighthearted touch was his hallmark as he saw the comedy in the ego’s "
"serious postures."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 85
#: sentence:180
msgid ""
"He laughed not at people, however, but at our treasured notions, beliefs, "
"and practiced self-deceptions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 86
#: sentence:181
msgid ""
"He had his own issues, of course, times that seemed depressing or fraught "
"with difficulty, but sooner or later, his emotional equilibrium would be "
"restored, the twinkle returning to his eye as he told his hilarious stories."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 86
#: sentence:182
msgid ""
"When we can laugh at the dramas, the formerly unhappy circumstances in our "
"lives, we know they are healed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 86
#: sentence:183
msgid ""
"With a rigid, humorless approach to any aspect of our lives, we still have "
"work to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 86
#: sentence:184
msgid ""
"Bill’s droll sense of humor pervaded his life and is the single "
"characteristic I believe he would most want remembered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:185
msgid ""
"While finishing the interviews for this book, Hugh Prather, best-selling "
"author and one of Bill’s confidants, and I reminisced by phone about the "
"gift he was to us, especially about how witty and funny he could be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:186
msgid ""
"One of Bill’s favorite early Course stories, told with kindhearted laughter,"
" was about a gentleman who discovered his address in Manhattan and came "
"knocking on his door."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:187
msgid ""
"When Bill answered, the man earnestly announced that he was a new ACIM "
"student and that the Holy Spirit told him to find Bill and ask him for "
"$10,000."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:188
msgid ""
"Without missing a beat, Bill responded that the Holy Spirit had already "
"alerted him to this request and indicated he was not to give it to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:189
msgid ""
"I can still see Bill’s delighted smile as he recounted such entertaining "
"tales about humankind in general and Course-related drama in particular."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:190
msgid ""
"He often said he thought he should write a book entitled A Course In "
"Miracles Follies about the craziness that occurred while bringing this "
"material into the world, as well as some of the strange ideas and "
"misperceptions that have been perpetuated in its name."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 87
#: sentence:191
msgid ""
"To his credit, he found these occurrences amusing rather than alarming, and "
"we would all benefit from emulating his lighthearted approach."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 88
#: sentence:192
msgid ""
"Why write a book about Bill now, years after publication of the Course in "
"1975 and his death in 1988?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 88
#: sentence:193
msgid ""
"Helen was asked a similar question: Why had she heard her “Voice” from 1965 "
"onward and not at some other time?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 88
#: sentence:194
msgid "Her answer applies both to ACIM and now to Bill’s biography:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:195
msgid ""
"I was given a sort of mental “explanation” . . . in the form of a series of "
"related thoughts that crossed my mind in rapid succession and made a "
"reasonably coherent whole."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:196
msgid ""
"According to this “information,” the world situation was worsening at an "
"alarming pace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:197
msgid ""
"People all over the world were being called on to help, and were making "
"their individual contributions as part of an overall, prearranged plan."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:198
msgid ""
"I had apparently agreed to take down a course in miracles as it would be "
"given me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:199
msgid ""
"The Voice was fulfilling its part in the agreement, as I would fulfill mine."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:200
msgid ""
"I would be using abilities I had developed very long ago, and which I was "
"not really ready to use again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:201
msgid ""
"Because of the acute emergency, however, the usual slow, evolutionary "
"process of spiritual development was being bypassed in what might be "
"described as a “celestial speed-up.” I could sense the urgency that lay "
"behind this “explanation,” whatever I might think about its content."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 89
#: sentence:202
msgid "The feeling was conveyed to me that time was running out.[2]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:203
msgid ""
"I remember that phrase, “celestial speed-up,” from my earliest conversations"
" with Bill; it seemed odd but accurate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:204
msgid "Now, thirty years later, it is even more so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:205
msgid ""
"Our world appears to be increasingly less stable, more complex, the years "
"moving by at an accelerated pace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:206
msgid ""
"William (Whit) Whitson, introduced later in this chronology, writes, "
"“Unknowingly, Bill and Helen had forewarned and forearmed America for what "
"Helen believed was the coming social and metaphysical crisis.”[3] Now that "
"crisis seems to be upon us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:207
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles reminds us that we are completely confused about what "
"is valuable and what is not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:208
msgid ""
"Our values are upside down and backwards, and we put precious and powerful "
"attention on what doesn’t matter, steadily ignoring what does."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:209
msgid ""
"We believe our actions and their influence are of great importance, but "
"thoughts are our own private business and, being invisible and silent, do "
"not count for much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:210
msgid ""
"Hence we set great store on the externals of our lives—our careers, material"
" possessions, the face we present to the world—while being oblivious to our "
"internal processes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:211
msgid ""
"With this in mind, we begin Bill’s story with highlights of his external "
"life: early history, the jobs he held, his overriding interests—those areas "
"that were compelling and fascinating for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:212
msgid ""
"These will serve as the framework for becoming better acquainted with his "
"interior life—his choices, struggles, gifts, and most of all, his loving "
"presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 90
#: sentence:213
msgid ""
"We shall observe the process as Bill steadily moves forward in releasing his"
" ego—“the block to the awareness of Love’s presence”—just as we must do if "
"we want to be joyous, free, safe, and abundantly cared for.[4]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 91
#: sentence:214
msgid ""
"Lest one think Bill’s life was easier or more charmed than others and that "
"living the Course was inherently less challenging for him, his early years "
"come alive via excerpts from an essay entitled “I Live Again,” which he "
"wrote as an English assignment when he was fifteen years old."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 91
#: sentence:215
msgid "Of his parents, John Randolph and Edna Mae Thetford, he wrote:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 92
#: sentence:216
msgid ""
"Then began an early married life of hard work and sacrifice and of the "
"rearing of three children."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 92
#: sentence:217
msgid ""
"John, Jr., the first child, died in infancy after seven days’ struggle for "
"life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 92
#: sentence:218
msgid ""
"A curly haired, beautiful baby girl, Patricia Ann, next entered our busy "
"household three years later. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 92
#: sentence:219
msgid ""
"On a bleak April morning [in Chicago, IL] in 1923, . . . the author of this "
"chronicle first saw the light of day. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 92
#: sentence:220
msgid ""
"When I look back upon what a strong-tempered little vixen I was, always "
"getting into scrapes, I realize how much extra trouble my behavior caused "
"her [his mother]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 93
#: sentence:221
msgid ""
"Patricia was the big dominating force of my early life—outside of Mother."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 93
#: sentence:222
msgid "The sun rose and set upon Patsy Ann."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 93
#: sentence:223
msgid "I was her constant shadow and continual worshipper."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 93
#: sentence:224
msgid ""
"A fostering of an unmanly interest in dolls and tea parties and other "
"effeminate things was the result of my close association with Patsy and her "
"girl friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 93
#: sentence:225
msgid "In fact, my fascination for the opposite sex has never deserted me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 94
#: sentence:226
msgid ""
"In May of 1930, when I was seven years old, my beloved sister was stricken "
"with a fatal infection of the throat."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 94
#: sentence:227
msgid ""
"Three weeks later she passed away leaving our family dazed with grief, "
"hardly believing that death could strike one so young and vibrantly alive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 94
#: sentence:228
msgid ""
"Even now, after eight years have elapsed, it scarcely seems possible that "
"the playmate of my youth can be gone. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 95
#: sentence:229
msgid ""
"The following December after having been quarantined for three weeks with "
"scarlet fever, I arose one morning, only to find my body wracked with "
"rheumatic pains and fever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 95
#: sentence:230
msgid "This led within a few days, to a serious heart ailment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 95
#: sentence:231
msgid "For three whole months I was unable to raise my head off the pillow."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 95
#: sentence:232
msgid ""
"During these long months of fighting to live, Mother was my nurse, playmate "
"and teacher. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 95
#: sentence:233
msgid ""
"Considering my illness as only a temporary thing, I soon began to plan as to"
" how I would spend my days in the outdoors playing baseball and other games "
"and sports, until I overheard a telephone conversation in which Mother, in "
"whispers, remarked that I would not be able to get out of bed for at least "
"another year and a half.[5]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 96
#: sentence:234
msgid "Bill and sister Patricia"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:235
msgid ""
"Bill told me he was devastated by that conversation and made a determined "
"choice to live, despite the doctor’s gloomy prognosis, rather than have his "
"parents suffer the loss of all three of their children."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:236
msgid ""
"Early on, he seemed aware that he had a choice in the matter—quite a "
"challenge for a seven-year-old and revealing of his heightened awareness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:237
msgid ""
"In retrospect, Bill recognized that his serious illness, commencing six "
"months after his sister’s passing, was not a coincidence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:238
msgid ""
"Those who work with grieving families observe that siblings of children who "
"die often feel guilty that they remain after the brother or sister has gone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:239
msgid ""
"Or they worry over the effect of the death on their parents’ stability, and "
"thus on their own welfare, and/or try diligently to deny the loss in their "
"young lives."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:240
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles is unequivocal about the role that guilt, fear, and "
"anger play in projecting the dis-ease or dis-harmony within our minds onto "
"the physical body and the role forgiveness plays in restoring both mind and "
"body to health."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:241
msgid ""
"Hundreds of pages address this topic in no uncertain terms. “Sickness is a "
"decision."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:242
msgid ""
"It is not a thing that happens to you, quite unsought, which makes you weak "
"and brings you suffering."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:243
msgid ""
"It is a choice you make, a plan you lay, when for an instant truth arises in"
" your own deluded mind, and all your world appears to totter and prepare to "
"fall."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 97
#: sentence:244
msgid ""
"Now are you sick, that truth may go away and threaten your establishments no"
" more.”[6]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 98
#: sentence:245
msgid "In his essay, Bill continues:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:246
msgid "The world all of a sudden caved in upon me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:247
msgid ""
"It was unbelievable that I must lie flat on my back, imprisoned by four "
"walls, for that seeming eternity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:248
msgid ""
"Gradually, however, I became accustomed to the thought and soon it held no "
"terror for me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:249
msgid ""
"Constant reading and the kindness of our family friends made the days fly "
"but too quickly. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:250
msgid ""
"Despite relapses, when I hovered near death’s door, I continued to progress,"
" until after two and a half years of shut-in convalescence, I took my first "
"step outside."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:251
msgid ""
"My first glimpse of the brilliant blue of the sky, after months of "
"seclusion, caused me to emit a gasp of wonderment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:252
msgid "At the time I thought it was the most beautiful sight I had ever seen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:253
msgid ""
"I was very unsteady on my feet, and in fact, I had to learn anew how to "
"walk. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:254
msgid ""
"My rediscovery of the world is the most thrilling and vivid of all my "
"recollections."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 99
#: sentence:255
msgid ""
"Being out of circulation had made me very shy and I found it extremely "
"difficult to mix with people.[7]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:256
msgid ""
"From the beginning, Bill was innately at home in the world of the abstract, "
"and for him this inner world was real, vivid, and as satisfying as if he "
"were physically engaged."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:257
msgid ""
"He credits “reading and family friends” as causing the time to fly, but that"
" observation is incomplete."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:258
msgid ""
"He doesn’t mention his rich inner life, taking that for granted and very "
"likely assuming, as we all do in our earlier years, that everyone processes "
"life as we do and that our own approach to circumstances is the norm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:259
msgid "That is hardly the case."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:260
msgid ""
"He wrote this essay before he knew about personality types or had yet "
"realized that not everyone has such readily available intuitive ability."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:261
msgid ""
"His being socialized to be alone was actually in keeping with his basic "
"tendencies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 100
#: sentence:262
msgid ""
"People today, particularly those with more outgoing temperaments, might find"
" such confinement unimaginable considering there were no TVs, video games, "
"or cell phones for distraction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 101
#: sentence:263
msgid ""
"It also seems, from our vantage point, that Bill learned the art of "
"surrender at an early age."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 101
#: sentence:264
msgid ""
"His long, solitary stay in bed, with its enforced introspection, facilitated"
" a capacity for acceptance that would have great transfer value to other "
"dimensions of his unfolding life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 101
#: sentence:265
msgid ""
"Just as Helen noted that the urgency of the times required her to practice "
"the art of “inner dictation” sooner than a more leisurely pace of spiritual "
"evolution might allow, it seems that Bill’s nascent spiritual development "
"was also accelerated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 101
#: sentence:266
msgid ""
"His years of quiet seclusion were like being in a monastery, where he could "
"examine such thoughts as “Who am I?” or “What is life’s purpose?” Catherine "
"Prescott, a friend he met many years later, remembers, “Bill described "
"himself as being very slow in reaction time, . . . in his childhood there "
"was always so much time that he would savor each moment; he didn’t have to "
"rush."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 101
#: sentence:267
msgid ""
"So that if one little thing happened, he was always slowing time down to "
"make the moment last."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 101
#: sentence:268
msgid ""
"I think part of his wisdom was the ability to hesitate and ponder what was "
"going on.”[8]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 102
#: sentence:269
msgid ""
"After a three-year absence from school, during which his mother tutored him,"
" Bill was placed in a school for children who were crippled or had cardiac "
"problems."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 102
#: sentence:270
msgid ""
"His continued poor health caused him to miss from six weeks to two months of"
" classes each semester."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 102
#: sentence:271
msgid ""
"Despite these prolonged absences, however, he completed grammar school "
"(through the eighth grade) in three years."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 103
#: sentence:272
msgid "Like every other child, Bill simply wanted to be normal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 103
#: sentence:273
msgid ""
"His early years had certainly been atypical, and once returned to school, he"
" was moved into classes, then taken out and reinstalled elsewhere as his "
"teachers tried to balance his extraordinary intellectual ability and, "
"through lack of exposure, his underdeveloped social skills."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 103
#: sentence:274
msgid ""
"With all the shifting around, he still ended up entering high school at age "
"twelve."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 103
#: sentence:275
msgid ""
"He did what he could to fit in, attempting to compensate for being sick and "
"missing three years of school."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 103
#: sentence:276
msgid ""
"He was innately gifted and intellectually far ahead of his age group from "
"the constant reading during his recovery period."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 104
#: sentence:277
msgid "Bill was also gifted in terms of music and theater."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 104
#: sentence:278
msgid ""
"Classical music, especially Mozart, which he would discover during his "
"college days, provided an important refuge and immense delight for him "
"throughout his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 104
#: sentence:279
msgid ""
"During his high school years, as his health returned, Bill took voice and "
"piano lessons, for which he was a natural."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 104
#: sentence:280
msgid ""
"In his school essay, he noted: “While I never expect to be a finished "
"pianist, nor a second Nelson Eddy, I find music a soothing as well as "
"stimulating recreation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 104
#: sentence:281
msgid ""
"Bill [his best friend at the time] and I have had a lot of fun appearing in "
"amateur shows and neighborhood musicals."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 104
#: sentence:282
msgid ""
"This summer I sang my first church solo at the Chicago Lawn Congregational "
"Church, which church I attend regularly.” Commenting on his current school, "
"Lindblom High, he said:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 105
#: sentence:283
msgid "It is here I have really found myself, in its numerous activities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 105
#: sentence:284
msgid ""
"The A Cappella choir is my first love, even though Mr. Taylor makes me sing "
"tenor when I have a naturally bass voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 105
#: sentence:285
msgid ""
"Participating in boys’ clubs, the Music Club, Camera Club and the Eagle have"
" broadened my social experiences and have helped me to overcome an innate "
"timidity. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 105
#: sentence:286
msgid ""
"Realizing that I will never be able to do strenuous physical work, I wish to"
" obtain a good educational foundation, with the possibility of becoming a "
"teacher.[9]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 106
#: sentence:287
msgid ""
"He did become a teacher, although he rather famously proclaimed during his "
"college years that the one thing he would never become was a professor, as "
"he insisted he had nothing to profess."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 106
#: sentence:288
msgid ""
"And wouldn’t you know, almost every position he held thereafter involved a "
"professorship as part of the job description. Never say “never”!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 107
#: sentence:289
msgid "College years"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 108
#: sentence:290
msgid ""
"After graduating from high school in 1940, where he was among the top ten "
"students in a class of about one thousand, Bill entered DePauw University in"
" Greencastle, Indiana, on a full scholarship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 108
#: sentence:291
msgid ""
"As part of his continuing quest for normalcy and for companionship in this "
"first experience living away from home, Bill joined a fraternity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 108
#: sentence:292
msgid ""
"He had no idea what he was getting into, believing this would be a support "
"system of some kind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 108
#: sentence:293
msgid ""
"Having known Bill well, I cannot imagine him amid the noise and uproar of a "
"fraternity house after long periods of near isolation, but somehow he "
"managed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 108
#: sentence:294
msgid ""
"He indicated it was a difficult challenge for him, with his strong need for "
"privacy and his genuine interest in scholarship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 108
#: sentence:295
msgid "It was hardly the support system he had naively envisioned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 109
#: sentence:296
msgid ""
"During high school Bill had reconnected with a kindergarten friend, Jo, whom"
" he had lost track of during the intervening years of his illness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 109
#: sentence:297
msgid ""
"Simply good friends in high school (she was “going steady” with someone else"
" then), their relationship evolved into something more after graduation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 109
#: sentence:298
msgid ""
"She was his only acknowledged girl friend, according to all available "
"information."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 109
#: sentence:299
msgid ""
"Their parents knew each other and the two young people were definitely "
"considered an “item.” At Thanksgiving in 1943 he gave her his fraternity "
"pin, in those days considered almost the same as an engagement ring. Jo "
"remembers:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 110
#: sentence:300
msgid "I kept saying, “Bill, why?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 110
#: sentence:301
msgid ""
"Why do you want me to take your fraternity pin?” thinking that he would say,"
" “I love you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 110
#: sentence:302
msgid "I want to marry you.” But he didn’t."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 110
#: sentence:303
msgid ""
"He just said, “Because I want you to wear it more than anyone else in the "
"world.” He just kept insisting I take it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:304
msgid "Yet I wasn’t swept off my feet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:305
msgid "He was also still my good kindergarten buddy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:306
msgid ""
"Anyway, I thought that if he wants me to wear it, I guess I’ll wear it, "
"although I felt kind of awkward."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:307
msgid "I went back to the sorority house where I was staying as their guest."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:308
msgid ""
"That night the girls came and got me, and brought me out to the front of the"
" house about midnight."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:309
msgid ""
"The Lambda Chi guys, with Bill right in the foreground, serenaded me. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 111
#: sentence:310
msgid ""
"I felt a bit guilty about it all, because all the girls were congratulating "
"me and I just couldn’t tell them that it didn’t mean what they thought it "
"meant.[10]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 112
#: sentence:311
msgid ""
"They went together, as a long-distance romance (he was at DePauw until his "
"graduation in February 1944), for the next year, and in the fall of 1944, Jo"
" left for the University of California at Berkeley."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 112
#: sentence:312
msgid ""
"As she prepared to board the train, Bill gave her an orchid corsage and she "
"questioned him about the fraternity pin."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 112
#: sentence:313
msgid ""
"He remained vague and would make no other commitment than, “Please wear my "
"fraternity pin.” After a week at Berkeley, Jo was swept off her feet by a "
"young marine whom she ultimately married."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 112
#: sentence:314
msgid ""
"She finally wrote to Bill of her new love and returned his pin in the spring"
" of 1945; Jo heard no more from him until the late 1970s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 113
#: sentence:315
msgid "From our current perspective, we can only imagine Bill’s situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 113
#: sentence:316
msgid ""
"His girlfriend was out of his life; he had been suspecting his latent "
"homosexuality but being open about it was taboo at that time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 113
#: sentence:317
msgid ""
"A gay lifestyle was so unsupported in American society that he could not "
"accept it totally within himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 113
#: sentence:318
msgid ""
"It’s possible, however, that living in a fraternity house in close quarters "
"with many young men, he allowed himself to be more honest privately about "
"his inclinations, an honesty that had been too difficult before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 114
#: sentence:319
msgid "Chapter 2"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:320
msgid ""
"World War II started while Bill was in college, but on graduating, he was "
"rejected for the draft because of his rheumatic heart condition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:321
msgid ""
"Thus, after receiving his undergraduate degree in psychology from DePauw in "
"February 1944 and being unable to participate in the military, Bill "
"submitted his application and was accepted into the University of Chicago "
"Medical School for the upcoming fall term."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:322
msgid ""
"In addition to taking courses necessary for his psychology degree, he had "
"also completed all necessary pre-med classes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:323
msgid ""
"Hoping to earn money for his first year of medical school during the "
"intervening six months, Bill applied for work at the University of Chicago."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:324
msgid ""
"He was hired as one of ten administrative officers overseeing several "
"buildings used as testing areas for some highly classified research."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:325
msgid ""
"Later, he learned it was research on atomic energy—the Manhattan Project."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:326
msgid ""
"Soon after being hired, he was promoted to the faculty payroll and given a "
"private office and secretary. “One of my special assignments was to be in "
"charge of a special crew of men,” Bill later wrote, “who went through "
"various radioactive areas and tried to decontaminate them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 115
#: sentence:327
msgid ""
"I was required to wear a Geiger counter from the time I arrived in the "
"morning until I left at night.”[11]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 116
#: sentence:328
msgid ""
"Atomic energy research was occurring in several locations around the country"
" at that time, the University of Chicago being one of them, in a furious "
"race with the Nazis to build a bomb during the final years of World War II."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 116
#: sentence:329
msgid "This research was the best-kept secret around."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 116
#: sentence:330
msgid ""
"More than 100,000 people were involved with the project in various "
"locations, but most were in the dark about its exact nature and specific "
"purpose, including Vice President Truman, who was told the details of the "
"project only on assuming the presidency after Roosevelt’s death."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 116
#: sentence:331
msgid ""
"Everyone did know, however, that the United States and its allies were "
"joined in a life-or-death struggle with a formidable enemy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 117
#: sentence:332
msgid ""
"Bill felt the excitement of this project he was part of but, like others, "
"was unaware of its purpose or ramifications; he was told only that if these "
"experiments were not successful in giving the United States the upper hand, "
"it might mean the end of Western civilization as he knew it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 117
#: sentence:333
msgid ""
"One testing area for which he was responsible was beneath the stands of the "
"University of Chicago football stadium, made available for research because "
"the university’s president had eliminated intercollegiate football as an "
"interference to academic learning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 117
#: sentence:334
msgid ""
"The first chain reaction in the world took place there in December 1942."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 117
#: sentence:335
msgid "The irony was not lost on twenty-year-old Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 117
#: sentence:336
msgid ""
"Given the heightened tensions throughout the country and the sense of "
"urgency related to his supposedly interim job, Bill chose to continue on for"
" another year, foregoing medical school that fall."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 117
#: sentence:337
msgid ""
"The bombs were dropped on Japan in August 1945, and he resigned shortly "
"thereafter on seeing the horrific results of the project’s success."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 118
#: sentence:338
msgid ""
"Although the university had given Bill the option to postpone entering "
"medical school to continue with the Manhattan Project, he decided, after "
"some consideration, not to enroll at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 118
#: sentence:339
msgid ""
"Thus, in the fall of 1945, without much thought about where it would lead, "
"he enrolled in the University of Chicago’s graduate school in psychology "
"where the already noted psychologist, Carl Rogers, was beginning to hold "
"forth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 118
#: sentence:340
msgid ""
"Unaware of what people sensed about him, Bill was confused and surprised "
"when Rogers offered him a teaching position almost immediately; he was "
"younger than almost all the other students and did not yet have a master’s "
"degree."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 118
#: sentence:341
msgid ""
"He was also the only member of Rogers’s staff not imported from Ohio State "
"University."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 118
#: sentence:342
msgid ""
"Soon thereafter, Rogers invited him to participate in research on the merits"
" of his signature “client-centered psychotherapy.” This was an innovative "
"new approach to psychotherapy that emphasized the importance of "
"relationships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 118
#: sentence:343
msgid ""
"Specifically, the Rogerian approach was based on “unconditional positive "
"regard,” or perfect love, and its essential place in the success of client-"
"centered therapy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:344
msgid ""
"Bill actually worked as a part-time Rogerian therapist for about a year but "
"did not feel called to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:345
msgid ""
"Researching the science that provided the foundation for therapy was more to"
" his liking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:346
msgid ""
"That inclination to examine therapeutic foundations through research into "
"personality development would dominate his work for decades."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:347
msgid ""
"Within this framework of emphasis on relationships, however, Bill received "
"his Ph.D. in psychology in the spring of 1949; his research focused on the "
"psycho-physiological changes in galvanic skin response, heart rate, and "
"respiration in clients tested before and after Rogerian psychotherapy, as "
"compared to a control group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:348
msgid ""
"Simply stated, his research showed that being loved, appreciated, and "
"listened to positively affects both mind and body."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:349
msgid ""
"Although now, sixty years later, that is old information, at the time it was"
" revolutionary."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 119
#: sentence:350
msgid ""
"Everyone who knew Bill remembers his saying how bizarre it was for him to be"
" involved, even though unknowingly, first with a project that resulted in "
"merciless devastation, and then with one that espoused the practice of "
"“unconditional positive regard.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 120
#: sentence:351
msgid ""
"As part of a standard psychology curriculum, Bill would have been familiar "
"with the work of Dr. Gardner Murphy, a pioneer in the field."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 120
#: sentence:352
msgid ""
"In his book, Personality–A Biosocial Approach to Origins and Structure, "
"published in 1947, Murphy gives an excellent and comprehensive overview of "
"the world of personality research at the time Bill entered the field."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 120
#: sentence:353
msgid ""
"In the foreword, he writes, “But lest the reader waste time upon what he "
"does not want, it must be emphasized that this is not a book on diagnosis or"
" therapy of personality problems, or upon any type of clinical approach."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 120
#: sentence:354
msgid ""
"It is simply an attempt at evaluation of data on how personality grows.”[12]"
" It is fortunate for readers that he limited his topic to this single one "
"as, 927 pages later, we have a recap of those major areas of research to "
"which Bill would contribute significantly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 121
#: sentence:355
msgid ""
"From today’s viewpoint, the information Dr. Murphy provides, current at that"
" time, seems limited."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 121
#: sentence:356
msgid ""
"It lacks today’s high level of technological sophistication that has made "
"possible amazing advances in neuroscience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 121
#: sentence:357
msgid ""
"Much less was known then about brain function, genetics and epigenetics, and"
" the body-mind connection, specifically as they relate to personality "
"development."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 121
#: sentence:358
msgid ""
"Nor was the interest in Eastern philosophies as wide-spread then as now."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 121
#: sentence:359
msgid ""
"Because of such limitations, Bill was very attracted to any new and "
"different approaches, particularly any related to the influence of positive "
"relationships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 122
#: sentence:360
msgid ""
"Murphy championed the idea that people are already highly formed at birth "
"with fundamentally different and unique predispositions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 122
#: sentence:361
msgid ""
"First voiced by Hippocrates in 370 B.C., the idea was predominant for "
"centuries."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 122
#: sentence:362
msgid ""
"Only in the early twentieth century did researchers of the time, constrained"
" by nineteenth-century models of both the universe and the individual, "
"formulate behaviorism, the notion that people are born without "
"predispositions and could have their behavior molded at will."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 122
#: sentence:363
msgid ""
"By midcentury, when Bill was entering the field of psychology, that "
"temporary reversal of psychological theory was coming to a close, and the "
"earlier premise that we are born inherently unique with distinctive energy "
"patterns was being rediscovered and newly researched."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 123
#: sentence:364
msgid ""
"Murphy also lamented Western researchers’ failure to examine the Eastern "
"approach to man’s psychology, which included the spiritual dimensions of "
"life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 124
#: sentence:365
msgid ""
"In a future psychology of personality, there will surely be a place for "
"directly grappling with the question of man’s response to the cosmos, his "
"sense of unity with it, the nature of his esthetic demands upon it, and his "
"feelings of loneliness or of consummation in his contemplation of it. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 124
#: sentence:366
msgid ""
"It is quite likely that selfhood will be better understood when reference is"
" made to the primordial non-self matrix from which it arises, and that the "
"synthesis, the capacity of human nature to function at self and non-self "
"levels at the same time, or to alternate when it so desires, may prove to be"
" an enrichment of personality far greater than that which the cult of self-"
"contained, self-defined individuality can grant.[13]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 125
#: sentence:367
msgid ""
"With this Murphy seems to anticipate both modern-day quantum physics and the"
" foundational premise of A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:368
msgid ""
"In addition to what he was learning about psychology in general and client-"
"centered psychotherapy in particular, Bill’s exposure to music broadened and"
" deepened during his years in graduate school, both interests dear to his "
"heart."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:369
msgid ""
"All who knew him in later life can attest to his deep and abiding love for "
"music; his home was continuously filled with music playing in the "
"background."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:370
msgid ""
"He had listened to friends’ classical music collections as much as possible "
"during his years at the University of Chicago and fell in love with Mozart."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:371
msgid ""
"In fact, he was so intimately acquainted with Mozart’s music that after "
"hearing a few bars of a recorded piece, he could accurately identify both "
"the performers and the conductor of that particular recording."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:372
msgid ""
"As he became more musically sophisticated during this time, his love of "
"opera grew and he realized that a good way to become more familiar with it "
"was to usher at the Chicago Opera House, home to several large opera "
"companies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:373
msgid ""
"He was on a tight budget, but after saving enough to buy a tuxedo (required "
"for the position), he did indeed become an usher there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 126
#: sentence:374
msgid ""
"Through attending every performance possible, he developed a deep "
"appreciation for and knowledge of that particular art form."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 127
#: sentence:375
msgid ""
"After receiving his Ph.D., something he had doubted he would ever get, Bill "
"still wasn’t sure what to do with it, although he knew it provided something"
" akin to a union card in his field."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 127
#: sentence:376
msgid ""
"He also realized that psychology really did appeal to him and that this "
"field felt exciting, rewarding, and compatible with his most basic nature."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 127
#: sentence:377
msgid ""
"In his autobiography he noted that, for the first time, he really started to"
" feel good (healthwise), to find himself, and to form some good and lasting "
"friendships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:378
msgid ""
"Although feeling at home and invigorated in the intellectual world of "
"psychology, Bill was also experiencing some disappointments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:379
msgid ""
"He had hoped his parents would be proud of him for earning a Ph.D., and at "
"such a young age (twenty-five), but they seemed incapable of understanding "
"his field, his basic interests, or his talents and accomplishments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:380
msgid ""
"To put his early years in context, theirs was a lower-middle-class family, "
"the parents knowing no other than hard physical work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:381
msgid ""
"His father was one of ten children from a poor, coal-mining family in "
"southern Illinois, though later he became a superintendent in the building "
"and construction department of the telephone company."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:382
msgid "Survival was important; culture was not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:383
msgid ""
"Bill had become ill at age seven during the depths of the Great Depression "
"when life was generally difficult."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:384
msgid ""
"Having lost two children earlier, his father worried greatly about how he "
"might have to support this ailing child who very likely would never be able "
"to do strenuous physical work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:385
msgid "How would he be able to support himself?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:386
msgid ""
"His father often verbalized his fear that Bill would end up on the “dole,” a"
" welfare case."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 128
#: sentence:387
msgid ""
"With their worldview, his parents could hardly appreciate his academic "
"pursuits; they thought a Ph.D. was a worthless piece of paper to hang on the"
" wall—useless in finding a real job."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 129
#: sentence:388
msgid ""
"Of course, Bill was aware of their lack of support for his accomplishments "
"and took that as a personal affront, adding grievances to his growing store."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 129
#: sentence:389
msgid ""
"We know he had been greatly affected by his sister’s early death and can "
"assume there was some upset about Jo’s “Dear John” letter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 129
#: sentence:390
msgid ""
"These hurts and disappointments were internalized and carried forward for "
"decades, creating a basis for later conflicts and frustrations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:391
msgid ""
"As Bill was graduating, his parents retired to Florida because his mother "
"was not well; she had been diagnosed with multiple sclerosis and advised to "
"move to a better climate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:392
msgid ""
"Alone now in Chicago, though more content than ever, his next venture was at"
" the Michael Reese Hospital, a major Jewish training hospital in Chicago and"
" the place to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:393
msgid ""
"A fellow graduate student mentioned to Bill that a position had unexpectedly"
" become available with Dr. Samuel Beck, head of the psychology department "
"and a leading authority on the Rorschach test (a method of psychological "
"evaluation in which subjects’ perceptions of inkblots are recorded and then "
"analyzed using intuitive insight and/or complex scientifically derived "
"algorithms."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:394
msgid ""
"This test is used to examine personality characteristics and emotional "
"function)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:395
msgid ""
"Bill applied and Beck offered him a position to study schizophrenia and the "
"Rorschach test, funded by the National Institute for Mental Health."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:396
msgid ""
"After Bill explained that he knew nothing about the Rorschach test, Beck "
"assured him he considered that to be an asset, as it would allow him to "
"conduct research uncorrupted by someone else’s teaching."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:397
msgid ""
"He was also enthusiastic about Bill’s Ph.D. dissertation, thinking it "
"sounded most scientific, a plus."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:398
msgid ""
"This first position as a doctor of psychology allowed Bill to become "
"acquainted with, among other things, personality tests and measurements, "
"which would prove useful as his career unfolded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:399
msgid ""
"Working there also provided the unusual experience of being the only non-"
"Jewish member of the department."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:400
msgid ""
"He wondered if he would be accepted, a question of possible reverse "
"discrimination, but he certainly was; his fellow staffers even explained "
"their Yiddish jokes to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:401
msgid ""
"After two-and-a-half years, the grant ended and he chose to move on, but "
"where?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 130
#: sentence:402
msgid ""
"The University of Chicago and Michael Reese Hospital were the city’s most "
"interesting and challenging places to work, and he had now “been there, done"
" that.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 131
#: sentence:403
msgid ""
"Like so many, Bill had moved forward from high school graduation without a "
"clear-cut sense of destiny or even an idea about what he wanted to do next."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 131
#: sentence:404
msgid ""
"He certainly didn’t know what he was getting into when he took the "
"administrative job at the University of Chicago related to the Manhattan "
"Project."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 131
#: sentence:405
msgid ""
"He also wasn’t particularly sure, at the outset, what pursuing a degree in "
"psychology was about, but by 1945 he had lost interest in medical school, "
"something of a fantasy anyway given that he hadn’t the funds to pay for it "
"and his family couldn’t help even if they had been inclined."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 131
#: sentence:406
msgid ""
"Moving to Michael Reese Hospital had a certain aimless quality about it, "
"from the world’s point of view, but in hindsight his particular destiny was "
"unfolding perfectly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 131
#: sentence:407
msgid ""
"As a harbinger of things to come, Bill said he would occasionally wonder why"
" he was studying psychology in the first place, and an inner response would "
"indicate that he would not know for many years—but when he finally did, it "
"would make him indescribably happy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 132
#: sentence:408
msgid "What was the underlying impetus that led him to study psychology?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 132
#: sentence:409
msgid ""
"The decision might have seemed a casual one, when other fields were also "
"open to him, but many major decisions in life are made offhandedly, without "
"exploring their ramifications, because we are unaware at the time that they "
"are leading to major changes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 132
#: sentence:410
msgid "We know that only after the fact."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 132
#: sentence:411
msgid ""
"Even at a young age Bill had demonstrated his ability as an able, "
"trustworthy administrator."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 132
#: sentence:412
msgid ""
"He had more than a little talent for music and theater, and he certainly had"
" the qualifications to succeed in medicine, which he once considered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 132
#: sentence:413
msgid ""
"He had also mused about a teaching career but was led inexorably to the "
"field of psychology, following the intuition that led him throughout his "
"life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 133
#: sentence:414
msgid ""
"Because research into personality types became Bill’s specialty, the "
"centerpiece of his academic research, and to understand him better, I am "
"including a brief look at personality types."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 133
#: sentence:415
msgid ""
"Men of genius through the ages have recognized not only that human beings "
"are born with specific characteristics but that humankind seems to fall "
"naturally into four distinct categories of temperament, character, and "
"intelligence or, in short, personality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 133
#: sentence:416
msgid ""
"Such categories were named according to the understanding available at the "
"time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 133
#: sentence:417
msgid ""
"An abbreviated list of persons who recognized four basic types include:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 134
#: sentence:418
msgid ""
"Plato (c340 B.C.), Aristotle (c325 B.C.), Galen (c190 A.D.), Paracelsus "
"(1550), Adickes (1905), Spranger (1914), Kretschmer (1920), Fromm (1947), "
"Myers (1958). . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 135
#: sentence:419
msgid ""
"And so the idea that individuals are predisposed to develop into one of four"
" different configurations of attitude and action has survived for well over "
"two thousand years."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 135
#: sentence:420
msgid ""
"Surely this idea would not have been employed for so long, by so many "
"people, in so many countries, had there not been some sort of widely shared "
"recognition of its usefulness.[14]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 136
#: sentence:421
msgid ""
"The last person on the list, Isabel Myers, with her mother Kathryn Briggs, "
"developed the now well-known system for identifying personality types—the "
"Myers-Briggs Type Indicator."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 136
#: sentence:422
msgid ""
"To this we add its shorter, but equally valid cousin, the Keirsey "
"Temperament Sorter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 136
#: sentence:423
msgid ""
"These tests, based on Carl Jung’s discoveries, started being used as "
"research tools in the early 1950s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 136
#: sentence:424
msgid ""
"Thus, Gardner Murphy did not mention them in his 1947 book, nor were they "
"available during Bill’s early work under Carl Rogers in Chicago."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 137
#: sentence:425
msgid ""
"Both these more recent tests use four sets of opposites to identify "
"temperaments: I/E—introvert/extrovert; N/S—intuitive/sensory; "
"T/F—thinking/feeling; and J/P—judging/perceiving."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 137
#: sentence:426
msgid ""
"Through her research, Myers discovered, like her predecessors, that the "
"sixteen possible combinations reduce to four major categories, SP, SJ, NF, "
"and NT, with characteristics consistent with the four types deduced by the "
"earlier researchers listed above."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 137
#: sentence:427
msgid ""
"For a more in-depth explanation, I recommend David Keirsey’s Please "
"Understand Me, II as a guide to understanding personality traits, especially"
" those unlike our own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 137
#: sentence:428
msgid "One of those early observers of humankind was Plato."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 138
#: sentence:429
msgid ""
"Plato was the quintessential Idealist [known as the NF, an abbreviation for "
"the intuitive-feeling type in the Myers-Briggs personality lexicon], the "
"inventor of a philosophy in which ideas are even more real than earth and "
"its inhabitants."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 138
#: sentence:430
msgid ""
"Plato’s word for an idealist like himself was noetic, which, roughly "
"translated, means “intuitive thought,” that is, pure thinking done without "
"recourse to either logical or empirical investigation.[15]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 139
#: sentence:431
msgid ""
"Bill Thetford was the poster child for the NF, or intuitive-feeling type, as"
" was his mentor, Carl Rogers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 139
#: sentence:432
msgid ""
"Keirsey gives some insight into what pulled Bill toward psychology and away "
"from what seemed to be equally viable options:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 140
#: sentence:433
msgid ""
"Diplomacy is the ability to deal with people in a skillful, tactful manner ."
" . . a metaphor for the interpersonal touch or sensitivity in which "
"Idealists [or NFs] seem to be both interested and particularly talented."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 140
#: sentence:434
msgid ""
"This sensitive way with people shows up so early in NFs that it is tempting "
"to assume they are born with it [emphasis added]—born to use their personal "
"empathy and interpersonal skills to improve relations between people. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 140
#: sentence:435
msgid ""
"With their instinct for seeking common ground, with their ability to "
"interpret each side’s communications in a positive way, with their gift for "
"putting themselves in the other’s place, and with their metaphorical "
"language easily and fluidly turning one thing into another, Idealists are "
"well-equipped for the difficult task of influencing people’s attitudes and "
"actions, not only inspiring them to grow, but also settling differences "
"among them, smoothing difficulties—ever looking to enlighten the people "
"around them and to forge unity among them.[16]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 141
#: sentence:436
msgid ""
"Thus, we are drawn in certain directions even when, in our earlier days, we "
"might not have a vocabulary to explain that attraction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 141
#: sentence:437
msgid ""
"As natural and automatic as the quest for self-realization is for the NFs, "
"it is quite bewildering to the other three types."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 142
#: sentence:438
msgid ""
"Idealists regard this search for identity as the most important enterprise "
"in their lives and with their gift for language they can be powerful "
"advocates for its being a necessary pilgrimage for all people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 142
#: sentence:439
msgid ""
"Very often the other types, the SJs, NTs, and SPs, are troubled by the "
"thought that they ought to be pursuing this goal, even if the search for "
"Self does not beckon them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 142
#: sentence:440
msgid ""
"The reluctance of over ninety percent of humanity to join the search for "
"self-actualization is a great source of mystification to the Idealists.[17]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 143
#: sentence:441
msgid ""
"This brief description of the NF, though general, gives us much insight into"
" Bill Thetford in particular."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 143
#: sentence:442
msgid ""
"The vast amount of research on personality types available today, some of it"
" done by Bill himself, provides the opportunity for anyone to understand "
"basic, human motivating factors more fully than ever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 143
#: sentence:443
msgid ""
"Without such explanations, others’ choices and inclinations seem uninformed "
"at best, and defective at worst—hardly a prescription for tolerance or "
"empathy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 144
#: sentence:444
msgid ""
"One advantage of living several decades, whether we know our personality "
"type or not, is that we can see patterns in our lives, and how seemingly "
"accidental, unrelated experiences all contribute to our unfolding awareness,"
" a prerequisite for healing the fearful ideas we hold about ourselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 144
#: sentence:445
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles promises that our lives are not random and that “those "
"who are to meet, will meet.” Although we each have an individualized "
"curriculum in terms of where we go, who we meet, the jobs we hold, the "
"abilities we develop, the places we live, and the lessons we encounter, the "
"Course assures us that all encounters are designed for our maximal and "
"mutual healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 144
#: sentence:446
msgid ""
"This is a very reassuring idea, and embracing it allays anxiety about the "
"correctness of our decisions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 144
#: sentence:447
msgid ""
"Keeping in mind ACIM’s major teaching of forgiveness, all circumstances "
"become perfect venues for its practice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 145
#: sentence:448
msgid ""
"We may never fully recognize all the reasons for acquiring our particular "
"skills, but we can learn to trust that there are no accidents."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 146
#: sentence:449
msgid ""
"What could you not accept, if you but knew that everything that happens, all"
" events, past, present and to come, are gently planned by One Whose only "
"purpose is your good?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 146
#: sentence:450
msgid ""
"Perhaps you have misunderstood His plan, for He would never offer pain to "
"you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 146
#: sentence:451
msgid ""
"But your defenses did not let you see His loving blessing shine in every "
"step you ever took."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 146
#: sentence:452
msgid ""
"While you made plans for death [or the strengthening of the ego], He led you"
" gently to eternal life.[18]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 147
#: sentence:453
msgid ""
"In 1950, Bill did not know any of this and, at twenty-seven, did not have "
"the advantage of age from which to view his seemingly arbitrary choices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 147
#: sentence:454
msgid ""
"Speaking of his inclination to study psychology, he often commented that he "
"had observed many psychologists and their endless, competing theories, but "
"that nothing really seemed to come of them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 147
#: sentence:455
msgid ""
"He saw no one integrating them in a way that actually changed the nature of "
"one’s life experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 147
#: sentence:456
msgid ""
"One of his favorite sayings was that “the emperor has no clothes”—a "
"prescient observation, as many years later he would read the section on "
"unhealed healers in the Course: “Such evident inconsistencies account for "
"why no one has really explained what happens in psychotherapy. Nothing "
"really does."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 147
#: sentence:457
msgid ""
"Nothing real has happened to the unhealed healer, and he must learn from his"
" own teaching.”[19]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 148
#: sentence:458
msgid "Chapter 3"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 149
#: sentence:459
msgid ""
"About the time Bill felt his interesting work opportunities in Chicago were "
"complete, he was recruited by the Central Intelligence Agency, the country’s"
" newly reorganized intelligence service."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 149
#: sentence:460
msgid ""
"All of Bill’s education and training up to that point had involved working "
"with leading-edge scientists, innovators in science and medicine."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 149
#: sentence:461
msgid ""
"Because his mentors and colleagues were well known, and publishing is always"
" an integral and necessary aspect of academia, he had become widely "
"recognized and respected throughout his field as a result of his own "
"publications and others to which he contributed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 149
#: sentence:462
msgid ""
"Thus, he was also easy to track, even before the age of computers and "
"modern-day surveillance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 149
#: sentence:463
msgid ""
"A friend of mine and Bill’s, conversant with how the CIA operates, indicated"
" they had levels of connections back then, far beyond what we might imagine,"
" to identify potential recruits who could prove useful to the Agency."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 149
#: sentence:464
msgid "Clearly, Bill fell into the “useful” category."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 150
#: sentence:465
msgid ""
"Although working for the CIA would seem an implausible choice of work for "
"him, it turned out to be essential for his path."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 150
#: sentence:466
msgid ""
"The Manhattan Project, the job he had “wandered into” ostensibly to earn "
"money for living expenses and medical school, had provided Bill with a high "
"security clearance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 150
#: sentence:467
msgid ""
"His work with Carl Rogers, with its emphasis on relationships, fed the soul "
"of this young NF, and he had gained some skill with early biofeedback "
"techniques using scientific equipment then available."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 150
#: sentence:468
msgid ""
"Next, he had become conversant with tests and measurement construction at "
"the Michael Reese Hospital, and all of these combined to grant him entrée to"
" the next important chapter of his life, work with the CIA."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 150
#: sentence:469
msgid "Outwardly, he was following a career path."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 150
#: sentence:470
msgid ""
"In retrospect, we see he was led through the necessary steps, including all "
"that emerged during his time with the CIA, toward his major spiritual "
"fulfillment of co-authoring A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 151
#: sentence:471
msgid "It all seems so obvious once our lives are over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 151
#: sentence:472
msgid ""
"If only we could trust the rightness of everything while it is happening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 151
#: sentence:473
msgid ""
"Watching Bill’s destiny unfold after the fact, we can see that events and "
"circumstances were always in good order, leading inexorably to his choice "
"for peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 152
#: sentence:474
msgid "Yet there is no step along the road that anyone takes but by chance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 152
#: sentence:475
msgid ""
"It has already been taken by him, although he has not yet embarked on it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 152
#: sentence:476
msgid "For time but seems to go in one direction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 152
#: sentence:477
msgid "We but undertake a journey that is over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 152
#: sentence:478
msgid "Yet it seems to have a future still unknown to us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 153
#: sentence:479
msgid ""
"Time is a trick, a sleight of hand, a vast illusion in which figures come "
"and go as if by magic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 153
#: sentence:480
msgid ""
"Yet there is a plan behind appearances that does not change. The script is "
"written."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 153
#: sentence:481
msgid "When experience will come to end your doubting has been set."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 153
#: sentence:482
msgid ""
"For we but see the journey from the point at which it ended, looking back on"
" it, imagining we make it once again; reviewing mentally what has gone "
"by.[20]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 154
#: sentence:483
msgid ""
"Patriotism was one of several factors in Bill’s decision to join the CIA, "
"though not the primary one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 154
#: sentence:484
msgid ""
"Someone asked Jack Luckett, one of Bill’s closest friends in his later "
"years, if he found Bill to be patriotic toward the end of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 154
#: sentence:485
msgid "Jack replied, “Not in the normal sense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 154
#: sentence:486
msgid "He saw himself as a citizen of the universe."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 154
#: sentence:487
msgid ""
"He was secretly proud of his CIA connection, and because of my ‘spook’ "
"background, chatted with me about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 154
#: sentence:488
msgid ""
"It was more pride in adventure than dedication to eliminating enemies.”[21]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 155
#: sentence:489
msgid ""
"The CIA’s predecessor, the Office of Strategic Services (OSS), which was "
"responsible for US intelligence operations during World War II, was "
"disbanded shortly after the war ended."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 155
#: sentence:490
msgid ""
"At that time, however, the cold war with the Soviet Union was intensifying "
"and the United States recognized the imperative need for strategic "
"intelligence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 155
#: sentence:491
msgid ""
"After some reshuffling of functions into various other agencies, the "
"National Security Act established the CIA in 1947."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 155
#: sentence:492
msgid ""
"It was unorganized, had no official headquarters, and was generally a mess, "
"bearing little resemblance to the present-day organization."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 155
#: sentence:493
msgid "From “William Newton Thetford and the Central Intelligence Agency”:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:494
msgid ""
"As the global total cold war gathered momentum, it became clear that the "
"young CIA desperately needed help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:495
msgid ""
"An extraordinary network of civilian universities and government agencies "
"had provided OSS with a steady stream of raw intelligence to guide the total"
" war against Nazi Germany and Japan."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:496
msgid ""
"In contrast, the young CIA in 1947 was treated like a stepchild, its "
"experienced leadership in short supply, its actual and legal authority still"
" unclear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:497
msgid "The new CIA needed more than old files from the OSS."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:498
msgid "Their greatest need was for personnel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:499
msgid ""
"During hearings on the National Security Act of 1947, the new director of "
"central intelligence, Allen Dulles, said, “The new intelligence entity would"
" be directed by a relatively small but elite corps of men with a passion for"
" anonymity and a willingness to stick at that particular job."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 156
#: sentence:500
msgid ""
"The agency must have a corps of the most competent men, which this country "
"can produce, to evaluate and correlate the intelligence obtained.”[22]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 157
#: sentence:501
msgid ""
"The challenge was how to recruit and evaluate this badly needed group of "
"people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 157
#: sentence:502
msgid ""
"At that time, various schools of psychology had been around for about one "
"hundred years; they seemed to hold the keys to human behavior—a must-have "
"for evaluating foreign leaders and how they might respond under different "
"circumstances—and to methods for recruiting those essential intelligence "
"officers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 157
#: sentence:503
msgid ""
"In 1950, the year before Bill was hired, the CIA had offered John Gittinger "
"the position of director of its assessment and evaluation staff."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 157
#: sentence:504
msgid ""
"Bill, hired in 1951 as one of about ten senior psychologists at that time, "
"worked for Gittinger in that department and would continue to work "
"indirectly with him throughout much of his academic career."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 157
#: sentence:505
msgid ""
"John made a tremendous impression on Bill and became a pivotal player in his"
" life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 158
#: sentence:506
msgid ""
"Bill’s duties included administering a series of tests to applicants seeking"
" to become intelligence officers and/or spies, then interviewing and "
"recommending them or not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 158
#: sentence:507
msgid ""
"There was a sense of danger in the air and great urgency about staffing up "
"as the cold war with the Soviet Union escalated and the Korean War "
"progressed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 158
#: sentence:508
msgid ""
"Obviously, in screening potential hires, the psychologists needed insight, "
"intuition, and the ability to read people accurately, all of which were "
"Bill’s strong suits."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 158
#: sentence:509
msgid ""
"Because of the sensitive nature of this work—interviewing those who would be"
" working for the Agency in various intelligence capacities—Bill soon "
"attained a top secret security clearance, something that usually took a "
"while to earn."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 158
#: sentence:510
msgid "It would serve him later as his worldly saga unfolded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:511
msgid ""
"Working with the CIA offered Bill, in addition to his position on the "
"assessment and evaluation team, the added opportunity to learn more about "
"Gittinger’s new project to assess people’s capabilities under various "
"conditions, stressful and otherwise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:512
msgid ""
"These innovations and their potential importance greatly impressed Bill, "
"providing the next chapter of his series of psychological explorations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:513
msgid ""
"Gittinger had developed a process, originally to describe the dynamics and "
"adjustments of mental dysfunction, but later widely used as a technique for "
"general psychological assessment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:514
msgid ""
"He reportedly was very charismatic and loved to talk for hours about his "
"theories."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:515
msgid ""
"An early colleague of Bill’s reported, “You couldn’t ignore John; he was "
"there, he filled up a room."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:516
msgid ""
"He was a pied-piper, guru-type, interesting individual who developed a "
"theory in terms of how people progressed through life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 159
#: sentence:517
msgid ""
"I know Bill was intrigued and would often sit and listen to John expound his"
" theories.”[23]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 160
#: sentence:518
msgid ""
"During his first year with the CIA, Gittinger continued work on his model of"
" personality development, newly named the Personality Assessment System, or "
"PAS."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 160
#: sentence:519
msgid ""
"For more than two decades, John and others, including Bill, continued to "
"refine what eventually Bill considered the most powerful and efficient "
"descriptive and predictive personality assessment system in the world, "
"deserving to be ranked with Freud and Jung’s discoveries."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 160
#: sentence:520
msgid ""
"Leaders in intelligence circles wholeheartedly agreed with this assessment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 161
#: sentence:521
msgid ""
"At that time [1961] CIA psychologists began to substitute such direct "
"evidence as body language and overt behavior for the one-hour test to assess"
" personality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 161
#: sentence:522
msgid ""
"However, the PAS remained the conceptual structure that guided any such "
"assessment from direct observation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 161
#: sentence:523
msgid ""
"Using the PAS to analyze and make accurate predictions about key world "
"leaders, Gittinger advised several presidents until his retirement in 1978."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 161
#: sentence:524
msgid ""
"As early as the Cuban missile crisis in October 1962, he conferred with "
"President Kennedy about the likely behavior of Nikolai Khrushchev under "
"stress."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 161
#: sentence:525
msgid ""
"The astonishing accuracy of the PAS eventually won for Gittinger promotion "
"to the role of Chief Psychologist of CIA for World Wide Operations.[24]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 162
#: sentence:526
msgid ""
"Early in our friendship, Bill told me more than once about his helping to "
"develop a test that could ferret out potential double agents."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 162
#: sentence:527
msgid ""
"It seemed to have some special appeal to him, as he became more animated "
"when he spoke of it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 162
#: sentence:528
msgid ""
"I knew nothing about the CIA’s early history at that point and couldn’t "
"fully appreciate the scope of the work and Bill’s major contributions to "
"refining that assessment tool, but I did recognize his enthusiasm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 162
#: sentence:529
msgid ""
"Even as a young man, when it came to understanding human behavior, Bill was "
"already in the vanguard and Gittinger recognized that talent."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 162
#: sentence:530
msgid "As David Goodrich, a colleague of Bill’s, reported:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:531
msgid ""
"John was not a doctor of psychology; he had a master’s degree in counseling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:532
msgid ""
"That’s not a big deal but I think it was to John, so someone with Bill’s "
"credentials was very attractive to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:533
msgid "And, obviously, he held a most favorable opinion of him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:534
msgid ""
"Everyone who ever worked with Bill realized he was an extremely bright guy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:535
msgid "John considered Bill one of his real protégés."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:536
msgid ""
"Basically, John was a very human guy, always somewhat overweight, and as "
"part of his theory, he believed that people were born with or soon acquired "
"something that either made them attractive or unattractive to people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:537
msgid ""
"He believed the world treated the cute baby or the attractive little child "
"very differently, allowing them to develop a totally different perspective "
"than people like John believed himself to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:538
msgid ""
"A great deal of John’s thinking was that those unattractive people had to "
"compensate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:539
msgid "That was his own self-account."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:540
msgid ""
"John was motivated by a sincere desire to be helpful to the Agency and he "
"was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 163
#: sentence:541
msgid ""
"He also had a huge investment in this theory and had at least as much ego as"
" the rest of us, if not more.[25]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 164
#: sentence:542
msgid ""
"The purpose of the PAS is to predict a person’s future behavior so that the "
"responding behavior can be appropriate in relation to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 164
#: sentence:543
msgid ""
"Where you cannot give the test directly—as for instance, to a foreign "
"leader—it is important to have ways to determine the personality that "
"underlies observable behavior, thus making it possible to predict that "
"person’s future actions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 164
#: sentence:544
msgid ""
"Obviously, greater comprehension of human behavior is very important in many"
" other areas, as well—all types of counseling and psychotherapy, personnel "
"work, classroom assessments, crime detection and prevention, to name a "
"few—and, of course, foreign relations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 165
#: sentence:545
msgid ""
"According to the Personality Assessment System Foundation web site, the PAS "
"contributes to the prediction of behavior in several ways:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 166
#: sentence:546
msgid ""
"• It indicates the kinds of internal and external cues the individual is "
"most likely to respond to overtly;"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 167
#: sentence:547
msgid ""
"• It suggests the types of stimuli most likely to produce behavior change;"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 168
#: sentence:548
msgid ""
"• It provides an understanding of the quality of environments in which the "
"individual is most likely to behave efficiently;"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 169
#: sentence:549
msgid ""
"• It offers insight into situations that are stressful for the individual;"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 170
#: sentence:550
msgid ""
"• It permits prediction of the probable nature of maladjusted behavior, "
"should maladjusted behavior occur."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 171
#: sentence:551
msgid ""
"The PAS thus contributes to individual assessment by providing practical "
"insights into a highly personalized pattern of strengths and weaknesses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 171
#: sentence:552
msgid ""
"At the same time, the system allows objective comparisons among the "
"personality features of different individuals, thereby offering a suitable "
"framework for behavioral research and definitive investigations of "
"personality structure and function.[26]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 172
#: sentence:553
msgid ""
"In other words, the PAS is an elaborate system for describing how "
"personality is built from infancy through adolescence and all the "
"compensations required when we reject our innate characteristics and "
"inclinations, when we are not self-accepting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 172
#: sentence:554
msgid "This applies to every person born."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 172
#: sentence:555
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles also speaks with revealing eloquence on the subject, "
"though with a decidedly different slant:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 173
#: sentence:556
msgid ""
"The building of a concept of the self is what the learning of the world is "
"for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 173
#: sentence:557
msgid ""
"This is its purpose; that you come without a self, and make one as you go "
"along."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 173
#: sentence:558
msgid ""
"And by the time you reach “maturity” you have perfected it, to meet the "
"world on equal terms, at one with its demands. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 174
#: sentence:559
msgid "A concept of the self is made by you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 174
#: sentence:560
msgid "It bears no likeness to yourself at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 174
#: sentence:561
msgid ""
"It is an idol, made to take the place of your reality as Son of God. . . "
".[27]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 175
#: sentence:562
msgid "You will make many concepts of the self as learning goes along."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 175
#: sentence:563
msgid ""
"Each one will show the changes in your own relationships, as your perception"
" of yourself is changed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 175
#: sentence:564
msgid ""
"There will be some confusion every time there is a shift, but be you "
"thankful that the learning of the world is loosening its grasp upon your "
"mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 175
#: sentence:565
msgid ""
"And be you sure and happy in the confidence that it will go at last, and "
"leave your mind at peace.[28]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 176
#: sentence:566
msgid ""
"Working with John Gittinger, Bill was becoming enamored with the PAS, this "
"very sophisticated process of describing how a personality is built and "
"under what conditions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 176
#: sentence:567
msgid ""
"The Myers-Briggs test, excellent and helpful though it is, does not have "
"this level of sophistication."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 176
#: sentence:568
msgid ""
"ACIM had not yet been written, although it would have much to say about "
"personality development in years to come."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 176
#: sentence:569
msgid ""
"We can already look ahead and compare the foundations on which the PAS is "
"built to those of the Course, and the life-altering decision that lay ahead "
"for Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 177
#: sentence:570
msgid ""
"Referencing personality development, “William Newton Thetford and the "
"Central Intelligence Agency” includes a firsthand description of twenty-"
"seven-year-old Bill by one of his colleagues in 1950."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 177
#: sentence:571
msgid ""
"Realizing that no observation is objective but colored by the mind-set of "
"the observer, I think the correlations between the theory of Bill’s "
"personality (see Appendix One) and this firsthand account are worth noting:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:572
msgid ""
"An independent but socially involved person, Bill had a high sense of "
"mission."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:573
msgid ""
"He was typically well organized, systematic, self-disciplined and socially "
"effective, if often aloof."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:574
msgid ""
"Although he could be intensely individualistic and unconventional, he was "
"rarely revolutionary, preferring to dedicate his practical, pragmatic nature"
" to improving, not dismantling, organizations and procedures."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:575
msgid ""
"He was very conscious of his own needs, which he usually kept under "
"effective control."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:576
msgid ""
"He was equally perceptive of the needs of others but was not likely to be "
"dominated by them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:577
msgid ""
"As a manager, he was thus concerned but relatively dispassionate, sometimes "
"appearing detached or even unsupportive if others failed to meet his high "
"standards."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:578
msgid ""
"He was typically ahead of or on top of events, confident of his ability to "
"cope with most situations and able to prepare for those that promised to be "
"challenging."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 178
#: sentence:579
msgid "He rarely got caught off guard or over his head.[29]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 179
#: sentence:580
msgid ""
"In researching this book, I spoke with three of Bill’s colleagues, then also"
" senior psychologists with the CIA, who indicated that in the early 1950s "
"they recruited only the “brightest and best,” originally graduates from Yale"
" and Harvard but later from other institutions as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 179
#: sentence:581
msgid ""
"They said it was a very interesting and exciting time, with much innovative "
"work in the assessment area and a great sense of esprit de corps."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 179
#: sentence:582
msgid ""
"Feeling part of the inner group, these bright young people entrusted with "
"sensitive, high-priority tasks were always very supportive of one another."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 179
#: sentence:583
msgid ""
"Friends conversant with the CIA from its earliest days confirmed the "
"collegial culture there and indicated that many who worked together stayed "
"in touch long after leaving their official employment with the Agency, "
"continuing to support each other and their interests whenever possible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 179
#: sentence:584
msgid "Apparently, one never really retires from the CIA."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 180
#: sentence:585
msgid ""
"One of his new friends at the Agency described Bill, on first meeting, as "
"very young in appearance (he was twenty-eight), bright-eyed, intelligent, "
"very enthusiastic about his interests, fun to be around, friendly and "
"gregarious, but somewhat restless, as if he had not quite found himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 180
#: sentence:586
msgid ""
"For all his outward charm, Bill was reticent about revealing himself; he did"
" not discuss his private life or how he felt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 181
#: sentence:587
msgid ""
"Despite his youthful enthusiasm, it seemed that Bill was not going to make "
"Washington and the Agency a permanent stop."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 181
#: sentence:588
msgid ""
"He spent as many weekends as possible in New York attending the theater, his"
" passion even then, and feeling very much at home in the city."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 181
#: sentence:589
msgid "Music and theater were already part of his very soul."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 181
#: sentence:590
msgid ""
"Friends remembered him wearing his tight-fitting khaki pants and boots, "
"conveying more the essence of the theatrical world than a government job."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 181
#: sentence:591
msgid ""
"One colleague said they often had lunch with a woman, Gertrude, who was also"
" especially interested in the theater; Bill was close to her although she "
"was ten years his senior."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 181
#: sentence:592
msgid ""
"With this early draw to New York and its culture, he was not finding or "
"establishing roots in Washington, D.C., despite being dedicated to his work "
"there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 182
#: sentence:593
msgid ""
"Bill preferred the company of women to the military or “macho” men who were "
"in the majority at the CIA."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 182
#: sentence:594
msgid ""
"That was understandable because by then he had recognized and accepted his "
"homosexuality, which would seem an impossible situation since homosexuals "
"were not allowed in the CIA."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 182
#: sentence:595
msgid ""
"Applicants were required to take a polygraph test that should have revealed "
"as much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 182
#: sentence:596
msgid ""
"Bill indicated many years later, however, that his familiarity with "
"biofeedback and various scientific instruments used during his time with "
"Carl Rogers and the completing of his Ph.D. taught him how to make the "
"polygraph machine read “inconclusive,” and he was hired."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 182
#: sentence:597
msgid ""
"He made certain his apartment was clear of anything that could give him "
"away, and when it was covertly checked—he had ways to determine if it was—no"
" evidence was there to find."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 183
#: sentence:598
msgid ""
"David Goodrich described him as a remarkably competent guy, very perceptive,"
" a delightful friend and companion with a great sense of humor—a trait "
"everyone in his life admired and found noteworthy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 183
#: sentence:599
msgid ""
"More than thirty years later they met again, this former colleague having "
"discovered Bill’s involvement with ACIM and now a student of it himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 183
#: sentence:600
msgid ""
"He had wondered if he would see Bill differently, as an “ascended master” of"
" some kind, but he did not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 183
#: sentence:601
msgid ""
"However, he found the same characteristics Bill had displayed in the "
"1950s—being very present, very casual, easy to relate to, and intensely "
"sincere—were still in place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 184
#: sentence:602
msgid ""
"In 2007 I met with Goodrich and again we discussed their last meeting about "
"a year before Bill’s passing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 184
#: sentence:603
msgid ""
"He pondered over why he had still seen him as a wonderful person but was not"
" struck forcefully, like so many others, by the power of his quiet presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 184
#: sentence:604
msgid ""
"The Course speaks to this issue, stating that we bring all past associations"
" with us when we observe anything, whether a person, object, or situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 184
#: sentence:605
msgid ""
"In this man’s case, he was seeing Bill again but not with a clean lens, so "
"to speak, inadvertently bringing his old perceptions of him, positive though"
" they were, to the encounter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 184
#: sentence:606
msgid ""
"ACIM exhorts us to practice viewing everything with new eyes, allowing "
"ourselves to see without the usual interpretations, judgments, biases, and "
"ever-present question, “How can I use this for my benefit?” It promises a "
"sense of well-being and peace when we view anything without our past history"
" laid on it, without the obstacle of accumulated thought."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 184
#: sentence:607
msgid ""
"People who met Bill for the first time in his later years, with no "
"expectations, were the ones who found the experience extraordinary and "
"comforting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 185
#: sentence:608
msgid ""
"Although the CIA’s promise of discovering exciting new psychological "
"processes was certainly alluring and served the purpose of relocating him to"
" Washington, D.C., the Washington School of Psychiatry (WSP) founded by Dr. "
"Harry Stack Sullivan, was the major draw and the real reason Bill agreed to "
"take the CIA position."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 185
#: sentence:609
msgid ""
"He couldn’t know in the beginning how important his association with John "
"Gittinger and the PAS would turn out to be long term, but he did know he was"
" fascinated by Sullivan’s philosophy, with its focus on interpersonal "
"relations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 185
#: sentence:610
msgid ""
"This pattern of emphasis on relationships anticipates the central role they "
"will play later on in A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 185
#: sentence:611
msgid ""
"Sullivan was also intrigued by personality development in children, another "
"interest Bill shared with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 185
#: sentence:612
msgid ""
"Incidentally, more than half the professional papers Bill published before "
"he moved to Washington focused on children."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 186
#: sentence:613
msgid ""
"Once again, that inevitable pull toward self-discovery, yearning for an "
"undefined something just out of reach, was at work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 186
#: sentence:614
msgid ""
"At the WSP he was able to study with some of the brightest lights in "
"psychology and psychiatry at the time, usually in the evening so not to "
"interfere with his work at the CIA, taking every class offered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 186
#: sentence:615
msgid ""
"The philosophy of the school was consistent with the work he had done "
"earlier with Carl Rogers and was very helpful with his work at the Agency."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 187
#: sentence:616
msgid ""
"We can also imagine he felt at home at the WSP and was likely surrounded by "
"fellow seekers, at that time mostly M.D.s but some Ph.D.s like Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 187
#: sentence:617
msgid "According to the NF profile:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 188
#: sentence:618
msgid ""
"Idealists heavily populate the social sciences, particularly the fields of "
"mental healing and personal or religious counseling—professions directed "
"toward human metamorphosis, or the unfolding of the mind and heart toward "
"greater self-understanding and spiritual peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 188
#: sentence:619
msgid ""
"NFs find great satisfaction in the mental health services, where they tend "
"to take the most humanistic of approaches, those advocating growth models of"
" counseling and psychotherapy rather than the more confronting or "
"controlling models.[30]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 189
#: sentence:620
msgid ""
"No wonder he took every class; from the profile given above, we can infer "
"that the place was swarming with fellow NFs like moths drawn to the same "
"flame."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 189
#: sentence:621
msgid ""
"His WSP experience made a lasting impression on Bill for he spoke of it "
"often, as if it were an honor to have been there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 190
#: sentence:622
msgid ""
"David Goodrich first met Bill when both were enrolled in a postdoctoral "
"certification program at the Washington School of Psychiatry. He remembered,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:623
msgid ""
"Bill and I were in a class on psychological testing and I thought I was "
"pretty good but, by golly, I had this one case and it was something, it was "
"terrific, and Bill just ran circles not only around me but everybody else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:624
msgid "It was amazing what he could come up with."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:625
msgid ""
"Subsequently, I learned that he did this on the basis of his work with John "
"Gittinger, who later funded his research up in New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:626
msgid ""
"He had developed an approach to personality assessment that was quite "
"unique."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:627
msgid ""
"The only problem was that it certainly didn’t work all the time or even "
"necessarily most of the time, but when it did, it was fantastic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:628
msgid "This was one of those times when it worked."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 191
#: sentence:629
msgid ""
"Now in fairness both to Bill and to John, though esoteric, it is an approach"
" still carried on by its followers and used very extensively by the Agency "
"around the world.[31]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 192
#: sentence:630
msgid ""
"Over the years, it became apparent to many that, in addition to his "
"excellent training and education, Bill had a specific, innate aptitude for "
"interpreting tests; psychometrics was his strong suit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 192
#: sentence:631
msgid ""
"Bill did base much of his case work on John Gittinger’s research but, of "
"course, also brought his own intuitive talent to bear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 192
#: sentence:632
msgid "Another passage from Please Understand Me, II illustrates this:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 193
#: sentence:633
msgid ""
"Idealists are naturally inductive in their thought and speech, which is to "
"say that they move quickly from part to whole, from a few particulars to "
"sweeping generalizations, from the smallest sign of something to its "
"entirety."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 193
#: sentence:634
msgid ""
"With their focus on unseen potentials, on the not visible and the not yet, "
"Idealists show an extraordinary sensitivity to hints of things, mere "
"suggestions, inklings, intimations, symbols."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 193
#: sentence:635
msgid ""
"To be sure, such inductive inferences, requiring what is called the "
"“intuitive leap,” can be astonishing to others, especially in cases of mind "
"reading and extra-sensory perception."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 193
#: sentence:636
msgid ""
"At the very least, Idealists are the best suited of all the types to read "
"between the lines, to have a sixth sense about people, and they do indeed "
"follow their hunches, heed their feelings, and insist they “just know” what "
"people are really up to or what they really mean."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 193
#: sentence:637
msgid ""
"Even with complicated issues, NFs need hear only the first words of an "
"explanation to feel they understand the subject fully, jumping from telling "
"details to larger meanings.[32]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 194
#: sentence:638
msgid ""
"A third CIA colleague referred to Bill as very congenial, well liked, and "
"conscientious in his work; he was trusted with all kinds of secrets—early "
"evidence of his ability to compartmentalize various areas of his life and "
"play his cards close to the chest."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 194
#: sentence:639
msgid ""
"He said that at one point, as Bill was assigned potential employees to "
"evaluate, the Agency apparently decided that some interviews, certainly "
"those involving foreign agents (spies), should occur somewhere other than "
"the CIA offices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 194
#: sentence:640
msgid ""
"Thus, Bill conducted some of these at a local hotel and, for a while, "
"actually lived there on the Agency’s behalf, subletting his own apartment to"
" this friend and colleague because the CIA thought it might appear strange "
"if he were at the hotel consistently in the daytime, but left no trace of "
"sleeping there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:641
msgid ""
"It’s difficult to convey just how out of character Bill’s later affiliation "
"with ACIM seemed to those who knew him as a dedicated and accomplished "
"psychologist with the Agency."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:642
msgid ""
"One woman saw the article in Psychology Today (September 1980) about the "
"Course and Bill’s involvement in it and thought it so strange because it was"
" atypical of his interests when she knew him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:643
msgid ""
"In fact, before the Course became central to his life, Bill and many of his "
"associates thought religion lacked intellectual respectability."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:644
msgid ""
"Although deeply involved with the psychological aspects of his fellow human "
"beings, Bill was not at all interested in organized religion or "
"spirituality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:645
msgid ""
"In his youth, his parents followed the Christian Science teachings, but "
"after the death of their first two children and Bill’s severe illness, they "
"lost faith in religion and never returned to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:646
msgid ""
"Thus, they never encouraged him in this area, although as noted earlier, he "
"did sing at the Chicago Lawn Congregational Church as a teenager."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 195
#: sentence:647
msgid ""
"I would guess this was motivated by his great love of music and an "
"opportunity to sing rather than by any interest in theology."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 196
#: sentence:648
msgid ""
"Bill was more traditional by today’s standards but quite on the leading edge"
" of psychology for that time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 196
#: sentence:649
msgid ""
"Goodrich spoke with John Gittinger before his death expressly to discuss "
"Bill’s role with A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 196
#: sentence:650
msgid ""
"In that conversation, he told John that Bill had mentioned his fear of "
"losing the research grants funded indirectly by Gittinger if he had learned "
"of his involvement with A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 196
#: sentence:651
msgid "John replied, “Oh, heavens, no!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 196
#: sentence:652
msgid ""
"I wondered what he was doing and would have been skeptical, but "
"tolerant.”[33] He added that, since Bill was doing such great work for him, "
"he would not in any way have withheld support."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 197
#: sentence:653
msgid ""
"The intricacies of how Bill received support from Gittinger is beyond the "
"scope of this book, but through him and his continuing covert CIA "
"connections, Bill was awarded ongoing, substantial grants to continue "
"refining the PAS."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 197
#: sentence:654
msgid ""
"Those grants followed him to Columbia University; both he and Helen Schucman"
" were conducting PAS research there, among other projects, when the Course "
"entered their lives."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 197
#: sentence:655
msgid ""
"That research continued in parallel throughout the scribing of ACIM, as Bill"
" regarded the PAS system as the most sophisticated personality test "
"available at the time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 197
#: sentence:656
msgid ""
"Of course, research on assessing personality traits and their consequent "
"behaviors extended far beyond usefulness to the CIA; it was well within the "
"civilian domain of research psychology and took place at other institutions "
"besides Columbia. (For a list of Bill’s publications related to that "
"research, please see Appendix Two.)"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 198
#: sentence:657
msgid ""
"It is important to correct and clarify some false and misleading information"
" currently on the Internet concerning Bill’s years with the CIA."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 198
#: sentence:658
msgid ""
"After Bill’s death, John Gittinger himself stressed that although Bill "
"worked tirelessly on refining the PAS, he was never involved with the "
"operational side of the CIA, including any behavior manipulation, drug "
"experiments, mind control, or anything that could possibly be considered "
"coloring outside the lines of propriety."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 198
#: sentence:659
msgid ""
"In fact, persons on the operational side were somewhat scornful of the "
"psychological approach to information gathering and preferred more dramatic "
"exploration and practices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 198
#: sentence:660
msgid ""
"Also, the paymaster in charge of sending grant-related funds to Bill, a "
"personal friend of Whit Whitson, has stated unequivocally that none of "
"Bill’s funding ever came through MKUltra, a controversial experimental "
"project."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 198
#: sentence:661
msgid ""
"Some Internet articles falsely state that Bill was funded through that "
"project."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 199
#: sentence:662
msgid ""
"Bill had seemed restless even as he began his work at the CIA, perhaps "
"realizing this was only a point along his career path but not a long-term "
"commitment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 199
#: sentence:663
msgid ""
"In 1953, after gaining experience with the Agency and having completed his "
"work at the Washington School of Psychiatry, he felt it was time to move on "
"and gave notice to that effect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 199
#: sentence:664
msgid ""
"One colleague said she believed that, although he was fascinated by "
"Gittinger’s work, Bill recognized that a great deal of it was based on "
"intuition and seemed somewhat unscientific."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 199
#: sentence:665
msgid ""
"She speculated he may have left the Agency for other institutions in order "
"to search for a hard scientific basis for the derived assessments, as that "
"type of research was not part of his primary job there—testing and "
"evaluating potential intelligence officers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 199
#: sentence:666
msgid "She was at least partly right."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 200
#: sentence:667
msgid ""
"After receiving his resignation, the Agency asked Bill to reconsider his "
"decision, and as part of an inducement package, sent him to the Middle East "
"for several months as a special consultant to the Foreign Service Institute "
"at the American University in Beirut, Lebanon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 200
#: sentence:668
msgid ""
"This assignment was topped off by several weeks of vacation in Europe and "
"the Middle East."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 200
#: sentence:669
msgid ""
"He said, in retrospect, that his Middle East trip was the most marvelous of "
"his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 200
#: sentence:670
msgid ""
"After returning, he was generously promised a range of positions with the "
"Agency, not necessarily in Washington, and felt some obligation to stay on "
"for a while."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 200
#: sentence:671
msgid ""
"He continued with the CIA until the summer of 1954, then was impelled to "
"move on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 201
#: sentence:672
msgid ""
"Since he had been drawn to New York for some years, Bill thought the next "
"obvious step was actually to apply for work there, which he did at the New "
"York Unemployment Service Psychological Placement Bureau."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 201
#: sentence:673
msgid ""
"Although he indicated he wanted to live in the city, the head of the service"
" said, “They want you in Hartford [CT]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 201
#: sentence:674
msgid ""
"That’s where you have to go, the Institute of Living.”[34] He sent Bill "
"immediately to the institute, an adjunct of the Hartford Hospital, one of "
"the first mental health centers in the country and then the largest "
"psychiatric hospital in the United States."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 201
#: sentence:675
msgid ""
"There is now reason to believe that, unknown to Bill at the time, the CIA "
"had a covert hand in steering him in that direction, and at the ripe old age"
" of thirty-one, he was hired as director of clinical psychology."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 201
#: sentence:676
msgid ""
"Although many well-known people were doing interesting things at the "
"institute, he felt it was not quite his place; it was not New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 201
#: sentence:677
msgid ""
"He did leave his imprint there, however, and according to the 1956 annual "
"report, the Division of Clinical Psychology under Bill’s direction expanded "
"its research to include “better diagnosis of organic pathology through "
"psychological tests, the use of projective techniques in predicting "
"aggressive behavior, and appraising changes resulting from "
"psychotherapy.”[35] This research was indeed a continuation of his work with"
" the PAS, and John Gittinger was involved with its funding."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 202
#: sentence:678
msgid ""
"During Bill’s short tenure at the institute, Dr. Harold Wolff, a world-"
"famous neurologist, one of the founders of psychosomatic medicine, and "
"chairman of the Neurology Department at Cornell University Medical Center in"
" New York, invited Bill to join him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 202
#: sentence:679
msgid ""
"Bill used to joke that if his qualification for employment at Michael Reese "
"Hospital had been to know nothing about the Rorschach test, his "
"qualifications for the Cornell position were singular."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 202
#: sentence:680
msgid ""
"Not only was his work in Washington germane to the Cornell program, he was "
"the only clinical psychologist around with top secret security clearance and"
" trained in neurophysiology."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 202
#: sentence:681
msgid ""
"Dr. Wolff had been offered the opportunity to do cross-cultural studies "
"funded by the CIA and he hired Bill as head of the psychological research "
"program."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 202
#: sentence:682
msgid ""
"Part of Bill’s job was to revise the PAS for use with foreign cultures, "
"particularly the Chinese."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 202
#: sentence:683
msgid ""
"In addition to his research work there, which was primary, he also became "
"first an instructor and soon thereafter an assistant professor of psychology"
" in the Department of Psychiatry."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 203
#: sentence:684
msgid ""
"Regarding his time there, Bill wrote of his “lunch time” experiences with "
"the famous and driven Dr. Wolff:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:685
msgid ""
"At first I thought he really meant for us to have lunch, but that was "
"ridiculous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:686
msgid ""
"I could never eat anything because Wolff would start interrogating me the "
"minute I sat down. “What have you learned this morning in terms of highest "
"integrative functions?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:687
msgid ""
"Are you going to change this and get our next publication out by tomorrow?” "
"He used to go on and on like that, so I would never eat lunch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:688
msgid ""
"I was used to working under high pressure, but I wasn’t used to that sort of"
" thing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:689
msgid "I did turn things out pretty fast, though, and I could type quickly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:690
msgid ""
"When he wanted something he would say, “I’m leaving in a few minutes; would "
"you please prepare an abstract for the International Biological Psychiatry "
"Congress."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:691
msgid ""
"I’ll have to have it in fifteen minutes.” I would go to my typewriter and "
"dash off what he wanted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:692
msgid ""
"I would tap into some inner source and put it into some sort of English."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 204
#: sentence:693
msgid "I learned to make it sound super scientific.[36]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 205
#: sentence:694
msgid ""
"Once again his comments reveal that Bill recognized—and trusted—his "
"intuition, or as he called it, inner source."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 205
#: sentence:695
msgid ""
"That intuition or guidance is always present for all of us, but we normally "
"pay little if any attention to it, relying instead on our intellects and "
"personal desires to direct us until that proves futile and we start honoring"
" our inner wisdom."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 205
#: sentence:696
msgid ""
"This is a particular conflict for those who pride themselves on being "
"rigorously scientific, as Bill did, but who also are very aware of “just "
"knowing.” He indicated that in his early days he acknowledged this gift and "
"took it for granted, but felt he couldn’t talk about it, fearing he would be"
" misunderstood."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:697
msgid ""
"As part of the research at Cornell, Bill worked with a number of Chinese "
"stranded in the U.S. after the Communists established the People’s Republic "
"of China in 1949."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:698
msgid "Some could not and others chose not to return."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:699
msgid ""
"While conducting research with them and their particular reactions to "
"stress, he was abruptly asked to go to China on a secret mission to escort "
"Harriet Mills on her return to the United States."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:700
msgid ""
"She was a Fulbright Scholar and Ph.D. candidate at Columbia University."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:701
msgid ""
"While doing field research there for her dissertation, Mills had come under "
"suspicion and was subsequently jailed by the Communist government."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:702
msgid ""
"The daughter of Presbyterian missionaries, Mills was born in Japan but "
"reared in China, was fluent in the language, and familiar with Chinese "
"customs—all of which had raised a red flag for them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 206
#: sentence:703
msgid ""
"After four and a half years, she was finally tried, released, and ordered to"
" leave the country."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:704
msgid ""
"This assignment, initiated indirectly from the CIA, both frightened and "
"fascinated thirty-two-year-old Bill—a real, live, James Bond-type secret "
"mission where he knew only as much as was provided at any given time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:705
msgid ""
"He was booked passage on a freighter, the last available vessel out of Hong "
"Kong, where Mills had been taken after being put on trial and expelled from "
"China."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:706
msgid ""
"Bill said in his biography, “All arrangements were made secretly and "
"undercover."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:707
msgid ""
"I was not told where I was first going, which was Manila [Philippines], "
"before proceeding to Hong Kong to board the ship.”[37] The freighter was "
"Mills’ choice of transportation after her years in a Beijing prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:708
msgid ""
"As there were only a handful of passengers, Bill and Harriet met almost "
"immediately and became friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:709
msgid ""
"She later told her sister, with whom I spoke in 2007, that after a few days "
"she realized Bill was “put on board to grill her.” She was right."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:710
msgid "He took notes on thin paper and kept them hidden in his pockets."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:711
msgid ""
"He didn’t want to leave anything lying around indiscriminately, as he didn’t"
" know who else might be on the ship watching them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:712
msgid ""
"They arrived safely in Vancouver, Canada, just before Christmas of 1955, and"
" his extensive notes were ultimately included as part of Harold Wolff’s "
"testimony before the House Committee on brainwashing in 1975."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:713
msgid ""
"According to her sister, Mills still won’t talk about what happened during "
"her confinement, so we don’t know what she may have disclosed to Bill, who "
"elicited deep trust from virtually everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 207
#: sentence:714
msgid ""
"He particularly enjoyed telling this story and was highly amused by the "
"drama of the intrigue, especially since the mission had a satisfactory "
"ending."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 208
#: sentence:715
msgid ""
"After two and a half years in the relentlessly high-pressured job at "
"Cornell, Bill was approached by an old friend from Chicago about a possible "
"appointment at Columbia University."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 208
#: sentence:716
msgid ""
"The job offered—designing a doctoral program, writing grants, and assuming "
"an assistant professorship—didn’t particularly appeal to him, but out of "
"courtesy he agreed to meet with the head of the psychiatry department."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 208
#: sentence:717
msgid ""
"Bill told him, thinking he could bring this episode to closure before it "
"began, that he might be interested if they offered him a higher professional"
" rank, which he was certain they would not consider as medical school "
"hierarchies are quite rigid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 208
#: sentence:718
msgid ""
"To his surprise, they accepted his condition, added a prestigious title, and"
" in the fall of 1957 appointed him to the faculty as an associate professor "
"of medical psychology in the College of Physicians and Surgeons at Columbia "
"University Medical School."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 208
#: sentence:719
msgid ""
"As with his clandestine trip to Hong Kong, he always laughed as he told "
"these stories, as if the way everything had turned out, the improbable "
"series of events, was all a delightful comedy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:720
msgid ""
"Although I cannot prove beyond doubt—either through interviews with key "
"players (now deceased) or through the Freedom of Information Act (I also "
"tried this route)—it seems obvious that the CIA and John Gittinger were "
"again maneuvering behind the scenes to place Bill in this important post, as"
" well as the earlier ones."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:721
msgid ""
"Jack Luckett’s conversations with Bill also supported this hypothesis; Bill "
"believed the Agency had a hand in arranging his various career "
"opportunities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:722
msgid ""
"It especially makes sense given the Agency’s propensity to develop a "
"person’s strengths, to push them along, so to speak."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:723
msgid ""
"Gittinger told Dr. Marshall Heyman, another former CIA colleague of Bill’s, "
"that Bill and later Helen were the only two “outsiders” (non-CIA "
"employees—Bill was an ex-employee and Helen never worked for the CIA, nor "
"did she know it was the source of some of their funding) at that time whom "
"he authorized to talk publicly about, hold seminars on, and generally "
"endorse the PAS and their research related to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:724
msgid ""
"Other institutions and individuals were doing PAS research, but Bill and "
"Helen became Gittinger’s surrogates of sorts, since he could not publicly "
"comment on his internal classified research."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:725
msgid ""
"In later years, Gittinger, by then head of the CIA’s psychological services "
"worldwide, visited Bill and Helen in New York and sometimes attended their "
"seminars anonymously."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 209
#: sentence:726
msgid ""
"He very much enjoyed the company of the academics there and being involved "
"with someone of Bill’s reputation and stature."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 210
#: sentence:727
msgid ""
"Although Bill was, in fact, a bit uncomfortable accepting money indirectly "
"from the CIA, his intense intellectual curiosity regarding the formation and"
" maintenance of the personality/ego and his conviction that this was "
"meaningful research tipped the scale in favor of his continuing to receive "
"funding."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 210
#: sentence:728
msgid ""
"The archivist at Columbia University, with whom I spoke in 2008, found "
"records for six of the grants listed on Bill’s curriculum vitae obtained "
"from 1961–1964, totaling $120,410."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 210
#: sentence:729
msgid "He received additional grant money but the records could not be found."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 210
#: sentence:730
msgid "Publication of PAS-related research continued until the early 1970s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 210
#: sentence:731
msgid ""
"Psychological Assessment Associates, Gittinger’s non-CIA business that "
"promoted the PAS, had a file card on record at Columbia, but there was no "
"attendant folder or paperwork related to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 211
#: sentence:732
msgid ""
"It is amusing at this point, as we see the CIA almost assuredly working "
"behind the scenes to move Bill forward in his “outer” career, to realize "
"that the Holy Spirit, to use ACIM terminology, is “using” the CIA just as "
"the CIA is “using” Bill, to place him on a collision course with Helen and "
"the consequent birth of the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 211
#: sentence:733
msgid ""
"As I write, I sense Bill’s presence, laughing at the notion that we think "
"we, at the ego level, are in charge—life is in charge!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:734
msgid ""
"In addition to the duties described to Bill when the job was offered at "
"Columbia, more were added when he arrived in February 1958."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:735
msgid ""
"Not yet thirty-five, he was additionally appointed as director of the "
"Division of Psychology at Presbyterian Hospital, an adjunct to Columbia "
"University and the largest private medical center in the country employing "
"thousands of people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:736
msgid "He was responsible for all clinical psychology practiced there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:737
msgid ""
"Attempting to bring order and cohesion to an essentially unorganized "
"department was wearing and complicated, given the disparate organizations "
"involved and the turf battles and jealousies that plague so much of "
"academia."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:738
msgid ""
"In addition, he was required to include the New York State Psychiatric "
"Institute in his attempt at administrative reorganization."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:739
msgid ""
"Ultimately, therefore, he had responsibilities at the hospital, the "
"university, and the institute, which he found incredibly complicated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 212
#: sentence:740
msgid ""
"And the majority of his work history was in research and writing, not "
"administration, so the challenges were immense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 213
#: sentence:741
msgid "We had 475 faculty members in the Department of Psychiatry alone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 213
#: sentence:742
msgid ""
"Now, most of them were part-time and in affiliated hospitals and things of "
"that kind, but it was an enormous complex maze."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 213
#: sentence:743
msgid ""
"I also found out that there was divided authority and responsibility, and "
"you had to report to the president of the hospital as well as the chairman "
"of the department, but there was a vice president in charge of professional "
"affairs that you really had to see first, but you couldn’t see him unless "
"you check through the business manager, and there were three business "
"managers because there were three institutions that were part of this—not "
"only the university but the Presbyterian Hospital and the New York "
"Psychiatric Institute, which were all part of this complex."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 214
#: sentence:744
msgid ""
"There were power struggles going on and people seemed quite happy to injure "
"their colleague’s reputation or career if they could get another office."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 214
#: sentence:745
msgid "And to get a secretary, oh that was fantastic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 214
#: sentence:746
msgid "You’d do anything—kill your grandmother, I guess."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 214
#: sentence:747
msgid ""
"It was the most competitive and power-driven setting that I had ever been "
"in, although I had seen a few.[38]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 215
#: sentence:748
msgid "Chapter 4"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 216
#: sentence:749
msgid ""
"Up to this point, the events, training, and circumstances in Bill’s life had"
" conspired to develop his many innate skills and to acquire general life "
"experience. Now the plot thickens."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 216
#: sentence:750
msgid ""
"Shortly after his appointment to Columbia, Bill was asked to hire a "
"psychologist with skills in creating instruments to test infants and young "
"children; the position would fulfill the requirements of a grant offered to "
"the university."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 216
#: sentence:751
msgid ""
"Although he was certainly knowledgeable in the general field of tests and "
"measurements and had a great deal of experience working with children, he "
"had not designed tests for them and needed a specialist in this area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 216
#: sentence:752
msgid ""
"He checked with a colleague, well known in the field, who promised to help "
"if he could."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 216
#: sentence:753
msgid ""
"Shortly thereafter, Bill received a phone call from a woman who introduced "
"herself thus: “My name is Dr. Helen Schucman."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 216
#: sentence:754
msgid "I was told to tell you that I am the person you are looking for.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 217
#: sentence:755
msgid ""
"Of course, she was the person Bill was looking for in more ways than one, "
"and he hired her, but not for a job she particularly liked."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 217
#: sentence:756
msgid ""
"Bill’s colleague, also a friend of Helen’s, had called her on hearing Bill’s"
" request and told her to forget looking anywhere else and to call Dr. "
"Thetford immediately."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 217
#: sentence:757
msgid ""
"On hearing his emphatic tone, Helen decided to forego her other options and "
"called Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 218
#: sentence:758
msgid ""
"I did not particularly want to work in a medical setting, and the little my "
"friend had told me about the job was not very appealing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 218
#: sentence:759
msgid ""
"Nevertheless, in view of his sense of urgency, I did make Dr. Thetford my "
"first call."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 218
#: sentence:760
msgid ""
"When I walked into his office a few days later, I made the first of a series"
" of silent remarks, which I did not understand myself. “And there he is,” I "
"said to myself. “He’s the one I’m supposed to help.”[39]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 219
#: sentence:761
msgid ""
"After Helen and Bill had become better acquainted, a second odd moment of "
"recollection occurred:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 220
#: sentence:762
msgid ""
"For a brief interval, I seemed to be somewhere else, saying as if in answer "
"to a silent but urgent call. “Of course, I’ll go, Father."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 220
#: sentence:763
msgid "He’s stuck and needs help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 220
#: sentence:764
msgid ""
"Besides, it will be only for such a little while!” The situation had "
"something of the quality of a long-forgotten memory, and I was somehow aware"
" of being in a very happy place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 220
#: sentence:765
msgid ""
"I had no idea to whom I was speaking, but I was sure that I was making some "
"sort of definite commitment that I would not break."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 220
#: sentence:766
msgid ""
"Nevertheless, the actual remark I made meant as little to me as did the "
"previous one in Bill’s office at the time of our first meeting.[40]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 221
#: sentence:767
msgid ""
"Over the next few years, Helen worked in a research position, only later "
"shifting into more teaching, training, and clinical work, for which she had "
"a natural aptitude."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 221
#: sentence:768
msgid ""
"In fact, years later, many who knew her personally described in glowing "
"terms just how talented she was when working with clients, how kind, "
"thoughtful, and loving she could be, and how quickly she could assess a "
"person’s actual situation and offer the most appropriate guidance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 221
#: sentence:769
msgid ""
"Bill found her psychodynamic insights profound, and ultimately, promoted her"
" to the position of chief psychologist at the Neurological Institute within "
"the medical center, making her his assistant, which allowed them to spend "
"more time together and, of course, to prepare for what neither knew was "
"about to unfold."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 222
#: sentence:770
msgid ""
"Bill later described his circumstances at Columbia at the time as absolutely"
" frightful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 222
#: sentence:771
msgid ""
"Co-workers were suspicious and hostile, the atmosphere was chaotic, and the "
"workload overwhelming."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 222
#: sentence:772
msgid ""
"He divided his time among administrative duties, teaching, conducting "
"research, writing research grants, editing journals, and publishing—moving "
"through a mountain of work without any sustained sense of satisfaction or "
"well-being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 222
#: sentence:773
msgid ""
"In retrospect, colleagues at the time noted that Bill produced a prodigious "
"amount of “regular” work, all expertly handled, while his secret life with "
"the Course was ongoing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 222
#: sentence:774
msgid ""
"For one thing, Bill could multitask in a very unusual way; he could, for "
"instance, type the notes for one research project while discussing the "
"details of something entirely unrelated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 222
#: sentence:775
msgid ""
"To many this was disconcerting, as if he were not paying attention to them, "
"but it was, instead, evidence of Bill’s peculiar ability to "
"compartmentalize, the trait that routinely appeared in other areas of his "
"life as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 223
#: sentence:776
msgid ""
"With Helen, some of their work together proceeded purposefully and "
"effectively, but in other areas they had a terrible time getting along."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 223
#: sentence:777
msgid ""
"Even though they had major personality differences and each handled their "
"upsets differently, it never occurred to either to stop working together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 223
#: sentence:778
msgid ""
"Both felt an unexplained compulsion to be there together, and they very much"
" wanted to work out their difficulties, but they seemed to have no idea how "
"to do that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 223
#: sentence:779
msgid "Helen wrote of their early years together:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:780
msgid ""
"When I reached the hospital about a year afterward [after Bill arrived at "
"Columbia] there was little doubt that Bill did need help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:781
msgid "He looked haggard and badly needed someone to talk to."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:782
msgid ""
"Gradually, he told me about the many problems with which he had been "
"confronted since coming to the hospital."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:783
msgid "There had been no real psychology department before he arrived."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:784
msgid ""
"A number of psychologists were working independently throughout the "
"hospital, some of whom had never even met."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:785
msgid ""
"In fact, a major though not previously specified part of Bill’s job had been"
" to organize and administer a cohesive departmental unit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:786
msgid "It was a hard assignment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:787
msgid ""
"When I arrived the newly established department was split into factions, and"
" beset by political rivalries and bitter resentments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:788
msgid ""
"Besides the obvious hostilities there was also a curious apathy toward the "
"department."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:789
msgid "Bill seemed to be the only person there who really cared about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:790
msgid ""
"As he told me one day, “I would do anything for the department,” and it was "
"evident that he meant it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:791
msgid ""
"That was the first note of real devotion I had heard since I came, and it "
"called forth an immediate response."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 224
#: sentence:792
msgid ""
"Bill and I entered into an agreement to work out the departmental problems "
"together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 225
#: sentence:793
msgid ""
"Our attempts were heart-breaking at first, although neither of us seriously "
"thought of withdrawing our commitment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 225
#: sentence:794
msgid ""
"My initial efforts were spent in frantically writing up grant proposals "
"against dead-lines, in a desperate attempt to bring in badly-needed funds."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 225
#: sentence:795
msgid "It was exhausting work for both Bill and me, and a dead end as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 225
#: sentence:796
msgid ""
"We were given encouragement and promises of support, but nothing actually "
"materialized."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 225
#: sentence:797
msgid ""
"Besides repeated discouragements of this kind, there was another source of "
"strain which we both found even more difficult to handle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 225
#: sentence:798
msgid ""
"Bill and I were an unlikely team, and in spite of our shared goal, we grated"
" on each other’s already jangled nerves a good part of the time.[41]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:799
msgid ""
"Despite their considerable challenges, for the several years before the "
"Course began, they worked together very closely, having lunch together every"
" day and, among other things, sharing their fascination for personality "
"theory."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:800
msgid "Bill was always interested in the entire topic of personal identity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:801
msgid ""
"At some point, he had brought Helen into the ongoing PAS research, to which "
"she made many valuable contributions, and they jointly published many papers"
" on their continuing refinements to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:802
msgid ""
"Both considered experts in their field, they were often called in jointly to"
" consult on “high-powered private patients” at Columbia; other psychological"
" associations in New York City also invited them to share their expertise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:803
msgid ""
"Dorothy Ulmann, a colleague at Cornell University in New York City, "
"remembered, “Once in a while I’d go up there [Columbia] with Helen and Bill "
"and their colleagues."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:804
msgid ""
"I remember there were all these big-shot psychologists and psychiatrists, "
"who were frequently mentioned in the New York Times’ columns. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 226
#: sentence:805
msgid "But these were Helen and Bill’s colleagues at lunch.”[42]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:806
msgid ""
"Obviously, from Bill’s recounting of what the university was like in general"
" and his relationships with Helen and others in particular, he was "
"projecting his own “shadow side,” his long-held fears and grievances, into "
"his situation there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:807
msgid ""
"Every beginning ACIM student learns that the subjective experience of one’s "
"outer circumstances faithfully reflects an inner state of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:808
msgid ""
"Stated more bluntly, the more guilt one carries, even though unconsciously, "
"the more one feels punished by outer conditions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:809
msgid ""
"Bill certainly contributed to the problems in his environment as he "
"projected his own judgments, fears, unconscious conditioning, and unexamined"
" assumptions about how life should be into the situation, as do we all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:810
msgid ""
"He knew about projection theoretically—the process of seeing in others what "
"we fear to own in ourselves—but clearly knew little about dealing with that "
"process personally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:811
msgid ""
"Despite his talents, training, and potential, he was as sound asleep as the "
"rest of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:812
msgid ""
"Early in ACIM’s text, one finds, “Yet the Bible says that a deep sleep fell "
"upon Adam, and nowhere is there reference to his waking up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:813
msgid ""
"The world has not yet experienced any comprehensive reawakening or rebirth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 227
#: sentence:814
msgid ""
"Such a rebirth is impossible as long as you continue to project or mis-"
"create.”[43] After the Course arrived and Bill became more familiar with its"
" uncompromising tenets on how we cause our own distress, he ultimately "
"became willing to begin changing his mind, and that willingness led to "
"success—to his actual waking up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 228
#: sentence:815
msgid ""
"Regarding their relationship, on one hand Bill felt Helen was genuinely, and"
" perhaps uniquely, interested in furthering his academic career and, on the "
"other, Helen desperately wanted Bill to play out her romantic fantasies "
"about him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 228
#: sentence:816
msgid ""
"Her childhood had been singularly barren in terms of affection and warmth "
"from her family, and as the Course points out, we try to find in our current"
" relationships what was missing in former ones, to require of present "
"companions what past ones seemed to withhold."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 229
#: sentence:817
msgid "I also played multiple roles for Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 229
#: sentence:818
msgid ""
"I was her boss, her fantasy love object, her savior in terms of this "
"material, and I was expected to do everything that had to be done at all "
"times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 229
#: sentence:819
msgid "I was a substitute for her husband, her brother, and her father."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 229
#: sentence:820
msgid ""
"I was supposed to make up for her feelings about her father, and what he "
"didn’t do in her life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 229
#: sentence:821
msgid "I don’t know why I accepted this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 229
#: sentence:822
msgid "It was a very complicated relationship.[44]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 230
#: sentence:823
msgid ""
"If he played multiple roles for her, he was also expecting something from "
"her in return."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 230
#: sentence:824
msgid ""
"No one can be disappointed with someone unless roles have first been "
"appointed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 230
#: sentence:825
msgid ""
"He, too, had dysfunction in his family with a critical father and an over-"
"protective mother and couldn’t help but search for acknowledgment not "
"received earlier."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 230
#: sentence:826
msgid "We endure a great deal in search of validation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 231
#: sentence:827
msgid ""
"Bill’s comment in the video, The Story of A Course In Miracles, that “Helen "
"felt a closer personal relationship with me than I felt I could "
"reciprocate,” was a massive understatement.[45] Helen wanted to possess Bill"
" and did everything she could to be involved in and to control all areas of "
"his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 232
#: sentence:828
msgid ""
"As an example, Judith Skutch Whitson, who later entered the Course’s "
"chronology, commented that after ACIM was scribed and she had become one of "
"the principal players, Bill, Helen, and Kenneth Wapnick, also yet to be "
"introduced in this narrative, often met at the Skutch home in the late "
"afternoons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 232
#: sentence:829
msgid ""
"Helen and Ken would leave and Bill often stayed for dinner, enjoying some "
"lighthearted time with the Skutches."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 232
#: sentence:830
msgid ""
"Helen would call later, upset because he was still there, and insist he "
"finish his dinner and leave."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 233
#: sentence:831
msgid ""
"A more bizarre example of her possessiveness involves Bill’s social life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 233
#: sentence:832
msgid "His most private life was with his male friends, and it was private."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 233
#: sentence:833
msgid ""
"Charles Lehman, who was Bill’s partner for three years from 1954–1957, "
"comments on his uncompromising secrecy:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 234
#: sentence:834
msgid ""
"Perhaps one difference between Bill and me was on the business of being gay."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 234
#: sentence:835
msgid "Bill was very reluctant to come out publicly as being gay."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 234
#: sentence:836
msgid ""
"I can understand that because up until the early 1970s, the American "
"Psychiatric Association was really defining gay people as psychoneurotic or "
"as having character disorders, like being sociopaths."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 234
#: sentence:837
msgid ""
"And being so directly involved in that field, I can understand that he would"
" want to stay in the closet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 234
#: sentence:838
msgid ""
"Even after he moved to California, I think he had perhaps an underlying "
"feeling that if he came out publicly, it might somehow impair his "
"credibility and the credibility of A Course In Miracles.[46]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 235
#: sentence:839
msgid ""
"I have not included more specific information about Bill’s gay life because "
"none is available."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 235
#: sentence:840
msgid ""
"His two major partners from the New York era are both deceased and no one I "
"interviewed knows about any others or how to contact them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 235
#: sentence:841
msgid ""
"I also have no way to determine who he may have known in his last years in "
"La Jolla, although there is a consensus that he had twelve or fifteen good "
"friends within that community."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 235
#: sentence:842
msgid ""
"He lived alone there except for the time he shared a home with the Lucketts."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 235
#: sentence:843
msgid ""
"Many persons I spoke with said he never commented on his private life, so "
"that aspect of Bill’s history, however important it was to him, remains a "
"closed book."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 236
#: sentence:844
msgid "Fire Island July 1959"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:845
msgid "Nonetheless, Helen wanted to be involved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:846
msgid ""
"At one point, Bill and a number of his close friends rented a house for "
"weekend use on Fire Island, an area known for its gay community."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:847
msgid ""
"Helen insisted they rent a place with a room for her and her husband Louis "
"as well, which they did; thus, on many occasions the improbable combination "
"of Helen, Louis, Bill, and various friends of his shared a house."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:848
msgid ""
"During part of those New York years, Bill and another friend owned a small "
"house in Watermill on Long Island, and Helen actually paid for a room and "
"bath to be added to the house for her and her husband."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:849
msgid ""
"She insisted on being included in all aspects of his life, inside the "
"university and out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:850
msgid "Everyone noticed this infringement on Bill’s time and space."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:851
msgid ""
"Cal Hatcher, an administrator at the hospital and a good friend of Bill’s, "
"commented, “I think sometimes I’d go out of my skin if I were Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:852
msgid ""
"This was because Helen would call him up anytime, day or night.”[47] Ken "
"Wapnick later confirmed that to call Helen possessive was definitely the "
"mildest of understatements."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:853
msgid ""
"And to thoroughly confound everyone, Helen was genuinely devoted to her "
"husband despite her obsession with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 237
#: sentence:854
msgid ""
"Bill’s friends also commented that even if he had been “in love” with Helen,"
" he would never have acted on it because he was so ethical he would not have"
" strayed into an illicit relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 238
#: sentence:855
msgid ""
"A selection from the Course text entitled “Shadows of the Past” says it all "
"about the drama in Helen’s and Bill’s lives and the reason anyone is drawn "
"into ego-based relationships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 238
#: sentence:856
msgid ""
"The “shadows” in this excerpt refer to what we project onto, and then see in"
" one another, when we look through the ego’s unloving perspective."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 239
#: sentence:857
msgid ""
"They [shadow figures] offer you the “reasons” why you should enter into "
"unholy alliances to support the ego’s goals, and make your relationships the"
" witness to its power."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 240
#: sentence:858
msgid ""
"It is these shadow figures that would make the ego holy in your sight, and "
"teach you what you do to keep it safe is really love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 240
#: sentence:859
msgid ""
"The shadow figures always speak for vengeance, and all relationships into "
"which they enter are totally insane."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 240
#: sentence:860
msgid ""
"Without exception, these relationships have as their purpose the exclusion "
"of the truth about the other, and of yourself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 240
#: sentence:861
msgid ""
"This is why you see in both what is not there, and make of both the slaves "
"of vengeance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 240
#: sentence:862
msgid ""
"And why whatever reminds you of your past grievances attracts you, and seems"
" to go by the name of love, no matter how distorted the associations by "
"which you arrive at the connection may be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 240
#: sentence:863
msgid ""
"And finally, why all such relationships become attempts at union through the"
" body, for only bodies can be seen as means for vengeance.[48]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 241
#: sentence:864
msgid ""
"Years after Helen and Bill began working together, another of the men who "
"provided their research grants, the lifeblood of academia, visited them in "
"New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 241
#: sentence:865
msgid ""
"He sized up the situation after being with them a while and rather "
"indelicately commented that Helen had the “hots” for Bill even though she "
"knew he was gay, a term not used at that time, and was “mad as hell” about "
"his lack of cooperation in her romantic fantasies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:866
msgid ""
"How could their relationship be anything but tortuous under these extreme "
"circumstances, with both “mad as hell”?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:867
msgid "The early 1960s were a really low point for Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:868
msgid ""
"His parents had passed away in the mid 1950s, and he was alone in the world "
"so far as family was concerned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:869
msgid ""
"As pressure mounted, related to various facets of his work—seemingly always "
"in crisis mode—and the continual turmoil with Helen, Bill finally reached "
"his limit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:870
msgid ""
"He had not yet realized we bring this seemingly “loveless” condition on "
"ourselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:871
msgid ""
"He felt surrounded by hostility and paranoia and was disappointed and "
"unhappy despite his fame and prestige."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:872
msgid "He had mastered his field, and yet something was still missing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 242
#: sentence:873
msgid ""
"It can be shattering to work so diligently and for so long toward your goal,"
" bringing everything one has to bear and finally achieving it, only to find "
"happiness and fulfillment are still absent."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 243
#: sentence:874
msgid ""
"The ego is certain that love is dangerous, and this is always its central "
"teaching."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 243
#: sentence:875
msgid ""
"It never puts it this way; on the contrary, everyone who believes that the "
"ego is salvation seems to be intensely engaged in the search for love [or "
"recognition, value, etc.]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 243
#: sentence:876
msgid ""
"Yet the ego, though encouraging the search for love very actively, makes one"
" proviso; do not find it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 243
#: sentence:877
msgid ""
"Its dictates, then, can be summed up simply as: “Seek and do not find.” This"
" is the one promise the ego holds out to you, and the one promise it will "
"keep."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 243
#: sentence:878
msgid ""
"For the ego pursues its goal with fanatic insistence, and its judgment, "
"though severely impaired, is completely consistent.[49]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 244
#: sentence:879
msgid "A real spiritual crisis was in the making."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 244
#: sentence:880
msgid ""
"Bill was afflicted with the “divine discontent” all of us experience sooner "
"or later."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 244
#: sentence:881
msgid ""
"This world simply is not satisfying no matter how much we may be getting our"
" way, and the insistence that it be inherently meaningful drives us insane."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 244
#: sentence:882
msgid ""
"As the Course says, “Tolerance for pain may be high, but it is not without "
"limit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 244
#: sentence:883
msgid ""
"Eventually everyone begins to recognize, however dimly, that there must be a"
" better way.”[50] Bill’s elegant comprehension of how we form and maintain "
"egos was not serving him here and could not relieve him of his pain—a great "
"example of seeking to find satisfaction “out there” rather than through "
"means that actually do bring peace. Helen’s observations corroborate Bill’s:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 245
#: sentence:884
msgid ""
"Along the way, Bill and I had become consultants to a research project at a "
"nearby medical center, where we spent an hour a week. We hated it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 245
#: sentence:885
msgid ""
"The various disciplines working on the project quarreled constantly and "
"became increasingly angry and competitive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 245
#: sentence:886
msgid ""
"Our weekly meetings there were hardly a relief from our own all-too-similar "
"professional setting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 245
#: sentence:887
msgid "Meanwhile the relationship between Bill and me deteriorated steadily."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 245
#: sentence:888
msgid ""
"While we had grown interdependent, we had also developed considerable anger "
"towards each other, and our genuine attempts to cooperate were offset by our"
" growing resentments.[51]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 246
#: sentence:889
msgid "Bill was now forty-two, the well-known “midlife crisis” time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 246
#: sentence:890
msgid "He was in such pain, something had to give."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 246
#: sentence:891
msgid ""
"He was at a breaking point and in June 1965, just before yet another power "
"struggle-type meeting, poured out his heart in his now famous declaration, "
"“There must be a better way and I’m determined to find it.” Helen remembers "
"the specifics of that conversation:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:892
msgid ""
"Bill proposed, quite specifically, to try out a new approach that day at the"
" research meeting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:893
msgid "He was not going to get angry and he was not going to attack."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:894
msgid ""
"He was going to look for a constructive side in what the people there said "
"and did, and was not going to focus on mistakes and point up errors."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:895
msgid "He was going to cooperate rather than compete."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:896
msgid "It was time to take a new direction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:897
msgid "We had obviously been headed the wrong way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:898
msgid ""
"It was a long speech for Bill, and he spoke with unaccustomed emphasis as he"
" delivered it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:899
msgid "When it was over he waited for my response in obvious discomfort."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:900
msgid "Whatever reaction he may have expected, it was not the one he got."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 247
#: sentence:901
msgid ""
"I jumped up, told Bill with genuine conviction that he was right, and said I"
" would try the new approach with him.[52]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 248
#: sentence:902
msgid ""
"Thus Helen, impressed and moved by his passion, agreed and their joint "
"venture began."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 248
#: sentence:903
msgid ""
"Bill always emphasized how touching and amazing he found her response—her "
"promise to help—as it was so out of character under the circumstances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 248
#: sentence:904
msgid ""
"This interaction between Bill and Helen, this sincere and urgent heartfelt "
"request for relief from pain, signaled the time for ACIM’s arrival into the "
"world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 248
#: sentence:905
msgid "The scribes were ready to listen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 249
#: sentence:906
msgid ""
"Neither Bill nor Helen thought they had been very successful at that fateful"
" June meeting, the anticipation of which had brought on Bill’s determination"
" to try a different way, but it was their beginning. Helen remembered:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:907
msgid "Many unexpected things have happened since."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:908
msgid ""
"At the factual level, the whole climate of the department gradually changed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:909
msgid ""
"Bill worked particularly hard on the departmental problems, determined to "
"turn hostilities into friendships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:910
msgid ""
"This took considerable effort on his part at first, but he did succeed "
"eventually."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:911
msgid "Tensions lessened and antagonisms dropped away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:912
msgid ""
"The wrong people left, though on friendly terms, and the right ones came "
"along almost immediately."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:913
msgid "A secure and interesting position opened up for me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:914
msgid ""
"Although our efforts were inconsistent and often half-hearted, there is "
"little doubt that they showed results."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 250
#: sentence:915
msgid "The department became smooth-functioning, relaxed, and efficient.[53]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 251
#: sentence:916
msgid ""
"Both also felt they needed to work on mending rifts in their respective "
"social lives as well, and both were happy with those results, although their"
" personal relationship still suffered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 251
#: sentence:917
msgid ""
"Helen had the vague sense that these reparative steps in healing assorted "
"relationships were part of a mandatory preparation for something, but what "
"that was remained unknown."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 252
#: sentence:918
msgid "Chapter 5"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:919
msgid ""
"As another sign that shifts in consciousness were occurring, almost "
"immediately after Bill’s crisis in the spring of 1965, Helen began having "
"waking visions and strange dreams; she acutely feared losing her vision and,"
" indeed, her mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:920
msgid ""
"Those dreams and waking visions, in retrospect, pointed to the coming of "
"ACIM, but at the time seemed obscure and unintelligible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:921
msgid ""
"For instance, one vision involved Helen’s seeing herself in a small boat "
"being carried along a lovely canal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:922
msgid ""
"She mused about the possibility of buried treasure in the area and noticed a"
" long pole with a hook in the bottom of the boat."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:923
msgid ""
"She dropped the hook into the water and pulled up an ancient treasure chest;"
" on opening it, she was disappointed to find nothing but a large black book,"
" specifically a black thesis binder, exactly like those that would be used "
"years later to store the typed notes of A Course In Miracles for "
"safekeeping."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:924
msgid "Down the spine was written one word in gold, Aesculapius."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:925
msgid ""
"Neither Bill nor Helen knew what it meant, although it had a familiar ring "
"to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:926
msgid ""
"A few nights later, she dreamed of that black book again, now with pearls "
"draped around it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:927
msgid ""
"Aesculapius was the Greek god of healing and historians believe the legends "
"surrounding his medical work were based on the life of an historical person."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:928
msgid ""
"A well-known physician of the second century, Galen, did much research at "
"the Aesculapion in Pergamon, Turkey (then part of the Roman Empire), and "
"embodied the Aesculapion traditions for treating not just the physically but"
" the mentally ill, as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 253
#: sentence:929
msgid ""
"Helen’s dream surely was an accurate premonition of the healing treasure to "
"come."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 254
#: sentence:930
msgid ""
"Other visions involved Helen’s experiences as a priestess in many times and "
"places, and they almost always included Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 254
#: sentence:931
msgid ""
"Sometimes the two were married, sometimes they collaborated in healing work,"
" and sometimes they were deadly enemies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 254
#: sentence:932
msgid ""
"Often the visions had a profound emotional impact, eliciting either sublime "
"joy or abject terror."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 254
#: sentence:933
msgid ""
"In one major vision, she was ready to kill him with a spear poised between "
"his eyes over the theft of a ruby from her priestess crown."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 254
#: sentence:934
msgid "She backed off at the last moment and died shortly thereafter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 254
#: sentence:935
msgid ""
"Helen’s response to telling Bill about this particular vision gives some "
"clue about her ongoing intense anger toward him:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:936
msgid ""
"The emotional effect of this last episode was intense and long-lasting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:937
msgid ""
"I still felt the anger after the images faded, and it later blazed into open"
" fury as I told Bill the story the next day, particularly when I spoke of "
"the theft of the ruby."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:938
msgid "It is as if it were happening all over again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:939
msgid ""
"A picture of the ruby, beautiful and blazing red, rose before my eyes and "
"for a brief period the scene became reality for me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:940
msgid ""
"Again I berated myself for dying for a rebellious slave who was nothing but "
"a common thief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:941
msgid ""
"I could barely contain my fury at Bill, who was understandably upset. So was"
" I."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:942
msgid "The intensity of my anger was quite surprising to both of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:943
msgid "It was a while before the next episodes in the series appeared."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:944
msgid "It was almost as though I had to recover a little before going on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 255
#: sentence:945
msgid ""
"Fortunately, the next installment was different, although it, too, did not "
"turn out too well for me.[54]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 256
#: sentence:946
msgid ""
"Speaking of Helens’s temper, her anger wasn’t directly solely at Bill but at"
" anyone who threatened her ego."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 256
#: sentence:947
msgid ""
"ACIM asserts that anger is a response to feeling powerless and Tammy Cohen’s"
" (Judith Skutch Whitson’s daughter) commentary reveals something of Helen’s "
"split mind, apparently known to all who knew her:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 257
#: sentence:948
msgid ""
"My mother catered to Helen’s every whim and it didn’t take too long for me "
"to realize that everyone else did as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 257
#: sentence:949
msgid ""
"Helen had a presence about her which demanded attention and care-taking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 257
#: sentence:950
msgid ""
"Yet I noticed that on the one hand she played the frail, fragile little old "
"lady to get her way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 257
#: sentence:951
msgid ""
"But on the other, when she wasn’t getting what she wanted, her presence grew"
" to the size of a Sumo wrestler."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 257
#: sentence:952
msgid ""
"With merely a glance or a quick slice from her sharp tongue, she could make "
"the largest of men shrink to the size of a pea."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 257
#: sentence:953
msgid ""
"As soon as she got what she wanted, though, she instantly returned to her "
"proper lady-like persona, like a genie returns to its lamp after a wish is "
"fulfilled.[55]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 258
#: sentence:954
msgid ""
"During midsummer, another particularly meaningful vision occurred at the "
"conclusion of what Helen termed the second (out of three) series of visions,"
" this time with a more positive outcome:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:955
msgid "The series ended on a note of final achievement and even glory."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:956
msgid ""
"I was standing in a room that seemed to be on the top floor of a church "
"building."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:957
msgid ""
"Bill, seated at a large, old-fashioned church organ, was playing Handel’s "
"Hallelujah Chorus with his face lit with joy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:958
msgid "We had finally reached our goal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:959
msgid ""
"I was standing in front of a simple brown wooden altar, on which two words "
"were written one underneath the other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:960
msgid "I cannot imagine a less appropriate pair."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:961
msgid ""
"The top word was “Elohim,” which I did not recognize at the time, and only "
"later discovered is one of the Hebrew names for God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:962
msgid ""
"The other word, “Evoe,” I did identify as the cry of the Greek Bacchantes [a"
" priestess or female votary of Bacchus; a female participant in a drunken or"
" orgiastic revel] in celebrating the rites of Bacchus [the god of grape-"
"growing and of wine]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:963
msgid ""
"As I watched, a streak of lightning from the back of the church struck the "
"altar and obliterated the second word entirely."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:964
msgid "Only “Elohim” remained, written in bright gold letters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:965
msgid ""
"The Hallelujah Chorus rose to a crescendo, and a figure outlined in "
"brilliant light which I recognized immediately as Jesus stepped from behind "
"the altar and came toward me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:966
msgid ""
"I started to kneel in front of him, but he came around to my side and knelt "
"at the altar with me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:967
msgid "Bill rose and knelt at his other side."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 259
#: sentence:968
msgid ""
"And then a Voice, with which I was to become increasingly familiar, said in "
"silent but perfectly clear words, “That altar is within you.” The emotional "
"impact of the conclusion was so powerful that I burst into tears.[56]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 260
#: sentence:969
msgid ""
"Helen kept a running account of those episodes and shared them with Bill, "
"who was extremely interested in all aspects of her unusual experiences."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 260
#: sentence:970
msgid ""
"He had recently discovered the famous “sleeping prophet,” Edgar Cayce, and "
"was becoming increasingly intrigued with his work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 260
#: sentence:971
msgid ""
"He urged Helen to read some of his books, but she found them disturbing even"
" though she tried to keep an open mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 260
#: sentence:972
msgid ""
"Her visions and waking dreams were followed by a growing capacity for other "
"types of psychic phenomena—remote viewing, and sending and receiving "
"messages at a distance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 260
#: sentence:973
msgid ""
"She was both fascinated and worried about her “magic phase,” as she called "
"it, which abruptly concluded with an episode that verified she had made a "
"clear and irrevocable choice:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 261
#: sentence:974
msgid ""
"I saw myself entering a cave cut into a rock formation on a bleak, wind-"
"swept seacoast."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 261
#: sentence:975
msgid "All I found in the cave was a large and very old parchment scroll."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 261
#: sentence:976
msgid ""
"Its ends were attached to heavy gold-tipped poles, and the scroll was "
"wrapped around them so that they met in the middle of the scroll and were "
"tied tightly together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 261
#: sentence:977
msgid ""
"With some difficulty I managed to untie the ends and open the scroll just "
"enough to reveal the center panel, on which two words were written: “God "
"is.” Then I unrolled the scroll all the way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 261
#: sentence:978
msgid "As I did so, tiny letters began to appear on both sides of the panel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 261
#: sentence:979
msgid ""
"The silent Voice, which I had “heard” before explained the situation "
"mentally to me:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 262
#: sentence:980
msgid ""
"“If you look at the left side you will be able to read the past.” said the "
"Voice. “If you look at the right side you will be able to read the future.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 263
#: sentence:981
msgid ""
"The little letters on the sides of the panel were becoming clearer, but I "
"hesitated only a moment before rolling up the scroll sufficiently to conceal"
" everything except the center panel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 264
#: sentence:982
msgid ""
"“I’m not interested in reading the past or the future,” I said with "
"finality. “I’ll just stop with this.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 265
#: sentence:983
msgid "The Voice sounded both reassured and reassuring."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 266
#: sentence:984
msgid "“You made it that time,” it said. “Thank you.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 267
#: sentence:985
msgid "And that, it seemed, was that.[57]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 268
#: sentence:986
msgid ""
"As they moved through the summer, both Helen’s psychic capacity and Bill’s "
"interest in the entire subject expanded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 268
#: sentence:987
msgid ""
"She told him she had a growing sense that something unexpected and unusual "
"was about to take place and had written him a letter during that time "
"stating, “Dear Bill, I’m not sure I want to write this, but I have an idea "
"I’m obeying an order."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 268
#: sentence:988
msgid ""
"These orders are rather stern and the main feeling I get is that I wouldn’t "
"dare disobey them.”[58] He urged her to keep a notebook with her at all "
"times so that if the “something unexpected” occurred, she could immediately "
"write about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 269
#: sentence:989
msgid ""
"As a parenthetical note, in the early 1960s, before the Course transmission "
"began, Bill was appointed to a space-planning committee for a new research "
"building for the Department of Psychiatry."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 269
#: sentence:990
msgid ""
"In that capacity, he was able to create two very private, secluded offices "
"for himself and Helen in one wing of the new building, with their own "
"private entrance; even their secretaries were quartered in a building across"
" the street."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 269
#: sentence:991
msgid ""
"Bill said he felt strongly at the time that there was a purpose for having a"
" secluded space, but he had no idea what that might be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 269
#: sentence:992
msgid ""
"The new research building was completed in the fall of 1965, and shortly "
"after settling in, the “something unexpected” began."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 270
#: sentence:993
msgid "00040.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 271
#: sentence:994
msgid ""
"One October evening, as Helen was writing some notes to herself, the Voice, "
"by now familiar to her, said, “This is a course in miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 271
#: sentence:995
msgid ""
"Please take notes.” Very frightened, she called Bill who asked if it was the"
" same familiar Voice; she replied that it was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 271
#: sentence:996
msgid ""
"After a short exchange, they agreed she would take the notes but not read "
"them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 271
#: sentence:997
msgid ""
"She would bring them to work the next morning, and if they were nonsense, "
"they could throw them away and no one would know."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 271
#: sentence:998
msgid ""
"The first notes she received were the introduction to the text, and both "
"were understandably stunned on reading it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 272
#: sentence:999
msgid ""
"The abbreviated version of ACIM’s genesis is that over a seven-year period "
"beginning in October 1965, Helen received an inner “dictation,” as it seemed"
" to her, which she wrote down in shorthand. (She was exceptionally fast at "
"shorthand, having devised her own hybrid method.) She could feel the writing"
" coming on, usually several times a day, but it never conflicted with work "
"or social activities. She recalled:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1000
msgid "The writing was highly interruptible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1001
msgid ""
"At the office I could lay the notebook down to answer the telephone, talk to"
" a patient, supervise a junior staff member, or attend to one of our "
"numerous emergencies, and return to the writing without even checking back "
"to see where I left off."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1002
msgid ""
"At home, I could talk with my husband, chat with a friend, take a nap, going"
" back to the notebook afterwards without disturbing the flow of words in the"
" slightest."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1003
msgid ""
"It did not matter whether I had stopped at the end of a paragraph or in the "
"middle of a sentence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1004
msgid ""
"It was as if the Voice merely waited until I came back and then started in "
"again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1005
msgid ""
"I wrote with equal ease at home, in the office, on a park bench, or in a "
"taxi, bus, or subway."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1006
msgid "The presence of other people did not interfere at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 273
#: sentence:1007
msgid ""
"When the time for writing came, external circumstances appeared to be "
"irrelevant.[59]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 274
#: sentence:1008
msgid ""
"Almost every day she would take her most recent notes to Bill’s conveniently"
" private office, where they would lock the door, pull down the shades as an "
"extra precaution against being discovered, and she would read while Bill "
"typed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 274
#: sentence:1009
msgid ""
"By her own admission, she was almost always in a state of panic, and the "
"reading required tremendous effort on her part."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 274
#: sentence:1010
msgid ""
"She would yawn, cough, cry, stutter, or sometimes lose her voice completely "
"and, in every conceivable manner, attempt to avoid speaking the words she "
"had received. She wrote:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 275
#: sentence:1011
msgid "For the most part, I was bleakly unbelieving, suspicious, and afraid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 275
#: sentence:1012
msgid ""
"Yet distressing as the writing generally was, reading the material to Bill "
"afterwards was infinitely more so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 275
#: sentence:1013
msgid ""
"We had agreed that I would read my notes to him at the end of the day, and "
"he would type them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 275
#: sentence:1014
msgid "I hated to hear what I had written."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 275
#: sentence:1015
msgid "I was sure it would be incoherent, foolish, and meaningless."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 275
#: sentence:1016
msgid ""
"On the other hand, I was likely to be unexpectedly and deeply moved and "
"suddenly burst into tears.[60]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 276
#: sentence:1017
msgid "Bill with the ACIM typewriter"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 277
#: sentence:1018
msgid ""
"After each typing session, they would jointly go over the typed version and "
"carefully check each word against her shorthand notes for accuracy, of major"
" import to Helen in particular."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 277
#: sentence:1019
msgid ""
"She told Bill, most irrationally, “You’re responsible for what it says,” and"
" declared her part was to assure grammatical correctness and purity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 277
#: sentence:1020
msgid ""
"She announced that she would simply refuse to continue if the dictation "
"contained grammatical errors."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 277
#: sentence:1021
msgid ""
"Fortunately, Helen did commit to this assignment absolutely, despite the "
"torment to her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 277
#: sentence:1022
msgid "A good thing, too, because she couldn’t permanently turn it off."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 277
#: sentence:1023
msgid ""
"Periodically, she would rebel and refuse to take notes for a while, "
"whereupon she became unable to sleep and generally dysfunctional, soon "
"returning to the dictation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 278
#: sentence:1024
msgid ""
"Bill assessed the situation, noting that Helen was never in a trance or "
"altered state when the scribing occurred:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1025
msgid ""
"So when Helen started hearing an inner voice, I knew it wasn’t something "
"that she was making up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1026
msgid ""
"In her attempts to gain attention, Helen had a strong self-dramatizing "
"tendency, but I knew this wasn’t that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1027
msgid "It didn’t fit that category at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1028
msgid "This was something that was quite authentic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1029
msgid ""
"She was frightened of it, but acknowledged it as having the kind of "
"authenticity that was not characteristic of her own ideas."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1030
msgid ""
"Yet she was also actually indifferent about it, despite its very compelling "
"quality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1031
msgid ""
"And contrary to what some might think, Helen said she did not hear an "
"external voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 279
#: sentence:1032
msgid ""
"What she heard really was a part of her mind which was clearly separated "
"from her ordinary ego consciousness or awareness.[61]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1033
msgid ""
"In Helen’s process, she didn’t hear voices in the way a schizophrenic does; "
"in her own words she described it not so much a matter of audition as a "
"sense of knowing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1034
msgid ""
"She said the material came very rapidly and smoothly, and she never knew how"
" a sentence would end."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1035
msgid ""
"Had she not been proficient in shorthand, she couldn’t have kept up with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1036
msgid ""
"Sometimes she asked the Voice to repeat an unclear message; in response, the"
" material then showed up on a sort of interior “blackboard” where she could "
"read it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1037
msgid ""
"She said all the writing was voluntary, never “automatic writing,” which she"
" could start and stop at will, and she was pleased with its coherence even "
"though the material was antithetical to everything she believed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1038
msgid "That, she said, confused her no end."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1039
msgid ""
"She ended her commentary by saying that the process of scribing is simply "
"impossible to explain in words: “I do not understand the events that led up "
"to the writing, I do not understand the process, and I certainly do not "
"understand the authorship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 280
#: sentence:1040
msgid "It would be pointless for me to attempt an explanation.”[62]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 281
#: sentence:1041
msgid ""
"Bill, too, found it impossible to describe a phenomena beyond the "
"intellect’s comprehension: “If one talked about the Holy Spirit or Jesus or "
"Christ or Higher Authority, whatever the term might be, it seemed to me that"
" we were talking at a level which was beyond conceptualization."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 281
#: sentence:1042
msgid ""
"And I couldn’t really pinpoint or identify that, except that I knew it went "
"way beyond our egos."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 281
#: sentence:1043
msgid ""
"It had nothing to do with our ordinary state of consciousness and awareness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 281
#: sentence:1044
msgid ""
"So I think I was perhaps more hesitant to talk in very specific Biblical "
"terms.”[63]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 282
#: sentence:1045
msgid ""
"Bill almost never referred to Jesus, not out of denial but because he "
"personally felt it confused people and fostered the already prevalent idea "
"about the historic Jesus being the author."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 282
#: sentence:1046
msgid ""
"Although the material is sometimes written in the first person as if a "
"specific person dictated the Course, it was not a personal Jesus speaking "
"through Helen as if she were a telephone line unrelated to the transmitted "
"message. “The name of Jesus Christ as such is but a symbol."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 282
#: sentence:1047
msgid ""
"But it stands for love that is not of this world.”[64] When specifically "
"asked about ACIM’s authorship, Bill tended to skirt the question, not "
"wanting to trivialize it or give a simplistic answer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 282
#: sentence:1048
msgid ""
"Thus, in deference to Bill’s protocol, I use the words “Author” or “Source” "
"of ACIM throughout this work, rather than the name Jesus."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 283
#: sentence:1049
msgid "From the ACIM teacher’s manual:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 284
#: sentence:1050
msgid ""
"The name of Jesus is the name of one who was a man but saw the face of "
"Christ in all his brothers and remembered God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 284
#: sentence:1051
msgid ""
"So he became identified with Christ, a man no longer, but at one with God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 284
#: sentence:1052
msgid ""
"The man was an illusion, for he seemed to be a separate being, walking by "
"himself, within a body that appeared to hold his self from Self, as all "
"illusions do. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 284
#: sentence:1053
msgid ""
"And Christ needed his form that He might appear to men and save them from "
"their own illusions.[65]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 285
#: sentence:1054
msgid "Ken Wapnick wrote:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1055
msgid "Again, Jesus [the Christ] does not speak in words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1056
msgid ""
"To say it differently and succinctly here, his is the content, our minds "
"(and brains) supply the form."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1057
msgid ""
"Therefore, Helen’s decision-making mind identified itself with the non-ego "
"presence that is in everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1058
msgid ""
"This non-judgmental thought system of love was represented for her by Jesus,"
" as it is for so many of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1059
msgid ""
"Her mind took that non-specific love and translated it into words, in much "
"the same way as our brains translate the upside-down image cast on the "
"retina into right-side-up perceptions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1060
msgid ""
"And so, as I have said many times, the form of the Course is from Helen. . ."
" ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1061
msgid ""
"The content of A Course in Miracles, however, is clearly not Helen’s, at "
"least not the Helen the world knew or the person she consciously identified "
"with."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1062
msgid ""
"This explains why she felt at liberty to change the form, though never the "
"content."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1063
msgid "Helen knew what the published Course ought to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 286
#: sentence:1064
msgid ""
"One could make recommendations, and Bill and I did from time to time, but "
"Helen had the finished form already in her head.[66]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 287
#: sentence:1065
msgid ""
"Finally, ACIM’s origin will remain unfathomable to our intellects, but "
"closer to us than our own breath."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 287
#: sentence:1066
msgid ""
"Since our goal is ultimately to experience the Source, we are better served "
"by focusing on forgiveness rather than on what our human minds can never "
"fully grasp."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 288
#: sentence:1067
msgid ""
"Though they couldn’t comprehend its source, they were convinced of ACIM’s "
"legitimacy and Bill’s support was unwavering and reassuring."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 288
#: sentence:1068
msgid ""
"He said that many times he typed with one hand and held Helen’s with the "
"other to try to mitigate her extreme anxiety about the material she was "
"relaying, which was so at odds with her own ego-based beliefs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 288
#: sentence:1069
msgid ""
"Bill, for his part, was also somewhat panicked, often making typographical "
"errors, rare for him, both because of the material’s implications and the "
"possible repercussions if anyone found out what they were up to."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 288
#: sentence:1070
msgid ""
"They would likely have lost their jobs and fine reputations, so long in the "
"making."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 288
#: sentence:1071
msgid ""
"And, of course, the entire process of scribing ACIM was woven throughout "
"their already impossibly busy schedules."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 288
#: sentence:1072
msgid "They made quite a pair."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 289
#: sentence:1073
msgid ""
"And thus was born the three-volume work consisting of a text, workbook, and "
"manual for teachers called A Course In Miracles—a title, by the way, neither"
" of them found acceptable in the beginning, thinking it sounded "
"embarrassing, awkward, and unscientific."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 289
#: sentence:1074
msgid "They even wanted the Author to change it, which did not happen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 289
#: sentence:1075
msgid ""
"Once they developed a greater understanding of the meaning of miracle (the "
"love that sustains the universe; a shift in perception that removes the "
"barriers to the awareness of love’s presence in our lives), they concluded "
"it was, indeed, the only possible title."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 290
#: sentence:1076
msgid ""
"Early on in the process, Bill and Helen both sensed they had started a "
"mission they had promised to fulfill at an earlier, unknown time and place "
"and were recommencing where they had left off."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 290
#: sentence:1077
msgid ""
"Despite their “wildly contradictory feelings,” as Helen described them, "
"neither considered abandoning the project."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 290
#: sentence:1078
msgid ""
"Two psychic readings given by talented, intuitive individuals, well known in"
" their fields, had much to say about Helen, Bill, their joint undertaking, "
"and their relationships in other lifetimes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 290
#: sentence:1079
msgid ""
"The material given in the readings was remarkably similar to the visions and"
" dreams Helen had experienced before “dictation” began."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 290
#: sentence:1080
msgid ""
"Incidentally, the issue of reincarnation, of ever increasing interest to "
"Bill, is addressed in the teacher’s manual under the chapter, “Is "
"Reincarnation So?”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 291
#: sentence:1081
msgid "In the ultimate sense, reincarnation is impossible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 291
#: sentence:1082
msgid ""
"There is no past or future, and the idea of birth into a body has no meaning"
" either once or many times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 291
#: sentence:1083
msgid "Reincarnation cannot, then, be true in any real sense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 291
#: sentence:1084
msgid ""
"Our only question should be, “Is the concept helpful?” And that depends, of "
"course, on what it is used for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 291
#: sentence:1085
msgid ""
"If it is used to strengthen the recognition of the eternal nature of life, "
"it is helpful, indeed. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 292
#: sentence:1086
msgid ""
"Does this mean that the teacher of God should not believe in reincarnation "
"himself, or discuss it with others who do?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 292
#: sentence:1087
msgid "The answer is, certainly not!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 292
#: sentence:1088
msgid ""
"If he does believe in reincarnation, it would be a mistake for him to "
"renounce the belief unless his internal Teacher so advised."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 292
#: sentence:1089
msgid "And this is most unlikely. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 293
#: sentence:1090
msgid ""
"The emphasis of this course always remains the same;—it is at this moment "
"that complete salvation is offered you, and it is at this moment that you "
"can accept it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 293
#: sentence:1091
msgid "This is still your one responsibility.[67]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 294
#: sentence:1092
msgid ""
"When these readings took place, neither psychic knew Bill, nor were they "
"familiar with the Course itself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 294
#: sentence:1093
msgid ""
"In addition, both were in a trance state and unaware of what was said until "
"the sessions were over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 294
#: sentence:1094
msgid ""
"The first excerpts are from a reading given for Bill in the spring of 1976 "
"by Paul Solomon shortly after ACIM was finished but not yet published."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 294
#: sentence:1095
msgid ""
"While a guest in the Skutch home, Paul had offered to do a reading for Judy "
"and she asked that he read for Bill instead."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 294
#: sentence:1096
msgid ""
"The second, in 1980, came at my request through LeRoy Zemke, a long-time "
"family friend, four years after the Course’s initial publication."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 294
#: sentence:1097
msgid "Bill was receptive to both these opportunities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 295
#: sentence:1098
msgid ""
"Bill, curious about his next function, had queried Paul, who responded that "
"Bill did not yet understand his relationship to the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 295
#: sentence:1099
msgid ""
"He stated that he should consider his contribution in terms of a "
"father/mother concept—a polarity—and that his presence was as necessary as "
"Helen’s in bringing the work to fruition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 295
#: sentence:1100
msgid ""
"He stated, “Begin to understand some of the laws of polarity and of the "
"priesthood, for in this sense you acted as a priest, a priest in the sense "
"of the go-between, the mediator, an energy that allowed the birth of the "
"material . . . participating as one encouraging, as a comrade, "
"counselor.”[68]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 296
#: sentence:1101
msgid ""
"Paul then referred to another life experience in which Bill and Helen, as "
"priest and priestess, had joined together in the highest and noblest sense "
"to evoke the oracle, to experience completion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 296
#: sentence:1102
msgid ""
"He indicated Bill would be unable to take his next step related to the "
"Course until he understood and owned his full participation in its "
"conception and birth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 296
#: sentence:1103
msgid "Once he did this, Paul said,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 297
#: sentence:1104
msgid ""
"There is another step, as might well be described—a step of application, a "
"step of completion, a step of commentary, as it will be seen concerning this"
" Course—as you will be the listener, the recorder, not the scribe "
"necessarily, but the listener."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 297
#: sentence:1105
msgid ""
"And this step will describe two purposes . . . the demonstration of the laws"
" spoken of in the Course itself, the application."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 297
#: sentence:1106
msgid ""
"It is the demonstration of the completion of application and the recording "
"of that effect that has been prophesied.[69]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 298
#: sentence:1107
msgid ""
"Paul stated further that the vast potential for bringing ACIM forward "
"existed in Helen, but Bill provided the energetic stimulus or key that "
"allowed the flow to begin. He suggested,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 299
#: sentence:1108
msgid ""
"Now see yourself in that role in relation to that which has been born and be"
" responsible concerning that birth and growth and maturity, for your "
"responsibility ends not with the introduction of this to the world, but with"
" its maturity and application, the responsibility of learning from it, using"
" it, not controlling how it shall be used but rather experiencing that which"
" is given to experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 299
#: sentence:1109
msgid ""
"Go out to the people on your own and express, assist, share ideas, be a part"
" of the Source of the material, and demonstrate its growth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 300
#: sentence:1110
msgid ""
"As to the past and its relationship to the present, understand here there "
"are so many times you’ve experienced this plane of existence, and every time"
" is directly involved with this in some way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 300
#: sentence:1111
msgid ""
"Many times you have known those who are close in this time, not only the "
"channel for this material, but others that are as a part of the family even "
"in this time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 300
#: sentence:1112
msgid ""
"You have returned together for a purpose, as men are inclined to do, and "
"each earlier time has played its part, its role, in the preparation.[70]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 301
#: sentence:1113
msgid ""
"Paul suggested, as do many other intuitives, that in various life "
"experiences we play different roles with those we are close to in the "
"current lifetime, and this provides a compelling force for returning "
"together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 301
#: sentence:1114
msgid ""
"He stated that Bill and Helen had been husband and wife before, but just as "
"important, they had been in a teacher/student relationship, with Bill as the"
" paternal teacher, instructing her how to listen as a channel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 301
#: sentence:1115
msgid "Further highlighting Bill’s challenges, Paul said:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 302
#: sentence:1116
msgid ""
"And your tendency has been, in that time and others, to isolate the self, to"
" set the self apart, to become a monk, a separated one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 302
#: sentence:1117
msgid ""
"And in the most recent life [before this one], disappointment, "
"disillusionment in marriage turned to a depth of spiritual quality that made"
" you feel that separation, isolation, being alone is best for soul growth, "
"for development, and yet that decision toward loneliness in that time has, "
"in this time, produced a regret, a feeling of loneliness, isolation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 302
#: sentence:1118
msgid ""
"Then you see how these things work together, that one time tempers another "
"and you are the product of all the times that you lived and all the "
"experiences, one tempering the other to produce that which is perfect for "
"this moment to express that which must be expressed through it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 303
#: sentence:1119
msgid ""
"Now you still continue with the illusion that each moment must have its "
"purpose in productivity. Something must be produced."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 303
#: sentence:1120
msgid "There must be a reason for this moment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 303
#: sentence:1121
msgid "You must have a goal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 303
#: sentence:1122
msgid ""
"There will not be that clarity of specific purpose, goal, or job until there"
" is the acceptance that living has purpose now."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 303
#: sentence:1123
msgid ""
"When being what you are is sufficient unto itself, then the means of "
"listening and the next step will appear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 304
#: sentence:1124
msgid ""
"Understand that the concerns for the physical are largely related to that "
"just given."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 304
#: sentence:1125
msgid "The energy needed will be found in finding purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 304
#: sentence:1126
msgid ""
"When there is a specific project, there is sufficient energy there too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 304
#: sentence:1127
msgid ""
"When there is a feeling of not having direct purpose, there is a feeling of "
"loss of energy, debilitation, lack of direction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 304
#: sentence:1128
msgid ""
"Let the moment, let living, let relationships—the relationship with God—be "
"sufficient to that motivation and build the energy for it.[71]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 305
#: sentence:1129
msgid ""
"Before I knew about this reading with Paul, I was conversing with Jaison "
"Kayn, a friend from Denver Bill would meet later. “Bill would defer to Helen"
" because she did the actual scribing,” he observed, as have many others "
"close to Bill, “but not a chance in hell it would have happened without him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 305
#: sentence:1130
msgid ""
"She required not only support but the confidence that he gave simply from "
"the power of his presence. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 305
#: sentence:1131
msgid "His respect, admiration, and appreciation for her helped her go on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 305
#: sentence:1132
msgid ""
"They were a team and he knew that.”[72] All who knew him commented on the "
"obvious—Bill was an equal, essential part of the Course’s coming forth; he "
"held the key to its transmission and was ultimately responsible for its "
"coming to pass."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 305
#: sentence:1133
msgid "Without him, this work would never have happened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 305
#: sentence:1134
msgid ""
"Of course, this is not to minimize Helen’s part, but to correct any "
"misperception that the Course was “her work” and Bill was the “helper.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 306
#: sentence:1135
msgid ""
"In 1980, LeRoy Zemke made many comments in a lengthy reading for Bill about "
"his and Helen’s relationship and its ancient origins."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 306
#: sentence:1136
msgid "Referring to Helen, LeRoy told him:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1137
msgid ""
"There is here another challenge for you and that involves the channel "
"through whom the energy [of ACIM] itself was directed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1138
msgid "The initial connection with this woman was a very, very powerful one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1139
msgid "It is still very powerful on the highest level of your being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1140
msgid ""
"There is within you a deep, abiding love, a love which goes back centuries "
"into the past, and it is the expression of a love, a connection initially "
"made in the ancient land of Egypt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1141
msgid ""
"You were both in the male form and your work involved the founding of a "
"school that became a kind of guideline for the training of the priesthood "
"that would form the foundations of the consciousness of healing in the "
"Egyptian religion of its time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1142
msgid "The school itself was thwarted, aborted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1143
msgid ""
"And the commitment to establish this energy as a teaching has now been "
"brought into this present time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1144
msgid ""
"It will be done without the form of the traditional school, but is still the"
" teaching that is here before you. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1145
msgid "There is perhaps one additional idea."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1146
msgid ""
"When this effort in ancient Saqqara [Egypt] was initiated, this entity, "
"Helen, was in the male form."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1147
msgid ""
"You were both in the male form at that time, as you know, and the energy "
"there was intensely powerful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 307
#: sentence:1148
msgid ""
"She felt a tremendous commitment and made a very powerful promise at some "
"junction to come forward with that which would be beneficial for those ready"
" to enter a force field that would permit the unfolding of the new Christ, "
"the Cosmic Christ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 308
#: sentence:1149
msgid ""
"Additional important information is that, from that period until this, there"
" have been other embodiments involved with commitments to experiences of "
"like essence and, in this life, the wrestling with the powers of the spirit "
"has been very intense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 308
#: sentence:1150
msgid ""
"As a result of that commitment made in ancient Egypt and the experiences in "
"other dimensions of being, there is a reluctance within her consciousness to"
" let go, and it is only through this deliberate shift created by the "
"personality to allow . . . this promise to be made whole through you [Bill]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 309
#: sentence:1151
msgid "Bill then questioned LeRoy, who was still in a trance state:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 310
#: sentence:1152
msgid ""
"I think I have been a very reluctant teacher in this life, and I’m aware of "
"feeling that teaching is part of my function, but there has always been a "
"sense of drag about this. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 310
#: sentence:1153
msgid ""
"Somehow I have a great deal of fear—a totally irrational, neurotic "
"fear—about getting up before groups, particularly large groups of people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 310
#: sentence:1154
msgid "Is there anything that would be helpful in that regard?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 311
#: sentence:1155
msgid "Zemke answered:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1156
msgid "There are several indications here that are significant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1157
msgid ""
"In the past, much of your in-depth work, in terms of the way in which you "
"have related to people, has been in a one-to-one setting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1158
msgid ""
"You have often been involved in the Catholic Church as a priest and have "
"lived the scholastic life, a very secluded, scholarly life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1159
msgid ""
"And much of your work has thus been involved in communicating with only one "
"person or a very small and/or select group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1160
msgid ""
"That energy from those life experiences is very much a part of your "
"consciousness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1161
msgid ""
"It’s a very powerful memory that acts as a resistance to your present "
"setting since you are no longer in the priesthood but have been in an "
"academic environment where that same secluded atmosphere has been prevalent."
" . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1162
msgid "Part of this fear comes from the past."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1163
msgid "In the priesthood role, your teaching was, as it were, protected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1164
msgid ""
"It came out of a very sacred dimension that might be challenged by the outer"
" world, but never fully challenged because the priesthood acts as a shield "
"to protect it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1165
msgid ""
"Therefore, whatever the priests have taught, be it true or false, has had "
"the aura of the Church to give it sanction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1166
msgid "However, in this life, that is no longer available to you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1167
msgid ""
"Now you are drawing much closer to the Source and having to stand alone "
"without the shield as you make the statements that need to be made. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 312
#: sentence:1168
msgid ""
"You have no difficulty communicating your ideas, as such, but there is that "
"fear that you are, in some way, going to dishonor the body of information "
"and the power of the God-force within in attempting to represent it "
"accurately. That holds you back.[73]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 313
#: sentence:1169
msgid "What our energy fields reveal about any of us is fascinating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 313
#: sentence:1170
msgid "We simply can’t hide what is going on in our so-called private space."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 313
#: sentence:1171
msgid ""
"Judith Skutch Whitson’s first impression of Bill was that of a trapped monk."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 313
#: sentence:1172
msgid ""
"She noted his darting eyes and very straight back poised as if he were "
"always getting ready to leave."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 313
#: sentence:1173
msgid ""
"About five months into their friendship she mentioned that first impression,"
" at which point he smiled and said, “I knew you knew.” What she noted was "
"not Bill’s usual demeanor, but the fear LeRoy identified occasionally "
"revealed itself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 314
#: sentence:1174
msgid ""
"It’s apparent by now that Bill and Helen’s relationship was unique, to say "
"the least."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 314
#: sentence:1175
msgid ""
"To illustrate, Whit Whitson recounts an early experience with Judy and the "
"Course:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 315
#: sentence:1176
msgid "In the spring of 1979, Judy visited Washington and we got together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 315
#: sentence:1177
msgid ""
"While she was there, I hoped to explore the relationship, if any, between "
"the PAS “ego” [personality] and the “ego” as defined by the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 315
#: sentence:1178
msgid ""
"To do that, I decided to introduce Mike [a colleague knowledgeable about the"
" PAS] to Judy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 315
#: sentence:1179
msgid ""
"Judy and Mike hit it off immediately at the lunch I had arranged for us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 315
#: sentence:1180
msgid "Soon Mike asked her to tell him about A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 315
#: sentence:1181
msgid ""
"I knew he would be somewhat skeptical about the fundamental precepts of the "
"Course and whoever had “dreamed up” such a system of thought."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 316
#: sentence:1182
msgid ""
"At the time, Bill and Helen had pledged Judy to silence about their roles in"
" scribing the Course, insisting on remaining anonymous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 316
#: sentence:1183
msgid ""
"So Judy refused to give Mike their names or even the locale of their "
"university."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 316
#: sentence:1184
msgid ""
"But as she continued to describe them—their personalities and relationship "
"with one another—Mike suddenly asked, “Are you talking about Bill Thetford "
"and Helen Schucman?”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1185
msgid "Judy was dumbfounded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1186
msgid "She wondered what she had said to reveal Helen and Bill’s secret."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1187
msgid ""
"In turn, Mike stared at Judy in disbelief, telling her that he knew them, "
"but that he never knew they had produced A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1188
msgid ""
"Mike explained that he couldn’t think of anyone else who fit Judy’s "
"descriptions; he would now have to reassess his prior judgments of Bill and "
"Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1189
msgid ""
"He also told Judy that he had worked with them and knew them as a truly "
"remarkable team. [Mike’s association with them related to funding many of "
"their projects.] He remembered Bill as being the stable, imperturbable "
"academic—calm and easy-going—which contrasted with Helen’s assertive "
"vitality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1190
msgid ""
"He thought of Helen as a tough-minded New York intellectual with a no-"
"nonsense, intensive, questioning mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 317
#: sentence:1191
msgid "Yet as a team professionally, he found them incredibly productive.[74]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 318
#: sentence:1192
msgid "So much for trying to hide!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 319
#: sentence:1193
msgid "Bill and Helen’s relationship was most unusual in other ways as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 319
#: sentence:1194
msgid ""
"Ken Wapnick noted that, although they could fight endlessly, when either "
"really needed help or support, the other was there without condition and for"
" as long as needed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 319
#: sentence:1195
msgid ""
"Also, when involved in Course work, they were loving and kind to one "
"another, all enmity put aside."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 319
#: sentence:1196
msgid ""
"On returning to their academic work, however, the sniping would resume."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 319
#: sentence:1197
msgid ""
"Bill would write, Helen would ferociously edit, he would take that "
"personally, and they were off and running."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 319
#: sentence:1198
msgid ""
"It’s as if they continually flipped a switch, operating at extremes—a real "
"love-hate relationship, but both were resolute in their commitment to the "
"Course and to avoiding endangering its transmission in any way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 320
#: sentence:1199
msgid "Their battles were not limited to normal work hours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 320
#: sentence:1200
msgid ""
"I asked Ken if he was included in the “after-hours war” once he joined the "
"project, and he answered emphatically,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 321
#: sentence:1201
msgid "Oh, God, yes—always!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 321
#: sentence:1202
msgid ""
"In general, we’d be together all day and they would argue all the time, I’d "
"go home with Helen to have dinner with her and Louis."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 321
#: sentence:1203
msgid ""
"After dinner, Helen would call Bill or he would call her, I’d go to another "
"room, and they’d continue where they left off for up to another hour."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 321
#: sentence:1204
msgid ""
"For a long time we’d have lunch together on Saturday, then go to Bill’s "
"apartment or take a walk in the park if it was nice, and then go to Bill’s "
"apartment and continue."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 321
#: sentence:1205
msgid ""
"At some point, we stopped doing it because it was just awful, the arguing "
"was enough already.[75]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1206
msgid "They both seemed determined to make themselves miserable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1207
msgid ""
"Bill used to say he thought he and Helen needed the Course because they "
"intensely resisted each other’s egos."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1208
msgid ""
"To say they were astonished as the message unfolded would be a gross "
"understatement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1209
msgid ""
"Bill quickly recognized he would need to examine and release virtually "
"everything he believed and seriously questioned his ability to do that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1210
msgid ""
"In fact, he described being in shock for a while, wondering how such an "
"abrupt shift could be possible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1211
msgid ""
"How important were all his academic achievements and recognition? What was "
"really valuable?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1212
msgid "Everything would have to be reevaluated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1213
msgid ""
"To live that schizophrenic kind of life, pursuing a career in traditional "
"psychology on one hand and trying to deal with the dynamics of the Course "
"and its ramifications on the other, was a huge feat for both of them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 322
#: sentence:1214
msgid ""
"From what Bill told me, the endless, wrenching nature of this dichotomy was "
"incredibly difficult for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 323
#: sentence:1215
msgid ""
"Relentlessly, day after day, the Course pointed out the mirroring nature of "
"our world—relationships, situations, circumstances—and the inescapable fact "
"that we are fully responsible for our subjective experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 324
#: sentence:1216
msgid "The world you see depicts exactly what you thought you did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 324
#: sentence:1217
msgid ""
"Except that now you think that what you did is being done to you. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 325
#: sentence:1218
msgid ""
"The world but demonstrates an ancient truth; you will believe that others do"
" to you exactly what you think you did to them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 325
#: sentence:1219
msgid ""
"But once deluded into blaming them, you will not see the cause of what they "
"do, because you want the guilt to rest on them. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 326
#: sentence:1220
msgid ""
"The secret to salvation is but this: That you are doing this unto yourself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 326
#: sentence:1221
msgid "No matter what the form of the attack, this still is true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 326
#: sentence:1222
msgid ""
"Whoever takes the role of enemy and of attacker, still is this the truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 326
#: sentence:1223
msgid ""
"Whatever seems to be the cause of any pain and suffering you feel, this is "
"still true.[76]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 327
#: sentence:1224
msgid ""
"As Bill and Helen worked together to produce a typescript of the Course, "
"they felt genuine excitement as the project unfolded, providing a truly "
"meaningful function as they joined in common purpose, and it was rewarding "
"in ways their regular work at Columbia was not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 327
#: sentence:1225
msgid ""
"Bill said later that it felt amazingly familiar, a feeling not unique to "
"them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 327
#: sentence:1226
msgid ""
"I have spoken with many people who have described how much at home they felt"
" with the material, how it resonated at a profound level like a long-lost "
"truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 327
#: sentence:1227
msgid ""
"Once when Bill and I were discussing the Course, I told him I felt like it "
"was mine, almost like I had written it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 327
#: sentence:1228
msgid ""
"He answered, “I’m sure you did.” He did not mean that I literally had "
"something to do with scribing it in its current form but that we are all "
"part of the unified Self from which it derives."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 327
#: sentence:1229
msgid ""
"At some level, we have all collectively written it in anticipation of our "
"comprehensive waking up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 328
#: sentence:1230
msgid ""
"Bill and Helen sometimes asked the Author, the Voice Helen “heard,” why they"
" were chosen to bring this material forward, because they often felt unfit "
"for the job."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 328
#: sentence:1231
msgid ""
"The Voice indicated that the confidence in them was not misplaced, as their "
"commitment and agreement to do this work was already known."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 328
#: sentence:1232
msgid ""
"Eventually, they realized the inevitability of their commitment, and neither"
" seriously considered giving it up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 328
#: sentence:1233
msgid ""
"The answer Bill gave, in the few interviews he granted, to the question of "
"“Why us?” was “Because you’re doing it.” That was a correct but insufficient"
" answer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 328
#: sentence:1234
msgid ""
"In the Urtext, defined as “a reconstructed proto-text set up as the basis of"
" variants in extant later texts,”[77] and in this case, Bill’s original, "
"unedited typed notes of ACIM, the Author gave them a more complete and "
"direct answer:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 329
#: sentence:1235
msgid ""
"You have been chosen to teach the Atonement precisely because you have been "
"extreme examples of allegiance to your thought systems and, therefore, have "
"developed the capacity for allegiance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 329
#: sentence:1236
msgid "It has, indeed, been misplaced."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 329
#: sentence:1237
msgid ""
"Bill has become an outstanding example of allegiance to apathy, and you "
"[Helen] have become a startling example of fidelity to variability."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 329
#: sentence:1238
msgid ""
"But this is a form of faith, which you yourselves had grown willing to "
"redirect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 329
#: sentence:1239
msgid ""
"You cannot doubt the strength of your devotion when you consider how "
"faithfully you observed it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 329
#: sentence:1240
msgid ""
"It was quite evident that you had already developed the ability to follow a "
"better model, if you could accept it.[78]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 330
#: sentence:1241
msgid ""
"Because Helen was so easily upset and challenged by the subject matter of "
"the Course, it was difficult for them to discuss the content once they "
"assured its accuracy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 330
#: sentence:1242
msgid ""
"Therefore, Bill, sworn to secrecy, had no one with whom to explore the "
"ideas, to discover what they actually said and how to apply them in his "
"life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 330
#: sentence:1243
msgid ""
"In the beginning, absolutely no one knew about the ACIM project, which they "
"carefully fit in around the edges of their official jobs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 331
#: sentence:1244
msgid ""
"Several months before the dilemma of having no one to talk with became "
"acute, Bill’s friend at the hospital, Cal Hatcher, had approached him about "
"his desire to discuss religious or spiritual matters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 331
#: sentence:1245
msgid ""
"Bill assured him he was talking to the wrong guy, because he had no "
"knowledge or interest in such subjects at that time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 331
#: sentence:1246
msgid ""
"Therefore, when ACIM turned his values, his assumptions, and his very life "
"upside down, Bill instinctively knew Cal was the person he could trust with "
"their secret."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 331
#: sentence:1247
msgid ""
"Although this thought system was entirely different from anything he had "
"learned or that psychology taught, it seemed imminently practical and thus "
"very appealing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 331
#: sentence:1248
msgid "He was anxious to try it out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 331
#: sentence:1249
msgid ""
"Predictably, Helen was more than upset when he told her that Cal would now "
"be his confidant. Bill wrote:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1250
msgid ""
"Afterward [after making the arrangement with Cal], when I would type up the "
"three copies, I would give Helen the original, keep one copy and give Cal "
"the other each morning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1251
msgid ""
"For several years we met in my office early in the morning, before 8am, "
"because we had to meet before scheduled activities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1252
msgid ""
"I would go over the material that I had typed the preceding day and try to "
"explain it to Cal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1253
msgid ""
"This was my attempt to learn what it meant by trying to teach it to him, and"
" it was enormously helpful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1254
msgid ""
"Cal knew much more than I did about the Bible, which was all very new to me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1255
msgid ""
"He had a critical, inquiring mind, and wanted to know what this meant, what "
"the implications might be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1256
msgid ""
"This gave me my first opportunity to try to find out what I thought about "
"it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1257
msgid ""
"Our talks were extremely helpful and made it possible for Helen and me to "
"continue even when I felt we were not learning it together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 332
#: sentence:1258
msgid "It was much more difficult to go over the material with Helen.[79]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 333
#: sentence:1259
msgid ""
"Although Cal proved to be a much needed partner in studying the material, "
"Bill was deeply disturbed that he and Helen seemed unable to decide "
"harmoniously how to use ACIM to work on their relationship, much less "
"actually put it into practice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 333
#: sentence:1260
msgid ""
"In fact, he felt their situation worsened as the Course continued to unfold."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 333
#: sentence:1261
msgid ""
"Helen became increasingly hostile as she projected onto Bill the sense of "
"threat engendered by the material, and from his perspective, she actively "
"attempted to undermine him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 333
#: sentence:1262
msgid ""
"He took the Course statements seriously and literally when it referred to "
"“you, Helen and Bill,” which they later translated throughout the books into"
" “the two of you” or “you and your brother.” He agonized over the observable"
" lack of progress with her; he used to say it was impossible to express how "
"much this seeming failure with Helen upset him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 333
#: sentence:1263
msgid ""
"And his ongoing angst with her was just a subplot in the pressure cooker "
"that was the highly competitive medical center."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 333
#: sentence:1264
msgid ""
"As he commented later, “Much of the time what I felt was a constant "
"temptation to walk the plank.”[80]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1265
msgid ""
"Because increased upset is such a common experience for new students of "
"ACIM, I believe it should be addressed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1266
msgid ""
"I have worked with many people who found that at some point in their early "
"practice of the Course, life seemed to get worse rather than better."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1267
msgid ""
"In fact, in my classes I warn students this is likely to happen and that "
"it’s reasonable to ask why they should embark on a practice that might stir "
"up more upset."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1268
msgid "The answer, of course, is that sooner or later it’s our only choice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1269
msgid ""
"Addressing our fears is ultimately required of everyone, not to inflict "
"punishment but because this is how to release them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1270
msgid ""
"Bill found—as everyone eventually finds—that tolerance for pain is only so "
"high."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1271
msgid ""
"The introduction to the text speaks of removing the blocks to the awareness "
"of love’s presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 334
#: sentence:1272
msgid ""
"When we ask for help, we become aware of those blocks or fears so that we "
"can address them directly and make happier, more sane and peaceful choices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 335
#: sentence:1273
msgid ""
"Since Bill and Helen were devoting extensive time to the Course project, but"
" seemed to be getting nowhere with healing their relationship, Bill decided "
"to test its premises with other, less volatile relationships that needed "
"attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 335
#: sentence:1274
msgid ""
"If it could produce changes with a difficult colleague, he thought, it ought"
" to work anywhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 335
#: sentence:1275
msgid ""
"Judy Skutch Whitson recalls Bill’s telling her more than a few times, with "
"unusual (for him) seriousness, about one of his first dedicated attempts to "
"practice ACIM as the lessons were being dictated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 336
#: sentence:1276
msgid ""
"Art was co-director of the department of psychology with Bill. [In fact, he "
"had been instrumental in Bill’s coming to Columbia in the first place.] They"
" were friends, had had a long walk together professionally, and I think "
"accepted and liked each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 336
#: sentence:1277
msgid "Then Bill hired Helen and all hell broke loose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 336
#: sentence:1278
msgid ""
"Art didn’t like Helen, really didn’t like her, and had great antipathy "
"toward her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 336
#: sentence:1279
msgid ""
"Bill told me that Art thought she certainly did excellent research work but "
"that she was too much trouble, a high-maintenance lady and distracting at "
"meetings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 336
#: sentence:1280
msgid "He found her sharp; in other words, they didn’t get along."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 336
#: sentence:1281
msgid ""
"At times, he asked Bill to fire Helen and Bill dug in, unequivocally "
"refusing to do that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 337
#: sentence:1282
msgid ""
"Of course, Art had no idea what was going on in their office as far as the "
"Course was concerned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 337
#: sentence:1283
msgid ""
"As dictation on the workbook began, Bill recognized it provided a process "
"one could pragmatically use to change relationships or re-envision them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 337
#: sentence:1284
msgid ""
"Wondering if it would really work, he chose Art, who was currently not "
"talking to him, for his experiment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 337
#: sentence:1285
msgid ""
"Art now had as much antipathy toward Bill as Helen and was including him as "
"a target of his anger."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 337
#: sentence:1286
msgid ""
"This fractured relationship with Art over Helen’s presence was a major "
"contributing factor to the chaos that made birthing the Course so difficult."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1287
msgid ""
"Art wouldn’t even look him in the eye, so Bill decided to go to his office "
"in the morning before work, knowing Art always went in early to read the "
"paper."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1288
msgid ""
"On his first attempt, Bill knocked on the door and asked if he could come "
"in; Art didn’t look up from his newspaper."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1289
msgid "Bill entered and sat quietly on a chair right across from Art’s desk."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1290
msgid "Art never put down his newspaper, so after a while Bill left."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1291
msgid ""
"Every day for about a month Bill went in and Art never put down his paper or"
" acknowledged him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1292
msgid ""
"By then he felt much more comfortable and knew that he was guided to "
"persevere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1293
msgid ""
"One day he said, “Good morning, Art,” who grunted from behind his newspaper."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1294
msgid "For Bill, this was a very big sign."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1295
msgid ""
"After several months of this routine, Bill had an early morning appointment "
"elsewhere and came to his office later than usual."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1296
msgid ""
"Around lunchtime, Bill saw Art, who said, “Where were you this morning?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 338
#: sentence:1297
msgid ""
"You didn’t come in.” Bill told him of his appointment and that was the "
"beginning of their talking again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1298
msgid ""
"Not long after that, all the upper staff members were invited to a "
"conference where Bill and Art represented their department at the "
"university."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1299
msgid ""
"Checking into the hotel, although not together, each found the hotel had "
"overbooked and there was a shortage of rooms."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1300
msgid "The hotel staff asked those who knew each other to double up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1301
msgid ""
"Art approached Bill and asked if he would like to share a room, stating, "
"“There is no one here I would rather be with.” Bill said he would be "
"delighted, and after unpacking their things, they went down to the bar "
"before dinner."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1302
msgid ""
"As they sat there talking and waiting for dinner to be announced, Art took "
"three almonds from a little bowl on their table, passed them to Bill, and "
"said, “Edgar Cayce says they’re very good for you.” Bill said he nearly "
"dropped his front teeth. “Edgar Cayce, Art?” Art replied, “Yes, he’s this "
"very famous psychic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1303
msgid ""
"During the war I was stationed in Virginia Beach and I used to go to his "
"house for lunch on Sundays."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1304
msgid ""
"He was really a very great guy.” Bill said at that moment he knew it was "
"over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1305
msgid ""
"The situation with Art was the first time he had deliberately practiced "
"ACIM, and of course, their changed relationship improved the department’s "
"functioning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1306
msgid "This quiet way was typical of Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 339
#: sentence:1307
msgid ""
"He didn’t go to Art saying, “Look, I know how you’re feeling about the "
"situation and I don’t blame you, but you’re making me really uncomfortable "
"and here are the reasons for my decisions,” etc. Instead, he sat there in "
"the chair quietly.[81]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1308
msgid ""
"The mention of Edgar Cayce was so meaningful to Bill because shortly before "
"Bill’s urgent speech to Helen that precipitated the onset of ACIM, he had "
"read a book by Hugh Lynn Cayce, Edgar’s son."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1309
msgid ""
"Although the claims regarding Cayce’s abilities seemed preposterous by his "
"own scientific standards, Bill sensed inwardly that the stories about him "
"were legitimate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1310
msgid ""
"On that basis, he planned a trip for Helen and himself to Virginia Beach to "
"meet Hugh Lynn."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1311
msgid ""
"Helen resisted going as she didn’t want to be considered a “psychic” or be "
"associated with them, although she was privately impressed with her growing "
"psychic abilities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1312
msgid ""
"She was often ambivalent about rejecting or embracing aspects of herself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1313
msgid ""
"Their visit took place in the fall of 1965 after her several months of "
"“heightened visual imagery,” just before the Course began in October."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1314
msgid ""
"Bill always thought that trip gave her “permission” to open up to her "
"immense intuitive abilities and also provided some rudimentary preparation "
"for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 340
#: sentence:1315
msgid ""
"He began to think “outside the box” and looked with growing, though quiet, "
"appreciation of his own intuitive abilities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 341
#: sentence:1316
msgid ""
"The healing with Art was only one of a number of relationships that seemed "
"smoother as Bill attempted to follow his own guidance and the Course "
"instructions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 341
#: sentence:1317
msgid ""
"Those around him began to notice that the department seemed less harried, "
"and his secretary, having no idea of the real meaning behind what she was "
"saying, would periodically proclaim, “Oh, Dr. Thetford has just performed "
"another miracle.”[82] Or a close colleague, the chairman of the psychology "
"department at the University of Chicago, would say, “There’s Bill, walking "
"on water again.”[83] Bill himself felt that by the time he left the medical "
"center, he had reached his goal—healing all his relationships there—all, of "
"course, except the primary one with Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 342
#: sentence:1318
msgid "Chapter 6"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1319
msgid ""
"Although neither Bill nor Helen had been consciously interested in religious"
" or spiritual matters before ACIM dictation began, Bill quickly recognized "
"the universal nature of the material and began a serious inquiry into the "
"world’s major religious traditions and teachings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1320
msgid ""
"In his search for corroboration, he discovered the nondualistic teaching of "
"Advaita Vedanta from India and immediately saw its parallels to the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1321
msgid ""
"Thus he dubbed ACIM the “Christian Vedanta” because of its use of Christian "
"language to present these truths."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1322
msgid ""
"He became more impressed with the Course as his study deepened, finding it "
"integrated and synthesized the best of the teachings he investigated—and it "
"was practical."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1323
msgid ""
"He read extensively in his newly discovered field of interest and became "
"extremely well versed in this formerly uninteresting subject."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1324
msgid ""
"Many of Bill’s friends and colleagues said he had an astounding capacity to "
"absorb vast quantities of written material quickly, a valuable trait given "
"that he had five thousand years of mystical traditions to explore."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1325
msgid ""
"Years later, he noted with some disappointment that the PAS, on which he had"
" lavished so much time and attention, did not explain or even address the "
"spiritual dimension of our life experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 343
#: sentence:1326
msgid "How unexpectedly our lives can change and even reverse course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1327
msgid ""
"As Bill was deepening his research into metaphysics, he became intrigued "
"with a chapter about mysticism and schizophrenia in the book, Higher States "
"of Consciousness, by John White."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1328
msgid ""
"It was written by Kenneth Wapnick, a young psychologist, and Bill shared it "
"with one of his graduate students, Father Benedict, a Capuchin friar."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1329
msgid ""
"Benedict, one of the three or four people entrusted with their “guilty "
"secret,” as Bill jokingly called it, subsequently became friendly with Ken "
"and later introduced him to Bill and Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1330
msgid ""
"Shortly after they met in late 1972, Ken left New York for Israel to live in"
" a monastery, presumably to be his permanent home, having converted from "
"Judaism to Catholicism."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1331
msgid ""
"Once there, however, he couldn’t get that meeting out of his mind; he dreamt"
" of it, aware of a very strong connection with both of them, especially "
"Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1332
msgid ""
"His guidance prevailed and in the spring of 1973, as if on cue, he returned "
"to New York (the last place he thought he wanted to be) to meet with them "
"again and to find out more about the manuscript his new friends had "
"mentioned to him earlier."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1333
msgid ""
"One look and that intriguing book “knocked him off his feet,” to use his "
"words—his fate was sealed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 344
#: sentence:1334
msgid ""
"He notified his Israeli friends of his change of plans and re-established "
"himself in New York to be close to “ACIM Central.” Thus, as the dictation "
"was concluding, Kenneth Wapnick officially entered the picture, commencing "
"three more years of editing, rereading, checking for errors, and improving "
"section and chapter titles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 345
#: sentence:1335
msgid ""
"As if there were not enough turmoil and high drama around Bill and Helen’s "
"busy professional lives, punctuated with general angst and their unrelenting"
" distress with each other, Ken’s arrival stirred the pot even more."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 345
#: sentence:1336
msgid ""
"Despite serious difficulties, they were extremely codependent and genuinely "
"and deeply cared for one another; introducing a third party into the mix was"
" more than a little unsettling for Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 345
#: sentence:1337
msgid ""
"Ken’s services were badly needed and truly appreciated, but they came at a "
"price from his perspective."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 345
#: sentence:1338
msgid ""
"Helen and Ken’s apparent mutual adoration, which developed right away, was "
"the perfect setup to trigger within Bill a deep sense of rejection and "
"betrayal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 345
#: sentence:1339
msgid ""
"Notice the word is trigger and not cause, as that feeling of rejection was "
"already in place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 345
#: sentence:1340
msgid ""
"This new situation brought those painful feelings into conscious awareness, "
"exactly what the Course and life under its guidance is designed to do in "
"order to be free of them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 346
#: sentence:1341
msgid ""
"The harshness and sarcasm evident in some of the following stories and "
"quotes is not an indictment of Ken, Helen, or Bill himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 346
#: sentence:1342
msgid ""
"Helen and Ken were, and are, brilliant, dedicated, and of incalculable value"
" in the ACIM saga, executing their special functions on schedule and as "
"promised."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 346
#: sentence:1343
msgid ""
"Bill’s upset was clearly his own responsibility, which he ultimately "
"recognized, but at this point, he responded like most of humanity, not "
"realizing that the difficult characters in his “drama” were merely "
"reflecting back to him the unloving projections of his own ego and the fears"
" he had thus far refused to own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 346
#: sentence:1344
msgid "Bill remembers in his autobiography:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 347
#: sentence:1345
msgid ""
"Helen and I were working desperately on a chapter for the Comprehensive "
"Textbook of Psychiatry."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 347
#: sentence:1346
msgid "We were on a deadline and we had to turn out a lot of material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 347
#: sentence:1347
msgid ""
"We had decided to cover one personality theorist a week, which was the only "
"way we could get it all done."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 347
#: sentence:1348
msgid "I was doing all the reference work and Helen was writing the material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 347
#: sentence:1349
msgid "It was a big job, and it had to be done well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1350
msgid "Ken surfaced in the midst of all this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1351
msgid ""
"Helen and I were both edgy, partly because we were trying to get our work "
"done."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1352
msgid "I also had a lot of other things I had to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1353
msgid "We were sharp with each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1354
msgid "Ken was appalled at our relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1355
msgid ""
"Here we had this holy book—this wonderful spiritual material—and we didn’t "
"know how to relate to each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1356
msgid "The two of us were bickering and carrying on in a terrible way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1357
msgid "We were obviously not being loving and holy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1358
msgid ""
"Ken decided he was going to demonstrate how relationships could be healed, "
"to demonstrate perfect love and that sort of thing, how to do it properly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1359
msgid ""
"He would take Helen on as the demonstration and show me the power of love—or"
" holiness—in action."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 348
#: sentence:1360
msgid "I was apparently to learn from watching.[84]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 349
#: sentence:1361
msgid "Ken observed:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1362
msgid "That first summer I spent a lot of time with them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1363
msgid ""
"They were writing this chapter for a very prestigious publication on "
"personality theories."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1364
msgid "They would argue and fight—it was awful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1365
msgid ""
"We were just getting to know one another so we spent a lot of time together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1366
msgid ""
"When we talked about the Course and the path that led me to them, there was "
"no acrimony, none whatsoever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1367
msgid ""
"We would finish, they’d go back to the chapter [for the textbook] and start "
"going at each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1368
msgid ""
"It was almost like Bill and Helen had a pact that they would not screw up "
"the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 350
#: sentence:1369
msgid ""
"They would screw everything else up, but they would be faithful to this.[85]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 351
#: sentence:1370
msgid "Bill continued:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1371
msgid ""
"Helen was susceptible to all this attention and massive devotion from Ken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1372
msgid ""
"It was amazing; she now had the word of Jesus and the whole thing—this was "
"it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1373
msgid "Ken thought Helen was sort of the Mother of God, the Virgin Mary."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1374
msgid "Helen thought Ken was one of the world’s greatest saints of all time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1375
msgid ""
"She would say things like, “I can’t think of any saint in history who was as"
" beatific as Ken.” So I would have lunch with the Virgin Mary and the "
"world’s greatest saint."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1376
msgid ""
"Of course, I was the world’s greatest sinner; I was the terrible guilty "
"party."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1377
msgid "I’m not sure why I was guilty; that was more obscure."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1378
msgid "But someone had to be guilty, so I was it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1379
msgid "Probably one thing was that I was not being loving enough with Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1380
msgid "I wasn’t impressed by the fact that she was the Mother of God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 352
#: sentence:1381
msgid ""
"This sort of thing went on for quite a while and I was both relieved and "
"annoyed by it all.[86]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 353
#: sentence:1382
msgid ""
"Clearly, Bill felt both replaced by Ken and, by his own acknowledgment, some"
" panic that he was not following the injunction to heal his relationship "
"with Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 353
#: sentence:1383
msgid "What would happen over that perceived failure?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 353
#: sentence:1384
msgid ""
"He also acknowledged that Ken tried to be inclusive, but the situation "
"remained difficult."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1385
msgid "Ken offers a revealing, and very different, perspective."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1386
msgid ""
"When I asked if he had felt as troubled by Bill as Bill had been by him, he "
"answered that he had not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1387
msgid ""
"He said Bill would so thoroughly hide his true feelings that he often didn’t"
" know Bill was upset with him until he heard about it from someone else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1388
msgid "He would then approach Bill to address the problem."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1389
msgid ""
"In his experience, there was very little tension between them and none at "
"all when the Course dominated their discussions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1390
msgid ""
"He acknowledged that Bill and Helen’s relationship was terrible in many "
"respects and that, indeed, it did get worse after he arrived."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1391
msgid ""
"His role was often that of a sounding board as they complained about each "
"other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 354
#: sentence:1392
msgid ""
"I asked Ken what they could still find to argue about after all those years "
"and he answered,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1393
msgid "They would recycle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1394
msgid ""
"It was always the same—you said that, and you did this, and didn’t do that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1395
msgid "I was there and I don’t even remember."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1396
msgid ""
"It didn’t matter; they had a strong love-hate relationship, they didn’t like"
" each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1397
msgid "Their personalities were so different."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1398
msgid "I’m sure they argued about me, but not in front of me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 355
#: sentence:1399
msgid "Helen would tell me about it later."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1400
msgid ""
"Helen thought Bill never fully understood the Course, so that would come up "
"occasionally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1401
msgid ""
"They would argue a lot about Bill’s choice of partners; that was a big one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1402
msgid "Then there was Harold, who lived with Bill for a year or so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1403
msgid ""
"Helen didn’t like Harold at all and let him know that in no uncertain terms."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1404
msgid ""
"Helen got very angry when Bill asked if I would see Harold [professionally],"
" which I did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1405
msgid ""
"Conversely, if one of them was in trouble or needed help, the other one "
"would be right there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1406
msgid ""
"They were very supportive of each other, very faithful to each other in that"
" way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1407
msgid "It was very strange, very unusual."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 356
#: sentence:1408
msgid "I was very struck by it.[87]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 357
#: sentence:1409
msgid ""
"Because Ken and Helen were so close, he offers an entry point into a third "
"perspective—Helen’s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1410
msgid ""
"One of the ways you could see their differences was that Helen was overtly "
"aggressive and Bill was passive aggressive; you always knew where you stood "
"with Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1411
msgid "Also, Helen was much more aware of her anger than Bill was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1412
msgid ""
"Helen was clear and she really never tried to justify it; I knew her very, "
"very well and it was kind of a given."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1413
msgid ""
"She did not forgive Bill, did not want to forgive Bill, would not forgive "
"Bill, and she wasn’t saying this was a spiritual position."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1414
msgid "Bill, on the other hand, was not aware."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1415
msgid "I can give you one example that typified the whole issue."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1416
msgid ""
"They had three offices, an outer office and their two private offices, very "
"secluded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1417
msgid "You have to picture this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1418
msgid ""
"We were sitting in Helen’s office; there was Helen and her desk, I sat "
"against the wall adjacent to her desk, and Bill would be standing in the "
"doorway, which he would do since every once in a while he would go to his "
"office and smoke."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1419
msgid "I was literally in the middle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1420
msgid ""
"Bill, who did this more often than Helen, tried to put me in the middle [of "
"their battle]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1421
msgid ""
"I don’t remember what it was about, but they were at each other’s throats."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1422
msgid ""
"They were sniping at each other, the tension was building, and Bill turned "
"to me, asking me to support him against Helen, saying something like, "
"“Wouldn’t you agree, Kenneth?” It was obvious they were both contributing, "
"but Bill, I know, was not conscious of what he was doing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1423
msgid "He was being very snide; he was wonderful with words, a master."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1424
msgid "I finessed it by saying, “Well, you’re both doing it,” which was true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1425
msgid ""
"Bill stormed out, really angry; Helen looked at me and said, “Now you see "
"what I’m up against.” She meant Bill’s being passive aggressive and not "
"knowing it; that was very, very common."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1426
msgid "He was just not aware of his own anger and how he was expressing it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1427
msgid ""
"Helen was just as much at fault, but she was right in your face, she knew "
"what she was doing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1428
msgid "Helen was clear, Bill was not, and that was often the problem."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1429
msgid ""
"Since he was so good with words, he could make a comment and not even know "
"he was doing it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 358
#: sentence:1430
msgid ""
"That particular morning typified, I think, what their relationship was like."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1431
msgid "Basically, Bill blamed Helen for problems in the relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1432
msgid "Even after Helen died, I noticed there was a lot of bitterness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1433
msgid "That’s what Helen had trouble understanding."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1434
msgid ""
"When she said Bill didn’t understand the Course, that is part of what she "
"meant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1435
msgid ""
"Somehow, he thought the relationship was not healed because Helen wouldn’t "
"change her mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1436
msgid ""
"He was always blaming her and feeling that if only Helen would change, he "
"would be healed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1437
msgid ""
"A lot of Bill’s and my discussions and our work together had to do with "
"that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1438
msgid ""
"That was a blind spot for Bill, making it impossible for him because Helen "
"was not going to change her mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1439
msgid ""
"On the other hand, she did not blame Bill for the relationship, she blamed "
"him for just being Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1440
msgid ""
"She was very clear about her own choices, how they kept the acrimony going."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1441
msgid ""
"She was brilliant, very insightful and basically said, “I’m not going to do "
"it [forgive him].” She would be very clear with people, “Do what I write, "
"not what I do.” We spent many, many hours—as an understatement—talking about"
" Bill and what she was doing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 359
#: sentence:1442
msgid ""
"What really impressed me about Bill was that, despite what he felt, there "
"was a deep sense of commitment and trust to whatever this was with "
"Helen.[88]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 360
#: sentence:1443
msgid "Helen and Bill—the good times"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 361
#: sentence:1444
msgid ""
"During the year 1965–1966, as an exception to their established norm, Helen "
"and Bill’s relationship did improve."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 361
#: sentence:1445
msgid ""
"They diligently practiced the Course lessons and, as promised, their "
"hostility lessened considerably but they didn’t keep it up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 361
#: sentence:1446
msgid ""
"Ken said, “They tried very, very hard to look at their projections, accept "
"them, and just be responsible for them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 361
#: sentence:1447
msgid ""
"I have some of their letters in my book [Absence From Felicity], plus they "
"both told me about this.[89] Then it got to be too much and they couldn’t "
"sustain it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 361
#: sentence:1448
msgid ""
"It got worse and worse, and when I met them, their relationship was at an "
"all-time low.”[90]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 362
#: sentence:1449
msgid ""
"To do them justice and to balance out the picture, however, Ken said the "
"three of them had many wonderful and funny times together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 362
#: sentence:1450
msgid ""
"They laughed a lot, kidded each other, and shared a common sense of humor "
"and total devotion to the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 362
#: sentence:1451
msgid ""
"As contradictory and nearly impossible as it sounds, they actually shared "
"great love and trust in one another that carried them through some very "
"difficult times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 362
#: sentence:1452
msgid ""
"Others around Bill and Helen also commented on their real love for one "
"another, though it was often eclipsed by their antagonism."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 363
#: sentence:1453
msgid ""
"When Ken returned to New York from Israel in April 1973, exactly how he was "
"going to be included in this monumental project was a bit unclear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 363
#: sentence:1454
msgid ""
"Since Ken was now frequently in their offices, Bill found him a part-time "
"job to justify his spending so much time there, observing normal protocol as"
" much as possible to avoid arousing suspicion about their hidden work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 363
#: sentence:1455
msgid ""
"As Ken looked over the previously edited material, now referred to as the "
"Hugh Lynn Cayce version (so named because Helen and Bill had made a copy for"
" Hugh Lynn and presented it to him as a gift in gratitude for his "
"considerable support and encouragement), he felt additional work was needed "
"and he was correct.[91] Helen and Bill had already gone through the text "
"more than once, and though they had removed much personal material as well "
"as references to Freud, Jung, Cayce, and several friends and colleagues, the"
" capitalization was inconsistent, some section headings were not clear, and "
"some personal information remained."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 363
#: sentence:1456
msgid ""
"Bill was burned out by the initial editing process, but he recognized the "
"need for more and had been urging Helen, although with ambivalence, for "
"several months to join him in renewing the process; she refused."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 363
#: sentence:1457
msgid ""
"Now, however, with growing admiration for Ken—tireless, enthusiastic, and "
"ready to serve her completely—she was persuaded to start another round of "
"editing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 364
#: sentence:1458
msgid ""
"When ACIM dictation first began, Bill and Helen had no idea what was "
"unfolding; they presumed it was a long and comprehensive answer to their "
"request for a better way to live."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 364
#: sentence:1459
msgid ""
"Therefore, Helen wrote everything as it appeared in her mind without "
"discrimination. Why not?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 364
#: sentence:1460
msgid "After all, it was for them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 364
#: sentence:1461
msgid ""
"Bill often had a list of questions for Helen to ask the Voice, and answering"
" them seemed helpful in facilitating her ability to receive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 364
#: sentence:1462
msgid ""
"As the material continued to appear, it became clear that some of it was not"
" intended to be part of the Course itself, but was personal advice, answers "
"to specific questions, something of a three-way conversation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 364
#: sentence:1463
msgid ""
"Now it is obvious that the nonpersonal Course is for anyone who chooses to "
"practice it, but that did not dawn on them until the Voice settled into a "
"monologue format, rather than the dialogue that seemed predominant in the "
"early text."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 365
#: sentence:1464
msgid ""
"As various versions of the Course have become available since the original "
"publication in 1976, controversy has surfaced over who did what kind of "
"editing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 365
#: sentence:1465
msgid ""
"Judith Skutch Whitson remarked that although she was not yet involved during"
" the time of the editing, she was included in subsequent decisions that "
"characterized Bill and Helen’s interactions:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1466
msgid "Helen was totally in charge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1467
msgid ""
"Bill made suggestions gently, Ken sat by quietly and unobtrusively, and "
"Helen would “rule the roost.” For those who promote the idea that Ken made "
"all the final decisions and had final editorial approval, quite the opposite"
" was the case."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1468
msgid ""
"I remember during the proofreading of the “blues” [final copy before "
"printing], when challenges to inappropriate capitalizations were made, Ken "
"would just shrug and Helen would always get her way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1469
msgid "The same was true even when it came to the color of the book’s cover."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1470
msgid ""
"Bill and I wanted blue; Ken also felt that would be an appropriate color, "
"but Helen was adamant about black and would not change her mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1471
msgid ""
"Finally Ken quietly queried if we should ask the book’s Author for a "
"decision."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1472
msgid ""
"Helen made a sour face but agreed that we should be silent, ask the "
"question, and listen for the answer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 366
#: sentence:1473
msgid ""
"When we opened our eyes, she muttered, “Okay, he says blue, but a very dark "
"blue!” And so, for the cloth-covered first edition, it was a very dark blue "
"indeed.[92]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 367
#: sentence:1474
msgid ""
"Ken confirmed Helen’s position as “ruler of the roost” and said absolutely "
"no one, not even the Author of the Course, could persuade her to take "
"another position once her mind was made up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 368
#: sentence:1475
msgid ""
"“Ken was difficult to know at first,” Bill writes of this editing time. “He "
"was always nice and he was going to work on Helen, not on me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 368
#: sentence:1476
msgid "It was a difficult triangle when the three of us were together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 368
#: sentence:1477
msgid ""
"After some exposure to all this, I told him I couldn’t stand it and I "
"thought there was a lot of spiritual grandiosity going on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 368
#: sentence:1478
msgid ""
"I didn’t think that was the spirit of the Course and I was fed up with "
"it!”[93] Though he didn’t express it directly, Bill’s early and biased "
"perception of this “difficult triangle” was that Ken talked down to him and "
"interceded between himself and Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 369
#: sentence:1479
msgid ""
"Ken returned to Israel in June 1973, but not before extracting a promise "
"from Helen that she would come over for a visit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 369
#: sentence:1480
msgid ""
"That August, Helen, Louis, and Bill joined him for what Bill described as a "
"very meaningful, magical trip—one that brought an unexplainable closure as "
"they revisited some of the places he had enjoyed on his 1953 trip."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 369
#: sentence:1481
msgid ""
"He particularly identified with the Holy Land, as well as Egypt and Greece, "
"which comes as no surprise; his various psychic and trance readings placed "
"him in those locales at major turning points in the evolution of his "
"consciousness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 370
#: sentence:1482
msgid ""
"Bill acknowledged that Ken’s help and knowledge of the country made possible"
" a much more meaningful adventure than they might have had, and he was "
"grateful for his contribution."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 370
#: sentence:1483
msgid ""
"A highlight for all of them was an extraordinary experience they shared "
"while visiting Qumran, the site where the Dead Sea scrolls were discovered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 370
#: sentence:1484
msgid "Helen suddenly shifted consciousness, as if flipping back in time:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 371
#: sentence:1485
msgid ""
"As they approached the actual area where the scrolls had been found, Helen "
"abruptly stopped, visibly shaken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 371
#: sentence:1486
msgid "She stared at the opening of the cave and suddenly burst into tears."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 371
#: sentence:1487
msgid ""
"Although Bill and Louis tried desperately to comfort her, she was unable to "
"speak for almost five minutes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 371
#: sentence:1488
msgid ""
"When she finally regained her composure, she spoke so quietly that the "
"others had to strain to hear her.[94]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 372
#: sentence:1489
msgid ""
"“This is the cave,” she said in a tremulous voice; “this is the cave where I"
" saw the scroll that said, “GOD IS.”[95] None of the others said a word; "
"there was nothing to say."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 373
#: sentence:1490
msgid ""
"A short while later, while they were breathing in the historical atmosphere "
"of the Dead Sea surroundings, Helen began musing half to herself. “You "
"know,” she said, “something’s wrong with the water level."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 373
#: sentence:1491
msgid ""
"It’s too low; it used to be much higher.” Bill, who took none of Helen’s "
"thoughts lightly, opened a guide book he had bought when they had arrived in"
" Israel and began thumbing through it. “Very interesting, Helen,” he "
"remarked. “It says here that at the time of the Essenes, the water level of "
"the Dead Sea was a good deal higher.” Everyone was quiet and finally Helen, "
"visibly moved, remarked quietly, “This is the holiest place on earth.”[96]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 374
#: sentence:1492
msgid "Chapter 7"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 375
#: sentence:1493
msgid "Life was very hard for Bill on returning home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 375
#: sentence:1494
msgid ""
"He felt depressed and lonely after the breakup of a long-term personal "
"relationship with Charles Parrish and shut out of the “special relationship”"
" that he perceived Helen and Ken were pursuing without him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 375
#: sentence:1495
msgid ""
"Bill was also increasingly dissatisfied with the absence of spiritual focus "
"in his job."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 375
#: sentence:1496
msgid ""
"He even considered leaving the medical center entirely, wanting only to "
"hurry up, complete the last clerical details of the Course, and call the "
"whole thing finished."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 375
#: sentence:1497
msgid ""
"Both Helen and Bill were clear that marketing and distribution were not "
"theirs to do once the final editing was complete in 1975, and not knowing "
"how else to proceed, Bill made twelve copies of the entire work, put them in"
" thesis binders, and locked them in the bottom drawer of his file cabinet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1498
msgid ""
"Obviously, this monumental work was not destined to remain in the bottom "
"drawer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1499
msgid ""
"In the spring of 1975, through a serendipitous series of events, Bill and "
"Helen placed ACIM into the capable hands of Judith Skutch (Whitson), who "
"became the undisputed matriarch of A Course In Miracles and ultimately "
"provided for its publication and widespread distribution."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1500
msgid ""
"Bill had become intrigued with a new acquaintance, Douglas Dean—a scientist "
"interested in paranormal healing—and had made plans to have lunch with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1501
msgid ""
"Dean rescheduled their meeting so he could bring his friend, Judith Skutch, "
"for he felt strongly that she should accompany him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1502
msgid ""
"Judy was known as a “cosmic catalyst and den mother to parapsychology,” a "
"leader in the field of consciousness exploration and the paranormal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1503
msgid ""
"On May 29, 1975, Judy, Douglas, Helen, Bill, and Ken had lunch in the "
"faculty dining room at Columbia."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1504
msgid ""
"During lunch, as their conversation evolved, Judy found herself unexpectedly"
" saying to Helen, “You’re hearing a voice, aren’t you?” Everyone was "
"stunned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 376
#: sentence:1505
msgid ""
"Therefore, after lunch in the privacy of Bill’s office, the three "
"collaborators showed Judy and Douglas the Course, still a secret known only "
"to a handful of people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 377
#: sentence:1506
msgid "We gave a copy to Judy to take home and read."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 377
#: sentence:1507
msgid ""
"Apparently, that evening when she began reading the Course, she couldn’t put"
" it down and read it the night through."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 377
#: sentence:1508
msgid "She was overwhelmed with the Course’s material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 377
#: sentence:1509
msgid ""
"Helen and I liked Judy immediately, and we all—she, Ken, and I—became fast "
"friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 377
#: sentence:1510
msgid "Judy’s arrival on the scene was both fortuitous and miraculous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 377
#: sentence:1511
msgid ""
"She had a very specific role, although we didn’t know it in the "
"beginning.[97]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1512
msgid ""
"Almost immediately, Judy became an integral part of the ACIM enterprise, and"
" Ken, Helen, and Bill spent more and more time at the Skutch home in "
"Manhattan."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1513
msgid ""
"Shortly after their meeting, they began to discuss the possibility of "
"publishing the material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1514
msgid ""
"Bill and Helen would not have tackled this on their own, but Judy had the "
"necessary skill and enthusiasm, and it became a serious consideration."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1515
msgid ""
"They showed the work to several friends possibly interested in publishing "
"it, but all wanted to change it in some way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1516
msgid ""
"As with every decision related to the Course, they jointly consulted their "
"guidance and were told to leave it intact and publish it themselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1517
msgid ""
"They questioned this advice from a financial perspective but were told to "
"commit and trust. They did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 378
#: sentence:1518
msgid ""
"The day after committing to its publication, Judy received a call from Reed "
"Erickson, a satisfied and inspired student (of a xeroxed copy), who said he "
"felt ACIM needed to be published officially and that he was sending a check "
"for $60,000 to fund the first five thousand sets. (Originally, the text, "
"workbook, and teacher’s manual were bound as separate books and later "
"combined into one volume.)"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 379
#: sentence:1519
msgid ""
"Several years before their meeting, Judy and her husband at the time, Robert"
" Skutch, had founded a nonprofit organization, the Foundation for "
"Parasensory Investigation, to help fund research for parapsychology."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 379
#: sentence:1520
msgid ""
"Deciding that name did not convey the purpose of ACIM, they all agreed to "
"retitle it the Foundation for Inner Peace, and in 1975 Helen entrusted to it"
" the copyright to A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 379
#: sentence:1521
msgid ""
"As of October 2003, the original copyright entered into the public domain."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 379
#: sentence:1522
msgid ""
"However, the Foundation for Inner Peace, the parent organization, and its "
"sister organization, the Foundation for A Course In Miracles, are the "
"repositories of all original archival materials."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 380
#: sentence:1523
msgid ""
"With Judy now on the scene, the trio had evolved into a quartet and the "
"dynamics changed quite dramatically."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 380
#: sentence:1524
msgid ""
"The anger between Bill and Helen was not healed, but it was diffused and "
"deflected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 380
#: sentence:1525
msgid ""
"An alliance was formed with Bill clearly allying himself with Judy and "
"against Helen. (This does not imply Judy was against Helen, quite the "
"contrary.) Ken recalls:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1526
msgid "Bill became a big supporter of Judy’s; they were very, very close."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1527
msgid ""
"Since I was identified with Helen, it’s as if sides had been chosen as far "
"as they were concerned, and Helen would get annoyed if I spent time with "
"Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1528
msgid "She withdrew more and more."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1529
msgid "She and Bill argued less because he wasn’t around as much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1530
msgid ""
"He spent more and more time with Judy and I spent more time with Helen and "
"Louis."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1531
msgid ""
"We would meet at Judy’s apartment, then Helen and I would go home and Bill "
"would stay."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1532
msgid ""
"From his point of view, Judy was a breath of fresh air; he was very "
"comfortable with her, enjoying a relationship that didn’t include Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1533
msgid ""
"Helen had her own relationship with Judy, who was now sometimes the "
"recipient of her anger, but still they were close."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1534
msgid ""
"When both Bill and Judy moved to the West Coast in 1978, that was the end as"
" far as Helen was concerned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1535
msgid ""
"She was very bitter about that, but I think Bill felt a sense of freedom."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1536
msgid "That’s when everything changed for him, like he was let out of prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1537
msgid ""
"But again, to Helen’s credit, she was always well aware of what she was "
"doing and that made dealing with her easier in a way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1538
msgid "She was very possessive of me and other people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1539
msgid ""
"She was furious at Bill, but in fact she knew that I knew, and I knew that "
"she knew, and we really didn’t talk much about it because what’s the point?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 381
#: sentence:1540
msgid "That’s how she was, how she wanted to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1541
msgid "I think when Judy came along they were very happy to step back."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1542
msgid ""
"They both felt comfortable turning the reins over to her and gave a big sigh"
" of relief, “Okay we’re done.” They both made the decision and it was not "
"right or wrong, it’s just what they did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1543
msgid ""
"Bill felt a clear sense of mission and purpose for this Course; Helen felt "
"that, too, and they were very faithful to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1544
msgid ""
"However, they did not see that they had to be faithful to each other in the "
"sense of healing the relationship and they did not feel their role included "
"anything else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1545
msgid ""
"I think it was unfortunate that they abdicated all responsibility for the "
"Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1546
msgid ""
"They gave it to Judy to take to the world and basically withdrew from any "
"kind of leadership or authority."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1547
msgid "If they hadn’t, the Course would have gone a different way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1548
msgid ""
"Although nothing is better nor worse, there are alternate scripts and I "
"think there was clearly a script for Helen, Bill, and myself to have more of"
" a sense of responsibility for shepherding the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1549
msgid ""
"It was also very clear to me that Helen could have written down more things,"
" but she refused."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1550
msgid ""
"Bill, as you know, . . . had such conflict over being an authority, being a "
"teacher, that he went the other way—he became a nonauthority."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1551
msgid ""
"It was always bizarre when we had those meetings and Bill said nothing as "
"the most outrageous things were being said."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1552
msgid "Not that he had to say something, but it was clear he chose not to."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1553
msgid "I think it was a real fear of being an authority, which he was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1554
msgid ""
"Until that meeting in Hawaii in 1985 [a one-time workshop featuring the "
"early Course “family” sponsored by the Unity Church in Honolulu], I had "
"never heard him speak publicly with a prepared talk, rather than simply "
"answering questions, and he was masterful, very funny, very good, a "
"wonderful voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1555
msgid "But seeing his fear of standing up and professing, that never left me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 382
#: sentence:1556
msgid ""
"He had a wonderful presence, was a wonderful speaker, but he chose not to do"
" it, and Helen, who was not afraid of teaching—she was an excellent "
"teacher—nonetheless, did not want any more of this Course.[98]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 383
#: sentence:1557
msgid ""
"Bill was innately a private person, an introvert, so he chose not to draw "
"attention to himself or seek publicity, although privately he was happy with"
" his accomplishments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 383
#: sentence:1558
msgid ""
"He avoided everything that would bring him notoriety related to ACIM; he "
"gave very few interviews for print media about the Course and did not make "
"TV appearances or write books under his own name, although he substantively "
"assisted others with theirs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 383
#: sentence:1559
msgid ""
"Until the end of their lives, neither Bill nor Helen had any desire to be in"
" the spotlight; they consistently withdrew from public attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 384
#: sentence:1560
msgid ""
"By the mid 1970s, the Course was finished and its next phase was unfolding "
"with Judy at the helm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 384
#: sentence:1561
msgid ""
"The four principals—Judy, Bill, Helen, and Ken—had established a pattern of "
"meeting regularly at the Skutch apartment in the late afternoons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 384
#: sentence:1562
msgid ""
"Judy confirms Ken’s observations that when Bill and Helen were working on "
"their scholastic endeavors—about 90 percent of their time—hostility was the "
"norm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 384
#: sentence:1563
msgid ""
"However, when they were involved with Course dictation and transcription, or"
" what needed to be done with it, they were of one mind, merging as “Bilen,” "
"a contraction of Bill and Helen denoting their beautiful sense of communion "
"and shared purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 384
#: sentence:1564
msgid ""
"So there were times during those late afternoon meetings when all was "
"tranquil and others when it most certainly was not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 385
#: sentence:1565
msgid ""
"On more than one occasion at the Skutches, as tension between them would "
"mount, Bill could keep his composure sufficiently to make light of the "
"situation, diffusing it before it became a problem with yet another "
"application of his quick wit and grand sense of humor. Judy recalls:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 386
#: sentence:1566
msgid ""
"Bill was taking a break from some intense stuff, and then we decided there "
"should be a musical of ACIM and Bill started to make up songs based on "
"different shows."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 386
#: sentence:1567
msgid ""
"Bill announced that as a take-off on Call Me Madam, they would present one "
"called Call Me Mad, whereupon he gave Helen, who had a beautiful operatic-"
"type singing voice, her lines:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 387
#: sentence:1568
msgid ""
"I hear voices but there’s no one there, I hear voices but the room is bare."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 388
#: sentence:1569
msgid "Then Bill would enter with his little soft-shoe dance number, singing:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 389
#: sentence:1570
msgid "You sure need analyzing and it’s not so surprisin’"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 390
#: sentence:1571
msgid "and they would sing their parts contrapuntally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 390
#: sentence:1572
msgid ""
"Bill’s impromptu musical numbers provided those rare occasions when Helen "
"could not contain her laughter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 390
#: sentence:1573
msgid ""
"Though perhaps unwilling to give credit, they each recognized the other’s "
"beautiful singing voice, but only under those circumstances did they ever "
"sing together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 390
#: sentence:1574
msgid ""
"Both of them adored Gilbert and Sullivan musicals and both were very "
"articulate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 390
#: sentence:1575
msgid ""
"Bill could kid around at my house, though never at the office, and "
"periodically, to everyone’s delight, he would add characters to the ACIM "
"“musical.”[99]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 391
#: sentence:1576
msgid "What a loss that the words were never recorded for posterity!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 392
#: sentence:1577
msgid ""
"On other occasions, not even Bill’s sense of humor was enough to end a "
"dispute."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 392
#: sentence:1578
msgid ""
"When he reached the end of his rope, he would simply walk out of the room in"
" a wave of passive aggression, an act of stinging rejection."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 392
#: sentence:1579
msgid ""
"During those moments, he must have been driven to uncontrollable distress, "
"because virtually everyone I’ve spoken with has commented on Bill’s extreme "
"patience with Helen as she acted out her more preposterous ego positions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 392
#: sentence:1580
msgid "At other times, their personal war would escalate even further."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 392
#: sentence:1581
msgid "Judy remembers the following example in vivid detail:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1582
msgid ""
"Bill, Helen, Ken, and I were in our New York apartment late one afternoon, a"
" sparkling, unusually clear October day."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1583
msgid ""
"It was so impressive that everyone had considered going for a walk, but it "
"never materialized."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1584
msgid "We were talking and Helen and Bill got into a scrap."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1585
msgid ""
"They were sitting next to each other on a loveseat opposite where Ken and I "
"were sitting, and it was like watching two cats suddenly rear up their backs"
" and spit at each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1586
msgid "Characteristically, Helen would attack and Bill would defend."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1587
msgid ""
"Finally, the words were flying and Ken knew enough to get up, kindly take "
"Bill by the arm, and guide him out on our back landing for a smoke."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1588
msgid "Bill was smoking up a storm in those days."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1589
msgid ""
"Helen stood up—she was very erect for a tiny person as she deliberately "
"practiced her posture—and she was seething!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1590
msgid "Her fists were clinched and her shoulders heaved with rage."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1591
msgid ""
"She went to the window and looked out at Central Park, a happy, busy, "
"peaceful scene—people riding bikes, mothers and children, nannies, dogs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1592
msgid ""
"She was looking but seeing nothing, just looking out the window and shaking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 393
#: sentence:1593
msgid ""
"I made the mistake of putting my arm around her shoulder and said, “Mama "
"(she liked for me to call her Mama), why can’t you be a little nicer to "
"him?” which was really a dumb thing to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 394
#: sentence:1594
msgid ""
"Of course, I was so uncomfortable as I had just witnessed the “parents” "
"fighting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 394
#: sentence:1595
msgid ""
"Helen turned on me and lifted her hands like a cat, almost to rake her very "
"long, well-kept, manicured nails—this day painted red—down my cheek, saying,"
" “You stupid, stupid child!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 394
#: sentence:1596
msgid "Don’t you know I would have followed him to the ends of the earth?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 394
#: sentence:1597
msgid ""
"I would have left everything, my work, my life, everything to be with him "
"wherever he said, and he didn’t want me![100]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 395
#: sentence:1598
msgid ""
"A perfect example of the incisive observation: “Hell hath no fury like a "
"woman scorned!”[101]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 396
#: sentence:1599
msgid "Judy continued, rhetorically, with a smile:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1600
msgid "So what would the Holy Spirit do with something like that?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1601
msgid ""
"It’s as if He said, “You know you can’t have him; I can’t do that for you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1602
msgid "However, I can keep him tied to you the rest of your life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1603
msgid "How would you like to write A Course In Miracles?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1604
msgid ""
"I’m going to give you a little bit every day and he’s going to be so "
"intrigued, believe me, he’ll never leave you.” There was all this furious, "
"romantic rage and fantasy life, a lot of fantasy life, in her mind with "
"Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1605
msgid "This was not the only time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 397
#: sentence:1606
msgid ""
"I once saw this same rage come out with Ken, where she literally scratched "
"him, drawing blood, over his leaving for a counseling appointment when she "
"wanted him to remain.[102]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 398
#: sentence:1607
msgid ""
"Years later, when the Skutches and Bill, after much consideration, moved to "
"California, Helen was so angry she wouldn’t talk."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 398
#: sentence:1608
msgid ""
"As they walked out the door, she said jealously to Judy, “I always knew you "
"would take him away from me!”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1609
msgid ""
"Helen and Bill’s particular function of bringing the Course into the world "
"did not give them a free pass to enlightenment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1610
msgid ""
"To benefit from the life-altering change of perspective taught through the "
"Course, they would have to practice like everyone else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1611
msgid ""
"At this point, both their lives were certifiably a mess despite their "
"brilliance and accomplishments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1612
msgid "And all who feel hopeless, take note: Their egos were just like ours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1613
msgid ""
"Revealing their “dark sides” encourages us to do the same to facilitate our "
"healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1614
msgid ""
"It is fascinating and reassuring to know that from such intractable "
"egocentricity, the Course, one of the most beautiful and profound teachings "
"on earth, sprang forth easily and without compromise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1615
msgid ""
"Helen and Bill, despite fearing they were not healing as they should, "
"steadfastly set aside their egos to produce it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1616
msgid ""
"Even in the midst of her frequent panic, Helen could completely suspend her "
"ego and allow herself to enter into her right mind where the material "
"existed already complete."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1617
msgid "Carefully and with great integrity, she listened and scribed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1618
msgid ""
"It seems she could move back and forth between her ego and spirit, her wrong"
" and right mind, with more skill than almost anyone on the planet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 399
#: sentence:1619
msgid "For her, the veil was very thin."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 400
#: sentence:1620
msgid "Bill tried to define this most conflicted relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 400
#: sentence:1621
msgid ""
"He always commented on his open and easy relationship with Louis, with "
"nothing clouding their friendship, but lamented the difficulty he "
"encountered with Helen despite his fascination with her “inner life” and his"
" deep trust and respect for her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 400
#: sentence:1622
msgid "He also actually loved her very much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 400
#: sentence:1623
msgid ""
"It sounds similar to LeRoy Zemke’s comment about their enduring love for one"
" another."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1624
msgid "On the other hand, my relationship with Helen was so complicated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1625
msgid ""
"I think I learned from it that love would persist despite everything that "
"seemed to block it and interfere with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1626
msgid ""
"I was aware of feeling close to Helen at some level that transcended "
"rationality and relationship barriers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1627
msgid "It seemed to go against any form of logic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1628
msgid ""
"I wasn’t that fond of Helen, but there was a deep love that continued in "
"spite of everything."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1629
msgid "It had nothing to do with anything."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1630
msgid "It seemed to represent our joining in love and cooperation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1631
msgid "We tried to do something that transcended our egos."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1632
msgid ""
"That was the thing that seemed real, the only thing that seemed really to "
"persist."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1633
msgid "Once having done that, there was no breaking away from it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1634
msgid "It was a commitment that went on forever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1635
msgid ""
"If love is eternal, when you make that kind of commitment, you have made it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 401
#: sentence:1636
msgid ""
"It doesn’t have anything to do with the usual things about commitments.[103]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 402
#: sentence:1637
msgid ""
"In retrospect, every position, encounter, and opportunity was essential for "
"Bill’s evolution, enabling him to tackle the huge assignment they had "
"accepted, one they both recognized as a prior agreement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 402
#: sentence:1638
msgid ""
"We can view our lives the same way, recognizing that each encounter and "
"situation is not an accident, but part of our individualized curriculum for "
"awakening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 402
#: sentence:1639
msgid ""
"Helen was not the villain, nor was the absent father or any of the “learning"
" partners” who paraded through Bill’s life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 403
#: sentence:1640
msgid ""
"Early conditioning promotes the belief that our particular strong "
"suits—those areas of vocation and avocation that come so naturally—our "
"possessions, friends or family, and everything else exist for our own self-"
"aggrandizement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 403
#: sentence:1641
msgid "The Course’s aim is to undo that perspective."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 403
#: sentence:1642
msgid "It encourages us always to ask, “What is this for?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 403
#: sentence:1643
msgid ""
"How are we using these gifts?” Bill developed talents and acquired "
"experience, as do we all, and was motivated by ACIM’s teachings to move from"
" a sense of specialness—the desire to appropriate his particular portfolio "
"of talents for personal gain—to his own unique special function, using those"
" same gifts for a higher purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 403
#: sentence:1644
msgid ""
"This shift in purpose provides the ideal opportunity for the unfolding of "
"our own service and, thus, for maximal healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 404
#: sentence:1645
msgid ""
"Such is the Holy Spirit’s kind perception of specialness; His use of what "
"you made, to heal instead of harm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 404
#: sentence:1646
msgid ""
"To each He gives a special function in salvation he alone can fill; a part "
"for only him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 404
#: sentence:1647
msgid ""
"Nor is the plan complete until he finds his special function, and fulfills "
"the part assigned to him, to make himself complete within a world where "
"incompletion rules. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 405
#: sentence:1648
msgid "Yet while in time, there is still much to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 405
#: sentence:1649
msgid ""
"And each must do what is allotted him, for on his part does all the plan "
"depend."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 405
#: sentence:1650
msgid ""
"He has a special part in time for so he chose, and choosing it, he made it "
"for himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 405
#: sentence:1651
msgid ""
"His wish was not denied but changed in form, to let it serve his brother and"
" himself, and thus become a means to save instead of lose.[104]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1652
msgid "One might reasonably ask, “What kind of healing?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1653
msgid ""
"I’m not sick.” A Course In Miracles reminds us that, indeed, our minds are "
"sick; we engage daily in judgmental, unloving, defensive thoughts and "
"behaviors that specifically interfere with our happiness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1654
msgid ""
"We need take only a cursory, unbiased look at the condition of the world to "
"know that something is terribly wrong."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1655
msgid ""
"It appears to be the domain of pain and suffering, and for most, that is the"
" case."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1656
msgid "ACIM teaches, however, this need not be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1657
msgid ""
"Our beliefs, attitudes, self-absorption, and attachment to having our way, "
"our unconscious programming, our endless attack, all can and must be changed"
" if we are to be free of insecurity and lack."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 406
#: sentence:1658
msgid "And it shows us how."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 407
#: sentence:1659
msgid ""
"Bill was determined to heal his attitudes and practice shifting his purpose "
"from specialness to special function, changing his mind from fear to love "
"and from holding resentments to doing no harm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 407
#: sentence:1660
msgid ""
"Like everyone, he began with a divided or compromised dedication, but the "
"Course promises that only a little willingness is required to move from our "
"fixed, unhelpful perspectives to those that bring peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 407
#: sentence:1661
msgid ""
"It would have been understandable for Bill to retire once ACIM was finished,"
" to rest on his academic laurels, congratulating himself for a job well "
"done, and such a path would certainly have been deserved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 407
#: sentence:1662
msgid "But that was not to be his choice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 407
#: sentence:1663
msgid ""
"So, fortified with a little willingness, Bill began to move away from his "
"role of esteemed professor and to redefine his primary goal as the practice "
"of forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 408
#: sentence:1664
msgid "Chapter 8"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1665
msgid "As with all chapters, Bill’s time in New York was coming to a close."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1666
msgid ""
"ACIM was finished and Helen, fourteen years his senior, had finally retired."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1667
msgid ""
"He had managed to keep her employed past the usual retirement age of sixty-"
"five to finish the last Course details."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1668
msgid ""
"Before they had contemplated its publication, Bill had applied for and been "
"granted a six-month sabbatical to begin in July 1976."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1669
msgid ""
"Through no intentional planning, the first edition of ACIM made its debut "
"the month before, in June 1976."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1670
msgid ""
"With the next stage of the Course’s history unfolding, coupled with the fact"
" that it was a difficult time at the university in general, it was a great "
"time to leave."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1671
msgid ""
"Bill felt he simply could not stay at Columbia now that their “guilty "
"secret,” as they called it, was out in the open, a potentially awkward "
"situation for everyone else concerned, as well. (He did not specifically "
"attempt to conceal or reveal his association with ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1672
msgid ""
"Some colleagues found out about it through conversation or the few articles "
"ultimately written about the work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 409
#: sentence:1673
msgid ""
"Others may never have found out.) He had been through a ten-year, life-"
"altering, spiritual overhaul, and to resume his work with traditional "
"psychology as though nothing had happened, no matter how proficient he was, "
"would have been an impossible backward step."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 410
#: sentence:1674
msgid ""
"Bill had labored diligently on the PAS for approximately twenty "
"years—teaching, mentoring, researching, writing papers, and teasing out "
"every available bit of insight into how human beings predictably operate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 410
#: sentence:1675
msgid "Nevertheless, he closed that door, too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 410
#: sentence:1676
msgid ""
"He gave up his research on the ego, which he considered his major academic "
"contribution, as he and Helen became immersed in scribing and attempting to "
"practice ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 410
#: sentence:1677
msgid "The Course had dealt a devastating blow to his favorite topic:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 411
#: sentence:1678
msgid ""
"If you believe you understand something of the “dynamics” of the ego, let me"
" assure you that you understand nothing of it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 411
#: sentence:1679
msgid "For of yourself you could not understand it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 411
#: sentence:1680
msgid "The study of the ego is not the study of your mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 411
#: sentence:1681
msgid ""
"In fact, the ego enjoys studying itself, and thoroughly approves the "
"undertakings of students who would “analyze” it, thus approving its "
"importance.[105]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 412
#: sentence:1682
msgid ""
"After years of statements like this, Bill could feel the foundations of his "
"academic life collapsing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 412
#: sentence:1683
msgid ""
"Finally, he found it too bizarre and contradictory to research the "
"intricacies of how egos form and operate on one hand and to actively "
"practice undoing them on the other. He abandoned his search."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 412
#: sentence:1684
msgid ""
"As Whit Whitson stated at Bill’s memorial service, “At the same time he was "
"mapping the ego, he was channeling the process by which we could escape—like"
" mapping an earthquake and then making a plan for how to get out of "
"it.”[106]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1685
msgid ""
"As his sabbatical was ending in early 1977, Bill took a leave of absence, "
"then applied for another, but the second one was denied."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1686
msgid ""
"He now had to make a final decision to stay or leave. He chose to leave."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1687
msgid ""
"Because he had started at Columbia in February 1958, he was eligible for "
"early retirement beginning in 1978."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1688
msgid ""
"Thus, after beginning his sabbatical in mid 1976, he never returned to his "
"academic or administrative duties."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1689
msgid ""
"During that period of being employed but not actively working, he made "
"several trips to California, at Judy’s invitation, to meet with groups about"
" the Course. (Helen also participated in a few of them, although under "
"protest because she strongly disliked traveling.) These trips planted the "
"seed in Bill and introduced the possibility of leaving not only Columbia, "
"but New York itself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1690
msgid ""
"The Skutches were entertaining the idea of moving to Tiburon because Judy "
"planned to work on her Ph.D. in San Francisco and, additionally, she knew "
"many people in the Bay area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1691
msgid ""
"Also, Jerry Jampolsky, a close friend of Judy’s, was a long-time resident of"
" Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1692
msgid ""
"During those visits, Bill realized that both Jerry and Judy needed help with"
" their personal lives and that living close to them would be ideal for "
"offering his assistance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 413
#: sentence:1693
msgid "This provided a pivotal rationale for moving."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 414
#: sentence:1694
msgid ""
"As he weighed his options, Bill also had to confront his fear about leaving "
"his secure, tenured position, one not easily attained."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 414
#: sentence:1695
msgid ""
"In addition to his fine reputation and the prestige of being associated with"
" Columbia, he was financially secure."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 414
#: sentence:1696
msgid ""
"Now he wavered as he looked at giving it all up, like standing with one foot"
" on each side of an ever-widening chasm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 414
#: sentence:1697
msgid ""
"It was that branching of the road we all come to eventually and he chose the"
" California path."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 415
#: sentence:1698
msgid ""
"Besides leaving academia behind, Bill also cut ties with most of his friends"
" and, obviously, the New York lifestyle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 415
#: sentence:1699
msgid ""
"He notes his propensity for leaving finished eras behind. “I talked about it"
" [the Course] when it was necessary and then I would leave."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 415
#: sentence:1700
msgid "Probably a lot of my life has been that way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 415
#: sentence:1701
msgid ""
"I do whatever I think is necessary at the time and then I withdraw from it "
"all.”[107] In characteristic fashion, he abandoned his life, his career, the"
" person he had been, like a suit of clothes left hanging in the closet. That"
" time was over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 416
#: sentence:1702
msgid ""
"ACIM states: “Fear not that you will be abruptly lifted up and hurled into "
"reality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 416
#: sentence:1703
msgid ""
"Time is kind, and if you use it on behalf of reality, it will keep gentle "
"pace with you in your transition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 416
#: sentence:1704
msgid ""
"The urgency is only in dislodging your mind from its fixed position "
"here.”[108] I think Bill often felt that, indeed, he had been picked up and "
"hurled into California by some volition not his own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 416
#: sentence:1705
msgid ""
"Leaving New York was wrenching, even though he was following his excellent "
"guidance in making the choice, the right and inevitable one for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 416
#: sentence:1706
msgid ""
"New York had been the center of Bill’s world even during his early days in "
"Washington, D.C., when he frequently traveled there on weekends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 417
#: sentence:1707
msgid ""
"As a sophisticated easterner, he did not fit the casual California "
"stereotype, but he traded his daily coat and tie for jeans and a sweater and"
" prepared to enter this new phase of his life, even if somewhat reluctantly "
"at first."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 417
#: sentence:1708
msgid ""
"As with the end of any life chapter, there was a sense of loss and some "
"grief at the prospect of leaving New York, but predictably, he found cause "
"for warm good humor regarding his new home, often joking about the "
"California lifestyle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 418
#: sentence:1709
msgid ""
"During the time of Bill’s sabbatical and leave-taking, Jim Bolen—a friend of"
" Judy’s, devoted Course student, and editor of a popular magazine, "
"Psychic—wanted to publish an article about ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 418
#: sentence:1710
msgid ""
"Bill and Helen felt it would be misleading to have it appear in a "
"publication with that name, so at Bill’s suggestion it was renamed New "
"Realities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 418
#: sentence:1711
msgid ""
"The article appeared in April 1977, and the response was overwhelming and "
"widespread."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 418
#: sentence:1712
msgid ""
"What remained of the first five thousand sets of the Course, printed a year "
"earlier with Reed Erickson’s generous donation, quickly sold out, requiring "
"an immediate second printing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 418
#: sentence:1713
msgid ""
"Thousands of letters and inquiries flooded in, indicating ACIM’s immense "
"impact on those first readers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 418
#: sentence:1714
msgid ""
"With the word out far and wide, Bill, for better or worse, would never again"
" enjoy anonymity regarding his role in birthing the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1715
msgid ""
"In the spring of 1978, a friend gave our family a subscription to New "
"Realities magazine and the inaugural issue featuring A Course In Miracles "
"arrived soon after."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1716
msgid "As for many, it was my introduction to the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1717
msgid ""
"For many years, I had been looking for answers to only vaguely defined "
"questions, reading endlessly, gradually getting in touch with feelings, "
"looking more honestly at my motivations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1718
msgid ""
"I was fascinated with this article, and when I read the Introduction to the "
"text, something in me responded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1719
msgid "I could feel the power, the truth, and life coming through the words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1720
msgid ""
"I ordered the books, and when I finally held the newly delivered, unopened "
"package, I knew without question that this was my way home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 419
#: sentence:1721
msgid ""
"I had no clue about the enormity of the shift that was bound to take place; "
"I only knew that my search was over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 420
#: sentence:1722
msgid ""
"I often tell students that “one’s life has a life of its own” and Bill’s was"
" no exception, nor was mine."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 420
#: sentence:1723
msgid ""
"During the year Bill was closing the doors on New York, I was devouring the "
"Course as the most amazing work I had ever encountered. It was literally "
"irresistible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 420
#: sentence:1724
msgid ""
"Second in importance only to raising my children, it became the most all-"
"encompassing element in my life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 420
#: sentence:1725
msgid ""
"In May 1978, on the last of Bill’s several cross-country trips to finalize "
"his move from New York to Tiburon, our paths crossed in Denver, Colorado, my"
" home at that time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 420
#: sentence:1726
msgid "My life would never be the same again."
msgstr ""

