#. Paragraph 530
#: sentence:1845
msgid "The early Tiburon years"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 531
#: sentence:1846
msgid "Chapter 9"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 532
#: sentence:1847
msgid ""
"This section includes some of my own personal experiences with Bill, along "
"with those of others, since we met at the point of his transition from New "
"York to California."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 532
#: sentence:1848
msgid ""
"After twenty-three years in New York, this was a major disruption for him, "
"and our time together seemed to be about helping him anchor into his new "
"home, accept his role with ACIM, and begin his final healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1849
msgid ""
"In the early spring of 1978, I received a brochure from the Association of "
"Humanistic Psychology (as I was not a member, I had never before received a "
"mailing from them, nor did I ever again) about their regional conference to "
"be held in Denver, featuring the publisher of A Course In Miracles, Judith "
"Skutch (Whitson)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1850
msgid ""
"Most captivating of all, it stated that Bill Thetford would also be there, "
"though not as a presenter. I was thrilled."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1851
msgid "By that time, I had been a devoted Course student for nine months."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1852
msgid ""
"I loved it and would have gone to any lengths to meet anyone involved with "
"ACIM, especially Bill or Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1853
msgid ""
"On the appointed evening, my husband Bob and I arrived at Regis College, the"
" conference location, and were surprised to find folding chairs and a "
"temporary stage set up outside, an ill-considered decision as May evenings "
"in Colorado can be very cold; there had been no mention of an outdoor event "
"in the brochure."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1854
msgid ""
"We greatly enjoyed Judy’s spirited presentation, which confirmed that ACIM "
"was, indeed, a world-class enterprise, despite no sign of Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 533
#: sentence:1855
msgid ""
"Since it was growing colder by the minute and I had brought only a "
"lightweight sweater, I left shortly before the end of the presentation and "
"headed for the nearest building."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1856
msgid ""
"On entering, I saw a tall, attractive man standing alone to one side of a "
"large reception area and instantly knew it was Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1857
msgid ""
"And in that same instant, looking into those indescribable eyes, I felt an "
"immediate and ancient recognition, a connection unlike any I had ever "
"experienced before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1858
msgid ""
"The sense of familiarity I had felt with the Course was amplified "
"severalfold on seeing him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1859
msgid ""
"I introduced myself, thanking him for all he had done to bring this "
"marvelous work forward."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1860
msgid ""
"In those delicious ten minutes before everyone else succumbed to the cold "
"and came indoors, I had the opportunity to visit with him but, more "
"important, to be in his powerful yet totally unassuming presence. Words fail"
" here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1861
msgid ""
"He seemed to be a man with no mask, no pretense, nothing to hide, and no "
"agenda to pursue, and he made no attempt to be impressive, or anything else,"
" for that matter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1862
msgid ""
"He was simply present—a graceful, authentic human being, a rarity in my "
"experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1863
msgid ""
"As we spoke for those few minutes before the crowd discovered him, I was "
"enchanted by his beautiful voice, although I cannot remember a word he said."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1864
msgid ""
"Anyone fortunate enough to have heard Bill speak, especially in person, "
"knows the healing quality of his lovely bass voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 534
#: sentence:1865
msgid ""
"After we shared a brief good-bye, I rode home in silence, spellbound and "
"intensely moved by this instant heart-to-heart connection with a seeming "
"“stranger.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 535
#: sentence:1866
msgid ""
"Tiburon, California—a progressive, upscale community with gorgeous views of "
"the Bay area, located across the Golden Gate Bridge from San Francisco—was "
"about to become Bill’s new home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 535
#: sentence:1867
msgid ""
"Now fifty-five, he was only a few weeks away from beginning the California "
"chapter of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 535
#: sentence:1868
msgid ""
"Inwardly, he recognized there was really no choice about this move, although"
" his ego mind was still ambivalent."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 535
#: sentence:1869
msgid ""
"Only later did I discover that his stop in Denver was on the last of several"
" trips to California to finalize his moving plans."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 536
#: sentence:1870
msgid ""
"On one of his earlier visits to Tiburon, while out for his usual morning "
"walk, Bill had unexpectedly met a recent acquaintance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 536
#: sentence:1871
msgid ""
"He asked him if he knew of any apartments for rent, and the man told him one"
" was available next door to him and that it had been vacant for a while, "
"most unusual for the area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 536
#: sentence:1872
msgid ""
"Bill looked at it, declared it perfect on all accounts, and made "
"arrangements to move in."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 536
#: sentence:1873
msgid ""
"His new home was on, aptly named, Paradise Drive right across from Angel "
"Island, paralleling the water’s edge with a stunning view of San Francisco "
"Bay, and only a two-minute walk to Jerry Jampolsky’s home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 536
#: sentence:1874
msgid ""
"Dr. Gerald Jampolsky, one of the first and most influential Course "
"advocates, had founded the Center for Attitudinal Healing in Tiburon based "
"on ACIM principles in 1975."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 536
#: sentence:1875
msgid ""
"Judy and Bob Skutch, also newly transplanted from New York, were a few "
"houses on the other side of Jerry, so all were neighbors and only a short "
"walk to charming downtown Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 537
#: sentence:1876
msgid ""
"Bill’s ease of finding a place to live was hardly the first serendipitous "
"experience for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 537
#: sentence:1877
msgid ""
"In New York, the same inner direction had led him to the apartment of his "
"dreams, where he lived for eighteen of his twenty-three years there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 537
#: sentence:1878
msgid "Of an earlier “perfect house find,” Bill wrote:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 538
#: sentence:1879
msgid ""
"At the time, I didn’t pay much attention to the fact that I had experienced "
"this inner prompting because that would be unscientific; I couldn’t "
"acknowledge that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 538
#: sentence:1880
msgid ""
"However, I did make note of it and thought it might be intuition so I could "
"talk about it a little, but not too much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 538
#: sentence:1881
msgid ""
"Yet I didn’t know what to do with it and I certainly couldn’t account for "
"it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 538
#: sentence:1882
msgid ""
"This was not the first time this sort of thing had happened to me, but was a"
" major example and I couldn’t ignore it.[1]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1883
msgid ""
"So here he was in June 1978 with a tabula rasa—a blank slate for a new "
"chapter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1884
msgid ""
"Jules Finegold, a retired architect and one of Bill’s early California "
"acquaintances who became a close friend and companion, was instrumental in "
"getting him settled into his apartment, decorating it with the few "
"possessions Bill had sent from New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1885
msgid ""
"When Bill left for his West Coast adventure, he had relinquished most of "
"what he owned, including a great many books and most of his music except his"
" entire Mozart collection, which was very dear to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1886
msgid ""
"And what he left behind was not a huge amount, as he was not particularly "
"into accumulating worldly possessions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1887
msgid ""
"For the ten years I knew him, he seemed more an advocate of voluntary "
"simplicity than consumerism."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1888
msgid ""
"In addition to leaving possessions behind, he abruptly cut almost all ties "
"with friends and acquaintances of many years, both professional and social, "
"as if clearing the decks for the final challenge of his life: to fully and "
"completely practice forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 539
#: sentence:1889
msgid ""
"Jules provided a service of paramount importance, helping him become "
"familiar with the day-to-day requirements of living in Tiburon, because the "
"practical matters of life were definitely Bill’s short suit, especially in a"
" strange setting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 540
#: sentence:1890
msgid "New home in Tiburon"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 541
#: sentence:1891
msgid ""
"Right away their friendship deepened and they discovered common interests."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 541
#: sentence:1892
msgid ""
"Jules and Bill settled into a pattern of helping to edit some of Jerry "
"Jampolsky’s earlier books, a process that worked very well for all "
"concerned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 541
#: sentence:1893
msgid ""
"They also collaborated in editing a book of Helen’s poetry, but their prize "
"project was extracting some of their favorite excerpts from ACIM, the most "
"beautiful and poetic, to create the book, Choose Once Again.[2] This "
"extensive editing occurred over a period of several years and, interwoven "
"with his other interests and projects, gave Bill an important focus during "
"this regrouping phase of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 542
#: sentence:1894
msgid ""
"Bill often commented on the feeling of discontinuity between the various "
"major chapters of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 542
#: sentence:1895
msgid ""
"Many people feel that way when they take new jobs, end or begin marriages, "
"or relocate to another city or country."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 542
#: sentence:1896
msgid ""
"It often seems, on settling into the new situation, that the old one was a "
"faraway dream unrelated to the present."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 542
#: sentence:1897
msgid ""
"Happily, every moment is discontinuous from the one preceding it, always "
"allowing us to make new choices about how to respond to current "
"circumstances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 542
#: sentence:1898
msgid ""
"Releasing past thoughts and concerns, and with it our stress, is essential, "
"since indiscriminately allowing past programming to dictate our present "
"approach to life is unsatisfactory at best and maddening at worst."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 543
#: sentence:1899
msgid ""
"During the summer of 1978, as Bill adjusted to his new environment, a tiny "
"ACIM community was evolving in Denver."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 543
#: sentence:1900
msgid ""
"I was still in my “evangelical” period, enthusiastically studying the Course"
" and attempting to persuade everyone I knew to check it out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 543
#: sentence:1901
msgid ""
"Many would open the book but immediately decide it was too long, too "
"“religious” in language, or too complicated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 543
#: sentence:1902
msgid ""
"Eventually, fourteen people coalesced who were sufficiently interested in "
"the material to meet regularly, so in August, a close friend and colleague, "
"Jaison Kayn, and I began facilitating our first study group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1903
msgid ""
"Later that summer an acquaintance called to say that Bill and the Skutches "
"had moved to Tiburon, California, a town I had never heard of."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1904
msgid ""
"I mentally filed that away, and within a month Jaison unexpectedly announced"
" he was going to Tiburon, of all places, for five weeks to study Aston "
"Patterning, an integration of deep tissue work, massage, and movement "
"education."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1905
msgid ""
"He had been Rolfing for five years and was feeling a deep call to study this"
" new work.[3] Little did he know the other reason he needed to go to "
"Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1906
msgid ""
"With that new information, I could practically hear Bill’s voice in my mind "
"calling, “Come out, come out,” encouraging a visit to Tiburon—a most "
"peculiar experience to say the least."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1907
msgid ""
"I could not imagine that he even remembered our short conversation, much "
"less that it would ever continue."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1908
msgid ""
"In fact, it seemed the most arrogant and preposterous thought I could "
"possibly entertain, but it strongly persisted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1909
msgid ""
"I had always recognized my intuitive faculty, very helpful when I listened, "
"but I didn’t always follow it; early conditioning prevailed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1910
msgid "Yet this “call from Bill” was so strong I simply couldn’t ignore it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1911
msgid "The internal turmoil was escalating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1912
msgid ""
"As a first step and not knowing where it would lead, I wrote a letter of "
"introduction to Bill on Jaison’s behalf, hoping to arrange a meeting for "
"them, and thanking him again for ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 544
#: sentence:1913
msgid ""
"Having no idea how to contact him, I sent the letter in care of the "
"Foundation for Inner Peace and hoped for the best."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1914
msgid ""
"Two weeks later, October 31, while I was getting my little boys ready for "
"Halloween, the phone rang and to my astonishment, there was Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1915
msgid ""
"He had received my letter and said he would be delighted to meet with "
"Jaison, and asked if would I be coming out also."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1916
msgid "It seemed he, too, had recognized something familiar, a common bond."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1917
msgid ""
"Ken Wapnick has noted that, for Bill, leaving New York was like leaving a "
"prison and it apparently took him no time at all to start exploring other "
"relationship options."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1918
msgid ""
"At first, as an habitual response, I declined the invitation; the next "
"morning, however, after considerable reflection, I accepted the incredible "
"gift being offered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1919
msgid ""
"Of course, I would go to Tiburon; I must surely have lost my mind to "
"consider doing otherwise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1920
msgid "Everyone but me was saying yes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1921
msgid "Bob was supportive of the plan and Jaison insisted I go."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1922
msgid ""
"Bob was not particularly interested in studying metaphysics, including ACIM,"
" but he never interfered with my pursuits."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1923
msgid ""
"Thus, in mid November 1978, watching the Rocky Mountains pass far below, I "
"marveled that I was really flying to California with no agenda, simply "
"following my own instincts and challenging old, entrenched ideas about what "
"I could or could not do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1924
msgid ""
"It was a crucial lesson for me—coming to terms with buried self-doubt as "
"well as old habits of taking care of the needs of others but not "
"acknowledging my own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1925
msgid "I was not always my own best advocate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1926
msgid ""
"Now I was actually acting on an intuitive urge, assuming I had a place to "
"fill, rather than repressing it in favor of “playing it safe” or being "
"polite."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 545
#: sentence:1927
msgid ""
"It seemed a big risk at the time, but everything had worked so well, and the"
" logistics were so uncomplicated, that the trip had every hallmark of "
"“destiny,” and it did turn out to be life-changing in many respects."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1928
msgid ""
"Jaison picked me up in Tiburon on a Thursday afternoon and took me to his "
"friend’s home where I stayed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1929
msgid ""
"Happily, it was within walking distance of the “ACIM neighborhood” on "
"Paradise Drive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1930
msgid ""
"We contacted Bill right away and he invited us to come to his apartment the "
"next morning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1931
msgid ""
"We arrived at the appointed hour and I will never forget that encounter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1932
msgid "His home felt like a sanctuary, the peaceful quarters of an old monk."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1933
msgid ""
"Bill was tall, smiling, and in his uniform—a favorite blue crewneck sweater "
"and levis; I’m quite short so as we embraced in a big hug, my head was on "
"his chest."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1934
msgid ""
"I could hear his heart, which seemed very loud and large—it was an "
"indescribably rich and wonderful moment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 546
#: sentence:1935
msgid ""
"I was thrilled to have a chance to spend more time in his wonderful "
"presence—a word that will appear often in this book because no other fits."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 547
#: sentence:1936
msgid "Jaison recalled his first impressions:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 548
#: sentence:1937
msgid "I remember walking in and thinking he looked like a college professor."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 548
#: sentence:1938
msgid ""
"He was immediately warm and friendly, giving me a big hug, and the first "
"thing he said to me was, “Oh, a healer.” [At that time, Bill knew nothing "
"about Jaison or his profession.] And it was like “Whoa!” He was just so "
"conscious and so tuned into everything and had the appearance of not being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 548
#: sentence:1939
msgid "From that first meeting, we had a relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 548
#: sentence:1940
msgid "There was no building a relationship; it just started."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 548
#: sentence:1941
msgid ""
"I felt accepted immediately, without hesitation, and we were instant "
"friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 548
#: sentence:1942
msgid ""
"That experience of his warm welcome will always be a profound and totally "
"precious memory.[4]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1943
msgid ""
"From that first moment of reconnection, Bill and I both recognized we were "
"old friends from some ancient time and place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1944
msgid ""
"We seemed to take up where we had left off, with a heartwarming degree of "
"openness and lack of formality or pretense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1945
msgid ""
"He seemed very willing to include Jaison and me in his daily life, and a "
"wonderful new chapter began to unfold for all three of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1946
msgid ""
"We spent the rest of the morning at his apartment, then ambled down to Main "
"Street for a four-hour lunch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1947
msgid "When it was time to leave, Bill asked if we knew Jerry Jampolsky."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1948
msgid ""
"We told him we did not and he said, “Well, you must meet Jerry,” so off we "
"went to his office a short distance away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1949
msgid ""
"Jerry was still a practicing psychiatrist, and his next patient was "
"fortuitously late, so the four of us gathered in his office for a half-hour "
"visit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1950
msgid ""
"Again, I experienced that intense, rich feeling, sensing the “family” was "
"reconvening after a long absence; this feeling was accentuated by a strong "
"pressure in my heart area, another first in my experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 549
#: sentence:1951
msgid ""
"It is difficult to describe that day except to say it was quite "
"breathtaking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 550
#: sentence:1952
msgid ""
"Bill and I were together most of the time over the next several days, with "
"Jaison joining us as his schedule permitted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 550
#: sentence:1953
msgid "The adventure simply got better and better."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 550
#: sentence:1954
msgid ""
"Jerry kindly invited Jaison and me to join what I came to call the “first "
"family” of the Course at their daily study/prayer group, almost always held "
"at his home but occasionally at the Skutches’."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 550
#: sentence:1955
msgid ""
"At nine o’clock every morning, Jerry, Bill, Bob and Judy Skutch, Frances "
"Vaughn, and Roger Walsh, the man she later married, would meet for about an "
"hour to read a lesson, sit quietly to see how it might apply personally, and"
" visit in an open and sharing way. (Frances and Roger are both distinguished"
" in their respective fields of psychology and psychiatry and pioneers in the"
" area of transpersonal psychology.) Of paramount importance was the feeling "
"in the room, the feeling of people deeply caring about one another."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 550
#: sentence:1956
msgid ""
"Jaison and I were most grateful to be included, and for the next several "
"years, every time either of us were there, we were invited to the meeting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 550
#: sentence:1957
msgid ""
"That courtesy was also extended to Jules Finegold, Pat Hopkins, and a few "
"others who did not live in Tiburon, when they were in town. (Pat became a "
"regular participant later when she moved to Tiburon.)"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 551
#: sentence:1958
msgid ""
"As an added bonus, Jaison and I spent a delightful evening with Bob and Judy"
" Skutch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 551
#: sentence:1959
msgid ""
"Judy is an effervescent, lively woman; Bob, her husband at the time and a "
"man of fewer words, is engaging and supportive in a more subdued manner and "
"still manages the business side of the Foundation for Inner Peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 551
#: sentence:1960
msgid ""
"As we became better acquainted that evening, Judy suddenly exclaimed, “I "
"know why you’re here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 551
#: sentence:1961
msgid ""
"After all his years in academia, Bill needs to be socialized; I bequeath you"
" Bill!” What exactly that would entail, I wasn’t sure, but without doubt I "
"was delighted with the assignment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 552
#: sentence:1962
msgid ""
"Right from the beginning, Judy seemed consistently to play the role of "
"Bill’s “big sister,” offering comfort, stability, and a large dose of loving"
" acceptance and good will. She said,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 553
#: sentence:1963
msgid ""
"I knew, the way knowing is encapsulated in your mind, that I was to take "
"care of him [Bill] the rest of his life, just as Helen knew when she first "
"saw Bill he was the one she was supposed to help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 553
#: sentence:1964
msgid "I can see the two of us, [she and I] played such a similar role."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 553
#: sentence:1965
msgid ""
"Layle [Luckett, who appears later in Bill’s life] got a little rhapsodic and"
" commented on what a great older sister I was, and I said, “Whoa, he was "
"eight years older than I.” She wrote back with a little smile sign and said,"
" “It doesn’t matter, you were his older sister.” I never thought of it like "
"that but I knew he was my assignment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 553
#: sentence:1966
msgid ""
"It didn’t mean I was to control his life, only that I would be his safety "
"net.[5]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1967
msgid ""
"As if carried on a tide of good fortune, I found myself the junior partner "
"in this “big sister” enterprise and, as with Judy, Bill did seem lighter and"
" more reassured when we were together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1968
msgid ""
"Judy and I never confided our sisterly conspiracy to him, nor do we know "
"what he might have thought about our prescription for his “re-"
"socialization,” but he did flourish during our times together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1969
msgid ""
"During his early days in California, Judy was still traveling, speaking "
"extensively on behalf of ACIM, and was not in Tiburon on a regular basis."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1970
msgid ""
"Thus, she welcomed anyone who could play a surrogate role and provide a "
"stabilizing influence for Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1971
msgid ""
"He had spent decades operating at a frantic pace with his multifaceted work,"
" including the time-consuming addition of the Course from 1965–1976."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1972
msgid ""
"Considering all the upsets and opportunities for psychological growth that "
"had occurred simultaneously with his workload at Columbia, Bill seriously "
"did need to decompress, and if ever there was a project I could "
"wholeheartedly embrace, it was this one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 554
#: sentence:1973
msgid ""
"To say I felt richly blessed at the prospect of spending more time with Bill"
" would be a major understatement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1974
msgid ""
"As our friendship deepened, Bill confided that when my original letter "
"arrived, he was not opening mail sent to him via the Foundation for Inner "
"Peace (his own address and phone were unlisted)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1975
msgid ""
"He was as surprised as I was that he not only felt compelled to read it but "
"to respond."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1976
msgid ""
"He chose not to open his letters then because he didn’t want to deal with "
"the inquiries or comments they may have contained; he was earnestly trying "
"to dissociate himself from the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1977
msgid ""
"After I had spent some time with him, I realized how extraordinarily out of "
"character it was for him to call me—and certainly to invite us to come out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1978
msgid "Jaison and I were strangers and he was an intensely private man."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1979
msgid ""
"I grew up in a socially active household with all sorts of "
"activities—gatherings, houseguests, group meetings, celebratory meals—and it"
" was entirely normal to invite persons we didn’t know well, along with "
"friends, to join us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1980
msgid ""
"My adulthood in Denver mimicked my growing-up years, so his warm invitation "
"didn’t seem odd, simply generous and altogether unexpected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1981
msgid ""
"Only later did I appreciate the leap of faith it took for him to call, just "
"as it had been for me to respond."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 555
#: sentence:1982
msgid "We were both being led into unfamiliar territory."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 556
#: sentence:1983
msgid ""
"What was in character for Bill at the time, however, was being reclusive and"
" pledging everyone to secrecy about his role with the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 556
#: sentence:1984
msgid ""
"Hugh Prather recalls when he and his wife Gayle planned their first meeting "
"with Jerry Jampolsky:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1985
msgid ""
"The first time I talked to Jerry, as we were setting up a lunch, he told me "
"there was someone he wanted me to meet but he wouldn’t tell me who it was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1986
msgid "He was very mysterious about this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1987
msgid "I think he referred to him as Dr. B or something like that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1988
msgid "He really wanted to tell me but had promised he wouldn’t."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1989
msgid ""
"I think we pretty well figured out who it was with Jerry’s “non-telling.” In"
" the beginning, Bill was very uncomfortable having people know that he was "
"the person associated with the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1990
msgid "He didn’t even use his last name."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 557
#: sentence:1991
msgid "When we met him, he was Dr. Bill. [6]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1992
msgid ""
"Having left Columbia only recently, Bill was reticent about openly "
"acknowledging his connection to A Course In Miracles—the title itself "
"sounded so peculiar and unscientific."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1993
msgid "He needed the security of a few close friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1994
msgid ""
"Just as he had not come out as a homosexual, and never did officially, he "
"had not yet come out of the ACIM “closet.” Certainly, other psychologists "
"have been involved with “channeling” or have received material from unusual "
"and unknown sources, but few had careers as auspicious as his."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1995
msgid ""
"In addition to his reticence about associating with the Course, the radical "
"shift from academic to ordinary citizen was a shock, and he was grieving "
"over the end of the New York era."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1996
msgid ""
"He wrote, “I thought it was amazing that I could see so clearly and yet the "
"same thing [old ego patterns] kept coming up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1997
msgid ""
"I had to leave the whole New York ambiance and go to a totally different "
"setting to begin to let go."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1998
msgid "It was very difficult for me to do that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 558
#: sentence:1999
msgid "I was so dedicated to working things out there [with Helen].”[7]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 559
#: sentence:2000
msgid ""
"Consistent with his ambivalence about his ACIM association, Bill "
"procrastinated about giving Bob Skutch permission to publish his book on the"
" Course’s origins, Journey Without Distance.[8] He had vetoed the earlier "
"version because he was not yet ready for more unwanted publicity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 559
#: sentence:2001
msgid ""
"Also, he was honoring Helen’s request not to publish the chronicle of the "
"ACIM scribing or their personal histories until after her death, which "
"occurred in February 1981."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 559
#: sentence:2002
msgid ""
"Ultimately, of course, Bill saw the wisdom of a complete account of how the "
"Course was written and worked with Bob to ensure its accuracy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2003
msgid ""
"Bill attributed his reticence about publicity partly to his clear "
"remembrance of a former life as Origen, one of the greatest theologians and "
"biblical scholars of the early church."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2004
msgid ""
"Martyred around 254AD for his heretical posture on many basic church "
"doctrines, he was the most influential theologian of the church before St. "
"Augustine."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2005
msgid ""
"ACIM students will find the mystical nature of Origen’s teachings strikingly"
" familiar."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2006
msgid ""
"Given the barbaric torture Origen endured for his beliefs, which probably "
"hastened his death, Bill’s reluctance to expressing his views publicly may "
"have been rooted in a bleed-through awareness of that traumatic time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2007
msgid "Incidentally, Helen also tuned into this former experience of Bill’s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2008
msgid ""
"Once she suddenly interrupted discussion of an unrelated topic to disclose "
"this former life to him, a confirmation he found both fascinating and "
"illuminating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 560
#: sentence:2009
msgid ""
"It was another of his favorite stories and he told it with his signature "
"smile of amusement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 561
#: sentence:2010
msgid "Chapter 10"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2011
msgid ""
"Early on in California, a coterie of people began to collect around Bill, "
"all part of a grounding network vital to his continued unfolding, while "
"mutually facilitating the healing for all concerned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2012
msgid ""
"The initial support group, consisting of Judy and Bob Skutch and Jerry "
"Jampolsky, was already in place when Bill left New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2013
msgid ""
"With the morning prayer group, Frances and Roger joined the circle and, "
"along with Jules, became central to his anchoring into the area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2014
msgid ""
"With careers in psychology and psychiatry, they functioned as colleagues but"
" also became his protégés."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2015
msgid ""
"Additional members of Bill’s support group, from different places and walks "
"of life, showed up throughout his last ten years in precisely the proper "
"order."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2016
msgid ""
"Those closest to him were all ACIM students and formed a family of sorts; "
"each provided different yet essential elements for his releasing, healing, "
"comforting, and grounding."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2017
msgid "The foundation was being laid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2018
msgid ""
"Bill had made a commitment to practice the Course’s version of forgiveness "
"and help to do so was coalescing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2019
msgid ""
"Of course, he had many wonderful friends, colleagues, and partners during "
"his first fifty-five years, but his goals then had been more worldly and "
"divided; he had not yet fully dedicated himself to a spiritual practice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2020
msgid ""
"Additionally, many other friends and acquaintances were part of his "
"California life, important in various ways, and who undoubtedly contributed "
"to his well-being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2021
msgid ""
"The Course clearly states that there are no accidents—even the briefest "
"encounter is meaningful and holds the possibility of great healing if we so "
"choose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 562
#: sentence:2022
msgid ""
"Nevertheless, Bill, like everyone, was destined to spend more time with some"
" than others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 563
#: sentence:2023
msgid ""
"In the channeled reading he gave Bill in 1980, LeRoy Zemke predicted that "
"key people would be drawn into his life to provide energy for his "
"transformation and that being open to allowing them in would bring healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 563
#: sentence:2024
msgid ""
"At the time of this reading, Bill had met some, but not all, of those "
"persons with whom he would spend significant time during his last ten years."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2025
msgid ""
"Each of the persons you have mentioned [Bill had given him seven names] are "
"parts of the pattern, are like keys in a pattern that will help you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2026
msgid "There are many who will help you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2027
msgid ""
"What you must be willing to do is to allow them space in your life to assume"
" some of the weight, some of the responsibility that is emerging."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2028
msgid ""
"You, as you know, have an infinitely careful, painstaking quality about "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2029
msgid "Whatever you attend to, you can very easily accomplish. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2030
msgid ""
"Now as these people appear, they have volunteered out of the love they bear "
"for you and/or the larger essence of what has emerged, to dedicate a portion"
" of their being to implementing that dimension."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2031
msgid "As you give them opportunity to assume the work, they will do it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 564
#: sentence:2032
msgid ""
"And thus, what you can do involves a giving, both in the form of guidance "
"and ideas that need to be set into motion, and secondly, the energy from "
"your own being expressed as love.[9]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 565
#: sentence:2033
msgid ""
"As Bill spent focused time with some, and then moved on to the next person "
"or group, release was occurring."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 566
#: sentence:2034
msgid ""
"Once you accept His plan as the one function that you would fulfill, there "
"will be nothing else the Holy Spirit will not arrange for you without your "
"effort."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 566
#: sentence:2035
msgid ""
"He will go before you making straight your path, and leaving in your way no "
"stones to trip on, and no obstacles to bar your way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 566
#: sentence:2036
msgid "Nothing you need will be denied you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 566
#: sentence:2037
msgid "Not one seeming difficulty but will melt away before you reach it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 566
#: sentence:2038
msgid ""
"You need take thought for nothing, careless of everything except the only "
"purpose that you would fulfill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 566
#: sentence:2039
msgid "As that was given you, so will its fulfillment be.[10]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 567
#: sentence:2040
msgid ""
"Bill had accepted that plan and, as promised, help was always there when he "
"needed it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 567
#: sentence:2041
msgid ""
"Zemke also commented, less than two years after Bill’s move west, “The most "
"important, perhaps, of all directions or aspects at present in your life is "
"to ground the physical form, to allow yourself to connect with the earth and"
" with the water, to experience a harmony with the basic elements within the "
"world . . . and thus provide a more smooth transition for all the work "
"unfolding.”[11]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2042
msgid ""
"Bill’s first priorities in Tiburon were to settle in, reestablish a sense of"
" stability and security after decades of daily structure, and to meet "
"concrete, worldly needs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2043
msgid ""
"Sufficient financial support and anchoring into normal everyday life "
"required attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2044
msgid ""
"Bill was skilled in many ways and adept at negotiating the labyrinth of "
"academic power, but he did not operate comfortably in ordinary daily life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2045
msgid ""
"He needed routine and support to function effectively in this world, to keep"
" his feet planted on the earth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2046
msgid ""
"For instance, Bill had contributed to his TIAA-CREF retirement fund while at"
" Columbia, but had forgotten to apply for his benefits when he retired."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2047
msgid ""
"When Pat Hopkins (who entered his life later) found out about this in 1984 "
"through a conversation with Cal Hatcher, she helped him apply for his "
"benefits, significantly increasing his monthly income."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 568
#: sentence:2048
msgid ""
"Despite chairing a department with a large staff and sizable budget, he was "
"quite detached when it came to personal finances. Jack Luckett corroborates:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2049
msgid "First, he was brilliant in abstract thought and analysis. No question."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2050
msgid ""
"He could go right to the center of an issue and understand it instantly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2051
msgid ""
"And the more abstract it was, the easier it was for him to see right into "
"it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2052
msgid "It’s why he was such a fantastic psychologist."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2053
msgid "But he was not well grounded in this world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2054
msgid ""
"Now that means relating to food, clothing, directions, appliances, "
"electronic gear, politics, gardening, animals, and children."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2055
msgid "He did not have a clue about these things."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2056
msgid ""
"He was not comfortable with and did not understand the governmental "
"political process."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2057
msgid "He was a great faker."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2058
msgid ""
"Because of this, he would establish routines in his life, probably because "
"he’d been laughed at earlier."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2059
msgid ""
"When he found something that worked, he would stick with it, make a routine "
"of it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2060
msgid ""
"He told me that for fifteen years, he ate at the same restaurant with the "
"same waitress at the same table, ate the same meal every night, except when "
"he was asked out by others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 569
#: sentence:2061
msgid ""
"I said, “Didn’t you ever want to go to a different restaurant?” and he "
"answered that, no, he knew this place, knew where it was. Can you imagine "
"that?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2062
msgid "Now Bill didn’t really understand food well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2063
msgid ""
"When he and Pat [Hopkins] got together as roommates, they agreed to share "
"responsibilities in cleaning and preparing food."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2064
msgid "Well, Bill never prepared his own food so he was quite nonplussed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2065
msgid ""
"He found these frozen enchilada dinners that were good, so he solved the "
"problem."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2066
msgid ""
"He went down and bought one year’s supply of the same kind of enchilada "
"dinner and put them in the freezer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2067
msgid ""
"Although that certainly seemed more than a little strange to Pat, to him "
"this was a perfect solution."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 570
#: sentence:2068
msgid ""
"He would just have those dinners from then on; they were fine, they "
"worked.[12]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 571
#: sentence:2069
msgid ""
"Bill’s New York acquaintances did say that he could cook one "
"thing—omelets—and if you were invited over, you would have no doubt about "
"the menu."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 571
#: sentence:2070
msgid "That was the extent of his culinary skill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 571
#: sentence:2071
msgid ""
"Because of his basic unfamiliarity with food preparation, he tended to "
"approach it more like an anthropologist than a gourmet and regularly "
"conducted unusual experiments with tastes and food combinations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 571
#: sentence:2072
msgid ""
"For instance, years later, Bill and the Lucketts stopped one night at a "
"Haagen Daz store for ice cream, and he ordered maple walnut combined with "
"raspberry tofutti."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 571
#: sentence:2073
msgid ""
"He had no idea what combining these flavors would be like; this was a "
"foreign world to him. Jack continued:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 572
#: sentence:2074
msgid ""
"As for clothing, he relied mostly on his gay male friends, and occasionally "
"others, to help him with clothes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 572
#: sentence:2075
msgid "He had no sense of what he should buy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 572
#: sentence:2076
msgid ""
"Usually he wore levis that hung down low on his hips with a pullover "
"sweater."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 572
#: sentence:2077
msgid ""
"One time at one of the garden [ACIM] meetings in San Diego, a fellow took "
"one look at Bill and exclaimed, “My dear, who is your tailor!”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 573
#: sentence:2078
msgid "Bill was spatially disoriented."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 573
#: sentence:2079
msgid "He simply did not understand how to get from one place to another."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 573
#: sentence:2080
msgid ""
"He liked to go to a meeting that was south from where we lived in La Jolla."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 573
#: sentence:2081
msgid ""
"Everything to him was linear so I could tell him, “You go down this street "
"until you come to the gas station and turn right; it’s like a line.” I gave "
"him these landmarks and he was so proud the first time he drove it; it was a"
" major accomplishment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 573
#: sentence:2082
msgid ""
"I do know that if he’d ever gotten off that line, he’d have been in real "
"trouble.[13]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 574
#: sentence:2083
msgid "Bill took on another challenge when he left New York—to quit smoking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 574
#: sentence:2084
msgid "He was a nonstop smoker and quitting was not easy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 574
#: sentence:2085
msgid ""
"However, he recognized the need to discontinue the habit, knowing it was "
"preventing long-buried feelings from surfacing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 574
#: sentence:2086
msgid ""
"In their stead, he carried cinnamon sticks and chewed on those when tempted "
"to smoke."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 574
#: sentence:2087
msgid ""
"Bill commented one time that in the hectic New York days, he lived mostly on"
" coffee, which he drank all day long, several packs of cigarettes, and "
"butter pecan ice cream."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 574
#: sentence:2088
msgid ""
"It’s a wonder he lived as long as he did, especially with a heart damaged by"
" rheumatic fever!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 575
#: sentence:2089
msgid ""
"Judy, looking out for his best interests, instinctively knew that proceeds "
"from the early sales of the Course would go to support Bill when he retired;"
" his receiving a stipend seemed inevitable and obvious."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 575
#: sentence:2090
msgid ""
"On the other hand, Bill noted, “I didn’t expect the Course to be a source of"
" financial support."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 575
#: sentence:2091
msgid "We never thought of that at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 575
#: sentence:2092
msgid ""
"Yet eventually it did happen and it took me a long time even to be "
"comfortable with the idea of living on funds from the Foundation for Inner "
"Peace.”[14] Thus, with his stipend from the Foundation, his pension, "
"investments in the stock market, and his capacity to “manifest as needed,” "
"he always lived comfortably."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 576
#: sentence:2093
msgid "Chapter 11"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 577
#: sentence:2094
msgid ""
"After our first visit in Tiburon, a pattern emerged: Bill and I met every "
"couple of months, with phone calls in between."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 577
#: sentence:2095
msgid ""
"He would come to Denver and stay with my family—my husband and two young "
"boys—and in turn, I would visit Tiburon and stay with him or, later, with "
"Jerry, sometimes to participate in planned events and sometimes for no "
"reason."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 577
#: sentence:2096
msgid "This schedule continued for about three years."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 577
#: sentence:2097
msgid ""
"Early on, it felt surreal to watch him sitting on our patio, listen to his "
"tales, or conversely, be included in his daily routine as he settled into "
"California."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 577
#: sentence:2098
msgid ""
"He had dropped suddenly and unexpectedly into the middle of my life, and it "
"took a bit of getting used to."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2099
msgid "During his visits to Denver, “socializing Bill” began in earnest."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2100
msgid ""
"I wish everyone could have seen him as he participated in that “normalizing "
"process.” He was so willing to explore."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2101
msgid ""
"He especially enjoyed our sons—six and eight when we met; he was fascinated "
"by what little boys could do and got such a kick out of their activities and"
" friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2102
msgid ""
"Although he had studied, tested, and written about children in his "
"professional life, he had very little experience being around them in normal"
" everyday life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2103
msgid ""
"As an adult, he was basically unfamiliar with families or the myriad details"
" and responsibilities of family life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2104
msgid ""
"Bill would stand in the kitchen as I prepared meals, with little ones "
"running in and out, and often exclaim, “I don’t know how you do all this!” "
"It was business as usual; parents learn, out of necessity, to multitask."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 578
#: sentence:2105
msgid ""
"He himself was a master at multitasking but in very different areas of life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2106
msgid ""
"Because of his lack of experience with young children in their usual "
"environments, he thoroughly enjoyed attending school functions or riding "
"along when it was my turn to drive the car pool."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2107
msgid ""
"I’ve not met anyone else who ever saw Bill in that role—riding in a car full"
" of little kids."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2108
msgid "It was a new adventure for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2109
msgid ""
"He sat in wonder as he listened to their conversations, finding them "
"hilarious and precious."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2110
msgid ""
"He would look over at me with eyes wide open, a huge grin on his face, as "
"their stories unfolded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2111
msgid ""
"Their parents would likely have been less than thrilled to hear their small "
"children candidly revealing private family business."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2112
msgid ""
"He loved such times, delighting in their complete ease and openness as they "
"prattled on, asking him questions, wholeheartedly including him as a matter "
"of course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 579
#: sentence:2113
msgid ""
"They were a marked contrast to his own early experience and to his long-"
"standing inclination to secrecy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 580
#: sentence:2114
msgid ""
"Bill often commented on how very different these children’s early years were"
" from his."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 580
#: sentence:2115
msgid ""
"On one trip to Denver, he watched my younger son energetically ride up and "
"down the sidewalk on his bicycle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 580
#: sentence:2116
msgid ""
"I could see the wistful look in his eyes and commented on how this seven-"
"year-old’s experience must seem worlds apart from his own at seven, lying in"
" bed gravely ill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 580
#: sentence:2117
msgid ""
"He acknowledged the difference, then responded with a broad smile, “Nothing "
"is ever going to get in his way in life!” In addition, both Bill and Helen "
"were true Gilbert and Sullivan aficionados, and he was especially pleased "
"that my older son had a significant role in his elementary school’s abridged"
" production of the musical, H.M.S. Pinafore."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 580
#: sentence:2118
msgid ""
"Greg was nine, an age when Bill was still confined to bed, which led to more"
" reminiscing about how different were their early childhood experiences."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 581
#: sentence:2119
msgid ""
"I can still see him—tall, handsome, charismatic, and often the only man "
"around—casually visiting with the mothers waiting for their children at the "
"end of the school day, soccer practice, or music lessons, as if he did this "
"every day."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 581
#: sentence:2120
msgid ""
"Actually, it was probably the first time he had ever been in such a "
"situation, but you wouldn’t have known it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 581
#: sentence:2121
msgid ""
"Bill had an amazing capacity to seem at home in any situation even when he "
"absolutely was not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 581
#: sentence:2122
msgid ""
"These various groups of children took to him at once and all unquestioningly"
" considered him part of their young lives, telling him their stories and "
"competing with one another to hold his hands."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 581
#: sentence:2123
msgid ""
"Sometimes he read stories to our boys at night, which they loved; they "
"regarded him as a favorite uncle, and in my mind I can still hear the sound "
"of his reassuring, resonant voice coming down the hall."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 582
#: sentence:2124
msgid ""
"On a few occasions, we took the boys to Tiburon, always infusing a burst of "
"energy into Bill’s world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 582
#: sentence:2125
msgid ""
"He watched with delight as they scrambled along the shoreline between his "
"apartment and Jerry’s home, a short distance away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 582
#: sentence:2126
msgid ""
"This infrequent plunge into typical, busy family life was a source of great "
"amusement—and perhaps some gratitude that he had opted for the single life! "
"Certainly it was different."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 582
#: sentence:2127
msgid ""
"In retrospect, it doesn’t seem a coincidence that Bill came to Denver while "
"my children were the same age he had been while bedridden."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 582
#: sentence:2128
msgid ""
"In ways we may never understand, I believe some healing of his difficult "
"early years took place through those casual interactions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 583
#: sentence:2129
msgid ""
"Although Bill enjoyed being included in our daily routine, the early morning"
" “get the kids up and off to school” uproar challenged his endurance, and he"
" always remained safely in his bedroom with the door closed until quiet "
"settled over the house."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 583
#: sentence:2130
msgid ""
"Then we had wonderful long talks in the kitchen, usually followed by a walk."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 583
#: sentence:2131
msgid ""
"Sometimes Bob joined us for an evening walk and remembered them fondly, “We "
"just walked and talked and exchanged thoughts and information and he was "
"always receptive to whatever was on your mind; he would listen to you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 583
#: sentence:2132
msgid "You could talk to Bill about anything and he would have an answer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 583
#: sentence:2133
msgid ""
"Somehow the two of us clicked; he was just a dear, dear, friend.”1[15] "
"Although Bob was not a Course student himself, he was a gracious host on "
"Bill’s visits; he made sure he had everything he might want or need as a "
"guest in our home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 583
#: sentence:2134
msgid ""
"He genuinely cared for Bill—and that was mutual—and even now (we have been "
"divorced for many years), he still talks about him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 584
#: sentence:2135
msgid ""
"So many others I interviewed for this book also emphasized the importance of"
" a walk with Bill, how satisfying it was and how much insight occurred "
"during those casual discussions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 584
#: sentence:2136
msgid ""
"Robert Rosenthal, a young psychiatrist friend of Bill’s, relates a typical "
"experience: “Often when Bill and I would get together we’d walk and chat."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 584
#: sentence:2137
msgid ""
"He’d catch me up on the latest ‘craziness’ going on with the Course or what "
"Jerry Jampolsky or other people were doing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 584
#: sentence:2138
msgid "But in a way, that was all window dressing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 584
#: sentence:2139
msgid ""
"Behind it was a shared sense of presence and peace, just meditating together"
" and sharing the moment.”[16] Hugh Prather also mentioned how they always "
"seemed to be walking together somewhere, discussing a range of issues, and "
"how important that was to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 584
#: sentence:2140
msgid "And Jaison Kayn found silent walking with Bill profoundly satisfying:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2141
msgid "Bill and I didn’t talk much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2142
msgid ""
"It was part of our relationship to be absolutely comfortable together, "
"physically and energetically."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2143
msgid "We would walk to the bakery on the dock near Jerry’s office."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2144
msgid ""
"It was a casual ritual, going down there every day [when Jaison was visiting"
" in Tiburon], ordering those wonderful custard-filled cream puffs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2145
msgid "They were his favorite and, at first bite, became mine as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2146
msgid "Since we were both basically shy people, there was not much to say."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2147
msgid "We simply sat, watched, and enjoyed our cream puffs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2148
msgid ""
"We accepted each other’s shyness very easily and did not need to entertain "
"each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2149
msgid ""
"It was more than comfortable; our energies seemed to be quietly "
"communicating something gracious and beyond words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2150
msgid ""
"I was probably one of the few people in his life he felt that way about."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2151
msgid ""
"My sense is that he often felt he had to talk to people more, that most "
"people required that of him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 585
#: sentence:2152
msgid ""
"Somehow with me he knew he didn’t have to talk because I couldn’t "
"either.[17]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 586
#: sentence:2153
msgid ""
"ACIM speaks beautifully of the implications of walking together, literally "
"or figuratively:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 587
#: sentence:2154
msgid ""
"This brother neither leads nor follows us, but walks beside us on the "
"selfsame road."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 587
#: sentence:2155
msgid ""
"He is like us, as near or far away from what we want as we will let him be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 587
#: sentence:2156
msgid ""
"We make no gains he does not make with us, and we fall back if he does not "
"advance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 587
#: sentence:2157
msgid ""
"Take not his hand in anger but in love, for in his progress do you count "
"your own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 587
#: sentence:2158
msgid ""
"And we go separately along the way unless you keep him safely by your side. "
". . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2159
msgid ""
"Forgive your brother all appearances, that are but ancient lessons you have "
"taught yourself about the sinfulness in you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2160
msgid ""
"Hear but his call for mercy and release from all the fearful images he holds"
" of what he is and of what you must be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2161
msgid ""
"He is afraid to walk with you, and thinks perhaps a bit behind, a bit ahead "
"would be a safer place for him to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2162
msgid ""
"Can you make progress if you think the same, advancing only when he would "
"step back, and falling back when he would go ahead?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2163
msgid ""
"For so do you forget the journey’s goal, which is but to decide to walk with"
" him, so neither leads nor follows."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2164
msgid "Thus it is a way you go together, not alone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 588
#: sentence:2165
msgid ""
"And in this choice is learning’s outcome changed, for Christ has been reborn"
" to both of you.[18]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 589
#: sentence:2166
msgid ""
"Something was reborn in those who walked with Bill; it was like coming home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2167
msgid ""
"Bill seemed to need, perhaps more than anything, some comfortable time and "
"space to assimilate his new life and slowly unwind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2168
msgid ""
"It was helpful for him to be away from places where the roles of teacher, "
"Course scribe, learned professor, or anything else were thrust upon him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2169
msgid ""
"On occasion, when we had our private space, he would break down and weep."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2170
msgid ""
"I comforted him as best I could, at the same time encouraging him to cry "
"those tears so long unshed—tears not so much over particulars, but a "
"lifetime accumulation of pain not fully acknowledged."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2171
msgid ""
"Nothing specific prompted those episodes; it was more a combination of "
"things."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2172
msgid ""
"We often spoke of his relationship with Helen, with the Course, and the "
"heaviness he carried about it all—the burden of unexpressed life, repressed "
"grief, hiding out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2173
msgid ""
"All of us hold onto some secrets, wearying at the very least, and this was "
"especially so for Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2174
msgid ""
"He constantly lived a dual life: his academic career intermixed with his "
"hidden ACIM work, his unresolved love/hate relationship with Helen, his "
"knowledge of various secret CIA projects—very likely carried to his "
"grave—and of course, his never publicly acknowledged homosexual private "
"life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 590
#: sentence:2175
msgid ""
"Thus, he could “hide out” in Denver, where almost no one had access to him, "
"and really let go."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 591
#: sentence:2176
msgid ""
"Over the years he also engaged in ongoing therapeutic work in Tiburon with "
"both Frances Vaughan and Catherine Riggs Prescott, a close friend he met in "
"1984, as well as learning from less formal interactions with others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 591
#: sentence:2177
msgid ""
"It is easy to see the Course operating in his life through a kaleidoscope of"
" relationships and encounters, helping him to identify and release unhelpful"
" beliefs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 591
#: sentence:2178
msgid ""
"It’s fair to say that all his relationships were mutually therapeutic, "
"though perhaps not recognized at the time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2179
msgid ""
"I regarded Bill as my mentor, as did almost everyone who knew him, and we "
"served as therapists for one another."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2180
msgid ""
"We were very respectful of one another’s capabilities and shared a close "
"connection as colleagues."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2181
msgid ""
"I, too, remember the importance of our long walks, as we shared our worlds, "
"at once so different and yet so similar."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2182
msgid ""
"We compared notes about my mother (also named Helen), who at that time was "
"retreating into Alzheimer’s disease, and about “his” Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2183
msgid ""
"He said he had tried for so many years to make her happy, to do or be "
"whatever she wanted, and that it was simply not possible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2184
msgid ""
"As simple as it sounds now, it was a significant breakthrough for him to "
"realize it was not his job to make Helen happy, and he advised me "
"accordingly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2185
msgid ""
"Her happiness had been his self-appointed responsibility, one she also "
"assumed was his."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 592
#: sentence:2186
msgid ""
"He used to say that it seemed Helen would never be happy, for she found very"
" little in life even to be acceptable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2187
msgid ""
"It took years for him to grow more accepting of his relationship with Helen,"
" as he released his sense of failure and the need for her approval."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2188
msgid ""
"Although he recognized it was pointless to continue trying, he didn’t find "
"peace with that relationship until near the end of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2189
msgid "Yet Bill was no different from the rest of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2190
msgid ""
"In my experience, most people learn that being okay, being worthy, having a "
"right to be here, is measured by others’ approval; unlearning that lie is "
"essential and often a lifelong venture."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2191
msgid ""
"He felt disappointed and betrayed because his vision of practicing the "
"Course with Helen and having a wonderful friendship didn’t happen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2192
msgid ""
"He also felt some resentment that she had gotten him into this situation and"
" was not fulfilling her part of the bargain, whatever he perceived that to "
"be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2193
msgid ""
"At the same time, he was compassionate with her, aware of her difficulties "
"when she was overtaken by phobias and compulsions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2194
msgid ""
"Also, during the last years of her life, after Bill and the Skutches had "
"moved to California, she grew ill with pancreatic cancer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2195
msgid "Many who knew her well said she became quite deranged."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 593
#: sentence:2196
msgid "She was definitely not the Helen everyone had known in her prime."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2197
msgid ""
"Once when Bill was in Denver, we were in the front yard watching the "
"children when a lovely dog—a handsome Irish setter—limped into the yard."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2198
msgid ""
"His paws were raw and bleeding as if he had had a very long, hard run on "
"concrete; he came straight toward us as if on purpose, clear about his "
"destination, then nearly collapsed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2199
msgid ""
"Bill had a very tender heart, was concerned about the dog, as were we all, "
"and asked several times what we could do for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2200
msgid ""
"We provided water, food, and a safe place to rest until the owner, whose "
"number was on his collar, returned our call that evening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2201
msgid ""
"The dog was very friendly and, despite his recent experience, seemed content"
" to sit with us for several hours until his owner arrived to collect him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2202
msgid ""
"Later, the owner told us the dog had been stolen from his backyard and "
"carried off for some unknown purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 594
#: sentence:2203
msgid ""
"He had escaped his captors and was trying to find his way back home; our "
"neighborhood was approximately on the way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 595
#: sentence:2204
msgid ""
"It seemed purposeful that Bill had this unanticipated encounter with the "
"dog."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 595
#: sentence:2205
msgid "The episode might seem trivial but it was important to Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 595
#: sentence:2206
msgid ""
"By his own account, he had been under tremendous strain—self-imposed though "
"it may have been—at Columbia, especially during the scribing years; he had "
"spoken of the struggle that seemed the hallmark of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 595
#: sentence:2207
msgid ""
"Our “outer” life is a seamless whole with the “inner,” and both Bill and the"
" dog, after long, difficult journeys, were on the final leg of returning "
"“Home.” A lesson from ACIM comments on our suffering when we “leave home,” "
"in other words, when we refuse to accept the truth about ourselves:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 596
#: sentence:2208
msgid ""
"He seems a sorry figure; weary, worn, in threadbare clothing, and with feet "
"that bleed a little from the rocky road he walks."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 596
#: sentence:2209
msgid ""
"No one but has identified with him, for everyone who comes here has pursued "
"the path he follows, and has felt defeat and hopelessness as he is feeling "
"them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 596
#: sentence:2210
msgid ""
"Yet is he really tragic, when you see that he is following the way he chose,"
" and need but realize Who walks with him and open up his treasures to be "
"free?[19]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 597
#: sentence:2211
msgid "Chapter 12"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2212
msgid ""
"While planning for one of his visits, I asked Bill if he would allow me to "
"host a reception so that some in the local ACIM community could meet him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2213
msgid ""
"He said he would be happy for that to happen; he willingly accepted even "
"though he could have said no."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2214
msgid ""
"On the appointed date, the house and yard filled with people eager to meet "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2215
msgid ""
"He responded to their enthusiasm graciously as if being a social butterfly "
"was his favorite thing, once again adapting to the situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2216
msgid ""
"Though he didn’t seek it, he understood their desire to meet and visit with "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2217
msgid ""
"However, as I grew to know his secret heart better, I learned that being the"
" focus of attention was contrary to his basic nature, and I never put him "
"through that again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2218
msgid ""
"In agreeing to the party, Bill was simply being generous, not phony or "
"selling out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 598
#: sentence:2219
msgid "He was able to rise to any occasion when he chose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 599
#: sentence:2220
msgid ""
"Bill didn’t object to socializing under the right circumstances, but he "
"strongly disliked being put on a pedestal as the center of attention, with "
"expectations attached."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 599
#: sentence:2221
msgid ""
"Friends from his New York days remembered Bill’s great cocktail parties with"
" many people in attendance, including colleagues from Columbia."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 599
#: sentence:2222
msgid ""
"They also remembered his inventing all kinds of irreproducible drink "
"concoctions of liquor and fruit juices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 599
#: sentence:2223
msgid ""
"He was only thirty-four when he joined the Columbia staff, and drinking and "
"cigarette smoking was the norm in his pre-Course days."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 599
#: sentence:2224
msgid ""
"However, I don’t recall his drinking anything but an occasional glass of "
"wine when I knew him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 599
#: sentence:2225
msgid ""
"Bill was a walking contradiction and could be either vivacious or completely"
" reserved, depending upon the circumstances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 600
#: sentence:2226
msgid ""
"At the reception in his honor, Bill met Bob Beale, another longtime friend "
"of ours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 600
#: sentence:2227
msgid ""
"Of all those he met in Denver, he felt most simpatico with Jaison and Bob, "
"both having a sensitive, compassionate nature similar to his."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 600
#: sentence:2228
msgid ""
"If Bill’s Denver “family” was about sanctuary and respite from the various "
"roles he played, these two certainly added to his sense of well-being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 600
#: sentence:2229
msgid ""
"I always arranged for them to get together when he came to town, and both "
"occasionally visited Bill in Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 601
#: sentence:2230
msgid ""
"During that reception and on other occasions, I watched as Bill was "
"inevitably asked two questions: the first about his role in the ACIM saga, "
"still a bit unnerving to him, and the second, “Well, Bill, what are you "
"doing now that you’re retired and living in California?” He would respond "
"that he was practicing forgiveness as a full-time job, which confused almost"
" everyone—Course and non-Course persons alike—since forgiveness is often "
"misunderstood even among long-time ACIM students."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 601
#: sentence:2231
msgid ""
"Like so many, he was still sorting out the relative importance of doing vs. "
"being, so he was a bit confused himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 601
#: sentence:2232
msgid ""
"His response of “practicing forgiveness” usually ended the conversation "
"about his career and personal world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 601
#: sentence:2233
msgid ""
"Most people would smile, change the subject, or look a bit blank, like, "
"“What does that mean?” Occasionally, however, someone would stumble, "
"acknowledge his response, then ask once again, “But what are you doing?” as "
"if practicing forgiveness was simply a clever answer or a dodge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 602
#: sentence:2234
msgid ""
"Normally he was gracious with such questions, patient with the lack of "
"understanding that practicing forgiveness is a full-time job, and if it is "
"not paramount in our lives, nothing else actually matters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 602
#: sentence:2235
msgid ""
"Once or twice I saw his eyes flash as if to say, “I’m so tired of answering "
"this question.” He probably felt interrogated but knew he was speaking the "
"truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 602
#: sentence:2236
msgid ""
"He realized most inquirers had no idea what he meant and took their "
"questions in stride, but a couple of times they momentarily pushed his "
"buttons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 603
#: sentence:2237
msgid ""
"Even if no one else understood Bill’s agenda, he was following his heart, "
"devoting himself as best he could to his own healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 603
#: sentence:2238
msgid ""
"Certainly his crowning achievement was his focus on practicing forgiveness "
"in everyday encounters as his new “career.” “I want the peace of God: Many "
"have said these words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 603
#: sentence:2239
msgid "But few indeed have meant them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 603
#: sentence:2240
msgid ""
"You have but to look upon the world you see around you to be sure how very "
"few they are."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 603
#: sentence:2241
msgid ""
"The world would be completely changed, should any two agree these words "
"express the only thing they want.”[20] Bill was committed to meaning what "
"these words say."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 604
#: sentence:2242
msgid ""
"What is this practice of forgiveness to which Bill was now dedicating his "
"life?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 604
#: sentence:2243
msgid ""
"It certainly isn’t what we have learned; the word itself carries a great "
"deal of baggage."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 604
#: sentence:2244
msgid "First, what it is not:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 605
#: sentence:2245
msgid ""
"Let us review the meaning of “forgive,” for it is apt to be distorted and to"
" be perceived as something that entails an unfair sacrifice of righteous "
"wrath, a gift unjustified and undeserved, and a complete denial of the "
"truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 605
#: sentence:2246
msgid ""
"In such a view, forgiveness must be seen as mere eccentric folly and this "
"course appear to rest salvation on a whim. . . .[21]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2247
msgid "The unhealed cannot pardon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2248
msgid "For they are the witnesses that pardon is unfair."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2249
msgid "They would retain the consequences of the guilt they would overlook."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2250
msgid "Yet no one can forgive a sin that he believes is real."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2251
msgid ""
"And what has consequences must be real, because what it has done is there to"
" see."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2252
msgid ""
"Forgiveness is not pity, which but seeks to pardon what it thinks to be the "
"truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2253
msgid ""
"Good cannot be returned for evil, for forgiveness does not first establish "
"sin and then forgive it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 606
#: sentence:2254
msgid ""
"Who can say and mean, “My brother, you have injured me, and yet, because I "
"am the better of the two, I pardon you my hurt.” His pardon and your hurt "
"cannot exist together.[22]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2255
msgid ""
"Perhaps we should call forgiveness “Process X” to distinguish it from the "
"misinformation we have learned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2256
msgid ""
"To paint a mental picture, imagine a thatch of many little twigs, sticks, "
"and grass, like a bird’s nest or the roof of a building found in many parts "
"of the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2257
msgid "The thatch, being tightly woven, is strong and impenetrable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2258
msgid ""
"All those little sticks and twigs, for our purposes, represent our incessant"
" train of thoughts—judgments, future plans, grievances, regrets, defenses, "
"learned behavior designed for our physical and psychological survival, "
"worries, self-images, roles we play, and pictures about how life is supposed"
" to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2259
msgid ""
"This omnipresent complex of thoughts, to which we are seriously addicted, "
"has become like a solid wall that seems to surround us, separating us from "
"the direct experience of life in the moment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2260
msgid "We “think” about life rather than experience it directly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2261
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles, brilliantly conceived and crafted, is so lengthy "
"because it presents a process for relinquishing these “twigs” rather than a "
"body of material to be learned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2262
msgid ""
"We tightly clutch these interwoven thoughts, believing we need them to "
"survive and flourish, and are rarely open-minded on the subject. “Strong and"
" impenetrable” are wonderful attributes if you want to keep the rain out or "
"the eggs in."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 607
#: sentence:2263
msgid ""
"However, they are a devastating liability if they impede experiencing the "
"present moment, with its inherent joy, peace, insight, and reliable "
"guidance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 608
#: sentence:2264
msgid ""
"The Course is designed for the overly active intellects of the Western "
"world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 608
#: sentence:2265
msgid ""
"It takes us through a process that systematically dismantles this barrier, "
"allowing freedom and happiness to increase in our daily experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 608
#: sentence:2266
msgid ""
"Forgiveness, as ACIM defines it, untangles and removes this accumulated "
"mental debris, the complicated mental filter through which we interact with "
"the people and circumstances in our lives—the blocks to the awareness of "
"Love’s presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 608
#: sentence:2267
msgid ""
"When we realize that forgiveness is about freeing ourselves from our self-"
"made prison—one we steadily and unwittingly make ever more secure through "
"ego-driven thought processes—and that it has nothing substantive to do with "
"the “other,” then we can proceed to liberation with real determination and "
"gratitude."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 609
#: sentence:2268
msgid ""
"So forgiveness is not about ascribing villainy, placing blame or finding "
"who’s at fault, and then trying to overlook “bad” actions, but in the "
"broadest sense it is allowing a completely new perspective to emerge on all "
"aspects of the world from personal to global, permitting an entirely "
"different experience of what we are—no small undertaking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 609
#: sentence:2269
msgid ""
"When inner conflict is gone, the outer experience of hassle disappears."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 609
#: sentence:2270
msgid "Love becomes known through all things."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 609
#: sentence:2271
msgid ""
"This is the centerpiece of the Course and the heart of all universal "
"metaphysical teachings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 610
#: sentence:2272
msgid "00011.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2273
msgid ""
"When possible, my husband Bob and I always arranged for us to attend musical"
" or theatrical events when Bill was in town."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2274
msgid ""
"He loved these as well as other activities he did not have access to "
"elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2275
msgid ""
"As he grew more willing to explore—literally—we took him to Vail and Aspen, "
"where we attended musical events, visited with friends, or drove up "
"backwoods mountain roads and marveled at the gorgeous scenery."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2276
msgid ""
"He had lived all his life in cities, inside academic institutions, and had "
"virtually no exposure to the great outdoors, but with his usual adaptability"
" he managed to fit right in on the hiking trails—although short ones, to be "
"sure."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2277
msgid ""
"We once took him through the Rocky Mountains over Independence Pass, the "
"back way into Aspen and a thrill ride for even the most seasoned mountain "
"travelers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2278
msgid ""
"He was awestruck with the scenic beauty and probably terrified, but he never"
" let on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2279
msgid ""
"We always discussed potential travel plans with him to make sure they would "
"not be too strenuous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 611
#: sentence:2280
msgid ""
"He was a bit nervous at the outset of some of our mountain adventures, "
"because of the high altitude and how that might affect his heart condition; "
"however, he always sincerely wanted to go and we did, with no problem."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 612
#: sentence:2281
msgid ""
"On one memorable occasion, Bob and I drove Bill to Santa Fe, New Mexico, "
"along with Bob Beale and his then wife Lucy, to attend the Santa Fe Opera."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 612
#: sentence:2282
msgid ""
"Hugh and Gayle Prather, who lived there at the time, joined us for part of "
"our visit, and the seven of us spent a couple of days together visiting, "
"sightseeing, dining out, and attending the opera."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 612
#: sentence:2283
msgid ""
"It was a riotously funny visit for all concerned and probably for everyone "
"within earshot, as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 612
#: sentence:2284
msgid ""
"Bill had warned us, however, that he always cried at the opera but not to be"
" alarmed—it had nothing to do with us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 612
#: sentence:2285
msgid "Other than that, all tears shed were because we laughed so hard."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 613
#: sentence:2286
msgid "Aspen, Colorado"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2287
msgid ""
"During our visits or on the phone, Bill and I rarely talked about the "
"content of ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2288
msgid ""
"Certainly, we spoke of its effects in our lives, but mostly we just enjoyed "
"the moment, simply being together with appreciation and delight."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2289
msgid ""
"A mundane accounting of everyday life was richer by far than grand "
"philosophical discussion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2290
msgid ""
"Occasionally, however, we did delve into the meaning of certain concepts."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2291
msgid ""
"Early on, I asked him about a sentence in the text, “Forgiveness is not real"
" unless it brings a healing to your brother and yourself.”[23] Since I was "
"fairly new to the Course, there was much I didn’t yet comprehend, including "
"the fact that intellectual understanding comes after the process of "
"forgiveness and not before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2292
msgid ""
"Presuming everything was already clear to Bill, I asked him what it meant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2293
msgid "He said he had no idea."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2294
msgid ""
"I was floored and thought to myself, “What do you mean, you don’t know what "
"this means?” I now realize that although he knew a tremendous amount about "
"the Course, he still retained unhealed grievances that would necessarily "
"cause blank areas or blind spots in his comprehension."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 614
#: sentence:2295
msgid ""
"When the mind is not clouded with grievances, everything becomes obvious and"
" simple; ultimately, that sentence became perfectly clear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 615
#: sentence:2296
msgid ""
"Bill and I sometimes meditated together, a precious way of relating that "
"many others also shared with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 615
#: sentence:2297
msgid ""
"Both Robert Rosenthal and Roger Walsh have eloquently described their "
"meditation experiences with Bill:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 616
#: sentence:2298
msgid "I recall in particular one meditation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 616
#: sentence:2299
msgid ""
"This was probably in the early 1980s in his Tiburon apartment one evening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 616
#: sentence:2300
msgid ""
"As we meditated, the room filled with a sense of utter stillness, a dense, "
"loving, overwhelming silence that was a positive presence, not just the "
"absence of noise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 616
#: sentence:2301
msgid ""
"In my mind I heard the words, “This is the peace that passeth "
"understanding.” It was a concrete experience of peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 616
#: sentence:2302
msgid ""
"A peace and silence so certain, so absolute and impenetrable, it could not "
"be disturbed by anything of this world—the peace of the Holy Spirit.[24]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2303
msgid ""
"Bill actually talked me into my first kensho or clear experience of "
"egolessness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2304
msgid ""
"One morning I was sitting with him in a restaurant by San Francisco Bay."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2305
msgid ""
"We were talking about something spiritual and although I don’t remember the "
"discussion, I do remember the experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2306
msgid ""
"As Bill was describing something about the nature of spiritual practice, I "
"felt a dramatic, progressive shift in consciousness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2307
msgid ""
"I had a sense of my awareness becoming focused in a simple point, which "
"moved up and up in a spiral and became disentangled from the workings of the"
" mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2308
msgid "Suddenly there was no exclusive identification with anything."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2309
msgid ""
"There was clear awareness without any sense of “Roger” or any separate-self "
"sense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2310
msgid ""
"There was a sudden recognition that the experience of egolessness that I’d "
"been reading about all this time, a state the Course had been trying to get "
"me to experience, is actually not a loss of the ego."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 617
#: sentence:2311
msgid ""
"Rather, the experience of egolessness is the recognition that the ego never "
"existed in the first place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 618
#: sentence:2312
msgid ""
"As I sat there happily absorbed in this novel state, I described to Bill "
"what had happened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 618
#: sentence:2313
msgid ""
"Amazingly, as I described the experience to him, he started having it, too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 618
#: sentence:2314
msgid ""
"He moved into the same state and we sat together for an hour or more in this"
" shared kensho experience, which he’d first talked me into and then, simply "
"by describing my experience to him, he had moved into himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 618
#: sentence:2315
msgid ""
"It was a wonderful experience for us both, and it was striking that it was "
"the relationship that had done it.[25]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2316
msgid ""
"Regarding the Course, I did ask Bill about changes to the scribed material "
"that were referred to briefly in the original write-up about how ACIM came "
"to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2317
msgid ""
"This was decades before any serious questions were raised about the editing "
"process."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2318
msgid ""
"First, he mentioned his amazement that Helen was able to leave the original "
"dictation alone, given her tendency to be a particularly ferocious editor."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2319
msgid ""
"She thoroughly edited anything that came her way, even a personal note; to "
"be able to leave the material unchanged was astonishing and completely out "
"of character for her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2320
msgid ""
"At the beginning of the transmission, if she changed a word because she "
"didn’t think it was the right one, she inevitably went back and reinstated "
"it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2321
msgid ""
"As the work progressed, she could see the necessity of the exact wording and"
" she specifically stated she didn’t want to intrude upon what was unfolding."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 619
#: sentence:2322
msgid ""
"Bill explained that they deleted their personal material as well as comments"
" about particular individuals, living or dead, that were interwoven with "
"what became the text."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 620
#: sentence:2323
msgid ""
"Anyone familiar with the Course notices that the first few chapters feel "
"disjointed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 620
#: sentence:2324
msgid ""
"Removing Helen and Bill’s personal material left gaps in the flow of "
"dictation and some sentences had to be rearranged, but Bill assured me—and I"
" believe him without question—that nothing substantive was omitted and that "
"the basic message was in no way altered by their editing choices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 620
#: sentence:2325
msgid ""
"Bill’s oversight was a governing factor and he gave his imprimatur to all "
"changes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 620
#: sentence:2326
msgid ""
"In the beginning, the Author specifically charged Bill to be responsible for"
" the editing choices (with the Author’s consent), as Helen still found the "
"entire scribing and editing process too disturbing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 620
#: sentence:2327
msgid ""
"Additional factors help explain the disjointed impression; Helen strongly "
"resisted the scribing process in the beginning, and Ken noted she was always"
" trying to impress Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 620
#: sentence:2328
msgid ""
"This scribing process was no different from other situations where she "
"sought Bill’s validation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 621
#: sentence:2329
msgid ""
"Occasionally, sentences were inadvertently omitted (though added back later)"
" during the typing and retyping process, and these weren’t discovered until "
"later when compared with Helen’s notebooks and the Urtext, the original "
"notes Bill typed directly while Helen read her shorthand notes to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 621
#: sentence:2330
msgid ""
"Sometimes the material didn’t come from notes dictated earlier, but came to "
"her directly while Bill was typing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 621
#: sentence:2331
msgid ""
"She also occasionally skipped over some notes she had taken, not reading "
"them to Bill at all, because she realized immediately they were personal and"
" should not be included. Helen explained,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 622
#: sentence:2332
msgid ""
"The “text” as it is given is unchanged except for the omission of some of "
"the more personal material which was included only at the beginning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 622
#: sentence:2333
msgid ""
"Chapter headings and subdivisions have been added later, but the arrangement"
" of the material, which seemed to fall naturally into these divisions, has "
"not been altered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 622
#: sentence:2334
msgid ""
"The “workbook,” which was dictated in the form of daily “lessons” is "
"presented as I took it down.[26]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 623
#: sentence:2335
msgid ""
"In recent years, I have heard such pronouncements as, “The sacred and secret"
" feminine teachings have been extracted from ACIM.” This simply is not true;"
" there is no “cult of the feminine” removed from the Course and reserved for"
" a special few."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 623
#: sentence:2336
msgid ""
"Bill set the record straight, telling me that everything essential about "
"ACIM remains as it was originally published."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 624
#: sentence:2337
msgid ""
"Finally, if you want to practice the Course, you have everything necessary "
"to do so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 624
#: sentence:2338
msgid ""
"In the early part of the text the Author states, “I have made every effort "
"to use words that are almost impossible to distort, but it is always "
"possible to twist symbols around if you wish.”[27] Because the basic tenets "
"of the Course are repeated so many times, you could remove half the content "
"and everything needed would still be in place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 624
#: sentence:2339
msgid ""
"Even though the several versions now available are slightly different from "
"the most recent edition of ACIM published by the Foundation for Inner Peace,"
" any edition chosen will foster the necessary “unlearning” of the obstacles "
"to peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 624
#: sentence:2340
msgid ""
"Most important, if you fully experience even one lesson, you will have the "
"whole Course since it’s about forgiveness and radically changing our minds."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 624
#: sentence:2341
msgid ""
"For an in-depth comparison of the various editions, I refer the reader to an"
" article by Robert Perry on the Circle of Atonement web site.[28]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 625
#: sentence:2342
msgid "00028.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 626
#: sentence:2343
msgid ""
"To broaden his experience with nontraditional subjects he always found "
"interesting, I told Bill about the great therapeutic benefits of Rolfing and"
" he indicated he was up for trying it ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 626
#: sentence:2344
msgid ""
"Our mutual friend, Jaison Kayn, a world-class Rolfer who personally studied "
"with Dr. Ida Rolf, the genius behind structural integration, was delighted "
"to oblige."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 626
#: sentence:2345
msgid ""
"I would drive Bill to Jaison’s home in Boulder for a session, and he would "
"emerge smiling and grateful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 626
#: sentence:2346
msgid ""
"So would Jaison; those sessions were a real win/win exchange for both. "
"Jaison comments:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2347
msgid "Well, it was delightful for many reasons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2348
msgid ""
"One is because I just loved Bill and wanted to do for him whatever I could."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2349
msgid "Two things stand out—first, how much he appreciated it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2350
msgid "He totally trusted me and put himself in my hands and was grateful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2351
msgid "And he was very aware that it was helpful to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2352
msgid "So anytime I was ready, he was ready."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2353
msgid ""
"But the biggest thing is that the first time I touched his body, I just saw "
"this light."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2354
msgid "It was like working on this shell that was full of light."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 627
#: sentence:2355
msgid ""
"There was this human body and inside that body was this bright, white "
"light.[29]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2356
msgid ""
"I asked Jaison if this phenomenon was more pronounced than with others he "
"had worked on, and he replied, “Oh, absolutely!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2357
msgid "Here was somebody who was full of light, literally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2358
msgid ""
"When I gave him bodywork, his flesh was more than receptive; he welcomed me "
"with gratitude."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2359
msgid ""
"He literally put himself in my hands and asked without words for whatever "
"help I could give."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2360
msgid "His yearning to heal and to open was tangible to my touch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2361
msgid "His ability to yield and to trust was remarkable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 628
#: sentence:2362
msgid "His longing to experience defenselessness was always on duty.”[30]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 629
#: sentence:2363
msgid ""
"Our fledgling ACIM group, which had started in August 1978, was still "
"gathering when Bill began his visits to Denver."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 629
#: sentence:2364
msgid ""
"He always attended our meetings, considering himself very much a fellow "
"student, and was both supportive and curious."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 629
#: sentence:2365
msgid "One of the early members recalled:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2366
msgid ""
"He really seemed to accept us all as students of the Course and was glad "
"that we, as a group, had taken on this year of study together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2367
msgid ""
"It was not anything he precisely said, but it was certainly his manner."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2368
msgid "I remember feeling very accepted by him, not special, just accepted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2369
msgid ""
"Particularly in those days, I was somewhat in awe of him, thinking, “This "
"man is very bright, he has a Ph.D., he helped put A Course In Miracles "
"together, so obviously he’s in a league different from mine.” But I didn’t "
"have that feeling around him at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2370
msgid ""
"There was nothing pretentious or ostentatious about him, nor did he look for"
" flaws or shortcomings; he just genuinely accepted us all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2371
msgid "Looking back, none of us really knew what we were getting into."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2372
msgid "I suspect that in those days we were kind of pioneers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 630
#: sentence:2373
msgid ""
"No doubt other people were doing something similar, but I got the feeling "
"from Bill of just being complimented for what we were doing.[31]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 631
#: sentence:2374
msgid ""
"As part of his new life, Bill simply liked being in Denver; he felt relaxed "
"and taken care of, as he was actually shy and naïve about many basic areas "
"of life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 631
#: sentence:2375
msgid ""
"In Colorado, he could leave behind the academic scripts of New York and "
"escape the patriarchal roles in Tiburon; he could be just plain Bill with as"
" little distraction and pressure as possible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 631
#: sentence:2376
msgid ""
"The Prathers, who knew many of the people and circumstances of his Tiburon "
"life, also served as long-distance confidants although he did not visit "
"their home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 631
#: sentence:2377
msgid ""
"Most of their encounters occurred while Hugh was in Tiburon helping to edit "
"Jerry Jampolsky’s books."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 632
#: sentence:2378
msgid ""
"Although I never met Helen, I spoke with her a half-dozen times on the "
"phone, either at Bill’s home or mine."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 632
#: sentence:2379
msgid ""
"He had agreed, when he left New York, to call her every day at noon, New "
"York time, a promise he faithfully carried out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 632
#: sentence:2380
msgid ""
"Those daily calls were a kind of test for him, and he diligently practiced "
"not reacting to her provocative comments. “The conversations usually didn’t "
"make any sense at all, but the important thing was extending love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 632
#: sentence:2381
msgid ""
"Sometimes she would sound very different, very tender, before I would hang "
"up. That was authentic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 632
#: sentence:2382
msgid ""
"I didn’t understand it, but it was there.”[32] He was ambivalent about "
"calling her daily, and although he felt a deep love and commitment toward "
"her, he also felt obligated, angry, and guilty."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 632
#: sentence:2383
msgid ""
"No matter what he did or said, or how faithful he was about calling, she "
"rarely found it sufficient."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 633
#: sentence:2384
msgid ""
"With the daily calls, they would quickly run out of things to say, so "
"occasionally when we were together, he would pass the phone to me and say, "
"“Okay, here, you talk to Helen.” They were superficial conversations at "
"best, and I have no idea if she even knew who I was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 633
#: sentence:2385
msgid ""
"During one of Bill’s Denver visits, however, in contrast to my rather "
"trivial exchanges with Helen, Jaison had a radically different "
"experience—illustrative for all of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 633
#: sentence:2386
msgid "Bill called her at the appointed hour as several of us were chatting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 633
#: sentence:2387
msgid ""
"He then passed the phone around so everyone could speak with her, and "
"eventually it was Jaison’s turn."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 633
#: sentence:2388
msgid "He interacted with her for a few moments, then handed on the phone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 633
#: sentence:2389
msgid ""
"Immediately after the “group” call concluded, Jaison grabbed Bill and "
"exclaimed,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 634
#: sentence:2390
msgid "Bill, I just heard this voice like it was coming out of heaven!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 634
#: sentence:2391
msgid "It sounded like it was echoing from inside St. John’s Cathedral."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 634
#: sentence:2392
msgid ""
"It was this majestic, angelic, powerful, soft, clear, feminine, simply "
"beautiful, beautiful voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 634
#: sentence:2393
msgid ""
"How could there be such richness in a voice, and over the phone no less?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 634
#: sentence:2394
msgid ""
"Her words were something like, “Thank you for being interested,” but it was "
"the quality of the voice; I am blown away that nobody else seemed to be "
"impressed by talking to Helen![33]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 635
#: sentence:2395
msgid ""
"To Jaison’s awe-filled pronouncement, Bill calmly responded, “Oh, she just "
"does that for people sometimes.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 636
#: sentence:2396
msgid ""
"Whether it was deliberate or accidental, as she and Jaison talked, Helen "
"accessed the loving aspect of herself that brought forward the Course, yet "
"with none of the rest of us present."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 636
#: sentence:2397
msgid ""
"Even though that was Jaison’s only conversation with her, three decades "
"later he still recalls, “I was totally blown away and grateful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 636
#: sentence:2398
msgid ""
"It was just an amazing experience.”1[34] The Voice never interfered with her"
" daily activity but was always there when she “tuned into” that channel, so "
"to speak; her ability to turn it off and on was crucial."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 636
#: sentence:2399
msgid ""
"She described it as definitely not her own voice, although she recognized "
"it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 636
#: sentence:2400
msgid ""
"Most important, that “channel” where the Course originated is within "
"everyone, which explains why so many feel a profound familiarity with ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 637
#: sentence:2401
msgid "Chapter 13"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2402
msgid ""
"Although Bill was gay, there were women he deeply cared for and considered "
"an integral part of his life, especially after moving to California."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2403
msgid ""
"I found no evidence from interviews or archival records that there was ever "
"an important woman in his New York life other than Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2404
msgid ""
"That is not surprising since he always had a male partner while living there"
" and Helen consumed almost all his attention, even during his personal time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2405
msgid ""
"It’s a wonder he had time for anything or anyone outside his work and "
"preoccupation with her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2406
msgid ""
"One of his good friends characterized him as “ambiguously gay,” and Bill "
"told Jo, his first and only girlfriend, that he considered himself bisexual "
"even though he was not intimate with women."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2407
msgid ""
"Others opined that he thought and interacted in the world like a straight "
"man but conducted his private life as a gay man."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2408
msgid ""
"In his high school essay, he wrote of constantly following his sister and "
"her friends around and about his ongoing fascination with the opposite sex, "
"a fascination that apparently continued into adulthood."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2409
msgid ""
"In the California era, Bill was attracted to a few other women and with them"
" he had the same intimate yet not intimate relationship he and I had as "
"well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2410
msgid ""
"We have all been confounded at trying to explain what that relationship was "
"like."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 638
#: sentence:2411
msgid ""
"Also Bill was concerned that his homosexuality might reflect negatively on "
"ACIM, a sacred trust in his eyes, and spending time with women could provide"
" “cover.” Bill cannot easily be categorized in terms of his private life and"
" his ambivalence challenged him, too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 639
#: sentence:2412
msgid ""
"Perhaps he felt safe with women, at least those who were not overly "
"aggressive, just as many women feel safe with their gay men friends, without"
" the complications and expectations of an intimate involvement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 639
#: sentence:2413
msgid ""
"Having no romantic agenda leaves room for a deep and abiding friendship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 639
#: sentence:2414
msgid ""
"Bill could be very flirtatious, and was capable of giving anyone his "
"complete, undivided attention, evoking a feeling of being valued and cared "
"for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 639
#: sentence:2415
msgid ""
"Once when we were walking together in Tiburon, perhaps holding hands, a "
"stranger suddenly stopped and with unusual fervor commented on how marvelous"
" it was to see two people who cared so much about each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 639
#: sentence:2416
msgid "Whatever he “saw” deeply confirmed what I felt, too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 640
#: sentence:2417
msgid ""
"Our time together was always easy, wide open, and without secrets from my "
"perspective (I found out later there were things I didn’t know)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 640
#: sentence:2418
msgid ""
"We didn’t project our unfinished business onto one another, which was not a "
"matter of being polite but of genuine openheartedness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 640
#: sentence:2419
msgid ""
"And in all fairness, we neither lived nor worked together for extended "
"periods of time, and it is usually in such close, continuous relationships "
"where people begin to abrade against one another, survival strategies begin "
"to surface, and opportunities for self-discovery appear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 640
#: sentence:2420
msgid ""
"All of us have had our share of challenging relationships, but mine with "
"Bill seemed more like a reward, a respite from “learning lessons.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2421
msgid ""
"The only time I remember seeing Bill angry was in Tiburon while attending "
"the regular nine o’clock prayer meeting/discussion group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2422
msgid ""
"Judy and Jerry were unhappy with each other over something, and Bill felt "
"their discord was disruptive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2423
msgid ""
"In an uncharacteristic display of temper, Bill picked up the text and "
"slammed it down on the table, saying, “If you two don’t stop it, I’m "
"leaving!” like a father admonishing his children."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2424
msgid "That surprising outburst got everyone’s attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2425
msgid ""
"He seemed afraid of anger, his own and others, and like so many, defended "
"himself against it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2426
msgid ""
"In my research I’ve found other instances when Bill displayed anger but I "
"witnessed only that one occasion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2427
msgid ""
"Although he rarely revealed his angry side, he was periodically depressed, "
"which usually indicates repressed anger directed against one’s self."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 641
#: sentence:2428
msgid "Hidden anger and upset always continue to disturb one’s peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2429
msgid ""
"A noteworthy and consistent experience occurred every time Bill and I were "
"together, whether in Denver, Tiburon, or elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2430
msgid ""
"About two days after every visit I had an unusual feeling of “more.” It did "
"not matter what had happened, who was present, or what we discussed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2431
msgid "Something shifted on a level beyond personality or even recognition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2432
msgid ""
"If someone had asked, “More of what?” I would have answered, “Everything in "
"general and nothing in particular.” It was less about acquiring information "
"and more about clarity—an insightful process."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2433
msgid ""
"If I had a specific question or an unresolved issue, it was answered or "
"resolved, but not through my effort."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2434
msgid ""
"With every encounter I discovered a new level of internal power, becoming "
"more aware of myself, larger and more loving."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 642
#: sentence:2435
msgid ""
"This feeling of literal expanding consciousness was a hallmark of our coming"
" together and it never failed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2436
msgid ""
"Additional opportunities for growth were in store for both Bill and me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2437
msgid ""
"One morning in January 1979, Jerry called to say that while meditating he "
"had received a “message” that I should join him, Bill, and a third person, "
"Aeesha, to present a day-long seminar on ACIM for the University of "
"California at Santa Cruz, to be held three months later in April."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2438
msgid ""
"This was a shocking invitation as I had been a Course student for only a "
"year and a half."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2439
msgid ""
"The Course does indeed present challenges, and this one raised the bar."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2440
msgid ""
"Looking back, I can’t fathom all I didn’t know then, but somehow, by the end"
" of the day, the seminar seemed to be a success and Bill was greatly "
"relieved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2441
msgid "He despised speaking before large groups."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2442
msgid ""
"He thought a group of five or six was the perfect size; that he enjoyed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2443
msgid ""
"However, standing in front of a large group produced great anxiety for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2444
msgid ""
"Not only was public speaking threatening to him, but for his first few years"
" after retirement, he was still trying to avoid notoriety about the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2445
msgid ""
"His New York friends indicated that he always hated public speaking while "
"living there too, relying on tranquilizers to get through what he considered"
" an ordeal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 643
#: sentence:2446
msgid ""
"Jerry noted on the drive down to Santa Cruz, however, that he seemed more "
"willing when we were together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 644
#: sentence:2447
msgid "After ACIM workshop in San Diego, CA"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2448
msgid ""
"On several other occasions, Bill, Jerry, and I teamed up to present the "
"Course, once with Ken Wapnick in San Diego in the early 1980s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2449
msgid "I had heard about Ken but hadn’t yet met him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2450
msgid ""
"Accustomed as I was to making extensive preparations for classes or "
"workshops, the prospect of the four of us spending the next day with "
"hundreds of people, with no collaboration or planning beforehand, made me "
"nervous, to say the least."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2451
msgid ""
"If Bill and Helen were being rushed in their spiritual evolution, so were "
"many of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2452
msgid ""
"I asked Jerry if we needed to make a plan and he indicated he had one: he "
"would go first, then Ken, myself, and finally Bill. “That’s it?” I said, "
"“That’s the plan?” “That’s the plan,” he said, as if that took care of "
"everything, and for him, it did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2453
msgid ""
"Jerry was skilled and experienced at letting events unfold, and I, of "
"necessity, learned a tremendous amount from him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2454
msgid ""
"I had no choice but to listen carefully and trust I would know what to do "
"next."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2455
msgid ""
"As Ken, Jerry, and I gave our various presentations, Bill periodically stood"
" up and announced, “I think it’s time to do a lesson.” He would then read a "
"lesson, inviting the audience to fully participate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2456
msgid ""
"He felt that teaching ACIM was not his mission, but he was happy to comment "
"on what someone else had to say, and he loved to read the lessons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2457
msgid "He could have recited the alphabet and it wouldn’t have mattered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 645
#: sentence:2458
msgid "People loved listening to Bill—and they loved him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 646
#: sentence:2459
msgid ""
"We ended the day on a happy note, and despite his anxiety, Bill’s "
"participation was marvelous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 646
#: sentence:2460
msgid ""
"With his beautiful voice and captivating presence, people were spellbound."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 646
#: sentence:2461
msgid ""
"Over the years, his attitude softened a bit and he became a little more "
"willing to participate, but he was never completely comfortable with public "
"appearances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 646
#: sentence:2462
msgid ""
"It was such a paradox, because he was a tremendously effective speaker and "
"people were always greatly moved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 647
#: sentence:2463
msgid ""
"In Denver in late 1979, six of us interested in attitudinal healing formed a"
" center based on Jerry’s Center for Attitudinal Healing in Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 647
#: sentence:2464
msgid ""
"Four years earlier Jerry had felt called to provide a forum for practicing "
"the insights gleaned from ACIM; he established a program based on its "
"principles for children with catastrophic illnesses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 647
#: sentence:2465
msgid ""
"Several other groups and/or individuals were so impressed by Jerry’s "
"“experiment” that they modeled centers after his."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 647
#: sentence:2466
msgid ""
"The Center for Creative Alternatives in Denver was either the fourth or "
"fifth center established, and Bill sat on our board of directors, the only "
"other board of any kind he was part of besides the Tiburon Center."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 647
#: sentence:2467
msgid ""
"In the mid 1970s, the idea of lay people substantively helping one another "
"was a new idea."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 647
#: sentence:2468
msgid ""
"Jerry pioneered the formation of lay support groups, and within a short time"
" after implementing his ideas, support groups sprang up like mushrooms."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 648
#: sentence:2469
msgid ""
"When we held our center’s grand opening in April 1980, Jerry and Bill joined"
" us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 648
#: sentence:2470
msgid ""
"Jerry made a wonderful presentation, as always, and Bill remained "
"unobtrusively in the background but definitely present, adding substance to "
"the occasion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 648
#: sentence:2471
msgid "We deeply appreciated his willingness to support our endeavor."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 648
#: sentence:2472
msgid ""
"During the reception afterward, he had a chance to mingle with the Denver "
"students, which gave him yet another opportunity to witness ACIM’s impact "
"firsthand and to hear more of its effect on changing people’s lives."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 649
#: sentence:2473
msgid ""
"Our center started with a handful of support groups, as well as what turned "
"into ACIM classes, although they were originally established as volunteer-"
"training classes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 649
#: sentence:2474
msgid ""
"Seeking to learn from challenges Jerry had faced, we clearly stated that the"
" services and groups offered were based on principles from ACIM, not on a "
"smorgasbord of potentially competing theories."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 649
#: sentence:2475
msgid ""
"We presumed we would make mistakes, but at least they wouldn’t be the same "
"ones he had encountered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 649
#: sentence:2476
msgid ""
"We wanted to practice Course principles with children or adults with "
"catastrophic illnesses, as Jerry was successfully doing, and in addition, to"
" include anyone in crisis or transition, anyone whose lives seemed "
"unfulfilled."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 649
#: sentence:2477
msgid ""
"Thus, we decided to conduct a volunteer-training series so those who chose "
"to join us would know what we stood for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 649
#: sentence:2478
msgid ""
"Offhandedly, we announced that the series would also be available to anyone "
"wishing to learn more about ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2479
msgid ""
"To our surprise, only a few wanted to be volunteers but many were interested"
" in learning about the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2480
msgid "Some apparently wanted to read it but found it difficult."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2481
msgid ""
"Our ACIM overview series, a retooled version of our volunteer-training "
"program, provided clarity about the Course’s philosophy, how it worked, what"
" it was and was not for, making the material much more accessible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2482
msgid ""
"Although not designed as a substitute for practicing ACIM, our classes made "
"it easier to take the first steps of self-study, its original purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2483
msgid ""
"Beginning in February 1980, we facilitated the series many times during the "
"early 1980s, spawning further study groups for those who wanted to continue "
"group work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2484
msgid ""
"It was a great example of proceeding in one direction only to find you have "
"been rerouted elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 650
#: sentence:2485
msgid ""
"Though not our original game plan, the classes turned out to be important "
"venues for teaching what we needed to learn and as preparation for chapters "
"not yet dreamed of."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2486
msgid ""
"Jaison Kayn and I originally taught the overview series, and a class was in "
"progress during one of Bill’s visits."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2487
msgid ""
"As we prepared for the evening, we asked him if he wanted to stay at home or"
" attend the class. “I want to come,” he answered, “but don’t tell anyone who"
" I am.” We promised not to disclose his identity, but were certain that "
"someone would find him out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2488
msgid ""
"For most of his life, I think Bill was honestly unaware that people "
"recognized something unique about him, and he thought if he didn’t say "
"anything, his anonymity would be protected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2489
msgid ""
"Since his name was common enough, we introduced him simply as Bill, a friend"
" visiting from out of town and attending just that one night."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2490
msgid ""
"The classes were long, from 7:30 to 10:00 and often beyond, with a break in "
"the middle."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2491
msgid ""
"Sure enough, suspecting he was not an ordinary Course student, people asked "
"during the break, “Who is that guy, anyway?” We repeated our story that he "
"was a friend visiting for a few days, which was accurate but incomplete."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2492
msgid ""
"Sensing something unusual, they started to talk to him, and predictably, as "
"he was drawn into conversation, the secret eventually came out, as he was "
"unwilling to lie when the questions became more probing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2493
msgid ""
"He still didn’t participate outwardly in any way, however, even after being "
"“discovered.” Class members asked questions but not of him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 651
#: sentence:2494
msgid ""
"I always found it hilarious that he thought he could sit there unnoticed, "
"radiating his light in the middle of the class."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 652
#: sentence:2495
msgid ""
"Although Bill and I had shared a platform on a few occasions before and "
"after those classes, I had never taught one with him in the audience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 652
#: sentence:2496
msgid "Having Bill there as a smiling student was somewhat unsettling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 652
#: sentence:2497
msgid ""
"It felt approximately like preaching the Sermon on the Mount with Jesus "
"sitting in the third row."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 652
#: sentence:2498
msgid ""
"On subsequent visits, I got used to it, but the first time was challenging, "
"to say the least."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 652
#: sentence:2499
msgid ""
"Hugh Prather commented that Bill would also faithfully attend his or Jerry’s"
" presentations, when they were in Tiburon, and was always interested in what"
" they had to say."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 652
#: sentence:2500
msgid "Hugh felt Bill genuinely thought he could learn something from him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 653
#: sentence:2501
msgid ""
"Just as teaching with Bill or having him in the audience was a stretch for "
"me, and standing before a group challenging for him, any person willing to "
"confront conditioning, long-held beliefs, and fear of the unknown is "
"courageous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 653
#: sentence:2502
msgid ""
"Every small step of self-discovery requires determination, and the Course "
"comforts and encourages us as we take them. So did Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 654
#: sentence:2503
msgid "00029.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2504
msgid ""
"Collaborating with Jules Finegold on several books, both Jerry Jampolsky’s "
"and their own, had been Bill’s first project on settling into his new life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2505
msgid ""
"That collaboration extended to include Pat Hopkins, Hugh Prather, and after "
"Helen’s death, Bob Skutch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2506
msgid ""
"Bill continued some of his own writing; he and Roger Walsh co-authored a "
"revised version of the chapter on personality theory for the Comprehensive "
"Textbook on Psychiatry."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2507
msgid "He also started a novel, but it never went anywhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2508
msgid ""
"Years earlier, more than one psychic reading told Bill he would be living by"
" the water some day, writing children’s books with cartoons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2509
msgid ""
"Naturally, with his background he found that the most unlikely of "
"predictions, but there he was, organizing Jerry’s book, Love Is Letting Go "
"of Fear, which included many cartoons to illustrate relevant points about "
"the Course.[35] His attention to detail and long history of voluminous "
"writing and editing was very helpful to Jerry and added substantively to his"
" books."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2510
msgid ""
"Jerry even asked him if he wanted to be listed as a co-author, but Bill "
"declined."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 655
#: sentence:2511
msgid "He was still dodging the spotlight."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 656
#: sentence:2512
msgid "There was plenty on his plate besides writing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 656
#: sentence:2513
msgid ""
"Just as his friends wanted to support and nurture him, Bill, in turn, was "
"consistently and generously available for all his close friends, "
"particularly Jerry."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 656
#: sentence:2514
msgid ""
"Being helpful to Jerry, who was going through some trying times, was a major"
" reason for his moving to California."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 656
#: sentence:2515
msgid ""
"Years later, as he became less of a “project” for Bill, Jerry jokingly mused"
" that he wasn’t sure if Bill had reduced his ministrations because he "
"thought he had succeeded or because it was a hopeless task!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 656
#: sentence:2516
msgid "Jerry knew perfectly well, of course, how much Bill cared for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 657
#: sentence:2517
msgid ""
"In Tiburon, in addition to focusing considerable time on writing and self-"
"reflection, Bill served on the board of directors for the Center for "
"Attitudinal Healing, where some issue or relationship often seemed to "
"require his wise counsel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 657
#: sentence:2518
msgid ""
"For several months he also devoted time to being interviewed for a video "
"history of ACIM, though that first attempt was never released commercially."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 657
#: sentence:2519
msgid ""
"A couple of years later, a BBC producer who was a friend of Judy’s directed "
"the video, The Story of A Course In Miracles, which involved more time-"
"consuming filming of Bill telling his story."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 657
#: sentence:2520
msgid ""
"He also had the daily nine o’clock meetings at Jerry’s, attended a weekly "
"Course group, and had countless meetings with new people he met through "
"Jerry or Judy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 658
#: sentence:2521
msgid ""
"“New people met through Jerry or Judy” should be emphasized because they "
"occupied no small portion of his time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 658
#: sentence:2522
msgid ""
"Jerry was the quintessential Pied Piper, drawing people to Tiburon from all "
"over; some were interested in learning about his center and some were "
"intrigued with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 658
#: sentence:2523
msgid ""
"When I entered the scene, the center was three and a half years old and had "
"already attracted major national publicity; its star was on the rise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 658
#: sentence:2524
msgid ""
"And any household over which Judy presides is always a three-ring circus at "
"the very least."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 658
#: sentence:2525
msgid ""
"The edition of New Realities magazine that first announced ACIM to the world"
" also featured an interview with Judy:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 659
#: sentence:2526
msgid "As president of the Foundation for Inner Peace, Judith R."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 659
#: sentence:2527
msgid ""
"Skutch’s life in the 1970s can best be summarized as a typical day in her "
"consciousness exploratorium salon in the Skutch’s large New York City "
"apartment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 659
#: sentence:2528
msgid ""
"In one room a motion picture is being screened to a group interested in "
"biofeedback."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 659
#: sentence:2529
msgid "In another are seekers deep in meditation training."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 659
#: sentence:2530
msgid "In still another room a medical research meeting is in progress."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 660
#: sentence:2531
msgid ""
"Skutch herself seems to be in all places at once as she also juggles three "
"telephones connecting people in the consciousness field to each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 660
#: sentence:2532
msgid ""
"And at any given moment, one might find an Edgar Mitchell, a Swami "
"Muktananda, or a Uri Geller on hand, not to mention the usual assortment of "
"mediums, mystics, and scientists—or just friends of friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 660
#: sentence:2533
msgid ""
"To a first-time visitor, it seems a miracle that such a petite lady can keep"
" all of this going at once, in addition to often serving her home-cooked "
"dinners to those gathered.[36]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 661
#: sentence:2534
msgid ""
"When the Skutches moved to Tiburon, Judy’s inclinations for gathering those "
"at the leading edge of consciousness exploration continued unabated, and "
"their home continued to be headquarters for the Foundation for Inner Peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 661
#: sentence:2535
msgid ""
"When Judy and her current husband, William (Whit) Whitson, established their"
" home, the Foundation functions were divided between their household and Bob"
" Skutch’s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 661
#: sentence:2536
msgid ""
"When Judy and Whit began overseeing the foreign-language translations of "
"ACIM (eighteen have been published and six more are in process), with all "
"the busyness and drama that involved, that comprised only one ring of the "
"ongoing circus."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 661
#: sentence:2537
msgid ""
"Thus, Jerry and Judy, with their respective households and organizations, "
"were responsible for legions of people—friends, family and extended family, "
"the famous and unknown, movers and shakers of the consciousness movement, "
"those who wanted to offer help, curiosity seekers, and more—streaming "
"through Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 661
#: sentence:2538
msgid ""
"They often included Bill in various activities, either to make sure he felt "
"included and welcome in his new environs or because they sought his advice "
"and counsel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 661
#: sentence:2539
msgid "He was one busy fellow. Judy’s daughter, Tammy, remembers:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 662
#: sentence:2540
msgid ""
"I noticed that when Bill moved to California, he began to relate to many "
"more people in the playful manner that he had always related to me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 662
#: sentence:2541
msgid ""
"It was as though the more he practiced the Course, and the farther he got "
"from his old establishment life in New York, the more he let loose his "
"indomitable, charming, childlike self."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 663
#: sentence:2542
msgid "Dressed up for the dinner parties"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 664
#: sentence:2543
msgid "After graduation, I didn’t see Bill for long intervals."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 664
#: sentence:2544
msgid ""
"Whenever we did see each other, it was usually for some special occasion or "
"dinner party my mother was orchestrating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 664
#: sentence:2545
msgid ""
"Inasmuch as the location and our lives were different, the situation still "
"seemed the same and we comfortably slipped into our playful roles with each "
"other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 664
#: sentence:2546
msgid ""
"We once again became participants in a never-ending dinner party in which "
"guests and conversations altered—but the dessert was always chocolate—and "
"Bill would continue somehow to make everything seem more palatable for "
"me.[37]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 665
#: sentence:2547
msgid "00012.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 666
#: sentence:2548
msgid ""
"When I was in Tiburon, aside from visiting with many people and having long "
"discussions with Bill, I would assist him with organizing and editing "
"Jerry’s work, beginning with a packet of eighteen cards featuring "
"commentaries on Course lessons particularly helpful to Jerry (now expanded "
"to book form: To Give Is To Receive: An Eighteen Day Mini-Course on Healing "
"Relationships).[38] Jerry’s first full-length book, Love Is Letting Go of "
"Fear, was Bill’s next collaborative project with him and I occasionally "
"joined him in that effort."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 666
#: sentence:2549
msgid ""
"At the least, it was another way to spend quality time in each other’s "
"company."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 666
#: sentence:2550
msgid ""
"We enjoyed socializing with others of the Tiburon group and, with Jules in "
"charge, toured San Francisco or the more scenic, rural parts of Marin "
"County."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 666
#: sentence:2551
msgid ""
"There was never a lack of interesting people to meet or things to do, but "
"relating was what really mattered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 667
#: sentence:2552
msgid ""
"Last but certainly not least, were the really funny episodes interspersed "
"throughout our time together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 667
#: sentence:2553
msgid ""
"Bill was a born comedian and would often make hilarious comments that were "
"inside jokes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 667
#: sentence:2554
msgid ""
"When other people, especially visiting dignitaries, were around, he might "
"innocently refer to something only he and I knew about, making it impossible"
" to keep a straight face if we made eye contact."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 667
#: sentence:2555
msgid ""
"Many of his friends also experienced his delightful, playful, and irreverent"
" side, sharing with him a personal joke or watching as he wiggled his ears "
"while looking very serious or proper (no one could figure out how he did "
"that)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 667
#: sentence:2556
msgid ""
"He was more than willing to lighten things up when he decided someone was "
"being overly serious or self-important."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2557
msgid ""
"In Bill’s earlier California days, he was not yet driving, and several years"
" passed before he felt comfortable enough to purchase a car and navigate "
"around his neighborhood."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2558
msgid ""
"In New York he had no need to drive and hadn’t owned a car for more than two"
" decades."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2559
msgid ""
"Therefore, if we went someplace farther afield than Tiburon and environs, "
"someone else drove."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2560
msgid ""
"When it was time to return to Denver, Jules usually would take Bill and me "
"to the airport."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2561
msgid ""
"As Jules waited, Bill always came to the gate and stayed with me until "
"boarding time (this was long before heightened security measures), and he "
"seemed genuinely sorry I was leaving."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2562
msgid ""
"We were very close but that doesn’t imply the “specialness” that precludes "
"closeness to others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2563
msgid ""
"Over the years, he had other treasured and important relationships as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2564
msgid ""
"The Course states: “Under the Holy Spirit’s teaching all relationships are "
"seen as total commitments, yet they do not conflict with one another in any "
"way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 668
#: sentence:2565
msgid ""
"Perfect faith in each one, for its ability to satisfy you completely, arises"
" only from perfect faith in yourself.”[39]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 669
#: sentence:2566
msgid "Chapter 14"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 670
#: sentence:2567
msgid ""
"Even as Bill had struggled during the ACIM scribing era, feeling it was so "
"difficult, the purifying effect was under way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 670
#: sentence:2568
msgid ""
"The entire process of receiving and typing the material—the discussions and "
"arguments about its meaning and then the editing—forced Bill and Helen to "
"focus on it continually."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 670
#: sentence:2569
msgid ""
"Even when not doing the lessons or studying, they were under its influence, "
"and by the time I met Bill, much “unlearning” had occurred, though it wasn’t"
" yet complete."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 670
#: sentence:2570
msgid ""
"He was becoming very clear and being with him always felt light and free, "
"even when he was depressed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 670
#: sentence:2571
msgid ""
"These “down” periods, when he entertained the preposterous notion that he "
"didn’t have much to offer, didn’t keep others from enjoying his marvelous "
"presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 670
#: sentence:2572
msgid ""
"He was a “work in progress,” still harboring some grievances, but his loving"
" nature was always apparent, his light still shining through, and his help "
"unfailingly available."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2573
msgid ""
"It is comforting to know we can be helpful even while we’re still getting "
"free ourselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2574
msgid ""
"We need not and should not wait until we are entirely clear before we choose"
" to be truly helpful, which would be like trying to remove the darkness "
"before turning on a light."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2575
msgid ""
"In fact, doing our best to be compassionate, open, and nonjudgmental is the "
"point, recognizing that correction is not our job but loving is."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2576
msgid ""
"Shortly after the scribing began, Bill was invited to a meeting on a subject"
" he knew little about."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2577
msgid ""
"For political reasons, those at the medical center felt it imperative that "
"he attend, and he was most uncomfortable about the prospect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2578
msgid ""
"In an instance of synchronicity, Helen took down a passage he found "
"extraordinarily helpful, just as it has been for many others since."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 671
#: sentence:2579
msgid ""
"It is often recited at the beginning of events or study groups—whenever one "
"needs to remember our true purpose:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 672
#: sentence:2580
msgid "I am here only to be truly helpful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 673
#: sentence:2581
msgid "I am here to represent Him Who sent me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 674
#: sentence:2582
msgid "I do not have to worry about what to say or what"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 675
#: sentence:2583
msgid "to do, because He Who sent me will direct me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 676
#: sentence:2584
msgid "I am content to be wherever He wishes, knowing"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 677
#: sentence:2585
msgid "He goes there with me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 678
#: sentence:2586
msgid "I will be healed as I let Him teach me to heal.[40]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 679
#: sentence:2587
msgid "Bill recalled his relief on receiving that special message:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 680
#: sentence:2588
msgid ""
"This message helped me recognize that I did not have to rely on my "
"intellectual defenses in preparing for the conference or anything else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 680
#: sentence:2589
msgid ""
"All I had to do was to recognize that I was there to be truly helpful and "
"that there would be guidance and help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 680
#: sentence:2590
msgid ""
"Regardless of what the assignment might seem to be, I didn’t have to plan, I"
" didn’t have to anticipate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 680
#: sentence:2591
msgid "All of this was very different."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 680
#: sentence:2592
msgid ""
"I was accustomed to planning, anticipating, having lectures and everything "
"worked out intellectually ahead of time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 680
#: sentence:2593
msgid ""
"Here, I think, the lesson in trust is really what is being emphasized.[41]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 681
#: sentence:2594
msgid "And a next lesson in trust was about to unfold."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 681
#: sentence:2595
msgid ""
"In 1981, Bill made arrangements to have Christmas with us in Denver, and all"
" four of us were very excited about his coming."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 681
#: sentence:2596
msgid ""
"We had planned several special treats, especially related to the seasonal "
"celebratory music; everything was prepared, with his presents under the "
"tree. Then the phone call."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 681
#: sentence:2597
msgid ""
"The day before his planned arrival, Jules called to say that Bill had had a "
"serious bout of atrial fibrillation, a malfunction of the heart."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 681
#: sentence:2598
msgid ""
"We were devastated, first out of concern for his well-being, and second, "
"because we were so looking forward to including him in what would probably "
"have been his first truly “family Christmas” since his own early childhood."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2599
msgid ""
"The day before, Pat Hopkins, then a consultant with the Center for "
"Attitudinal Healing, had gone by Bill’s home after work at his request."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2600
msgid ""
"They were becoming much better acquainted and had developed a routine of "
"getting together at the close of her business day."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2601
msgid ""
"He had called her earlier in the day to say he was not feeling quite up to "
"par, a characteristic understatement, and asked if she would take him to the"
" hospital when she finished work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2602
msgid ""
"His condition steadily worsened after her arrival and she called the "
"paramedics."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2603
msgid ""
"They required considerable time to stabilize his acutely dangerous "
"condition, then they rushed him to the hospital by ambulance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2604
msgid "No doubt, Pat saved his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2605
msgid ""
"She later assumed the task of handling all paperwork related to insurance, "
"medication, and the details of recovery, which, given his basic "
"unfamiliarity with such matters, would have been more than overwhelming to "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 682
#: sentence:2606
msgid "She was literally a God-send."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 683
#: sentence:2607
msgid ""
"Bill returned to Denver only once or twice after his near-fatal collapse."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 683
#: sentence:2608
msgid ""
"Our Center for Creative Alternatives had teamed up with the Mile High Church"
" of Religious Science in Denver to sponsor a workshop featuring Jerry and "
"Hugh Prather in April 1982."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 683
#: sentence:2609
msgid ""
"We had a sellout crowd, and while planning that event, Jerry and I "
"intuitively felt we had some joint work to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 683
#: sentence:2610
msgid ""
"Three weeks later, I went to Tiburon and we brainstormed about the nature of"
" possible projects."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 683
#: sentence:2611
msgid ""
"For the next two years, Jerry and I worked closely together in a number of "
"areas, which entailed frequent visits to Tiburon and ongoing contact with "
"Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 683
#: sentence:2612
msgid "Thus, between 1978 and 1985, I was there many times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 684
#: sentence:2613
msgid ""
"During his first four years in Tiburon, Bill’s life was busy, especially for"
" a retiree, but not extraordinary."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 684
#: sentence:2614
msgid "His days were not filled with particularly grand or exotic events."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 684
#: sentence:2615
msgid ""
"He worked, meditated, wrote, visited, recovered from his cardiac "
"difficulties, helped friends, and faithfully walked."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 684
#: sentence:2616
msgid ""
"Because his daily routine sounds so ordinary, it doesn’t convey the magic so"
" many felt on being around him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 684
#: sentence:2617
msgid ""
"Therefore, before continuing with the chronology of his earthly adventure, "
"here are more details of his major positive characteristics and their life-"
"altering impact on others, as well as the “demons” that plagued him—all the "
"challenges, fears, and concerns that had to be forgiven."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 685
#: sentence:2618
msgid ""
"And for all of us drawn into his energy field and who feel part of his "
"lineage, our job is to continue our own forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 685
#: sentence:2619
msgid ""
"The world can’t wait for us to be “ready.” As with Bill, we can be helpful "
"while we’re still “in process,” and we must."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 685
#: sentence:2620
msgid "The stakes are very high and ignoring our calling could be disastrous."
msgstr ""

