#. Paragraph 729
#: sentence:2669
msgid "Chapter 15"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 730
#: sentence:2670
msgid ""
"There is no doubt Bill’s external life history is fascinating, but more "
"important, it ultimately provides éntree to his inner experience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 730
#: sentence:2671
msgid ""
"Bill was highly regarded, widely known, and included in assorted “Who’s Who”"
" lists of the academic world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 730
#: sentence:2672
msgid ""
"As should be obvious by now, he was brilliant, erudite, painstakingly "
"meticulous, sophisticated, dignified, and a great lover of music and "
"theater."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 730
#: sentence:2673
msgid ""
"Those persons interviewed for this book added their assessments—gracious, "
"courtly, a real gentleman, compassionate and encouraging, an impeccable man."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 730
#: sentence:2674
msgid ""
"He was also reserved, nonconfrontational, and rarely emotionally expressive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 730
#: sentence:2675
msgid "Catherine Prescott, a good friend, observed:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 731
#: sentence:2676
msgid ""
"Bill was an old-fashioned, almost Victorian transplant into this century."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 731
#: sentence:2677
msgid "He had very formal, perfect manners and protocol."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 731
#: sentence:2678
msgid ""
"I saw him in a lot of different environments and he never lost that really "
"charming and debonair quality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 731
#: sentence:2679
msgid "In many ways he was a real chameleon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 731
#: sentence:2680
msgid "I think he was many things to many people.[1]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 732
#: sentence:2681
msgid ""
"He could be ultrawitty and was a universally acknowledged master of the pun,"
" even a double pun."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 732
#: sentence:2682
msgid ""
"And because he was so smart and sophisticated, his ability to be funny was "
"on the leading edge of the bell curve."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 732
#: sentence:2683
msgid ""
"As with many, his humor could also be a defense, a way of deflecting a "
"subject that got too close for comfort, a distraction from his own pain."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 732
#: sentence:2684
msgid ""
"He was courageous, having steadfastly continued with ACIM’s secret unfolding"
" in the face of potential disgrace and loss of employment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 733
#: sentence:2685
msgid ""
"Bill was also private, shy, deliberately compartmentalized, and secretive, "
"often keeping various relationships separate from other friends and "
"colleagues."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 733
#: sentence:2686
msgid ""
"His ability to compartmentalize was ideal for someone who had worked for the"
" CIA and held diverse positions at Columbia, especially for a gay man, given"
" that our society was much less tolerant several decades ago."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 733
#: sentence:2687
msgid ""
"Incidentally, Bill would not have discussed his sexual preference even if he"
" had been heterosexual, considering that déclasse and none of anyone’s "
"business."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 733
#: sentence:2688
msgid ""
"He used to joke, “Keep your life a muddle and no one will ever know what’s "
"going on.” In his reading in 1980, Leroy Zemke described a characteristic of"
" the indigo blue color in Bill’s aura:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 734
#: sentence:2689
msgid ""
"This color also indicates that you can be very secretive, that you have a "
"way of sharing what you feel you can share, but if you choose not to share, "
"no living person will every draw it out of you, period."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 734
#: sentence:2690
msgid ""
"That color indicates nobody gets through and that is between you and God. . "
". ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 734
#: sentence:2691
msgid ""
"You are not about to open yourself to the place where you’re almost going to"
" be put on an operating table, to be taken apart piece by piece."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 734
#: sentence:2692
msgid ""
"This color represents your not wanting to share yourself with the world, or "
"even with close or intimate friends.[2]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 735
#: sentence:2693
msgid ""
"Although it sounds contradictory, he was also very open, authentic, warm, "
"friendly, casual, unassuming, gentle, kind, and as a friend mentioned "
"earlier, intensely sincere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 735
#: sentence:2694
msgid ""
"He operated from a deep sense of integrity, which partially accounts for the"
" instantaneous sense of safety almost everyone felt around him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 736
#: sentence:2695
msgid ""
"Regarding his challenges, Bill could be depressed, ungrounded, restless, and"
" argumentative; he required routine in order to function effectively in many"
" areas of life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 736
#: sentence:2696
msgid ""
"He could also display an edge when his passive aggressive nature was aroused"
" and was perfectly capable of analyzing another’s ego, seeing what was "
"inconsistent or unworkable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 736
#: sentence:2697
msgid ""
"In the presence of loud or pushy people, whom he found distressing, he would"
" “back up” emotionally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 736
#: sentence:2698
msgid "When upset, he could be uptight and not at all funny."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 736
#: sentence:2699
msgid ""
"Not knowing much about the world outside academia, he tended to observe life"
" rather than fully participate in it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 736
#: sentence:2700
msgid ""
"For the most part, I never personally experienced his “down” side, but to "
"complete the picture, others’ experiences and observations deserve "
"inclusion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2701
msgid ""
"Almost everyone was disarmed by Bill’s transparency, which was profoundly "
"effective."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2702
msgid ""
"One might ask how this squares with being secretive, but the answer is easy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2703
msgid ""
"He felt the need for privacy at the human level and to keep secret his "
"thoughts and actions, but he couldn’t hide his energetic presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2704
msgid "The unalterable truth of him, his loving reality, was always apparent."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2705
msgid ""
"As part of his inclination to secrecy, he rarely expressed a strong personal"
" opinion or commented on political issues or current events."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2706
msgid ""
"I never heard anyone attempt a political or other controversial conversation"
" with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2707
msgid ""
"Jack Luckett shared his thoughts about Bill’s sense of patriotism: “He knew "
"he was lucky to be born a white American male but he wasn’t sure about the "
"gay part."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2708
msgid ""
"We used to go to 4th of July celebrations in La Jolla, and when well done, "
"he found them moving."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2709
msgid ""
"I think sometimes he found my gung-ho Marine commitment amusing, but he "
"admired it as well.”[3] His wife Layle added, “You knew Billy very well and "
"know he was not passionate about much except opera and Mozart!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2710
msgid "I’d call him ‘neutral’ regarding patriotism."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2711
msgid ""
"Certainly he was not a flag-waving, ‘America first’ kind of a guy, but he "
"appreciated being born here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 737
#: sentence:2712
msgid ""
"Maybe he was too removed from human ‘life-in-time [and space]’ to concern "
"himself with feeling superior over his choice of birthplaces.”[4] Jack "
"concluded, “Bill was as complex as a Chinese puzzle but had a strong desire "
"just to be normal.”[5]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 738
#: sentence:2713
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles states that what we perceive in others is up to us; we "
"can see them through eyes of love or fear and our “perception is a choice "
"and not a fact.”[6] That said, it is fascinating to note that almost "
"everyone I interviewed described their experience with Bill in nearly "
"identical terms—repeatedly emphasizing a few signature traits."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 738
#: sentence:2714
msgid ""
"These comments, for the most part, were offered by those who knew him in his"
" post-Columbia years, and thus after he had been strongly influenced by the "
"Course for more than a decade."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 738
#: sentence:2715
msgid "ACIM was working on him even while he was working on it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2716
msgid "What does it mean that the Course was “working” on him?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2717
msgid ""
"Bill knew very well that one doesn’t “take the Course,” as one might take an"
" algebra or chemistry class."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2718
msgid ""
"The point is not to learn how to get one’s way or acquire facts or "
"strategies more effectively, but to unlearn our early programming."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2719
msgid ""
"Some persons have labeled ACIM a mind-training course—indeed, it is and "
"thank goodness for that!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2720
msgid ""
"From birth, our minds are trained to believe in separation, self-absorption,"
" and lack, not only through our families but through all our societal "
"encounters—educational, political, religious, and through the media."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2721
msgid ""
"That training—unhelpful and inaccurate but not necessarily deliberate—to "
"regard ourselves as smaller and less deserving or important than we really "
"are, must change if we hope to experience any peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2722
msgid ""
"The consistent practice of Course principles drives long-standing, limiting "
"beliefs from our original mind training into conscious awareness, so we can "
"decide whether to be bound by them or not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2723
msgid ""
"It’s as if we have all been born and raised in a cult, with the ego as the "
"tyrannical leader, requiring absolute allegiance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2724
msgid ""
"Since we know of no other way of being, we presume this is the only way to "
"live."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 739
#: sentence:2725
msgid "ACIM acts as a “deprogrammer” for our ego-directed brainwashing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 740
#: sentence:2726
msgid ""
"Socrates famously declared that the unexamined life is not worth living."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 740
#: sentence:2727
msgid ""
"In modern parlance, if we refuse to look at the mental/emotional "
"conditioning we originally learned for survival, we become like reactive "
"robots unable to make appropriate choices, basing our lives on an irrelevant"
" past rather than living in the here and now."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 740
#: sentence:2728
msgid ""
"A Course In Miracles is a spiritual technology, celestial cleanser for the "
"soul, cleaning our vision so we can know surely and directly we are safe, "
"loved, and valuable—now and always."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 740
#: sentence:2729
msgid "The introduction to the workbook states:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 741
#: sentence:2730
msgid ""
"The purpose of the workbook is to train your mind in a systematic way to a "
"different perception of everyone and everything in the world. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 742
#: sentence:2731
msgid "This will require no effort on your part."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 742
#: sentence:2732
msgid ""
"The exercises themselves meet the conditions necessary for this kind of "
"transfer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 743
#: sentence:2733
msgid ""
"Some of the ideas the workbook presents you will find hard to believe, and "
"others may seem to be quite startling. This does not matter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 743
#: sentence:2734
msgid "You are merely asked to apply the ideas as you are directed to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 743
#: sentence:2735
msgid "You are not asked to judge them at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 743
#: sentence:2736
msgid "You are asked only to use them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 743
#: sentence:2737
msgid ""
"It is their use that will give them meaning to you, and will show you that "
"they are true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 744
#: sentence:2738
msgid ""
"Remember only this; you need not believe the ideas, you need not accept "
"them, and you need not even welcome them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 744
#: sentence:2739
msgid "Some of them you may actively resist."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 744
#: sentence:2740
msgid "None of this will matter, or decrease their efficacy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 744
#: sentence:2741
msgid ""
"But do not allow yourself to make exceptions in applying the ideas the "
"workbook contains, and whatever your reactions to the ideas may be, use "
"them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 744
#: sentence:2742
msgid "Nothing more than that is required.[7]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 745
#: sentence:2743
msgid ""
"Notice there’s not a word about carefully learning anything, only daily "
"practicing in the face of one’s disbelief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 745
#: sentence:2744
msgid "And practice Bill did, but what was he practicing?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 745
#: sentence:2745
msgid ""
"The last section of the text, “Choose Once Again,” was one of his favorites "
"and he took it to heart. “Trials are but lessons that you failed to learn "
"presented once again, so where you made a faulty choice before you now can "
"make a better one, and thus escape all pain that what you chose before has "
"brought to you.”[8] He was determined to notice the times when he lost his "
"peace—times that threatened his self-image or when things weren’t unfolding "
"as he thought they should."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 745
#: sentence:2746
msgid ""
"As swiftly as possible he would choose to let them go, realizing he was the "
"author of his own distress."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 745
#: sentence:2747
msgid ""
"One can almost see his original mind-set being released and these new, yet "
"timeless, values being adopted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 746
#: sentence:2748
msgid ""
"Bill’s inner life can best be explored in three ways: through quotes and "
"illustrations from members of his extended ACIM family who knew him well; "
"through his own words; and through revealing comments made by the Author of "
"A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 746
#: sentence:2749
msgid ""
"My task is to facilitate joining these “voices” to reveal the most "
"comprehensive picture possible of Bill’s inner life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 746
#: sentence:2750
msgid ""
"The reason for providing an inside view is that his inner life and ours are "
"so alike."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 746
#: sentence:2751
msgid ""
"Even though the externals of our lives may look entirely different, the "
"internal process of release is the same for everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2752
msgid ""
"Remember the observation about Bill’s being as complex as a Chinese puzzle?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2753
msgid ""
"In choosing to release his grievances, quiet his mind, and live "
"defenselessly, Bill allowed the love that was the ground of his being, and "
"of everyone’s, to appear effortlessly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2754
msgid "He was letting go of the learned “untruth” about himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2755
msgid "The word Bill’s friends most often used to describe him was presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2756
msgid "Although inadequate, it is the closest available."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2757
msgid "Something happened around him; one felt lighter, more expansive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2758
msgid ""
"Some expressed it as a calming and radiant quality; others said it was like "
"the room became electrified or filled with an exuberant energy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2759
msgid ""
"In any case, it was a great influence in people’s lives and left an "
"indelible mark."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 747
#: sentence:2760
msgid "Zemke speaks eloquently about this quality that everyone observed:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2761
msgid "You have three shades of rose red [in his aura]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2762
msgid "This first shade is a very pale pastel shade."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2763
msgid "It is the color of divinity incarnate in the form of love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2764
msgid "You bring that energy forward through your being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2765
msgid ""
"This is the divine essence or divine loving force transmitted into the "
"earth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2766
msgid ""
"Then there is another step-up of that color and it is mixed with a lot of "
"white, indicating transformation through love, the capacity to transform "
"people, life circumstances, through love, and this is the mark of a very "
"advanced teacher or soul."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2767
msgid ""
"Then still another color attached to this rose spectrum is a rose-white, a "
"blend of the two so subtle that it seems more white than rose, and this "
"indicates the connection to the divine that at times is so strong and so "
"clear that there is no way you can translate that information in words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2768
msgid ""
"It is simply a transmission that occurs on an energy level of your being and"
" gradually filters into form in whatever way is best."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2769
msgid ""
"It happens without your doing anything about it consciously and is "
"responsible for the attraction that people feel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2770
msgid ""
"Many of the people who experience this with you do not understand what they "
"are experiencing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2771
msgid "They just know they want to have it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 748
#: sentence:2772
msgid "They want to be near you, be around you, close to you.[9]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 749
#: sentence:2773
msgid ""
"The following excerpts from many interviews help identify and explain more "
"fully Bill’s prominent qualities as listed at the beginning of this chapter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2774
msgid ""
"If presence was a term universally ascribed to Bill, several noteworthy "
"subsets derive from it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2775
msgid ""
"A sentence from Dante’s Paradiso succinctly captures so many people’s "
"subjective experience of him: “You are my sire, said I: you give me heart "
"freely to speak my thought: above myself you raise me.”[10] Or a more modern"
" translation: “You give me full courage to speak; you lift me until I am "
"more than myself.”[11] That was Bill, and it most fully articulates his "
"greatest gift, the most noted aspect of his way of being—his unsurpassed "
"capacity to support and accept almost anyone or anything."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2776
msgid ""
"I say “almost,” because in his last decade there were still a few loose ends"
" of forgiveness not yet handled and some persons could still push his "
"buttons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2777
msgid ""
"Offering acceptance has a noticeable, substantive healing effect both on "
"those who give and receive it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2778
msgid ""
"It speaks in ways far more compelling than words that we are not judged, "
"that we are completely acceptable as we are and deeply cared for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2779
msgid ""
"Within the light of Bill’s acceptance, frantic or mindless thought could "
"settle down, accompanied by a deep sense of relief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2780
msgid "Imagine no need to defend, impress, convince, or dominate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2781
msgid "People relaxed in his presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2782
msgid ""
"Bill’s acceptance had the instantaneous, profound effect of orienting people"
" to their own innate value, and the expansion was automatic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 750
#: sentence:2783
msgid ""
"The Course speaks of the healing effect that practicing forgiveness has on "
"others:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 751
#: sentence:2784
msgid ""
"The power of witness is beyond belief because it brings conviction in its "
"wake. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 752
#: sentence:2785
msgid ""
"Now in the hands made gentle by His touch, the Holy Spirit lays a picture of"
" a different you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 752
#: sentence:2786
msgid ""
"It is a picture of a body still, for what you really are cannot be seen nor "
"pictured. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 752
#: sentence:2787
msgid ""
"Show this unto your brother, who will see that every scar is healed, and "
"every tear is wiped away in laughter and in love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 752
#: sentence:2788
msgid ""
"And he will look on his forgiveness there, and with healed eyes will look "
"beyond it to the innocence that he beholds in you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 752
#: sentence:2789
msgid ""
"Here is the proof that he has never sinned, that nothing which his madness "
"bid him do was ever done, or ever had effects of any kind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 752
#: sentence:2790
msgid ""
"That no reproach he laid upon his heart was ever justified, and no attack "
"can ever touch him with the poisoned and relentless sting of fear.[12]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 753
#: sentence:2791
msgid "No wonder people were so drawn to him!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 753
#: sentence:2792
msgid ""
"It was like being absolved at the confessional, not as a ritual but as an "
"absolute and incontrovertible fact."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 753
#: sentence:2793
msgid ""
"Many still speak of the magic of being around him and the unforgettable "
"experience of being unconditionally loved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 753
#: sentence:2794
msgid ""
"Praise for him is so consistent that it might tend to sound worshipful, "
"precisely what he would not want. “Fair and balanced” reporting would "
"require my listing as many complaints of Bill as glowing reports, but I "
"would have to manufacture them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 753
#: sentence:2795
msgid ""
"The representative quotes below, echoed by many others, express the power of"
" his influence:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 754
#: sentence:2796
msgid ""
"Jaison Kayn reflects, “He was comforting in the sense that if there were "
"pretenses, it didn’t matter to him whatsoever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 754
#: sentence:2797
msgid ""
"He was also going to stabilize the situation beyond any pretenses, any "
"situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 754
#: sentence:2798
msgid ""
"He knew what was true and you could just take that lead from him.”[13] Bruce"
" Gregory, a friend from New York, remembers:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 755
#: sentence:2799
msgid "After a visit with him, I felt so free and at ease."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 755
#: sentence:2800
msgid ""
"Something about Bill’s expansive, liberating “just be happy, just be loving,"
" don’t worry” quality took by osmosis."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 755
#: sentence:2801
msgid ""
"That is the answer for all of us, so barriers were loosening and crumbling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 755
#: sentence:2802
msgid ""
"He was able to see more and to love more and when you’re around that, when "
"you’re not highly defended, you have this wonderful sense of loving "
"acceptance as well as encouragement; it just fans the flame of spirit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 755
#: sentence:2803
msgid "Bill was very, very gifted in that sense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 755
#: sentence:2804
msgid ""
"He would listen, was compassionate and encouraging like, “Don’t let that "
"bother you, it’s okay, don’t hold onto it.”[14]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 756
#: sentence:2805
msgid ""
"Judith Skutch Whitson comments on that first fateful luncheon with Bill and "
"Helen, “I was quite uncomfortable with Helen, or I should say slightly "
"terrified, because I didn’t know which social skills to use with her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 756
#: sentence:2806
msgid "She was an anomaly to me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 756
#: sentence:2807
msgid "You didn’t know if you were getting through."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 756
#: sentence:2808
msgid ""
"You didn’t know whether you should be open, closed, chatty, quiet—at least I"
" didn’t know."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 756
#: sentence:2809
msgid ""
"But with Bill I was so relaxed because I felt so comfortable with him.”[15]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 757
#: sentence:2810
msgid ""
"Although Bill knew that teaching the Course was not his mission, he fully "
"supported other people’s efforts on behalf of the Course. Hugh Prather "
"noted,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 758
#: sentence:2811
msgid "He was open to almost any approach."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 758
#: sentence:2812
msgid ""
"Once at a meeting in La Jolla, Bill was just as happy as a Cheshire cat "
"sitting in this absolutely far-out, “woo-woo” California atmosphere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 758
#: sentence:2813
msgid ""
"Some people would say things I know he didn’t believe philosophically, yet "
"he was completely accepting of whatever they had to say, their attempts to "
"heal, the songs that they would sing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 759
#: sentence:2814
msgid ""
"Also, I was impressed with his gentleness, his openness—he would talk about "
"anything you wanted to talk about—his lightheartedness, his humor, and of "
"course, he was very intelligent with that sort of eastern sophistication, "
"which being from Texas I’m sometimes intimidated by, but not with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 759
#: sentence:2815
msgid "It was a relief to find him so open and friendly and accessible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 759
#: sentence:2816
msgid "I just connected with him right from the beginning.[16]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 760
#: sentence:2817
msgid "Catherine Prescott remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2818
msgid ""
"He was so generous with me and my children in the sense of making me feel "
"secure, his kindness when I moved to Marin County was just over the top and "
"I needed it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2819
msgid "I was a single mother and scared!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2820
msgid ""
"I never felt more deeply empowered by another human being; he helped me know"
" in a profound way that I was okay."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2821
msgid ""
"I could move toward self-love or self-acceptance because he showed his "
"humanity so much, being willing to be the bumbler."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2822
msgid ""
"He put no weight on degrees or fame or anything. He was not impressed. That "
"was interesting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2823
msgid ""
"He was also funny and cynical and made comments about everybody, including "
"himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2824
msgid ""
"He was always self-deprecating and always “we’re just people.” Aside from "
"his funny, really ironic humor, as far as character, he was the actual "
"living proof of unconditional love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 761
#: sentence:2825
msgid "His kindness and tender heart came through everything.[17]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 762
#: sentence:2826
msgid "Bill finding peace of mind"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 763
#: sentence:2827
msgid ""
"Diane Cirincione, Jerry Jampolsky’s wife, always felt supported with Bill,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2828
msgid ""
"There was a time when, like so many others, I was consciously exploring the "
"depths of my own spirituality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2829
msgid ""
"He gave me encouragement and support, not because he said, “I’m going to "
"encourage and support you,” but our interaction simply gave me permission to"
" be me and find my voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2830
msgid "He did that for a lot of people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2831
msgid ""
"He had the ability to validate your being without having to say anything, to"
" help you feel good about yourself—perhaps the greatest gift anyone gives "
"anybody."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2832
msgid ""
"It’s as if he said, “If anyone needs permission to be themselves, I grant "
"it,” only it wasn’t done at a conscious mind level."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2833
msgid "It happened automatically around him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2834
msgid ""
"If I had an issue, something I wanted to work on, he would say, “Why don’t "
"you do that? Just change it all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2835
msgid ""
"Change it in your mind.” I went, “Oh, okay, why don’t I?” He was free and "
"unattached to the whole thing, a very empowering person, not to overuse an "
"old word."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2836
msgid "I found him to be equally loving to everybody."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2837
msgid ""
"I think he loved a lot of us, his love was strong and that was very "
"important."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2838
msgid "I never felt judged by Bill in any way, shape, or form."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 764
#: sentence:2839
msgid ""
"He had a way of being kind of egalitarian, not elitist at all, and of "
"course, I loved his humor.[18]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 765
#: sentence:2840
msgid ""
"Carlagaye Olson, who became a close friend of Bill’s in the 1980s, fondly "
"recalls,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 766
#: sentence:2841
msgid ""
"You know, the most important moments with Bill were those personal ones."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 766
#: sentence:2842
msgid ""
"There is nothing I can condense into some words of wisdom, except to say "
"that he was so incredibly accepting, just that feeling that this was a "
"family and we were unconditional members of that family and there was "
"nothing in him that said, “I pick you and not you.” You know how the Course "
"says our only problem is the feeling of worthlessness?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 766
#: sentence:2843
msgid ""
"Well, just being in the presence of someone you admire a great deal . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 766
#: sentence:2844
msgid "I don’t know anybody else who could have provided that experience.[19]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 767
#: sentence:2845
msgid "My older son, Greg, recalled from his experience as a young boy,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2846
msgid "It didn’t matter what he said, or what we did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2847
msgid "I just remember what it was like to be around him—that was the key."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2848
msgid "When he was in the house, you could feel it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2849
msgid "You could breathe a sigh of relief like there was a way home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2850
msgid ""
"There was something about his presence that was so comforting and reassuring"
" and had nothing to do with what he said."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2851
msgid "I always felt an endearing sense of calmness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2852
msgid "He brought a sense of safety, which is the key point."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2853
msgid ""
"People will naturally gravitate toward individuals like that because they "
"want that sense of safety and peace and tranquility."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2854
msgid "It’s an unbelievably powerful feeling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2855
msgid ""
"Most people have some hard edges; he seemed to have soft edges with nothing "
"that made you feel rough or constricted or uninviting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2856
msgid ""
"When you were near him, everything was a little bit finer, a little more "
"okay, more resolved, none of which quite do justice to what it was like to "
"be around him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 768
#: sentence:2857
msgid "There was something about Bill that was almost angelic.[20]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 769
#: sentence:2858
msgid ""
"LeRoy Zemke made some interesting far-out observations about Bill in the "
"early 1980s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 769
#: sentence:2859
msgid ""
"He indicated that he represented a new kind of awakened cosmic teacher, a "
"living example of what’s possible—a guru, but not in the traditional sense "
"of the word."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 769
#: sentence:2860
msgid ""
"As he tuned into Bill, he picked up his awakened heart-center energy, a "
"deeply integrated sense of holiness, almost a saintly quality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 769
#: sentence:2861
msgid ""
"Bill would have had difficulty accepting any of that, certainly balking at "
"the guru idea, but the final outcome of his life gives credence to those "
"earlier observations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 770
#: sentence:2862
msgid ""
"Frances Vaughan remembers, “He took himself lightly, but he never made light"
" of other people’s concerns."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 770
#: sentence:2863
msgid ""
"His presence was very even, even during times when he was not well or when "
"he was struggling with some of his own issues."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 770
#: sentence:2864
msgid "He was still able to give others loving attention.”[21]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 771
#: sentence:2865
msgid "Chapter 16"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2866
msgid "So what were the issues he struggled with?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2867
msgid ""
"The same as ours—grievances, of course, and feelings of guilt and failure, "
"as well as the defenses that hide the pain and distress they cause."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2868
msgid ""
"Despite his outward demeanor and his obvious loving nature, he still had "
"some long-held notions about himself to release."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2869
msgid ""
"Bill may have been kind to others, but he was hard on himself, troubled by "
"perceived deficiencies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2870
msgid ""
"It’s amazing that he could have had such a profound effect on others while "
"still battling with his own guilt, testimony to the two starkly different "
"modes of living in this world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2871
msgid ""
"Just as Helen could alternate between polar opposites—bowing to her "
"difficult, demanding ego and accessing the love that created the "
"Course—Bill, too, could operate from an unconditional loving space or be "
"caught in the grip of self-doubt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 772
#: sentence:2872
msgid ""
"And just as ACIM dictation was not compromised when Helen didn’t feel good, "
"so too, love is present along with confusion about lack of worth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 773
#: sentence:2873
msgid ""
"There are three avenues we can use to discern the challenging aspects of "
"Bill’s interior life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 773
#: sentence:2874
msgid ""
"First is the direct material in the Urtext that addresses both his "
"assessment of his unworthiness and the defenses he employed to cope with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 773
#: sentence:2875
msgid ""
"The purpose of the Course is to illustrate how to release entirely the "
"notion of unworthiness, rather than provide more sophisticated strategies "
"for keeping and dealing with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 773
#: sentence:2876
msgid ""
"Second, throughout his life, Bill elicited certain behavior patterns in "
"others, which allows great insight into what he feared or found troubling in"
" himself, although perhaps unconsciously. “Unacceptable” behaviors in "
"others, of course, reflect our own unfinished business and condemnation of "
"ourselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 773
#: sentence:2877
msgid ""
"Third, he specifically commented on certain characteristics he found "
"objectionable in himself and others; no detective work required here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 774
#: sentence:2878
msgid ""
"The Author of ACIM was firm and unequivocal in the messages to Bill and "
"Helen about what they needed to look at, release, and make different choices"
" about—attitudes they needed to trade in for a happier way of living."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 774
#: sentence:2879
msgid ""
"Bill was a master of ego discernment, but the Author of the Course was a "
"step ahead of him, and after reading the personal commentary in the Urtext, "
"one can see why neither Bill nor Helen wanted this personal material, "
"disclosing their most basic fears and shortcomings, to be part of a public "
"record."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2880
msgid "A significant digression is called for here related to the Urtext."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2881
msgid "Why was the personal material in it deleted?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2882
msgid ""
"In addition to the potential embarrassment to the scribes, the Author "
"specifically stated it should not be included."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2883
msgid ""
"It is important for both new and seasoned students to realize the Author "
"requested that specific or personal material be removed to avoid confusion, "
"rather than thinking this was done unilaterally by Helen, Bill, or Ken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2884
msgid ""
"Where she had a personal investment, Helen did interfere to a degree, "
"contaminating some of the very earliest material (and only the earliest) "
"with her own biases, because she was not yet a totally clear channel."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2885
msgid ""
"Such material was inconsistent with the actual Course, and Ken referred to "
"these parts as “Helen-isms.” The scribing was very informal, especially in "
"the beginning; the form was not sacrosanct."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 775
#: sentence:2886
msgid ""
"Ken Wapnick writes in an unpublished manuscript, “The History of the "
"Manuscripts of A Course In Miracles”:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 776
#: sentence:2887
msgid ""
"What is most important to consider about the public exposure of these "
"earlier manuscripts [the Urtext, the Hugh Lynn Cayce version, and a couple "
"of others] is that regardless of the version you read, you will receive the "
"essential teaching of the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 776
#: sentence:2888
msgid "In that sense, no real harm has been done."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2889
msgid ""
"In another sense, however, the situation is unfortunate because people could"
" be misled and at this point, nothing can be done about it . . . except, "
"perhaps, to clarify what inquiring students may be reading."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2890
msgid "Let me cite some examples."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2891
msgid ""
"There is material in the Urtext about sex and sexuality, an area that will "
"almost certainly pique the curiosity (if not prurient interest) of students."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2892
msgid ""
"Thus, for example, one will read that homosexuality is essentially a "
"pathology (the traditional psychoanalytic view) and that the only purpose "
"for sex is procreation, two positions that are antithetical to Jesus’ own "
"teachings in the Course about seeing all forms of the ego’s world as the "
"same, the correction to the ego’s first law of chaos that there is a "
"hierarchy of illusion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2893
msgid ""
"To believe that these would be the words and thoughts of Jesus is as "
"preposterous and unthinkable an idea as to believe that I could influence "
"Helen as to what belonged in the Course and what did not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2894
msgid ""
"It should be obvious that these beliefs belong to Helen and not to Jesus."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2895
msgid ""
"Helen had her own biases about sex, and unfortunately they came through in "
"these early passages."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2896
msgid ""
"Yet those who believe that every word in the Urtext is sacred and are Jesus’"
" words can use statements like these to support their own preconceived "
"notions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 777
#: sentence:2897
msgid ""
"This same issue holds, though perhaps with less emotionality, with material "
"related to Edgar Cayce, Freud and other psychologists. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 778
#: sentence:2898
msgid ""
"Thus, it became very clear to me in the years I knew Helen that I should "
"take with a grain of salt some of the things she said or wrote as coming "
"from Jesus, and this clearly included the early Urtext material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 778
#: sentence:2899
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, there are also some things there that if you do not know the "
"context, you will not understand what they refer to, or what they mean."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 778
#: sentence:2900
msgid ""
"This inevitability means that those who were not present and did not know "
"Helen and Bill will misunderstand much of what is found there.[22]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 779
#: sentence:2901
msgid ""
"Helen did recognize this periodic corruption of the material where her "
"biases intruded and discussed it with Ken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 779
#: sentence:2902
msgid ""
"She may also have talked with Bill about it, but that is only conjecture as "
"their relationship was so often discordant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 779
#: sentence:2903
msgid ""
"A short while into the text, Helen’s resistance relaxed; the dictation "
"flowed evenly and no longer included dialogue or personal material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 779
#: sentence:2904
msgid ""
"Bill often commented on how difficult scribing the Course was for both of "
"them; being thoroughly examined by the Author makes “difficult” seem, at the"
" least, an understatement."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 779
#: sentence:2905
msgid ""
"Both Bill and Helen called on considerable courage to continue their scribal"
" commitment while being in the “hot seat” with the Author."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 780
#: sentence:2906
msgid ""
"A few examples from the Urtext reveal both the specific nature of some of "
"Bill’s issues, remembering they allude to his state of mind at the onset of "
"the Course, and how universal they really are."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 780
#: sentence:2907
msgid ""
"They concerned his fear that he was not going to succeed without being "
"special in some way and that without specialness everyone would see his "
"unworthiness, and thus failure. (By the way, Ken indicated that the quotes I"
" have chosen for inclusion in this book are valid, not ones where Helen’s "
"personal opinions bled through.) Despite his outer success, Bill still "
"harbored resentments and was plagued by a lack of self-worth. Sound "
"familiar?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 780
#: sentence:2908
msgid ""
"The following material comes from the early part of the Urtext, which was "
"deleted from the first six chapters of the published text."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 780
#: sentence:2909
msgid ""
"The Author was equally firm with Helen, but her issues are not the subject "
"of this book. (Bill capitalized some words as he typed Helen’s notes to "
"denote emphasis, but I have changed them to italics.) This message for Bill "
"was relayed to Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 781
#: sentence:2910
msgid "His real specialness does not stem from exclusion, but from inclusion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 781
#: sentence:2911
msgid "All my brothers are special."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 781
#: sentence:2912
msgid ""
"He should stop interpreting this as “all except Bill.” This is ridiculous!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 781
#: sentence:2913
msgid ""
"Tell him that the implied lack of love that his version contains is way off "
"the mark and misses the level of right thinking entirely."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 781
#: sentence:2914
msgid "He must heal his perception in this respect.[23]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 782
#: sentence:2915
msgid ""
"You and Bill do have special talents which are needed for the celestial "
"speed-up at this time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 782
#: sentence:2916
msgid ""
"But note that the term “speed-up” is not one which relates to the "
"transcending of time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 783
#: sentence:2917
msgid ""
"When time is abolished and all of the Sons of God have come home, no special"
" agents will be necessary."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 783
#: sentence:2918
msgid ""
"But do not underestimate the power of special agents now, or the great need "
"there is for them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 783
#: sentence:2919
msgid "I do not claim to be more than that myself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 783
#: sentence:2920
msgid ""
"No one in his right mind (a term which should be especially noted) ever "
"wants either more nor less than that.[24]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 784
#: sentence:2921
msgid ""
"At the end of a long dissertation on the confusion about communication and "
"knowledge, the Author listed four general statements about the misuse of "
"knowledge (as we understand the word, not as the Course uses it), and then "
"specifically called their attention to this list:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 785
#: sentence:2922
msgid "4."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 785
#: sentence:2923
msgid "Knowledge can also be misinterpreted as a means of possession."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 785
#: sentence:2924
msgid ""
"Here, the content is not physical and the underlying fallacy is more likely "
"to be a confusion of mind and brain. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 785
#: sentence:2925
msgid ""
"The fallacious use of knowledge can result in several errors, including:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 786
#: sentence:2926
msgid "a."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 786
#: sentence:2927
msgid ""
"The idea that knowledge will make the individual more attractive to others. "
"This is possession-fallacy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 787
#: sentence:2928
msgid "b."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 787
#: sentence:2929
msgid "The idea that knowledge will make the individual invulnerable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 787
#: sentence:2930
msgid ""
"This is the reaction formation against the underlying fear of vulnerability."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 788
#: sentence:2931
msgid "c."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 788
#: sentence:2932
msgid ""
"The idea that knowledge will make the individual worthy. This is largely "
"pathetic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 789
#: sentence:2933
msgid ""
"Both you and Bill should consider type 4 [all of the above] very carefully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 789
#: sentence:2934
msgid ""
"Like all these fallacies, it contains a denial mechanism, which swings into "
"operation as the fear increases, thus canceling out the error temporarily, "
"but seriously impairing efficiency."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 790
#: sentence:2935
msgid ""
"Thus, you claim that you can’t read and Bill claims that he can’t speak."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 790
#: sentence:2936
msgid ""
"Note that depression is a real risk here, for a Child of God should never "
"reduce his efficiency in any way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 790
#: sentence:2937
msgid "The depression comes from a peculiar pseudo-solution which reads:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 791
#: sentence:2938
msgid "A Child of God is efficient."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 792
#: sentence:2939
msgid "I am not efficient."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 793
#: sentence:2940
msgid "Therefore, I am not a Child of God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 794
#: sentence:2941
msgid ""
"This leads to neurotic resignation and this is a state which merely "
"increases the depression.[25]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 795
#: sentence:2942
msgid ""
"However uninviting these messages were, Bill did take them to heart and "
"diligently practiced reaching out to others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 795
#: sentence:2943
msgid ""
"As he took the steps offered him in the Course, he became more than willing "
"to spend a great deal of time with many people in order to help them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 795
#: sentence:2944
msgid ""
"He lavished attention on those with whom he had strong connections, as well "
"as in more casual encounters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 795
#: sentence:2945
msgid ""
"For many of us, he was our greatest cheerleader, inspiring us to take our "
"next steps, both internally and externally, and helping each to let go of "
"whatever was in our way—modern-day disciples, perhaps."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 795
#: sentence:2946
msgid ""
"As one person stated, “I just can’t imagine anyone else playing that kind of"
" [inspirational] role and for so many of us!”[26]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 796
#: sentence:2947
msgid ""
"He was also willing, as a demonstration of love, to do things he really "
"didn’t care to do, but he honored those who asked, if his guidance so "
"dictated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 796
#: sentence:2948
msgid ""
"Do not mistake this for being wimpy, having no boundaries, or being unable "
"to say no."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 796
#: sentence:2949
msgid ""
"For sure, when Bill felt it was not right for him to do something, nothing "
"in heaven or earth could move him from his position."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 796
#: sentence:2950
msgid "He really lived this admonition:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 797
#: sentence:2951
msgid ""
"Suppose a brother insists on having you do something you think you do not "
"want to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 797
#: sentence:2952
msgid ""
"His very insistence should tell you that he believes salvation lies in it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 797
#: sentence:2953
msgid ""
"If you insist on refusing and experience a quick response of opposition, you"
" are believing that your salvation lies in not doing it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 797
#: sentence:2954
msgid ""
"You, then, are making the same mistake he is, and are making his error real "
"to both of you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 797
#: sentence:2955
msgid ""
"Insistence means investment, and what you invest in is always related to "
"your notion of salvation.[27]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 798
#: sentence:2956
msgid ""
"As one example, Jerry Jampolsky remembered this favorite: “You know he never"
" exercised and I thought maybe if I bought him a jogging suit for his "
"birthday, he might get interested in walking and doing things like that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 798
#: sentence:2957
msgid ""
"He said, ‘No way am I going to do that, but I’ll tell you what I’ll do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 798
#: sentence:2958
msgid ""
"I’ll let you take one picture of me with that suit on.’ He took it off and "
"never wore it again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 798
#: sentence:2959
msgid ""
"He wasn’t going to a gym.”[28] Actually, he did walk every day, sometimes "
"more than once, and he enjoyed that a great deal; it made possible the "
"wonderful experiences so many had on those walks."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 798
#: sentence:2960
msgid "But true to his word, he never went to a gym."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 799
#: sentence:2961
msgid "Jogging suit—present from Jerry"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 800
#: sentence:2962
msgid ""
"Jerry was also aware of the great love and brotherhood they felt for one "
"another, exemplified by Bill’s willingness to serve on the board of the "
"Center for Attitudinal Healing, which was “the last thing in the world his "
"ego would want to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 800
#: sentence:2963
msgid "I remember his infinite patience with me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 800
#: sentence:2964
msgid "I asked him a thousand questions and later came back with more."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 800
#: sentence:2965
msgid "His willingness to do his best to listen to the Voice was amazing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 800
#: sentence:2966
msgid "What I remember about him was that steadfast commitment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 800
#: sentence:2967
msgid ""
"He was like a rudder on a ship going straight in the direction toward "
"God.”[29]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 801
#: sentence:2968
msgid "Jaison Kayn remembered:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 802
#: sentence:2969
msgid ""
"He would never think of speaking himself, but as other people asked it [to "
"speak] of him, he would."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 802
#: sentence:2970
msgid ""
"That was one of his forms of generosity, as if to say, “If that’s what you "
"want, then I’ll talk.” Another thing he gave me was the sense that if there "
"was anything he could do to make me comfortable, he would."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 802
#: sentence:2971
msgid ""
"He mostly did that with his presence in terms of reassurance, not verbally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 802
#: sentence:2972
msgid ""
"He honored people for who they were and let them know that there was nothing"
" about them that he judged. He supported your being.[30]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 803
#: sentence:2973
msgid "Bob Beale occasionally visited Bill in Tiburon:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 804
#: sentence:2974
msgid ""
"One of the things I loved about him was his gentle manner and that he subtly"
" offered some really powerful insights, always made in low-key statements, "
"and I was very receptive to listening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 804
#: sentence:2975
msgid ""
"Sometimes people try to give you advice or insights and they come on fairly "
"strong and one instinctively pushes back."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 804
#: sentence:2976
msgid ""
"He never made emphatic statements and I had no feeling of wanting to push "
"back with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 804
#: sentence:2977
msgid "It was a delight to experience his gentle manner."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 804
#: sentence:2978
msgid ""
"I can distinctly remember when it was time to leave, I would go up that hill"
" from Tiburon over to San Francisco and things would really just start to "
"vibrate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 804
#: sentence:2979
msgid "All of a sudden I’d really get what Bill said.[31]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 805
#: sentence:2980
msgid ""
"Bill always modeled the wonderful way we can be helpful to each other "
"without being oppressive or giving advice or fixing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 805
#: sentence:2981
msgid ""
"How comforting it is when information comes through the loving presence "
"within, rather than from the ego’s critical perspective of, “Here is what’s "
"the matter with you, so shape up.” It’s not that Bill saw things and then "
"had to work to overlook them; somehow they fell off the radar screen for "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 805
#: sentence:2982
msgid ""
"He touched people deeply because it was his goal to be aware only of their "
"underlying love, and he was determined to let go of judgment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 805
#: sentence:2983
msgid ""
"It was not in keeping with his goal of unconditional acceptance to try to "
"change a person or buy into their fears."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 806
#: sentence:2984
msgid ""
"Bruce Gregory met Bill at the Skutch home in New York, which he described as"
" “Miracle Central.” He left Manhattan in 1979 and moved to rural Arizona, "
"where he worked in a prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 806
#: sentence:2985
msgid "Being closer then to Tiburon, he visited Bill occasionally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 807
#: sentence:2986
msgid ""
"Those visits with Bill, though small in number, were quality times with a "
"gentle, settled soul who was kind enough to hear out my challenges in my "
"personal and work life in a small town that was friendly but openly critical"
" of anyone who wasn’t “normal.”. . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 807
#: sentence:2987
msgid ""
"He also provided such kind support as I tried to integrate my spiritual "
"yearnings with the fact of being gay in a world that did not really "
"understand or accept either."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 808
#: sentence:2988
msgid ""
"Bill was able to exude acceptance and normalcy and even a little feistiness "
"about my self-acceptance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 808
#: sentence:2989
msgid ""
"I can’t say that I resolved my issues completely with his help, but I "
"certainly did come back to my new home after my visits refreshed and with "
"more peace of mind, along with the magic of self-acceptance and acceptance "
"of others, even in their bigotry."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 808
#: sentence:2990
msgid ""
"That was a miracle for me, in that I saw no need to fight or struggle to "
"change the minds of others to accept me as I was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 808
#: sentence:2991
msgid "It was more important to accept them as they were."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 808
#: sentence:2992
msgid ""
"I then found that this started to translate into acceptance of the inmates I"
" worked with in my substance abuse groups.[32]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 809
#: sentence:2993
msgid ""
"Although there are many examples of how Bill’s supportive attitude led "
"people to greater forgiveness, and thus to a more rewarding and helpful "
"life, excerpts from Bruce’s essay are typical."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 810
#: sentence:2994
msgid ""
"I’m sure that when I asked God if I should go with my friends out to Arizona"
" for this new life in forming a small spiritual community of friends, and "
"the answer I got was “Go!” that some interesting plans for my healing were "
"put in place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 810
#: sentence:2995
msgid ""
"I had spent my life avoiding any kind of bullies, after a rough encounter in"
" the third grade, leaving me with a firm but tearful decision to “never "
"trust anyone again.” That firm rule had never really been challenged until "
"my move to Arizona."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 810
#: sentence:2996
msgid ""
"When I went for a job, there were only two available: skinning coyotes "
"(seasonal) and counseling inmates at the local prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 810
#: sentence:2997
msgid ""
"I wanted neither, but I had to earn money to pay off my part of the "
"mortgage."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 810
#: sentence:2998
msgid "The prison paid better and was steady pay, so that’s what I chose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:2999
msgid ""
"My first day on the prison yard was a nightmare, as I got all sorts of "
"comments and catcalls and whistles from the inmates."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3000
msgid ""
"Not a great beginning, especially when I really didn’t want to be there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3001
msgid ""
"But since skinning coyotes was definitely worse, I knew I had to find a way "
"through this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3002
msgid ""
"I went home that night to the peace and quiet of our new home and tried to "
"sort it out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3003
msgid ""
"I figured that the inmates had responded to my fears, and found an "
"opportunity to feel stronger than me by comparison, especially in their one-"
"down position in prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3004
msgid ""
"I decided then and there to choose to go beyond my fears of the inmate "
"bullies and focus on my desire to be of help in whatever way I could."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3005
msgid ""
"I went back to work the next morning, and I never had another negative "
"encounter with them in the twenty-seven years that followed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 811
#: sentence:3006
msgid ""
"In fact, one of the highest compliments I’ve ever received came from a "
"fellow counselor, who told me that if ever a riot were to break out among "
"the inmates, he was planning to stand behind me because no one would ever "
"hurt me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 812
#: sentence:3007
msgid "Bill helped me to develop this inner calm from his own example."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 812
#: sentence:3008
msgid ""
"And when I was asked to work with medium-custody inmates, a rougher, tougher"
" crowd, I found myself dealing with personal attacks again, this time in the"
" classroom from those who didn’t want to be there, but were required to be "
"“for their own good.” At this point, again with some time spent with Bill "
"under my belt, I found myself not caring about the obvious barbs intended to"
" put me down, but caring more for the inmates’ well-being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 812
#: sentence:3009
msgid ""
"It was a new-found freedom that came from this that eventually led to a "
"greater acceptance, appreciation, and even joyous love for the inmate "
"“bullies” that I had so assiduously avoided all my life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 813
#: sentence:3010
msgid ""
"Understanding his [the childhood bully’s] background as well as my own "
"attack thoughts helped me to break down the barriers I had built toward "
"everyone and forgive my “bully.” I’ve never met him again, and yet I have "
"met him in so many others, especially in prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 813
#: sentence:3011
msgid "Even the inmates have told me, “I know you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 813
#: sentence:3012
msgid ""
"You’re the person I used to give such a hard time to.” We both knew that we "
"were speaking of substitutes, later in life, but we could see that we were "
"both moving beyond our old roles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 813
#: sentence:3013
msgid "So I thank Bill for his loving encouragement not to be afraid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 813
#: sentence:3014
msgid ""
"I know it meant a lot to have that deeper part of me recognized and "
"energized by his knowing gaze.[33]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 814
#: sentence:3015
msgid "Bill had not always been consistently supportive and accepting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 814
#: sentence:3016
msgid ""
"For instance, one of his friends at the CIA told of going to lunch without "
"him after they had specifically planned to get together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 814
#: sentence:3017
msgid ""
"She apologized and indicated that she and her friend had simply forgotten "
"about his going, but that it certainly wasn’t deliberate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 814
#: sentence:3018
msgid ""
"Bill replied that that was worse, interpreting her explanation as an obvious"
" rejection, though perhaps not on a conscious level."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 814
#: sentence:3019
msgid ""
"He told her, “We go to lunch together but then at a subconscious level I’m "
"not someone you want to be with.” She still remembers being quite taken "
"aback by that comment because he was serious, and not playful, about feeling"
" rejected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 815
#: sentence:3020
msgid ""
"A famous magician of the early twentieth century, David Verner, aka Dai "
"Vernon, spoke of the deep hunger within us for the “numinous”—divine power, "
"creative energy, spiritual elevation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 815
#: sentence:3021
msgid "We love the idea that something mystical and unexplainable can occur."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 815
#: sentence:3022
msgid ""
"A true magician can project and change the experience of those he "
"influences."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 815
#: sentence:3023
msgid ""
"In that way, Bill was like a magician, although it was not contrived but "
"automatic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 815
#: sentence:3024
msgid ""
"Through his openness to them, he could invite people into a sense of Self "
"and was delighted as he witnessed that occur."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 815
#: sentence:3025
msgid ""
"Frances Vaughan speaks of a particularly important aspect of Bill’s "
"acceptance:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 816
#: sentence:3026
msgid ""
"One of Bill’s gifts was a presence that enabled people to grow. He was very "
"accepting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 816
#: sentence:3027
msgid "He never tried to impose his own views on anybody."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 816
#: sentence:3028
msgid "I would describe his way of being as an absence of personality noise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 816
#: sentence:3029
msgid "He created a safe place for people to be who they were."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 816
#: sentence:3030
msgid ""
"He was definitely very attentive to whomever he was with; it was as though "
"he didn’t need to take up any room."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 816
#: sentence:3031
msgid ""
"By making a space for you to fill up, he made you feel that you could just "
"be who you are."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 817
#: sentence:3032
msgid ""
"When I talked to Bill I felt he really listened and could understand what I "
"had to say."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 817
#: sentence:3033
msgid "That was one of the nicest things about him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 817
#: sentence:3034
msgid ""
"He wasn’t full of his own agenda or ideas about the way things should be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 817
#: sentence:3035
msgid ""
"He provided a spaciousness and a quality of listening that was very deep."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 817
#: sentence:3036
msgid "I felt he gave loving, non-interfering attention to everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 817
#: sentence:3037
msgid "That is a great gift that can be very healing.[34]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3038
msgid "These observations include several critically important ideas."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3039
msgid ""
"First, we all know individuals who take up a great deal of psychic space, "
"who seem to take all the air out of a room, who dominate with “I, me, and "
"mine—it’s all about me.” No one warms to that person and yet we all believe "
"that we require some degree of self-promotion to be happy, secure, and "
"prosperous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3040
msgid ""
"However, if you ask someone to elaborate on how that happens, you will not "
"get a valid answer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3041
msgid ""
"We have fallen into the trap of believing that taking up space is good and "
"necessary, competing for it through attempts to be special."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3042
msgid ""
"The philosopher Douglas Harding often speaks of “disappearing in favor of "
"the other person,” another way of stating Bill’s capacity for open "
"acceptance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3043
msgid ""
"It seems a paradox that the more wholeheartedly present we are for others, "
"the more we “disappear,” the more everyone gains."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3044
msgid ""
"This contradicts our earliest programming of how to “stake out our "
"territory.” If we gathered up all the “I, me, and mine” thought patterns and"
" rolled them up to almost nothing—figuratively speaking—our happiness would "
"increase."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3045
msgid ""
"Focusing on the other, rather than self, is a major component of "
"forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3046
msgid ""
"One caution: taking up no space does not mean withholding, hiding, or "
"defending."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3047
msgid ""
"Keeping things bottled up for fear of being unacceptable is hardly a no-"
"space situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 818
#: sentence:3048
msgid ""
"Feeling inferior with the need to hide can result in one’s being an "
"irritable, high-maintenance person, indeed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 819
#: sentence:3049
msgid ""
"A second important aspect of the acceptance Bill demonstrated was his "
"capacity to listen fully, to give another his undivided attention regardless"
" of the subject matter; this is healing for both parties."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 819
#: sentence:3050
msgid ""
"The one being listened to feels completely and unconditionally accepted, and"
" it quiets the mind of the listener, bringing both into the present "
"moment—the only time a change of mind can occur."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 819
#: sentence:3051
msgid ""
"Undivided attention also clears the mind enough so that guidance or "
"intuition about what to do or how to change perspective becomes possible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 819
#: sentence:3052
msgid ""
"Counterintuitively, “taking up no space” incurs no sacrifice whatsoever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 819
#: sentence:3053
msgid ""
"ACIM, understanding that we believe this change of outlook is dangerous, "
"states:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 820
#: sentence:3054
msgid ""
"Therefore, the period of overlap is apt to be one in which the teacher of "
"God feels called upon to sacrifice his own best interests on behalf of "
"truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 820
#: sentence:3055
msgid ""
"He has not realized as yet how wholly impossible such a demand would be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 820
#: sentence:3056
msgid ""
"He can learn this only as he actually does give up the valueless [ego self-"
"promotion]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 820
#: sentence:3057
msgid ""
"Through this, he learns that where he anticipated grief, he finds a happy "
"lightheartedness instead; where he thought something was asked of him, he "
"finds a gift bestowed on him.[35]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 821
#: sentence:3058
msgid "Deeply listening to others is an act of love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 821
#: sentence:3059
msgid ""
"Where we think that genuinely deferring to others will bring us loneliness "
"and unhappiness, instead we find ourselves included and revered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 821
#: sentence:3060
msgid ""
"The following passages from the Urtext indicate some of Bill’s errors that "
"he corrected through deep listening and engaging with others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 822
#: sentence:3061
msgid ""
"Tell Bill the reason he was so strained yesterday is because he allowed "
"himself a number of fear-producing attitudes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 822
#: sentence:3062
msgid ""
"They were fleeting enough to be more will-of-the-wisps than serious will-"
"errors but unless he watches this kind of thing, he will find the notes "
"fearful, and knowing him well, will mis-distantiate. [In short, he would "
"keep the notes at an intellectual or emotional distance "
"inappropriately.][36]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 823
#: sentence:3063
msgid ""
"You, Bill, have not made consistent efforts to change your mind except "
"through applying old habit patterns to new ideas."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 823
#: sentence:3064
msgid ""
"But you have learned, and learned it better than Helen, that your mind gains"
" control over itself when you direct it genuinely toward perceiving someone "
"else truly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 823
#: sentence:3065
msgid ""
"Your lack of vitality is due to your former marked effort at solving your "
"needless depression and anxiety through disinterest."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 823
#: sentence:3066
msgid ""
"Because your ego was protected by this unfortunate negative attribute, you "
"are afraid to abandon it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 824
#: sentence:3067
msgid ""
"When you have given up this voluntary dis-spiriting, you have already seen "
"how your mind can focus and rise above fatigue, and heal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 824
#: sentence:3068
msgid ""
"But you are not sufficiently vigilant against the demands of your ego that "
"you disengage yourself.[37]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 825
#: sentence:3069
msgid ""
"Do not disturb yourself about repression, Bill, but do train yourself to be "
"alert to any tendency to withdraw from your brothers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 825
#: sentence:3070
msgid ""
"Withdrawal is frightening and you do not recognize all the forms it takes in"
" you. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 825
#: sentence:3071
msgid ""
"You, Bill, will learn somewhat differently because you are afraid of all "
"complete involvements, and believe that they will lessen you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 825
#: sentence:3072
msgid ""
"You have learned to be so much more clear-sighted about this that you should"
" be ready to oppose it in yourself relatively easily."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 825
#: sentence:3073
msgid ""
"As you come closer to a brother, you do approach Me, and as you withdraw "
"from him, I become distant to you.[38]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 826
#: sentence:3074
msgid "Detachment is essentially a weaker form of dissociation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 826
#: sentence:3075
msgid ""
"This is one of the major areas of withholding that both you and Bill are "
"engaging in.[39]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 827
#: sentence:3076
msgid "Tell Bill that his delaying tactics are holding him back."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 827
#: sentence:3077
msgid ""
"He does not really understand detachment, distantiation, and withdrawal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 827
#: sentence:3078
msgid ""
"He is interpreting them as “holding himself aloof” from the Atonement.[40]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 828
#: sentence:3079
msgid ""
"There is much evidence that Bill often felt trapped, an interior experience "
"but one he tried to rectify in his outer world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 828
#: sentence:3080
msgid ""
"For instance, he always preferred to sit by a door at meetings or in an "
"aisle seat at the theater or concert hall, any place that facilitated a "
"quick escape."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 828
#: sentence:3081
msgid ""
"Ken noted Bill’s propensity for standing in the doorway of Helen’s office as"
" they met during the editing phase, not only as an escape route but also to "
"retreat to his office for a cigarette, another type of escape."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 828
#: sentence:3082
msgid ""
"Also, when one is uncomfortable in a situation and can’t “escape” "
"geographically, it is common simply to detach from it and disappear "
"emotionally, a defense universally employed until one realizes it doesn’t "
"bring happiness or peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 828
#: sentence:3083
msgid "Bill used that strategy as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 829
#: sentence:3084
msgid ""
"Bill is better at understanding the need to study the notes than you are, "
"but neither of you realizes that many of the problems you keep being faced "
"with may already have been solved there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 829
#: sentence:3085
msgid "You do not think of the notes in this way at all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 829
#: sentence:3086
msgid ""
"Bill does from time to time, but he generally says, “It’s probably in the "
"notes,” and doesn’t look it up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 829
#: sentence:3087
msgid ""
"He believes that, although he reads them over, they cannot really help him "
"until they are complete."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 830
#: sentence:3088
msgid "First of all, he cannot be sure of this unless he tries."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 830
#: sentence:3089
msgid "Second, they would be completed if both of you so willed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 830
#: sentence:3090
msgid ""
"You vaguely know that the course is intended for some sort of preparation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 830
#: sentence:3091
msgid "I can only say that you are not prepared."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 831
#: sentence:3092
msgid ""
"I was amused when you reminded Bill that he, too, was being prepared for "
"something quite unexpected and he said he was not at all curious about what "
"it was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 831
#: sentence:3093
msgid "This disinterest is very characteristic of him when he is afraid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 831
#: sentence:3094
msgid ""
"Interest and fear do not go together as your respective behavior clearly "
"shows.[41]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 832
#: sentence:3095
msgid ""
"Bill’s behavior is not chaotic because he is not so much goal-divided as not"
" goal-oriented."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 832
#: sentence:3096
msgid ""
"Where Helen has over-invested in many goals, Bill has under-invested in all "
"goals."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 832
#: sentence:3097
msgid ""
"He has the advantage of potentially greater freedom from dis-tractability, "
"but he does not care enough to use it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 832
#: sentence:3098
msgid ""
"Helen has the advantage of great effort, but she keeps losing sight of the "
"goal.[42]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 833
#: sentence:3099
msgid ""
"Bill has very intelligently suggested that you both should set yourself the "
"goal of really studying for this course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 833
#: sentence:3100
msgid ""
"There can be no doubt of the wisdom of this decision for any student who "
"wants to pass it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 833
#: sentence:3101
msgid ""
"But, knowing your individual weaknesses as learners, and being a teacher "
"with some experience, I must remind you that learning and wanting to learn "
"are inseparable.[43]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 834
#: sentence:3102
msgid "Chapter 17"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 835
#: sentence:3103
msgid ""
"Bill’s sense of humor ran a close second to presence and un-conditional "
"acceptance as his most-mentioned outstanding characteristics."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 835
#: sentence:3104
msgid "In the Urtext, the author commented:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 836
#: sentence:3105
msgid ""
"I wish he would decide to use that talent of his [for making puns] "
"constructively."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 836
#: sentence:3106
msgid "He has no idea how powerful it could be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 836
#: sentence:3107
msgid ""
"Actually, it does come from the unconscious and is really a distorted form "
"of miraculous perception, which he has reduced to word twisting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 836
#: sentence:3108
msgid "Although this can be quite funny, it is still a real waste."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 836
#: sentence:3109
msgid ""
"Maybe he’d care to let me control it, and still use it humorously himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 836
#: sentence:3110
msgid "He doesn’t have to decide it is one or the other.[44]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 837
#: sentence:3111
msgid ""
"Bill must have surrendered some control over that talent because he could be"
" simply hilarious."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 837
#: sentence:3112
msgid ""
"Whit Whitson, a superb wordsmith himself, noted, “I was soon captivated by "
"Bill because he struck me as a voice of balance and sanity packaged in dry "
"wit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 837
#: sentence:3113
msgid ""
"The more I listened to his views about the Course, the more my respect grew "
"for it and for the whimsy and sparkle of his mind.”[45] His innate "
"lovingness, combined with his wonderful ability to be lighthearted, was "
"indeed sparkling and compelling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 837
#: sentence:3114
msgid ""
"Everyone, without exception, recalled with delight their times of rich, "
"heartwarming laughter with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 838
#: sentence:3115
msgid ""
"LeRoy Zemke’s reading confirmed this trait, even though Bill was an unknown "
"client at the time: “You have a remarkable talent to aid you in this, and it"
" is your capacity to draw upon the wit and the clarity of your own mind that"
" stems from warmth and from your capacity to see a sense of the ridiculous "
"in all that life offers. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 838
#: sentence:3116
msgid ""
"Use it amply whenever it applies and you will find that whatever you have to"
" teach, this will be the tool that will aid you in the work that needs to be"
" done.”[46]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3117
msgid "And aid us all, it did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3118
msgid ""
"Getting a handle on Bill’s humor moves you very close to his essence—it was "
"one of his ways of loving."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3119
msgid ""
"He was never malicious with humor, which is often a thinly disguised cover "
"for a put-down, but not with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3120
msgid "His really funny way of being was not at someone else’s expense."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3121
msgid ""
"Bill laughed at the absurdity of life and found nothing too sacred for his "
"lighthearted touch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3122
msgid ""
"It was all amusing—his work, the science of psychology, people, situations, "
"or sex."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 839
#: sentence:3123
msgid ""
"Predictably, when people started taking themselves or a situation too "
"seriously, he became an impish, irreverent jokester, as if to say, “Lighten "
"up, everybody!”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 840
#: sentence:3124
msgid "Happy to be alive in 1982"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 841
#: sentence:3125
msgid ""
"Fast forwarding to the La Jolla era, Bill occasionally enjoyed the company "
"of some lady friends there, although they were never actual romances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 841
#: sentence:3126
msgid ""
"Jack Luckett recounted that sometimes, when someone from Tiburon would visit"
" and one of those women were around, Bill would “hold and kiss her and act "
"as if this was a real huge romance; he thought it was a great kick [to shock"
" the visitor] because he had a little bit of a trickster in him.”[47] Jack’s"
" wife Layle remembers a great story many of us can identify with, having "
"been in similar situations with Bill:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 842
#: sentence:3127
msgid ""
"I heard about a poetry reading way across San Diego on the far east side of "
"town."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 842
#: sentence:3128
msgid ""
"We found the small, old frame house and entered to find a small room jammed "
"with chairs and people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 842
#: sentence:3129
msgid ""
"We found seats far from the aisle, a very bad sign for Billy in case escape "
"was required."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 842
#: sentence:3130
msgid ""
"Also, we learned that the house had no back door—the back overhung a steep "
"canyon—and that there was only one bathroom, but we persevered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3131
msgid ""
"The first reader, a man, started out reading something terminally boring in "
"airy-fairy Victorian style with full expression and an almost nausea-"
"producing rhythmic beat, sway, and facial expression."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3132
msgid "Soon, Billy and Jack found this hilarious, but couldn’t escape!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3133
msgid ""
"We didn’t dare look at each other for fear of setting off explosive "
"laughter!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3134
msgid ""
"They tried not to be rude, but they were holding back so hard that little "
"snorts were escaping their noses and mouths."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3135
msgid ""
"Finally both—on either side of me—had their faces in their laps shaking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3136
msgid "I was bored, but oblivious, so thought they were emoting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3137
msgid ""
"Naturally, this event went on for about ninety hours until we were finally "
"released."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3138
msgid "Imagine how fast we got out of there, never to return."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 843
#: sentence:3139
msgid "Jack can still get almost hysterical remembering this.[48]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 844
#: sentence:3140
msgid "Hugh Prather remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 845
#: sentence:3141
msgid ""
"Well, I can tell you, everything about him was this deep connection with God"
" combined with his advice not to take it all too seriously—one of the "
"primary themes of Bill’s life and the great gift he gave the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 845
#: sentence:3142
msgid ""
"Every conversation I had with him had an effect on me because I was taking "
"the Course very seriously and you just couldn’t do that with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 845
#: sentence:3143
msgid ""
"I wish everyone could have felt his very lighthearted approach to the "
"Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 845
#: sentence:3144
msgid ""
"As a matter of fact, I think one of the reasons he kept telling these "
"stories, pointing out the absurdity of everything that had gone on when the "
"Course came, whether done consciously or not, was for the effect it had of "
"lightening me up on the whole subject."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 845
#: sentence:3145
msgid ""
"Additionally, he just thought it infinitely amusing that the CIA had "
"financed so much of their work, and he always joked about the typewriter—the"
" CIA-funded typewriter that typed ACIM.[49]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 846
#: sentence:3146
msgid ""
"Incidentally, the CIA never orchestrated the production of the Course in any"
" way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 846
#: sentence:3147
msgid ""
"There is some misleading speculation to that effect on the Internet, but "
"anyone who knew either Helen or Bill or has the slightest knowledge of the "
"material would find that patently absurd."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 846
#: sentence:3148
msgid ""
"This profound and transformative work could not possibly have been faked or "
"planned by even the best of intellects, no matter what the purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 846
#: sentence:3149
msgid ""
"And for those who knew Helen, the notion that she could be coerced or "
"manipulated into doing something she didn’t want to do is also ridiculous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 846
#: sentence:3150
msgid "When she said no, that was it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 847
#: sentence:3151
msgid ""
"Among his stories from Columbia, Bill delighted to talk about being co-"
"editor of the Journal of Abnormal Psychology from 1965–1971, the years of "
"Course dictation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 847
#: sentence:3152
msgid ""
"He periodically rejected articles that were “not sufficiently scientific,” "
"and, of course, he found this situation ridiculous and very humorous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 848
#: sentence:3153
msgid ""
"In the early 1980s, a woman who was writing a spiritually based sex manual, "
"which she believed was being dictated by Jesus, started corresponding with "
"Bill to inform him about messages she was getting from “Jesus.” Being a bit "
"nonplussed and not knowing quite how to respond, he finally wrote her back "
"after receiving several letters and said that he, too, had talked to Jesus, "
"who told him they should not communicate for five years!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 848
#: sentence:3154
msgid ""
"Once again, this particular use of humor was not to denigrate the woman but "
"to infuse a greater sense of lightheartedness into the situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 848
#: sentence:3155
msgid ""
"Most of us take everything so seriously, but this was quintessential Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 849
#: sentence:3156
msgid "Whit Whitson remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 850
#: sentence:3157
msgid ""
"I often told my children when they were growing up, as a first principle you"
" really should be more than you seem."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 850
#: sentence:3158
msgid "And that to me was Bill in spades."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 850
#: sentence:3159
msgid ""
"On the surface, he was a good-looking guy and with just a little exposure "
"one found there was something in Bill that was gentle, that was tolerant; "
"his punning, his propensity to humor, the light touch were very important to"
" me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 850
#: sentence:3160
msgid "I just enjoyed him, especially the laughter—we laughed a lot.[50]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 851
#: sentence:3161
msgid ""
"During the mid 1980s, the Unity Church in Hawaii sponsored a large ACIM "
"conference and invited those of us from the early Course days to be "
"presenters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 851
#: sentence:3162
msgid ""
"By this time, it’s obvious that being besieged by adoring fans was not "
"Bill’s favorite situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 851
#: sentence:3163
msgid ""
"One evening, the church treated the entire group of participants to a cruise"
" lasting several hours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 851
#: sentence:3164
msgid "Bill’s major goal quickly became to find someplace private."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 851
#: sentence:3165
msgid ""
"The Prathers, Bill, my husband Bob, and I found a little bench up near the "
"bow away from the festivities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 851
#: sentence:3166
msgid ""
"As we sat down to chat with no one around, Bill said, “It’s so good not to "
"be one with my brother, with whom I am one!”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 852
#: sentence:3167
msgid ""
"ACIM was dictated during the cold war era with the Soviets, and "
"“brinksmanship” was a word often used then."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 852
#: sentence:3168
msgid ""
"Bill used to refer to practicing the Course as “celestial brinksmanship.” "
"After all, it asks that we take on faith a very different way of living, and"
" it seemed to him that he was plunging into the unknown, not knowing exactly"
" what experiences he might be precipitating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 852
#: sentence:3169
msgid "Humor enabled him to “take the plunge” more gracefully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 852
#: sentence:3170
msgid ""
"He was aware of his human frailties but was able to see through and not "
"invest in them; he advised all who would listen to do the same, to laugh at "
"their own judgments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 852
#: sentence:3171
msgid ""
"As important as ACIM was for him, and as dedicated he was to practicing, he "
"still could witness the entire project from a distance and find it all "
"amusing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 852
#: sentence:3172
msgid ""
"He closed many a conversation with a smile, saying, “I know it’s hopeless, "
"just not serious.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 853
#: sentence:3173
msgid "Chapter 18"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 854
#: sentence:3174
msgid "Although Bill was a superb speaker, he seriously did not like it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 854
#: sentence:3175
msgid ""
"This certainly is an anxiety-producing situation for a professor and the "
"Author addressed it a number of times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 854
#: sentence:3176
msgid ""
"These passages from the Urtext address his fear of teaching and the problems"
" caused him by his defenses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 855
#: sentence:3177
msgid ""
"The role of a teacher, properly conceived, is one of leading himself and "
"others out of the desert [i.e., ignorance or unawareness]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 855
#: sentence:3178
msgid ""
"The value of this role can hardly be underestimated, if only because it was "
"one to which I very gladly dedicated my life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 855
#: sentence:3179
msgid "I have repeatedly asked my pupils to follow me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 855
#: sentence:3180
msgid ""
"This means that to be effective teachers they must interpret teaching as I "
"do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 855
#: sentence:3181
msgid "I have made every effort to teach you entirely without fear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 855
#: sentence:3182
msgid ""
"If you do not listen, you will be unable to avoid the very obvious error of "
"perceiving teaching as a threat."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3183
msgid ""
"It is hardly necessary to say that teaching is a process whose purpose is to"
" produce learning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3184
msgid "The ultimate purpose of all learning is to abolish fear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3185
msgid "This is necessary so that knowledge can happen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3186
msgid "The role of the teacher is not the role of God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3187
msgid ""
"This confusion is all too frequently made by parents, teachers, therapists "
"and the clergy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3188
msgid "It is a real misunderstanding of both God and His miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3189
msgid ""
"Any teacher who believes that teaching is fearful cannot learn because he is"
" paralyzed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 856
#: sentence:3190
msgid "He also cannot really teach."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 857
#: sentence:3191
msgid ""
"Bill was quite right in maintaining that this course is a prerequisite for "
"his [upcoming teaching assignment]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 857
#: sentence:3192
msgid "However, he was really saying much more than that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 857
#: sentence:3193
msgid "The purpose of this course is to prepare you for knowledge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 857
#: sentence:3194
msgid "So is the real purpose of any legitimate course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 857
#: sentence:3195
msgid "All that is required of you as a teacher is to follow Me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3196
msgid ""
"Whenever anyone decides he can function only in some roles but not in "
"others, he cannot but be attempting to make a compromise which will not "
"work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3197
msgid ""
"If Bill is under the misbelief that he is coping with the fear problem by "
"functioning as an administrator and a teacher of interns, but not as a "
"teacher of students, he is merely deceiving himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3198
msgid "He owes himself greater respect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3199
msgid ""
"There is nothing as tragic as the attempt to deceive one’s self, because it "
"implies that you perceive yourself as so unworthy that deception is more "
"fitting for you than the truth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3200
msgid ""
"Either you can function in all of the roles you have properly undertaken to "
"fulfill, or you cannot function effectively in any of them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3201
msgid "This is an all or none decision."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3202
msgid "You cannot make inappropriate level distinctions within this choice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3203
msgid "You are either capable or not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3204
msgid ""
"This does not mean that you can do everything, but it does mean that you are"
" totally miracle-minded, or not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3205
msgid "This decision is open to no compromise whatsoever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3206
msgid ""
"When Bill says that he cannot teach, he is making the same mistake that we "
"spoke of before when he acted as if universal laws applied to everyone "
"except him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3207
msgid "This is not only arrogant, but patently untrue."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3208
msgid "Universal laws must apply to him, unless he does not exist."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 858
#: sentence:3209
msgid "We will not bother to argue about this. . . .[51]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 859
#: sentence:3210
msgid ""
"I emphasize this only because I do not want you to allow any fear to enter "
"into the thought system toward which I am guiding you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 859
#: sentence:3211
msgid "I do not call for martyrs, but for teachers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 860
#: sentence:3212
msgid ""
"Bill is an outstanding example of this confusion, and has literally believed"
" for years that teaching is martyrdom."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 860
#: sentence:3213
msgid ""
"This is because he thought, and still thinks at times, that teaching leads "
"to crucifixion rather than to re-awakening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 860
#: sentence:3214
msgid ""
"The upside down nature of this association is so obvious that he could only "
"have made it because he felt guilty.[52]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3215
msgid ""
"Bill may claim (and he has certainly done so in the past) that the "
"professorship was thrust upon him. This is not true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3216
msgid "He wanted it very much and also worked hard to get it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3217
msgid ""
"He would not have had to work so hard either if he had not misunderstood it."
" . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3218
msgid ""
"Bill could not be afraid to teach unless he still believes that interaction "
"means loss and that learning means separation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3219
msgid ""
"He stands guard over his own ideas, because he wants to protect his thought-"
"system as it is, and learning means change."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3220
msgid ""
"Change is always fearful to the separated, because they cannot conceive of "
"it as a change toward healing the separation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 861
#: sentence:3221
msgid ""
"They always perceive it as a change for further separation, because "
"separation was their first experience of change."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 862
#: sentence:3222
msgid ""
"Bill, your whole fear of teaching is nothing but an example of your own "
"intense separation anxiety, which you have handled with the usual series of "
"mixed defenses in the combined pattern of attack on truth and defense of "
"error, which characterizes all ego-thinking.[53]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 863
#: sentence:3223
msgid ""
"In addition to describing him in consistent terms, a number of people had "
"similar first impressions when they met Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 863
#: sentence:3224
msgid ""
"Layle Luckett, excited to meet the man who brought ACIM forward, said, "
"“After the next Thursday night class, or maybe it was at a Christmas party, "
"I met Bill—this long, tall string bean—and I looked up into those deep brown"
" eyes and I do not remember anything he said."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 863
#: sentence:3225
msgid "I don’t remember how he was dressed; I just remember deep brown eyes."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 863
#: sentence:3226
msgid "It was so compelling, so mesmerizing.”[54]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 864
#: sentence:3227
msgid ""
"Frances Vaughan recalls: “The first time I met Bill, I didn’t pay much "
"attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 864
#: sentence:3228
msgid "I thought he was just another visitor from New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 864
#: sentence:3229
msgid ""
"But the second time I met him, I really saw him and was astounded by the "
"light that I experienced as coming through him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 864
#: sentence:3230
msgid ""
"There was something about his simplicity, his being nothing special, while "
"at the same time seeing the love, the kindness, the generosity of spirit, "
"and a sense of humor that touched me deeply.”[55]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 865
#: sentence:3231
msgid ""
"I was fascinated by these and other responses because it was so like my own,"
" as well as the experience of a number of others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 865
#: sentence:3232
msgid ""
"Sarah Whalen-Kraft, a dear friend since childhood, had quite a startling "
"experience on her first meeting with Bill, and given that she is an "
"accomplished editor and writer, I asked her to share her thoughts on that "
"first encounter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 865
#: sentence:3233
msgid ""
"Here is an excerpt from that essay—a synopsis of the effect Bill had on so "
"many, and why."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 866
#: sentence:3234
msgid "A Reminiscence of Bill Thetford"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 867
#: sentence:3235
msgid ""
"In March 1980, Carol invited me to attend a presentation about the Course "
"given by Jerry Jampolsky, a widely known author and teacher of its "
"principles, and Bill Thetford, the man who had transcribed ACIM in the late "
"sixties and early seventies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 867
#: sentence:3236
msgid ""
"She had often spoken of these two, and I very much wanted to hear them, "
"regardless of my lukewarm interest in the books."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 867
#: sentence:3237
msgid ""
"So it was on the morning of April 12, I drove to Denver for the day-long "
"event."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3238
msgid "It was held in a rather small, old church in a quiet neighborhood."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3239
msgid ""
"I was a bit early, and as I entered the foyer, Carol came over to greet me, "
"saying she wanted to introduce me to Jerry and Bill before things got "
"started."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3240
msgid ""
"Jerry is a delightful, radiant person whom I have since heard several times,"
" always with pleasure and gratitude for his great understanding of the "
"Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3241
msgid ""
"He was already engaged with other participants, so after introducing us, "
"Carol steered me toward a tall, slender man standing alone to one side."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3242
msgid ""
"In contrast to Jerry’s ebullience, this person was rather restrained and "
"unassuming, with a gentle easiness of manner about him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3243
msgid ""
"Carol introduced us, then darted off, and we started to shake hands and "
"exchange the usual “I’ve heard so much about you” pleasantries."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 868
#: sentence:3244
msgid ""
"Then a most extraordinary process suddenly began dominating what was "
"happening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 869
#: sentence:3245
msgid ""
"As we shook hands, Bill began speaking, but while I looked into his kind, "
"friendly eyes, his words receded and a powerful jolt of recognition rushed "
"through me, simultaneously with the thought, “But I know you!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 869
#: sentence:3246
msgid ""
"We’ve already met before!” Immediately following I felt intense anxiety and "
"a devastating sense of loss, accompanied by thought of “But where?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 869
#: sentence:3247
msgid ""
"What happened?” and a desperate longing: “I can’t bear to lose you again!” "
"Then my entire being flooded with light and peace and the realization, “Of "
"course I know you—you are my Self and I’ll never lose you again.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 870
#: sentence:3248
msgid ""
"The experience receded as quickly as it had come; all had taken place within"
" a couple of minutes at most."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 870
#: sentence:3249
msgid ""
"We had both been talking and were still shaking hands as Bill finished "
"whatever he was saying, completely innocent, I’m sure, of the upheaval he "
"had precipitated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 870
#: sentence:3250
msgid ""
"I thanked him rather incoherently, turned around, walked over to the sales "
"table, and bought the ACIM set on the spot."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 870
#: sentence:3251
msgid ""
"I literally don’t remember anything else from that day, except that they "
"spoke and I was at peace inside."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 871
#: sentence:3252
msgid ""
"I started the Course that day, and it has changed my life, joining the "
"knowledge and experiences I had gained from Eastern traditions with a new "
"understanding of Jesus’ eternal teachings, which had been in my life since "
"childhood."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 871
#: sentence:3253
msgid "In the process I have come to understand also what happened that day."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 872
#: sentence:3254
msgid ""
"Bill apparently was a very modest “teacher of God,” the Course’s term for "
"one who has chosen to see another as himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 872
#: sentence:3255
msgid ""
"He was reluctant to be “out front,” preferring a behind-the-scene advisory "
"role in promoting ACIM principles and seeing his role as scribe as his most "
"important contribution."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 872
#: sentence:3256
msgid ""
"Considering the Course’s transforming effect on countless thousands "
"worldwide, this is an accurate assessment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 872
#: sentence:3257
msgid ""
"I’m told, however, that Bill didn’t see himself as important or even "
"especially good."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 872
#: sentence:3258
msgid ""
"I believe that even though he was a learned, sophisticated man, his greatest"
" strength by the end of his life lay in his innocence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3259
msgid ""
"The Vedic tradition of India is where I first understood that Truth—the "
"Veda, or Knowledge—is universal, eternal, and always present and available."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3260
msgid ""
"It manifests in a particular time and place because of the willingness of a "
"few to minister to the spiritual needs of the many."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3261
msgid ""
"For a while this specific form of Truth spreads and flourishes, but often it"
" becomes too far removed from the original inspiration and is diluted or "
"lost."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3262
msgid ""
"A true teaching, however, will inevitably revive and once again transform "
"people’s lives, as A Course In Miracles is demonstrating for thousands who "
"had become dissatisfied with traditional Christian structures."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3263
msgid ""
"Wherever this renewal process begins, it is because even one or two "
"individuals are willing to allow changes in their perception of each other "
"and the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3264
msgid ""
"They are not perfect, but they consistently seek to suspend judgment, see "
"another’s interests as not separate from their own, and forgive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 873
#: sentence:3265
msgid ""
"Those who make this effort witness to the Truth, and as they accomplish "
"their goal—and all do eventually—they are able to bring others to their own "
"healing within, sometimes knowingly, often inadvertently."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3266
msgid "Bill Thetford was such a witness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3267
msgid ""
"After the Course was transcribed and published, he continued for the "
"remainder of his life to try to live its principles on a daily, neverending "
"basis."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3268
msgid ""
"This is surely the most difficult and fearful task, it seems, but it is "
"ultimately all we are asked to do in this world, for the process of "
"forgiveness is what removes “the blocks to the awareness of love’s "
"presence,” in the Course’s words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3269
msgid ""
"I doubt that Bill was ever fully aware of the power that his willingness and"
" commitment gave him, but I was only one of many recipients of the fruits of"
" his labor."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3270
msgid ""
"For one moment he suspended all prejudice, judgment, and expectations of me,"
" providing a mirror unclouded by egoic perceptions and needs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3271
msgid ""
"In that clear mirror he showed me Who I really am—and opened the door to the"
" way home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3272
msgid ""
"As we return to an innocent perception of each other, the Christ comes "
"forward and reveals the Self that is always present."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 874
#: sentence:3273
msgid ""
"An old gospel hymn sings, “Jesus, lover of my soul, let me see my soul at "
"last.” Thanks, Bill—I got it![56]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 875
#: sentence:3274
msgid ""
"Bill was a walking miracle, innocently loving, exerting an enormously "
"powerful healing influence while not realizing what he was providing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 875
#: sentence:3275
msgid ""
"His gift was innocence, not specialness, and that came from being willing to"
" change his mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 875
#: sentence:3276
msgid ""
"What more need be said about the unutterable power of perceiving one "
"another, and ourselves, as innocent at our very core, despite what our "
"senses observe?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 875
#: sentence:3277
msgid "The choice is universally available to everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 875
#: sentence:3278
msgid ""
"Thus, despite his ambivalence about teaching, for many Bill was the greatest"
" teacher they had ever known."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 876
#: sentence:3279
msgid "00030.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 877
#: sentence:3280
msgid ""
"Throughout the Course we are told in every possible way that attacks must "
"stop and that defenses are not only unnecessary but counterproductive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 877
#: sentence:3281
msgid ""
"They do not make us safe but only add to our sense of danger, producing "
"exactly what we are trying to avoid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 877
#: sentence:3282
msgid ""
"Like everyone, Bill had developed his own defense strategies—primarily "
"withdrawal from others, holding in and holding back, which result in "
"depression, apathy, and a stubborn insistence on “being right.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3283
msgid ""
"ACIM is very clear that physical birth is not our beginning and physical "
"death is not the end."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3284
msgid ""
"In this life—a chapter in the ongoing continuity—defenses develop early and "
"take place within the context of “family,” however that is construed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3285
msgid "Bill seems to have had a loving relationship with his mother."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3286
msgid ""
"She read to him and took care of him while he was ill; apparently, he had no"
" particular issues with her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3287
msgid "His father, on the other hand, was his challenge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3288
msgid "Bill rarely mentioned him, perhaps even feared him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3289
msgid ""
"He was a working man and often absent, and it seems Bill experienced him as "
"not being present for him physically or emotionally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3290
msgid ""
"Bill confided that he had felt “the wrong child died,” a haunting, guilt-"
"ridden statement about his beloved sister’s sudden passing when he was "
"seven."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3291
msgid ""
"Deeply traumatized by her death, he said that, at his sister’s funeral, his "
"father, who adored the little girl, seemed to convey that Bill should have "
"been the one to die."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3292
msgid ""
"No one knows if that was the father’s intention, but he did shut off from "
"his son, and six months later Bill became seriously ill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3293
msgid ""
"He also remembered his father berating him later on for being a financial "
"burden because of that illness and ultimately becoming ill himself through "
"worry and grief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3294
msgid ""
"Jo, his college girlfriend, knew both Bill’s parents and commented, “His "
"father was sort of a strict, rigid gentleman."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3295
msgid "I don’t think Bill ever really related to him well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3296
msgid ""
"His mother [who worked two jobs to help supplement their income], I would "
"say, was probably over-protective and pampered him. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 878
#: sentence:3297
msgid ""
"His mother would fix us these beautiful picnic lunches to take with us when "
"we would go bicycling.”[57]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3298
msgid ""
"No wonder Bill was always in the “prepare to escape” mode, being "
"relentlessly preoccupied with his own imagined guilt. “If you did not feel "
"guilty, you could not attack, for condemnation is the root of attack. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3299
msgid ""
"For it is guilt that has obscured the Father to you, and it is guilt that "
"has driven you insane.”[58] He carried forward the burden of guilt and "
"projected it onto others, causing him much unnecessary pain along the way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3300
msgid ""
"Catherine Prescott remembers, “We used to talk about yielding, about how "
"there was the tendency of his ego to yield to whatever power was in his "
"space. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3301
msgid ""
"But what was underneath that was his guilt about being alive when his sister"
" had died so young."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3302
msgid "And so he just became smaller rather than bigger."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3303
msgid ""
"It was like he thought if he could just make himself small, then it was okay"
" for him to be alive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 879
#: sentence:3304
msgid "He admitted to being deeply traumatized by her death.”[59]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 880
#: sentence:3305
msgid ""
"The following extensive commentary from the Urtext about his relationship "
"with his parents in particular, and parenting in general, is instructive for"
" everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 881
#: sentence:3306
msgid ""
"As you have so often said, no one has adopted all of his parents’ attitudes "
"as his own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 881
#: sentence:3307
msgid ""
"In every case, there has been a long process of choice, in which the "
"individual has escaped from those he himself vetoed, while retaining those "
"he voted for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 881
#: sentence:3308
msgid ""
"Bill has not retained his parents’ political beliefs, in spite of the "
"particular kind of newspapers that constituted their own reading matter in "
"this area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 881
#: sentence:3309
msgid ""
"The reason why he could do this was because he believed he was free in this "
"area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 882
#: sentence:3310
msgid ""
"There must be some acute problem of his own that would make him so eager to "
"accept their misperception of his own worth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 882
#: sentence:3311
msgid "This tendency can always be regarded as punitive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 882
#: sentence:3312
msgid ""
"It cannot be justified by the inequality of the strengths of parents and "
"children."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 882
#: sentence:3313
msgid ""
"This is never more than temporary, and is largely a matter of maturational "
"and thus physical differences."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 882
#: sentence:3314
msgid "It does not last unless it is held onto."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 883
#: sentence:3315
msgid ""
"When Bill’s father came to his new office and “destroyed” it, it is quite "
"apparent that Bill must have been willing to let it be destroyed.[60] The "
"many times that he has commented on this event alone would suggest the "
"extreme importance of this misperception in his own distorted thinking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 883
#: sentence:3316
msgid "Why should anyone accord an obvious misperception so much power?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 883
#: sentence:3317
msgid ""
"There cannot be any real justification for it, because even Bill himself "
"recognized the real problem by saying, “How could he do this to me?” The "
"answer is, he didn’t."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 884
#: sentence:3318
msgid "Bill has a very serious question to ask himself in this connection."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 884
#: sentence:3319
msgid ""
"We said before that the purpose of the Resurrection was to “demonstrate that"
" no amount of misperception has any influence at all on a Son of God.” This "
"demonstration exonerates those who misperceive by establishing beyond doubt "
"that they have not hurt anyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 884
#: sentence:3320
msgid ""
"Bill’s question, which he must ask himself very honestly, is whether he is "
"willing to demonstrate that his parents have not hurt him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 884
#: sentence:3321
msgid "Unless he is willing to do this, he has not forgiven them. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 885
#: sentence:3322
msgid ""
"Parents do not create the image of their children, though they may perceive "
"images that they do create."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 885
#: sentence:3323
msgid "However, as we have already said, you are not an image."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 885
#: sentence:3324
msgid "If you side with image-makers, you are merely being idolatrous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3325
msgid ""
"Bill has no justification whatever for perpetuating any image of himself at "
"all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3326
msgid "He is not an image."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3327
msgid "Whatever is true of him is wholly benign."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3328
msgid ""
"It is essential that he know this about himself, but he cannot know it while"
" he chooses to interpret himself as vulnerable enough to be hurt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3329
msgid ""
"This is a peculiar kind of arrogance whose narcissistic component is "
"perfectly obvious."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3330
msgid ""
"It endows the perceiver with sufficient unreal strength to make him over, "
"and then acknowledges the perceiver’s mis-creation [about himself]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3331
msgid ""
"There are times when this strange lack of real courtesy appears to be a form"
" of humility."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 886
#: sentence:3332
msgid "Actually, it is never more than simple spite."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3333
msgid ""
"Bill, your parents did misperceive you in many ways, but their ability to "
"perceive was quite warped, and their misperceptions stood in the way of "
"their own knowledge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3334
msgid "There is no reason why they should stand in the way of yours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3335
msgid "It is still true that you believe they did something to you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3336
msgid ""
"This belief is extremely dangerous to your perception and wholly destructive"
" of your knowledge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3337
msgid ""
"This is not only true of your attitudes toward your parents, but also of "
"your misuse of your friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3338
msgid "You still think you must respond to their errors as if they were true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 887
#: sentence:3339
msgid ""
"By reacting self-destructively, you are giving them approval for their "
"misperceptions.[61]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3340
msgid ""
"As noted above, insistence on feeling unworthy is associated with arrogance "
"and narcissism, not with humility."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3341
msgid ""
"We come into form with our inclinations already intact, and conditioning "
"commences at birth and even before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3342
msgid ""
"Most of us learn at a very young age to be afraid of “being seen” or of "
"others discovering what we’re really like, so we fortify our defenses, the "
"prime one being the mask we hide behind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3343
msgid ""
"Hiding convinces us we really do need to hide, as if our survival depends on"
" it, and we are not open-minded about this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3344
msgid ""
"It is crucial to look directly at what we fear is wrong with us because this"
" fear is nothing more than one end of the spectrum of beliefs we hold about "
"ourselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3345
msgid ""
"Those beliefs, both positive and negative, collectively constitute the ego, "
"which is a convenient verbal handle for what ACIM is designed to address."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3346
msgid ""
"The Course states clearly that everything true about us is completely loving"
" and harmless."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 888
#: sentence:3347
msgid ""
"As this material poured forth, exposing their defenses, one can imagine Bill"
" and Helen’s shock; did they ever wonder why they had ever asked for a "
"better way?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 889
#: sentence:3348
msgid ""
"From years of teaching, counseling, and simply living, I can testify that "
"virtually everyone suffers from a sense of deficiency accompanied by the "
"need to hide it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 889
#: sentence:3349
msgid ""
"It is not possible to go through the early maturation process without "
"acquiring some belief in inadequacy by the age of five or six."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 889
#: sentence:3350
msgid ""
"Years ago, a man came to see me about an emergency in his life, having never"
" previously sought professional counseling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 889
#: sentence:3351
msgid ""
"After a short while, he asked, “Do very many people who come to see you feel"
" kind of unworthy?” I answered, “How about 100 percent?” (This is true even "
"if they are not aware of it.) Of course, he felt much better knowing he had "
"a great deal of company, including Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 890
#: sentence:3352
msgid "Stated another way in the Little Book of Runic Wisdom:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 891
#: sentence:3353
msgid "An Oracle does not give you instruction as to events."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 891
#: sentence:3354
msgid ""
"An Oracle points your attention towards those hidden fears and motivations "
"that will shape your future by their unfelt presence within each present "
"moment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 891
#: sentence:3355
msgid ""
"Once seen and recognized, these elements become absorbed into the realm of "
"choice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 891
#: sentence:3356
msgid ""
"Oracles do not absolve you of your responsibility for selecting your future,"
" but rather direct your attention towards those inner choices that may be "
"the most important elements in determining your future.[62]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 892
#: sentence:3357
msgid ""
"The key phrase here is, “hidden fears and motivations that will shape your "
"future.” While fear and guilt remain hidden, they powerfully disrupt our "
"peace of mind, causing us to experience our world as threatening or, at the "
"least, unsatisfactory."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 892
#: sentence:3358
msgid ""
"These unconscious fears shape our lives and we are helpless to effect real, "
"substantive change until we look straight at them, acknowledging the pain "
"they engender."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 892
#: sentence:3359
msgid "Thus, what is hidden must be brought to light for healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 893
#: sentence:3360
msgid "Do not hide suffering from His sight, but bring it gladly to Him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 893
#: sentence:3361
msgid "Lay before His eternal sanity all your hurt, and let Him heal you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 893
#: sentence:3362
msgid ""
"Do not leave one spot of pain hidden from His Light, and search your mind "
"carefully for any thoughts you may fear to uncover."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 893
#: sentence:3363
msgid ""
"For He will heal every little thought you have kept to hurt you and cleanse "
"it of its littleness, restoring it to the magnitude of God.[63]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 894
#: sentence:3364
msgid ""
"As a restatement of this idea, many Eastern traditions teach that happiness "
"and peace of mind require destroying the vasanas, variously defined as "
"mental images, latent tendencies, memory-stores, past impressions, and "
"predispositions, in other words, the self-limiting ideas we hold."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 894
#: sentence:3365
msgid ""
"Those early traditions referred to the necessity of “scorching the seeds of "
"tendencies.” The Course, keeping ancient company, restates this as removing "
"the blocks to the awareness of love’s presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 894
#: sentence:3366
msgid ""
"All viable traditions of self-knowledge include facing our early "
"conditioning in order to be released from it, thus restoring peace of mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 894
#: sentence:3367
msgid "Everyone is reading from the same page."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 895
#: sentence:3368
msgid ""
"Just as Bill’s defenses were transparent to the Author, we can deduce other "
"examples of self-judgment not yet relinquished from his relationship "
"difficulties, both before and after moving to California."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 895
#: sentence:3369
msgid ""
"Since relationships with others reveal the relationship we have with "
"ourselves, the hassles he experienced in New York and beyond clearly pointed"
" to fears and expectations about what he thought he deserved, though perhaps"
" unconsciously."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 895
#: sentence:3370
msgid ""
"Every “difficult person” in his life was a red flag pointing to his own "
"self-condemnation, mirroring judgments he may have been unaware of, or "
"unwilling to face."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 895
#: sentence:3371
msgid ""
"They sat there, staring back at him, each representing some facet of his "
"guilt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 895
#: sentence:3372
msgid ""
"What we complain about in others always indicates what we need to own in "
"ourselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3373
msgid "So what did Bill complain about, even minimally?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3374
msgid ""
"One of his greatest issues, played out through relationships, was his "
"objection to being “forced” to appear as something he wasn’t."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3375
msgid ""
"Certainly, no one can coerce anyone in any way unless all parties cooperate "
"in that process."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3376
msgid ""
"From his perspective, he felt he was told who he was rather than allowing "
"that to reveal itself and also that there were agendas and expectations "
"about his having to be a certain way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3377
msgid ""
"Of course, these merely revealed his own expectations and agendas for "
"himself, which at times he conveniently forgot."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3378
msgid ""
"His anger about not being accepted for who he was provides a specific clue "
"about his own failure to accept himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 896
#: sentence:3379
msgid ""
"Who has not engaged in that behavior somewhere along the way? “Whenever you "
"consent to suffer pain, to be deprived, unfairly treated or in need of "
"anything, you but accuse your brother of attack upon God’s Son.”[64] ACIM "
"never lets us off the hook, always bringing all our distress back to our own"
" self-attack."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 897
#: sentence:3380
msgid ""
"If Bill felt others made demands of him, trying to push him into a mold that"
" didn’t fit, he needed to look no farther than his own inclinations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 897
#: sentence:3381
msgid ""
"If he labeled some persons as “pushy,” we can be sure he harbored, even in a"
" latent state, some guilt or fear about his own pushiness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 897
#: sentence:3382
msgid ""
"Catherine Prescott commented, “The pushy part of Bill was that he wanted "
"everyone to be happy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 897
#: sentence:3383
msgid ""
"If I complained or felt burdened, he would say, ‘Come on, Usha [Catherine "
"used to be called by her middle name, Usha], let’s go and forget about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 897
#: sentence:3384
msgid ""
"Let’s play instead of being overly responsible, or overworked and "
"negative.’”[65]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 898
#: sentence:3385
msgid ""
"Also, it is common for those who don’t honor themselves to be considerate of"
" everyone else but not themselves; this failure to include themselves is "
"often disguised as a false notion of humility. Catherine remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 899
#: sentence:3386
msgid ""
"On one hand, he wanted to be kind, to say yes, to be good and loving and "
"generous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 899
#: sentence:3387
msgid ""
"He was such a fountain of giving, of pure generosity to everyone, and when "
"he had to set limits and enforce boundaries, it was quite devastating to "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 899
#: sentence:3388
msgid ""
"He had to sort out what might be hurting someone else and what was hurting "
"himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 899
#: sentence:3389
msgid "He worked with that a lot."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 899
#: sentence:3390
msgid ""
"He could have written the book about “When I say no, I feel guilty,” and "
"rising up from that was really his challenge."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 899
#: sentence:3391
msgid "He often would say, “It’s the guilt, it’s the guilt.”[66]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 900
#: sentence:3392
msgid "Then there was possessiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 900
#: sentence:3393
msgid ""
"He felt that some, chiefly Helen, wanted to own a piece of him for "
"themselves."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 900
#: sentence:3394
msgid ""
"Bill had created a tremendously constrained and constraining environment for"
" himself, as is evident in how consistently events unfolded, and he was "
"always trying to break free of that constraint."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 900
#: sentence:3395
msgid ""
"In the meantime, people who seemed to restrict him appeared throughout most "
"of his life—the “wherever you go, there you are” principle at work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 900
#: sentence:3396
msgid ""
"His “inner jailer” was always on duty, playing out its role, from his "
"subjective point of view, in his relationships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 901
#: sentence:3397
msgid "Catherine recalled another aspect they worked on together:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3398
msgid ""
"He was breaking out of the heaviness of New York and was intolerant of "
"anything that wasn’t really free and joyous and up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3399
msgid ""
"He wanted a more uplifting experience and was pretty intolerant of, "
"frustrated by, heaviness in himself and others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3400
msgid ""
"He was trying to escape from it, thinking, “Oh, my God, now I’m a hippie!” "
"It’s as if he were getting out of jail, and it reminded me of his getting "
"out of the bed after his scarlet fever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3401
msgid "It was almost like he was jailed as a kid."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3402
msgid ""
"He wanted to reconnect with the seventeen-year-old; he was more “adultified”"
" and skipped being a carefree teenager."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3403
msgid "The chains were breaking and his spirit finally flying free."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3404
msgid ""
"That wanting to play is who and what his spirit quintessentially was/is."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3405
msgid "He did it, he did the work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 902
#: sentence:3406
msgid "He really processed it through.[67]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 903
#: sentence:3407
msgid ""
"Neither Bill, nor the rest of us, can escape this very direct statement "
"related to our “challenging relationships”: “Learn this, and learn it well, "
"for it is here delay of happiness is shortened by a span of time you cannot "
"realize."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 903
#: sentence:3408
msgid "You never hate your brother for his sins, but only for your own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 903
#: sentence:3409
msgid ""
"Whatever form his sins appear to take, it but obscures the fact that you "
"believe them to be yours, and therefore meriting a ‘just’ attack.”[68]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 904
#: sentence:3410
msgid ""
"In contrast to some behaviors and attitudes to which he was still blind, "
"other areas of his discontent were clear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 904
#: sentence:3411
msgid ""
"He really despised his bouts of depression and moments of irrationality and "
"condemned himself for them, considering them a real deficiency on his part."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 904
#: sentence:3412
msgid ""
"He felt terrible after a display of anger, which stirred up much self-doubt "
"and self-loathing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 904
#: sentence:3413
msgid ""
"He also felt remorse for the comments he had made in 1982 about Ken in his "
"autobiographical interviews."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 904
#: sentence:3414
msgid ""
"When Ken read the notes and asked Bill about them, he responded very "
"differently, telling Ken that now he realized he had inherited a most "
"difficult task, which he had performed admirably under the circumstances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 904
#: sentence:3415
msgid ""
"Not only had Bill developed a broader perspective, but he detested conflict."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 905
#: sentence:3416
msgid ""
"He also did not like glamour in relation to the Course—deliberately courting"
" the “rich and famous”—in fact, couldn’t stand it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 905
#: sentence:3417
msgid ""
"When he saw people feeding their egos through ACIM association, he reacted "
"to it, indicating an unhealed fear of his own."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 905
#: sentence:3418
msgid ""
"You cannot have an aversion to something unless you already feel guilty "
"about it. According to Catherine,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 906
#: sentence:3419
msgid ""
"Actually he hated it [the glamour], but yet, funny enough, when I "
"interviewed him [for a TV pilot], he loved it and laughed about it, saying "
"he “looked good.” He had that vanity way down underneath—way, way, way down."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 906
#: sentence:3420
msgid ""
"He was so good-looking, so charismatic, and so amazingly modest and humble."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 906
#: sentence:3421
msgid ""
"I think that [a love-hate relationship with glamour] was a juggling act for "
"him.[69]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3422
msgid ""
"In the early California days, as Bill was coming to terms with his "
"involvement with ACIM, he sometimes voiced concern that it would be misused,"
" misunderstood, trivialized, presented by people who didn’t necessarily know"
" what they were doing, or generally corrupted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3423
msgid ""
"We discussed this at length and, although it was not my experience with him,"
" others noticed he became upset when people misused the material, preaching "
"concepts he thought were superficial or incorrect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3424
msgid ""
"He was clear that ACIM is basically a self-study course and did not like the"
" idea of churches or organizations being formed to promote it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3425
msgid "This has, indeed, occurred, rendering an important service to many."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3426
msgid ""
"He continued to shift his position on this, however, recognizing that so "
"long as he was attached to its being used a certain way, he wasn’t learning "
"his lesson."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3427
msgid ""
"Despite his private concerns, he never advocated preventing the varied uses "
"made of it or fighting something already implemented, trusting that there "
"are no mistakes and that learning can come from any situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3428
msgid ""
"By the end of his life, he was very accepting of anything done with the "
"Course, realizing it now had a life of its own and couldn’t possibly be "
"contained."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 907
#: sentence:3429
msgid "There simply was no way to control what people might do with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 908
#: sentence:3430
msgid ""
"He also felt some pain that the relationship with Helen wasn’t how it was "
"supposed to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 908
#: sentence:3431
msgid ""
"She was back in New York, sick and angry, and he was in California, out of "
"“prison,” with a new set of friends and opportunities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 908
#: sentence:3432
msgid ""
"Bill felt strongly they were supposed to work on their healing together, so "
"not successfully applying ACIM teachings with her was still a major "
"disappointment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 908
#: sentence:3433
msgid "And if he blamed Helen for that, he also blamed himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 909
#: sentence:3434
msgid "Chapter 19"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3435
msgid ""
"It is evident by now that Bill’s hallmarks were his almost unparalleled "
"ability to accept and support others and his fabulous sense of humor "
"inviting everyone to lighten up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3436
msgid ""
"Their effect was healing—of body and spirit—both for Bill and those around "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3437
msgid ""
"There was often no conscious discussion of or focus on healing; it just "
"happened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3438
msgid ""
"For some, it was merely being in his presence, for others it was hearing his"
" voice; but in other cases, he intended for healing to occur."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3439
msgid ""
"He never stated directly what he thought ought to be healed in a person."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3440
msgid ""
"Layle Luckett remembers, “One thing I learned about myself during that "
"process is that there is a wonderful indirect way of teaching [and healing]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3441
msgid "Bill would usually tell us some story that would illustrate a point."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 910
#: sentence:3442
msgid ""
"For instance, he would never say, ‘Forgive your mother,’ but he’d talk about"
" some instance of forgiveness.”[70]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 911
#: sentence:3443
msgid ""
"Under any circumstances, the Course speaks eloquently and often about our "
"own need for healing and why and how that is the only requirement for being "
"truly helpful to everyone else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 911
#: sentence:3444
msgid ""
"It also emphasizes that relevant healing is of the mind, and that with a "
"healed mind, a healed body and/or situation can follow."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 911
#: sentence:3445
msgid ""
"Healing the body is never the direct focus of ACIM. “Come to the holy "
"instant and be healed, for nothing that is there received is left behind on "
"your returning to the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 911
#: sentence:3446
msgid "And being blessed, you will bring blessing. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 911
#: sentence:3447
msgid ""
"Thus is your healing everything the world requires, that it may be "
"healed.”[71]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 912
#: sentence:3448
msgid ""
"No one who subscribes to the worldview of dualism, who believes he is an "
"entity separate from virtually everyone, can possibly make any sense of this"
" statement, but those who had the good fortune of spending time with Bill "
"did experience it directly, whether they understood it or not."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 912
#: sentence:3449
msgid ""
"Understanding is much less relevant when results occur right on the spot."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 912
#: sentence:3450
msgid ""
"ACIM promises that as we practice forgiveness, we automatically become a "
"healing presence for those around us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 912
#: sentence:3451
msgid ""
"Not only did Bill’s change of mind affect him but also those he was with."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 912
#: sentence:3452
msgid ""
"He recognized the Course was about both teaching and healing, but the "
"healing part was more attractive to him than the teaching."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 912
#: sentence:3453
msgid ""
"He always emphasized that healing was not tied to some special skill, but "
"was the automatic result of releasing grievances—a gift available to every "
"man, woman, and child who chooses a defenseless, forgiving way of relating. "
"Hugh Prather remembered,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 913
#: sentence:3454
msgid ""
"Certainly, I would always regain my perspective when I was around Bill, "
"because one of the things, as I’m sure you’ve found on your spiritual "
"journey, is that it’s all so simple, so simple that it’s almost "
"embarrassing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 913
#: sentence:3455
msgid ""
"It just gets down to a matter of “Are you going to do it [let go of "
"grievances] or not?” So his effect on me was how to make things unimportant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 913
#: sentence:3456
msgid ""
"Something is important only in the sense that it provides an opportunity to "
"know peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 913
#: sentence:3457
msgid ""
"Bill was a living example of the Course, rather than someone who teaches it "
"or talks it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 913
#: sentence:3458
msgid "He actually lived it; that was his real intent.[72]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 914
#: sentence:3459
msgid ""
"Jack Luckett spoke of the healing that occurred when Bill was present: “He "
"did not have to lay hands on people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 914
#: sentence:3460
msgid "He did not have to give them a diagnosis or something like that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 914
#: sentence:3461
msgid "His mere being was enough to alter something in their consciousness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 914
#: sentence:3462
msgid ""
"What he actually did was to remind people of who they were, and with that "
"reminder, they had the power to do what they wished.”[73]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 915
#: sentence:3463
msgid ""
"In another instance Jerry remembers, “In Hawaii, a woman with a lot of "
"orthopedic problems asked for a private audience [with Bill], and following "
"that, her pain disappeared."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 915
#: sentence:3464
msgid ""
"Bill had trouble thinking it had anything to do with him, as if it almost "
"threatened him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 915
#: sentence:3465
msgid "I think that kind of thing happened a lot.”[74]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3466
msgid "Judy also recounts a healing that took place in her kitchen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3467
msgid ""
"On one of the many occasions when fascinating guests filled the Skutch "
"household, Judy was preparing food while others enjoyed the lively company "
"elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3468
msgid ""
"As she cooked French fries, she found herself a bit out of sorts about "
"missing all the fun."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3469
msgid ""
"While busy feeling sorry for herself and not paying attention to her work, "
"she spilled hot grease on her hands."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3470
msgid ""
"Bill heard the racket that ensued and came in to see what was happening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3471
msgid ""
"Completely serious, he asked if she wanted the burn and, of course, she said"
" no."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 916
#: sentence:3472
msgid ""
"He held his hands above and below hers without touching them and the burn "
"disappeared miraculously."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 917
#: sentence:3473
msgid ""
"Carlagaye Olson recalled a life-changing moment of resolution while visiting"
" Bill in La Jolla years later."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3474
msgid ""
"When Bill moved to La Jolla, Jules [Finegold] and I went down to help him "
"get settled."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3475
msgid ""
"Jules had to return home, but I was still there, so Bill insisted that I "
"stay in his room and he’d take the guest room."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3476
msgid "I felt treated like visiting royalty."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3477
msgid ""
"In the morning when I woke up, I looked up through the clerestory window and"
" the word in my mind was both—a simple word."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3478
msgid ""
"I went down to the kitchen, he was already up, and I told him of this "
"wonderful experience of the word both."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3479
msgid ""
"Now whenever I feel any anxiety arise within me about my worth, my lessons, "
"anybody else, I use that word, both, and just calm right down."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 918
#: sentence:3480
msgid ""
"The gift Bill gave me was passing into some place where I don’t have to "
"choose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 919
#: sentence:3481
msgid ""
"It’s not about here or there, or this or that, or them and me, where "
"everything is pivotal about making the right choice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 919
#: sentence:3482
msgid "All of that went away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 919
#: sentence:3483
msgid "It’s both—just take a deep breath."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 919
#: sentence:3484
msgid ""
"In that feeling of being so honored with Bill, I finally got a word that "
"would reduce me to grace.[75]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 920
#: sentence:3485
msgid ""
"Another of Carlagaye’s stories illustrates not only Bill’s healing influence"
" on her—indeed, their mutual healing—but also one of the foundational "
"premises of the Course: that we must be willing to look at our “dark side,” "
"our own unforgiving, judgmental thoughts."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 921
#: sentence:3486
msgid ""
"Bill, Jules and I started doing our field trips together in the spring of "
"1981."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 921
#: sentence:3487
msgid ""
"I would arrive at 11:00 a.m., our meeting time, and we’d go someplace for "
"lunch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 921
#: sentence:3488
msgid ""
"Jules was our leader and he would line up things for us to do in the "
"afternoon; we would take field trips to see unusual or natural sights."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 921
#: sentence:3489
msgid ""
"Bill, of course, was not a nature boy, not liking to be off the sidewalks, "
"so we didn’t get too adventurous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 921
#: sentence:3490
msgid ""
"He then would take a nap later in the afternoon for his meditative time. "
"[Then they would have dinner, often with others, and attend the Tiburon ACIM"
" meeting.] I was a very strict Course fundamentalist and that was very "
"attractive to Bill, because there was such a spiritual sideshow going on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 921
#: sentence:3491
msgid "He liked it if I made comments in the group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3492
msgid ""
"Time during the day with Bill was very playful, but the drive back home "
"every week from Tiburon, leaving at 9:30 and getting back at 11:00 p.m., was"
" filled with just incredible reactions I was having—negative reactions to "
"myself, to other people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3493
msgid ""
"My ego and its reactions to everyone and everything were incredibly intense!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3494
msgid "Things were bubbling up and I was responding in a very heightened way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3495
msgid ""
"I would have this wonderful day of fun and affection and then I can’t tell "
"you the things that got dredged up in me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3496
msgid ""
"We would have so much fun and laugh and laugh and then I’d come home with "
"this creepy, horrible ego and I would realize, “My God, this is really an "
"incredible process going on and it doesn’t happen with people other than "
"Bill!” I was such an imperfect student."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3497
msgid "Intellectually, I was fine with it, but the practice of it!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3498
msgid ""
"So everything that was unlike Jesus in me would come up on those drives home"
" and I was so grateful for being with Bill, because I came back every week "
"into those loving arms of acceptance and then every week I would drive home "
"seeing the worst in me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 922
#: sentence:3499
msgid "I just can hardly explain that!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 923
#: sentence:3500
msgid ""
"The relationship with Bill helped to settle me down, get quiet, and realize "
"this is all happening internally."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 923
#: sentence:3501
msgid "It’s happening to everybody and it’s taking its own course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 923
#: sentence:3502
msgid ""
"I think I trust more in the whole deep process rather than expecting "
"extraordinary things, events, and circumstances."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 923
#: sentence:3503
msgid ""
"Somehow it was a very gracious thing, a very blessed thing [to know him] and"
" none of the words that say, “It was a great honor to be with him,” sound "
"right."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 923
#: sentence:3504
msgid ""
"That has too much of a worldly cast, but there was grace involved in being "
"with him.[76]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 924
#: sentence:3505
msgid ""
"If this isn’t a perfect example of how ACIM works, I don’t know what is."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 925
#: sentence:3506
msgid ""
"What is healing but the removal of all that stands in the way of knowledge?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 925
#: sentence:3507
msgid ""
"And how else can one dispel illusions except by looking at them directly, "
"without protecting them?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 925
#: sentence:3508
msgid ""
"Be not afraid, therefore, for what you will be looking at is the source of "
"fear, and you are beginning to learn that fear is not real. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 925
#: sentence:3509
msgid "Do not be afraid, then, to look upon fear, for it cannot be seen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 925
#: sentence:3510
msgid ""
"Clarity undoes confusion by definition, and to look upon darkness through "
"light must dispel it.[77]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 926
#: sentence:3511
msgid ""
"The Course dredges up that unconscious material for review, so we can choose"
" whether to hang on to guilt or release it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 926
#: sentence:3512
msgid ""
"It’s like comforting arms around us, with a voice saying, “Okay I’m going to"
" be here with you while we look at these ugly thoughts.” Bill, to me, "
"thoroughly personified the process of being there for so many as their dark "
"sides surfaced."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 926
#: sentence:3513
msgid "And, as promised, awareness expanded and healing happened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 927
#: sentence:3514
msgid ""
"The following is an excerpt from a dialogue between a student and Ramana "
"Maharshi (Bhagavan in quote below)—an awakened Indian master who passed away"
" in the 1950s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 927
#: sentence:3515
msgid ""
"It addresses the phenomenon, from the Eastern perspective, of how healing "
"one’s self facilitates the healing of everything else."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 928
#: sentence:3516
msgid ""
"Question: While sitting near you, what sort of mental state should we have "
"so as to receive the transmission from your pure being, or Self?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 929
#: sentence:3517
msgid "Bhagavan: Keep your mind still, that is enough."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 929
#: sentence:3518
msgid ""
"You will get spiritual help sitting in this hall if you keep yourself still."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 929
#: sentence:3519
msgid "The aim of all practices is to give up all practices."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 929
#: sentence:3520
msgid ""
"When the mind becomes still, the power of the Self will be experienced."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 929
#: sentence:3521
msgid "The waves of the Self are pervading everywhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 929
#: sentence:3522
msgid "If the mind is at peace, one begins to experience them.[78]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3523
msgid ""
"The noise within us decreased around Bill, and the loving “waves of the "
"Self” could be felt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3524
msgid ""
"From my perspective, Ramana’s teaching of nondualism echos that of ACIM, and"
" Bill thought so too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3525
msgid ""
"Ramana taught that attainment of Self-realization requires: a) diverting the"
" mind from its object and ceasing the objective view of the world; b) "
"bringing an end to the mind’s internal activities; c) rendering the mind "
"characterless; and d) resting the mind in pure vichara (inquiry of “who am "
"I?”)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3526
msgid ""
"When one looks closely, we see this as a restatement of removing the blocks "
"to the awareness of love’s presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3527
msgid "And like the Course, silence and stillness of mind is a prerequisite."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3528
msgid ""
"Hence the need for mind training, which ACIM both refers to and provides."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3529
msgid ""
"Noise and confusion subsided around Bill because it was reduced in him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3530
msgid ""
"As his focus on the intellect as a source of power and wisdom diminished, "
"his mind grew more quiet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 930
#: sentence:3531
msgid ""
"And, of course, when our intent is our own healing, we receive all the "
"necessary assistance without fail."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 931
#: sentence:3532
msgid ""
"In the early 1980s, an unlikely event—but not uncommon when we are serious "
"about practicing forgiveness—occurred at a presentation by Hugh Prather and "
"Jerry Jampolsky at a Religious Science church in San Diego."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 931
#: sentence:3533
msgid ""
"There was a good crowd of over three hundred, including Bill, who sat in the"
" back and frequently sneaked out for a smoke. The Lucketts remembered:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3534
msgid ""
"Shortly before lunch, Jerry or Hugh suggested that we each hug someone next "
"to us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3535
msgid ""
"Billy tried to run, but got snared in the doorway by another escapee, a "
"blonde woman who hugged him intensely (naturally) and forever!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3536
msgid "Then they leaned back and looked at each other."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3537
msgid ""
"He exclaimed, “Jan!” as she screamed, “Bill!” They knew each other from "
"Columbia."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3538
msgid "Her husband had worked for Bill and she had done her Ph.D. there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3539
msgid ""
"They had all been best of friends but then had a bitter falling out, I think"
" because her husband had divorced her and moved in with Bill. She hated Bill"
" intensely!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3540
msgid "At this point, she was in some cancer treatment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3541
msgid "Imagine all the venom she’d stored up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3542
msgid ""
"And out of all people on earth, here these two were in each other’s arms at "
"the end of a whole morning’s highly inspiring talk about forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3543
msgid ""
"As the past melted, they instantly forgave themselves and each other on the "
"spot and spent some time together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3544
msgid ""
"Billy was actually very healing for her, though she eventually died of "
"cancer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 932
#: sentence:3545
msgid ""
"What a demonstration and what a kick-off for moving to San Diego over five "
"years later![79]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 933
#: sentence:3546
msgid ""
"As for healings that took place related to Bill’s speaking voice, Leroy "
"Zemke commented:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3547
msgid ""
"Immediately now is another step, which has also been initiated elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3548
msgid ""
"There is before you a work that involves the uses of the voice, the uses of "
"the mechanical energies of the material world involved in the engineering of"
" sound."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3549
msgid ""
"You are to involve yourself in the projection of voice in many different "
"ways that can be utilized to inform the teachings already in print."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3550
msgid ""
"It is simply another way to demonstrate the source of the power, the essence"
" of Holy Spirit. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3551
msgid "You have a quality of healing that is transmitted through your being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3552
msgid ""
"Your words become as tools through which this force, or focus, is directed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3553
msgid ""
"And all who hear them will experience a sense of direction and feel the "
"vibratory patterns of their own being resonating with those flowing through "
"you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 934
#: sentence:3554
msgid ""
"Many will experience healing—some instantaneous, others through gradual "
"forms of healing—but the process is the same.[80]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 935
#: sentence:3555
msgid ""
"Bill had a beautiful voice through which much healing automatically "
"occurred, something of an embarrassment to him, but he was also mindful that"
" it was his gift and always had been. Jerry recalled:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 936
#: sentence:3556
msgid ""
"For me, when he read passages from ACIM, there was a vibration in his voice,"
" different from when he was just talking to you, that was the vibration of "
"God and I bathed in that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 936
#: sentence:3557
msgid ""
"It allowed people to experience the peace of God and I’m not the only one, "
"I’m sure, who felt that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 936
#: sentence:3558
msgid "He was like an older brother."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 936
#: sentence:3559
msgid ""
"He was wearing the “cloak” of Bill Thetford, but as far as I’m concerned he "
"was a manifestation of the Christ spirit.[81]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 937
#: sentence:3560
msgid ""
"Judy recalled a situation that was typical of how people responded to Bill’s"
" voice, particularly when he read from the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 937
#: sentence:3561
msgid ""
"She had introduced him to some friends, both of them psychologists and "
"students of Assagioli (an Italian psychotherapist who developed the "
"technique known as psychosynthesis); they were well known in their field and"
" had helped a great many."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 937
#: sentence:3562
msgid ""
"About twenty minutes into the visit, the woman, who was very matter of fact "
"and down to earth, asked Bill if he would mind reading something from ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 937
#: sentence:3563
msgid ""
"Both Bill and Judy were surprised, as no one had ever made that request."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 937
#: sentence:3564
msgid ""
"He asked if she had a preference about what to read and she answered no. "
"Judy recounts:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 938
#: sentence:3565
msgid ""
"Bill opened the book at random, read for about fifteen minutes, and I saw "
"the tears flowing down this woman’s face."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 938
#: sentence:3566
msgid ""
"She was holding her husband’s hand and I could still see her silently "
"weeping, which was so powerful for me!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 938
#: sentence:3567
msgid ""
"When Bill put the book down, he suddenly saw them sitting there—he really "
"did get into what he was reading—and the woman said, “I’ve heard the voice "
"of God.” She wasn’t trying to be flattering."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 938
#: sentence:3568
msgid ""
"She meant, with his reading, she heard the voice of God, and when they left,"
" she asked if he could be persuaded to record his favorite parts, which he "
"later did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 938
#: sentence:3569
msgid "When he read the Course, it was transporting.[82]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 939
#: sentence:3570
msgid ""
"Bill’s own healing, always related to relinquishing the ego, was a work in "
"progress."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 939
#: sentence:3571
msgid ""
"He was still “unlearning” the storehouse of conflicting impressions he had "
"amassed and was still partially an “unhealed healer.” The Course writes a "
"great deal about “unhealed healers” because, obviously, it came through two "
"experts in traditional psychotherapy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 939
#: sentence:3572
msgid ""
"They must have been shocked to have their life’s work so roundly dismissed "
"as unhelpful, at least as they assumed it should be practiced, in the "
"section entitled “The Unhealed Healer”:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 940
#: sentence:3573
msgid "The ego’s plan for forgiveness is far more widely used than God’s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 940
#: sentence:3574
msgid ""
"This is because it is undertaken by unhealed healers, and is therefore of "
"the ego."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 940
#: sentence:3575
msgid "Let us consider the unhealed healer more carefully now."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 940
#: sentence:3576
msgid "By definition, he is trying to give what he has not received."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 940
#: sentence:3577
msgid ""
"If an unhealed healer is a theologian, for example, he may begin with the "
"premise, “I am a miserable sinner, and so are you.” If he is a "
"psychotherapist, he is more likely to start with the equally incredible "
"belief that attack is real for both himself and the patient, but that it "
"does not matter for either of them. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3578
msgid "A therapist does not heal; he lets healing be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3579
msgid ""
"He can point to darkness but he cannot bring light of himself, for light is "
"not of him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3580
msgid "Yet, being for him, it must also be for his patient."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3581
msgid "The Holy Spirit is the only Therapist."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3582
msgid "He makes healing clear in any situation in which He is the Guide."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3583
msgid "You can only let Him fulfill His function."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3584
msgid "He needs no help for this."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 941
#: sentence:3585
msgid ""
"He will tell you exactly what to do to help anyone He sends to you for help,"
" and will speak to him through you if you do not interfere.[83]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 942
#: sentence:3586
msgid ""
"Once when Bill was in Denver, he and Bob Beale had lunch with a well-known, "
"“larger than life” financial guru."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 942
#: sentence:3587
msgid ""
"Bob remembers Fred (not his real name) as a self-promoting person with a "
"strong ego, who talked at length about his accomplishments. Finally Bob "
"said,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 943
#: sentence:3588
msgid ""
"“Fred, this is Bill Thetford who is one of the two scribes who created A "
"Course In Miracles.” That didn’t particularly impress Fred, who knew what it"
" was but so what?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 943
#: sentence:3589
msgid ""
"Bill added, “Yes, I was part of the team that brought that in,” and started "
"to be a little boastful."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 943
#: sentence:3590
msgid ""
"Then he just stopped, as if he thought, “I don’t really want to do this,” "
"and said no more in that vein."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 943
#: sentence:3591
msgid ""
"It was an interesting meeting, watching him rise to the bait and then let it"
" go."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 943
#: sentence:3592
msgid ""
"Bill started to relate on the same level as Fred—not a very pleasant one—and"
" then he stopped."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 943
#: sentence:3593
msgid ""
"He just let it go and I thought that was commendable, to say the least.[84]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 944
#: sentence:3594
msgid ""
"Here is a marvelous object lesson—in mid-sentence you can choose to let "
"something go when you realize your error."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 944
#: sentence:3595
msgid "Bill did that frequently and remarkably well from the beginning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 944
#: sentence:3596
msgid ""
"During my early visits to California, I saw him bow only once to an obvious "
"ego inclination, as he showed me various books he had contributed to and "
"more than one academic “Who’s Who” in which he was listed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 944
#: sentence:3597
msgid ""
"It was almost as if he wanted to reassure himself, and me, of his "
"value—“See, I really did do wonderful work before I left the academic "
"world”—vacillating between wanting to be special and wanting to give that "
"up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 944
#: sentence:3598
msgid ""
"One friend said, “Bill’s only self-promotion was a conspicuous undersell.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 945
#: sentence:3599
msgid ""
"Bill truly desired to give up the ego-enhancing needs to be right or to "
"prove his value and he worked very hard at not taking things personally and "
"recognizing what did and did not matter. Hugh Prather remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 946
#: sentence:3600
msgid ""
"Right from the beginning there were little things he would say, making it "
"obvious that not everyone agreed on what had actually happened [in terms of "
"the Course’s history]. I remember one detail."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 946
#: sentence:3601
msgid "He said, “It’s now been decided that it only lasted eight years."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 946
#: sentence:3602
msgid ""
"It actually lasted ten, but it’s been decided that this process took place "
"over a period of eight.” He made several comments like that, but the "
"interesting thing to me was that he didn’t care."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 946
#: sentence:3603
msgid ""
"It was just fine for it to be eight years, whatever it was; he saw that it "
"was not important; he had no ego in the details."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 946
#: sentence:3604
msgid "He was happy to accept whatever.[85]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 947
#: sentence:3605
msgid ""
"Leroy Zemke noted how important music was to Bill’s healing and sense of "
"well-being:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 948
#: sentence:3606
msgid ""
"Music, incidentally, is very, very much a trigger for you, and in former "
"lives you have been involved musically."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 948
#: sentence:3607
msgid ""
"It has been very much a part of your training as a priest in Egypt, in "
"Tibet, in India, and also when you have lived in Europe, particularly in "
"Italy and Austria."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 948
#: sentence:3608
msgid "There is a very strong, strong musical attachment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 948
#: sentence:3609
msgid ""
"Voice comes forward particularly and instruments like the piano and stringed"
" instruments are very, very, very, strong. [Bill took both voice and piano "
"lessons when he was young.] There is a very powerful, powerful tie to that "
"and it is a very transformative energy in you."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 948
#: sentence:3610
msgid ""
"Whenever you really need to touch that [healing] dimension of yourself, you "
"can simply go to music.[86]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 949
#: sentence:3611
msgid ""
"As he dedicated himself to his healing through forgiveness, Bill continued "
"to become more transparent and open."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 949
#: sentence:3612
msgid ""
"Catherine Prescott, with whom he spent much time in therapeutic exploration,"
" commented on his noticeable healing:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3613
msgid "He became happier, looser, less burdened, way more energized."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3614
msgid ""
"We did voice dialogue work on his rheumatic heart condition and realized "
"that part of him was still frozen from back then, so we woke that up again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3615
msgid ""
"It was almost like soul retrieval for the part of himself he had dedicated "
"to his mother, to be sure she didn’t lose her third child."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3616
msgid ""
"He and the sister made a contract, with her death, that he wasn’t going to "
"live fully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3617
msgid "That was the core of the work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3618
msgid ""
"So we looked at what it would it be like to wake up every cell in the body, "
"get out of that rigid frozen state, and live fully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3619
msgid "I feel that was part of his moving down to La Jolla."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3620
msgid "He became way more joyous."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3621
msgid ""
"He always had such a great spirit, even from the beginning, but it was like "
"he was wearing some kind of a mental straightjacket."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 950
#: sentence:3622
msgid ""
"He was really in a psychological shutdown and it felt so wonderful to watch "
"the blooming.[87]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 951
#: sentence:3623
msgid "And bloom he did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 951
#: sentence:3624
msgid ""
"Judy remembers reminiscing about Bill’s “olden days” at Columbia with a "
"colleague who declared, “l can’t believe that the guy who smoked five packs "
"a day and drank coffee all the time is the same gentle, loving, peaceful "
"Bill we know now. ACIM works!”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 952
#: sentence:3625
msgid "Whit Whitson noted in his remarks at Bill’s memorial service,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3626
msgid ""
"It was then my privilege to watch Bill’s transformation into a healed "
"healer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3627
msgid ""
"As he disciplined his mind to perceive the world and himself through the "
"lenses of the Course, he became the personification of the process of inner "
"growth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3628
msgid "His courage and his pain were masked by his inspired sense of humor."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3629
msgid ""
"His humor was a gentle expression of his compassion toward the glory and the"
" absurdity of the human condition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3630
msgid ""
"He was a master teacher and while he would not wish such recognition, "
"preferring anonymity, the day will come when his work in pioneering the PAS "
"and helping Helen channel the Course will receive worldwide recognition. "
"Knowledge sets us free."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3631
msgid "Bill truly understood the ego."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 953
#: sentence:3632
msgid "His knowledge set him free and beckons each of us to follow.[88]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 954
#: sentence:3633
msgid "Chapter 20"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 955
#: sentence:3634
msgid ""
"Another defining characteristic that Bill possessed was a simple, "
"uncomplicated wisdom that was anything but simple-minded or elementary—quite"
" the opposite."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 955
#: sentence:3635
msgid ""
"And, with the dwindling instances of ego involvement mentioned earlier, Bill"
" was the poster child for genuine humility, intellectual and otherwise."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 955
#: sentence:3636
msgid "Frances Vaughan referred to his being “wonderfully nothing special.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 956
#: sentence:3637
msgid "He was a very important mentor to me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 956
#: sentence:3638
msgid ""
"One thing about Bill that not everyone saw was his incredible knowledge and "
"understanding of psychology, philosophy, and comparative religions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 956
#: sentence:3639
msgid "He was extraordinarily erudite and well read."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 956
#: sentence:3640
msgid ""
"He never flaunted his intellectual brilliance, yet he really had a profound,"
" universal understanding of human beings and the way we grow and change.[89]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 957
#: sentence:3641
msgid ""
"A friend from Florida said, “I loved his careful, clear mind, so precise but"
" so well buffered with kindliness, and I can easily appreciate how you would"
" be drawn together in friendship.” Another unusual and compelling trait was "
"his willingness to grant wisdom where he found it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 957
#: sentence:3642
msgid ""
"He was always very happy to give everybody credit for their capabilities, "
"regardless of their “official” credentials."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 958
#: sentence:3643
msgid "Jaison Kayn spoke for so many when he noted:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 959
#: sentence:3644
msgid ""
"He was more than just a dear friend who was there to listen; it was his very"
" simple and direct wisdom."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 959
#: sentence:3645
msgid "I was comforted by the knowingness that he had."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 959
#: sentence:3646
msgid ""
"It’s nice to know someone who was that clear and alive and personally caring"
" of me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 959
#: sentence:3647
msgid ""
"One time we were actually in your backyard and he was enjoying Shanna "
"[Jaison’s dog] and he just looked at me and said, “Well, isn’t she your "
"alter ego?” Bill didn’t wear his knowledge at all, but if you asked him "
"something, he would give the clearest, brief summary of anything—the "
"Vedanta, the Urantia book, or whatever."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 959
#: sentence:3648
msgid ""
"This guy was a library, not only of knowledge, but a library of very precise"
" understanding."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 959
#: sentence:3649
msgid ""
"He was so tuned in without the outward appearance of it, almost as if he "
"were surprised that it came out.[90]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 960
#: sentence:3650
msgid "Sometimes that wisdom could be very direct and short."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 960
#: sentence:3651
msgid ""
"One of Judy’s favorite stories is about a time when she was utterly furious "
"with Jerry and caught in the grip of her own anger."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 960
#: sentence:3652
msgid "Not to put too fine a point on it, she was having a fit!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 960
#: sentence:3653
msgid "She called Bill and ranted to him about Jerry’s various shortcomings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 960
#: sentence:3654
msgid ""
"Bill’s calm response was, “Are you willing to see your brother sinless?” She"
" shouted that no, she was not!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 960
#: sentence:3655
msgid ""
"He said to her, “When you’re ready to do just that, you will feel much "
"better,” and hung up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 961
#: sentence:3656
msgid ""
"Pat Hopkins recalls, “Also, while he had a brilliant mind and a naturally "
"elegant way of speaking, he never clobbered you over the head with his "
"knowledge or the power of his intellect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 961
#: sentence:3657
msgid ""
"He was truly the most modest, gentle man I’ve ever known.”[91] Another "
"example of Bill’s confirming wisdom was this response to Bob Beale:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 962
#: sentence:3658
msgid ""
"One early morning while we were on that trip to Santa Fe, I jogged around "
"the national cemetery there for about forty-five minutes or so, and after "
"returning, we were all having breakfast and I said, “You know Bill, when I "
"was in that cemetery I got a sense that a number of the spirits of those "
"people buried there were around."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 962
#: sentence:3659
msgid ""
"And it seemed like they were talking to me so I just decided to have a "
"conversation with them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 962
#: sentence:3660
msgid ""
"I told him Sergeant So-and-So said this and Captain Jones said that, calling"
" them by name.” I remember Bill saying, “Well, of course, that’s what "
"happens.” He didn’t elaborate on things, just giving such amazing "
"confirmation.[92]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 963
#: sentence:3661
msgid ""
"That quiet, behind-the-scenes brilliance manifested in other ways. Whit "
"Whitson noted,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 964
#: sentence:3662
msgid ""
"When we were at parties or elsewhere, Bill and I would see someone come in "
"and watch their body language to try to fit that personality into the PAS, "
"not dissecting the person but playing with the basic structure of the PAS as"
" applied to that person."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 964
#: sentence:3663
msgid "Then we would embellish it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 964
#: sentence:3664
msgid ""
"It was as if we had found the basic Christmas tree and then decided what "
"kind of baubles would be hung on that kind of Christmas tree [in terms of "
"fine-tuning the exact details of that particular personality type, after "
"noting the basic personality components]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 964
#: sentence:3665
msgid ""
"Bill knew so much more about it than I did that I would sit there "
"fascinated."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 964
#: sentence:3666
msgid ""
"He enjoyed that kind of intellectual discourse because at the level of "
"analyzing the ego, he was the best.[93]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 965
#: sentence:3667
msgid ""
"Whit also commented that Bill possessed a talent for evaluation that was "
"almost psychic and always empathetic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 965
#: sentence:3668
msgid ""
"However, that particular demonstration of his talent remained private, "
"shared only with Whit in Tiburon, who could appreciate Bill’s ability from "
"his own experience with the PAS."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 966
#: sentence:3669
msgid "Hugh Prather noted,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 967
#: sentence:3670
msgid ""
"Another thing that was very interesting to me about Bill’s life was that he "
"never used ACIM to his benefit, where all the rest of us have."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 967
#: sentence:3671
msgid ""
"To one degree or another, we’ve made money off the Course; we’ve increased "
"our reputations with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 967
#: sentence:3672
msgid ""
"I don’t think there’s anything wrong with that, but it was just remarkable "
"that Bill never once used the Course to enhance himself or put money in his "
"pocket in any way, nor did he have any interest in doing that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 967
#: sentence:3673
msgid "In fact, he had great reluctance.[94]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 968
#: sentence:3674
msgid "Roger Walsh commented on his first impression of Bill:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3675
msgid "The one that immediately comes up is that he was so shy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3676
msgid ""
"It took me a while to appreciate that it was an extraordinary degree of "
"humility."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3677
msgid ""
"He was unduly self-deprecating but I came to appreciate that that was just a"
" very genuine and deep form of humility."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3678
msgid ""
"When I first saw the Course, I opened it up and saw those words “God” and "
"“Holy Spirit” and said, “No thanks.” One time, Bill and Jerry were making a "
"presentation on ACIM at the American Psychiatric Conference in San "
"Francisco."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3679
msgid ""
"I remember going to the gathering afterwards and meeting Bill there and "
"literally having the thought, “Well, if this guy’s into it, I’m interested.”"
" . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3680
msgid ""
"He served the purpose of opening doors for me in the sense that I came from "
"a very hard-core scientific, materialist, reductionist, anti-spiritual "
"background and he was someone who I could not pretend to be brighter than, "
"and yet who himself had come around to appreciate this material, so I "
"appreciated it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3681
msgid ""
"Here was someone with a very impressive intellect who was impressed by it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 969
#: sentence:3682
msgid ""
"It’s one thing when people who may not be so analytically or critically "
"inclined get into something but another, indeed, with someone whose "
"credentials are impeccable, whose intellectual and skeptical faculties are "
"good.[95]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 970
#: sentence:3683
msgid ""
"At Bill’s memorial service, Roger additionally commented on the deep impact "
"of Bill’s choice to leave no legacy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 970
#: sentence:3684
msgid ""
"Although so many devote enormous amounts of time to creating a legacy and "
"identifying their lives with it, Bill’s intention was to leave no personal "
"footprint but simply to be ordinary."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 971
#: sentence:3685
msgid "Bill’s life was a model of the opposite."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 971
#: sentence:3686
msgid ""
"He had already created a legacy, one of priceless worth, and worked very "
"hard to make sure he was not identified with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 971
#: sentence:3687
msgid ""
"Bill could have symbolized many things—an extraordinarily successful "
"psychologist or a really successful person of the world, or a spiritual "
"symbol as someone who was the source and creator of this most important "
"spiritual text."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 971
#: sentence:3688
msgid ""
"He didn’t do any of the things I would assume to be part of making an "
"important spiritual contribution—lecturing, writing books or papers on ACIM,"
" appearing on TV, giving interviews."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 971
#: sentence:3689
msgid ""
"He stayed home most of the time, studied the Course, and tried to make his "
"relationships whole, humbly and unpretentiously practicing the material."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 971
#: sentence:3690
msgid "That, I find, is just an extraordinary example.[96]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 972
#: sentence:3691
msgid ""
"One aspect of Bill’s wisdom was his willingness to acknowledge what he "
"didn’t know, despite all the knowledge he possessed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 972
#: sentence:3692
msgid ""
"If you believe you should already know it all and must not reveal that you "
"don’t, protecting your image as an accomplished self becomes job one—a "
"terrible trap."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 972
#: sentence:3693
msgid "In contrast, Jaison Kayn noted,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3694
msgid ""
"Bill, clearly being human at the time, had all his normal human stuff to "
"deal with too, just like the rest of us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3695
msgid "And he never tried to pretend that wasn’t so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3696
msgid ""
"The feeling he conveyed was that he was in this soup like all the rest of "
"us, and enjoyed being with us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3697
msgid ""
"I also had the sense that he liked being included [in our Denver group] "
"because in a certain way he was shy and naive about some things."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3698
msgid ""
"I expected someone who was the authority, but he was very open about his "
"confusions and doubts."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3699
msgid ""
"Everybody assumed he knew everything, but he was just another guy trying to "
"figure life out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3700
msgid ""
"Sometimes he was the opposite of the guy with all the answers and would get "
"that look in his eyes like, “I haven’t got a clue, don’t ask me.” He would "
"defer as much as possible, put everybody else in the middle of things and "
"have them speak because he didn’t want to be the center of attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3701
msgid ""
"He didn’t want to be the big cheese at all, but when he spoke, everyone "
"listened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3702
msgid ""
"He did not like having that much responsibility, but he accepted it as if he"
" knew his gems were seeds that he needed to scatter."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3703
msgid ""
"He also knew he was giving more than information or wisdom; he was giving "
"support and encouragement, an act of love that would help people believe in "
"the message and do their inner work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 973
#: sentence:3704
msgid "When he spoke, there was no preaching; it was all about practice.[97]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 974
#: sentence:3705
msgid "Catherine Prescott remembered,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 975
#: sentence:3706
msgid "He seemed very egoless to me, I will say that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 975
#: sentence:3707
msgid "I’m sure he had one, but he was so humble himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 975
#: sentence:3708
msgid ""
"Probably the worst [in terms of the ego revealing itself] was in those "
"sessions where he got in touch with the angry side of himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 975
#: sentence:3709
msgid "He would blow up and then feel remorseful and disgusted with himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 975
#: sentence:3710
msgid ""
"I think he was finishing up some work with Helen, and of course, we talked "
"about all that nonstop."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 975
#: sentence:3711
msgid ""
"He always reflected back, wondering if he was a good or a bad person.[98]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 976
#: sentence:3712
msgid ""
"Many of us had conversations with Bill about who the intended recipients of "
"the Course’s teachings were to be. Hugh Prather said,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3713
msgid ""
"I remember one of the things he brought up right from the beginning was his "
"confusion over why ACIM was so popular."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3714
msgid ""
"I think he interpreted the guidance he and Helen received as meaning this "
"was for them and maybe a few others and that wasn’t the way it was turning "
"out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3715
msgid "Even then, it was obvious that it had, in a sense, taken off."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3716
msgid ""
"I remember his telling me that Helen’s guidance was that the Course was only"
" for about two hundred people, so he thought there was some sort of conflict"
" here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3717
msgid ""
"It was as if it seemed obvious to everyone else that it was for everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3718
msgid ""
"He didn’t have any proprietary sense about this; I didn’t pick up that he "
"was in any way resentful, simply amazed and perplexed as to why this had "
"happened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 977
#: sentence:3719
msgid ""
"That was a deep concern to him [early on], but it left him in the latter "
"part of his life.[99]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 978
#: sentence:3720
msgid "Perhaps Helen was right."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 978
#: sentence:3721
msgid ""
"Maybe, comparatively speaking, only a few people in the world really want to"
" dedicate themselves to letting go of all grievances, totally accepting all "
"aspects of their lives without reservation, and living without resistance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 978
#: sentence:3722
msgid ""
"The other millions of ACIM students, either directly or through its "
"surrogates, are proceeding in their own perfect and helpful way toward "
"accepting the single goal of peace of mind, moving from understanding what "
"the Course says to applying its principles in more and more situations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 978
#: sentence:3723
msgid "Therefore, it is both for a few and for everyone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 978
#: sentence:3724
msgid "How unusual and reassuring when everyone is right!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3725
msgid ""
"Personally, I knew only a couple of people who were uncomfortable in Bill’s "
"presence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3726
msgid ""
"One woman didn’t actively dislike him; she just thought he was socially "
"inept and somewhat dull and boring."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3727
msgid ""
"When I discussed this with a friend, he said, “I think she saw in Bill the "
"very things that I saw, but had a different label for it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3728
msgid ""
"I saw that he knew how to handle himself, was obviously socially skilled so "
"that he could participate, but he wasn’t completely comfortable with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3729
msgid "He just did the best he could."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3730
msgid ""
"He did prefer to be quiet, but to me, that wasn’t boring, that was "
"fabulous!”[100] His attempts to let go of ego, not call attention to "
"himself, and practice forgiveness in every possible way paid off."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 979
#: sentence:3731
msgid ""
"He was just “ordinary Bill” in the end, but the most extraordinary person "
"most of us ever knew."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 980
#: sentence:3732
msgid "Chapter 21"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 981
#: sentence:3733
msgid ""
"Bill’s ability to turn directly to God manifested, among other ways, in his "
"excellent sense of guidance, his ability to follow his intuition or hunches."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 981
#: sentence:3734
msgid ""
"The Course clearly states that spiritual direction is always available and "
"actually leading us, but most don’t believe they have that capability."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 981
#: sentence:3735
msgid ""
"ACIM teaches that, “The Holy Spirit’s Voice is as loud as your willingness "
"to listen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 981
#: sentence:3736
msgid ""
"It cannot be louder without violating your freedom of choice, which the Holy"
" Spirit seeks to restore, never to undermine.”[101] Quite simply, we have "
"chosen not to listen and can change our minds whenever we choose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 981
#: sentence:3737
msgid "Bill helped many make that decision."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 982
#: sentence:3738
msgid ""
"Bill himself often meditated in order to access his connection with God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 982
#: sentence:3739
msgid ""
"When Bill felt things were getting stuck for himself or others, he would "
"recommend doing a Course lesson or meditating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 982
#: sentence:3740
msgid "Hugh commented on Bill’s meditation process:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 983
#: sentence:3741
msgid "I would peek at how he was meditating."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 983
#: sentence:3742
msgid ""
"He would pray quite deeply, then open his eyes and sort of look around, and "
"then he would close his eyes and meditate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 983
#: sentence:3743
msgid "He would go back and forth in that way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 983
#: sentence:3744
msgid ""
"There are some lessons in the early part of the workbook where you open your"
" eyes and it was interesting to see."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 983
#: sentence:3745
msgid ""
"But I remember being struck right from the beginning at how deeply he could "
"turn to God."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 983
#: sentence:3746
msgid ""
"It’s as if the ego side, or the outward side, of Bill was filled with doubt "
"and laughter and vulnerability with a wonderful, very interesting, appealing"
" personality, but he could click that off, put all that aside, and turn very"
" deeply and directly to God.[102]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 984
#: sentence:3747
msgid ""
"Long before ACIM, Bill had deep faith in something, always knowing things "
"would work out somehow."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 984
#: sentence:3748
msgid ""
"He had an inner sense of being prompted or led, tapping into omnipresent "
"wisdom, as all of us can when we believe it possible; he didn’t quite know "
"how to use that talent, not knowing where it came from."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 984
#: sentence:3749
msgid ""
"It didn’t seem very scientific or a likely subject for testing or "
"evaluation, so in his younger years he usually ignored it or at least didn’t"
" talk about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 984
#: sentence:3750
msgid ""
"One of the greatest limitations we adopt early on is that only what we "
"apprehend with our senses is legitimate and all else is suspect."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 984
#: sentence:3751
msgid "Of course, quite the contrary is true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 985
#: sentence:3752
msgid ""
"Bill told many of us this story, one of his favorites, about “things working"
" out” and acknowledged that it had a very profound effect on him (this "
"account taken from a 1984 interview with Bill in New Realities magazine):"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 986
#: sentence:3753
msgid ""
"On Easter Sunday in 1970 I had agreed to take Jean, an elderly woman artist,"
" down to dinner in Greenwich Village with some other artist friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 986
#: sentence:3754
msgid ""
"It was a very cold, stormy, wintry day with sleet and high winds—unusual for"
" that time of year."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 986
#: sentence:3755
msgid ""
"Being without a car, I realized I was going to have a lot of trouble getting"
" a taxi and so I meditated briefly about what to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 986
#: sentence:3756
msgid ""
"I got a clear message that I was to go to the corner of 78th Street and "
"Fifth Avenue, near where I lived, at exactly 3:15 and the problem would be "
"taken care of."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 986
#: sentence:3757
msgid ""
"I had enormous resistance to doing this but I put on my stormy weather gear "
"anyway, walked to the corner, and tried to hail a cab."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 986
#: sentence:3758
msgid ""
"Since I was in competition with all the doormen on Fifth Avenue, it seemed "
"utterly useless."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 987
#: sentence:3759
msgid ""
"Then for just a moment I closed my eyes and let go of my troubled thoughts, "
"saying to myself, “Thank you, Father, it’s already done.” And for an instant"
" I truly believed that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 987
#: sentence:3760
msgid ""
"When I opened my eyes, a chauffeur-driven limousine had stopped right in "
"front of me at the corner and the driver rolled down his window and asked, "
"“May I help you, sir?” This, as anyone who’s been to New York or lived there"
" knows, was a highly improbable happening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 988
#: sentence:3761
msgid ""
"I was very tempted to ask him why he had stopped for me, and then I realized"
" that this would be an inappropriate question; I was simply to accept this "
"gift."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 988
#: sentence:3762
msgid "I got in and we drove over to Jean’s and picked her up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 988
#: sentence:3763
msgid ""
"She was absolutely thrilled that I had come to pick her up in a limousine!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 989
#: sentence:3764
msgid ""
"The interesting thing, too, is that I didn’t discuss a fee with the driver."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 989
#: sentence:3765
msgid ""
"He simply took me without any question and when we arrived at our "
"destination, I asked him how much it was and he said something ridiculous "
"like five dollars."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 989
#: sentence:3766
msgid ""
"I think I gave him several times that amount out of enormous gratitude and "
"relief.[103]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 990
#: sentence:3767
msgid "He recounts another instance of “just knowing”:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 991
#: sentence:3768
msgid ""
"Louis [Schucman] once told me that one of the profound experiences of his "
"life, that made him believe in the reality of “this Course stuff,” happened "
"a number of years ago when he called me one day and said, “I would like to "
"see you privately.” I remember that particular occasion quite well, because "
"of what took place."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 991
#: sentence:3769
msgid "It just occurred to me that Louis needed at least $1,000."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 991
#: sentence:3770
msgid ""
"Without any further thought, I wrote a check to have ready for him so that "
"when he arrived he wouldn’t be embarrassed about asking for it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 991
#: sentence:3771
msgid ""
"When he got to my office and started telling me about having some temporary "
"difficulties with his business, I said, “I thought maybe you were having "
"some problems, so here it is.” It blew his mind.[104]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 992
#: sentence:3772
msgid ""
"Many people commented that one of Bill’s major gifts was his ability to "
"suspend the ego and let the Voice speak through him, not just when he was "
"reading from the Course but in his normal daily discourse."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 992
#: sentence:3773
msgid ""
"This does not mean he went into a trance state, but simply that in everyday "
"interactions he was inspired, calmly and naturally, to make just the perfect"
" comments to help someone, often without his knowing that had occurred."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 992
#: sentence:3774
msgid ""
"And this capability was in addition to the inherent healing quality of his "
"physical voice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 992
#: sentence:3775
msgid "During our Santa Fe trip in the early 1980s, Bob Beale remembered,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 993
#: sentence:3776
msgid "We really had time to just hang out with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 993
#: sentence:3777
msgid ""
"I don’t know that Bill was the kind of guy who just hung out, but "
"nevertheless, that’s what we did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 993
#: sentence:3778
msgid ""
"I distinctly remember we were all having lunch on the patio of a restaurant "
"when Bill turned to me and, not as part of the conversation, said, “Bob, you"
" need to trust your presence and you don’t, you know."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 993
#: sentence:3779
msgid ""
"And if you’ll just learn to trust your presence, you’ll find that you’ll do "
"what you’re here to do.” At the time it seemed an odd statement but it "
"really resonated with me and I’ve never forgotten it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 993
#: sentence:3780
msgid ""
"It was just “trust your presence.” There was something about the simplicity "
"of his comment and his tone of voice, very gentle and loving, that "
"reverberated like a ton of bricks.[105]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3781
msgid ""
"Over the years, Bill would speak of his life adventures, especially those "
"related to guidance, not boasting but with amusement and fascination about "
"the way things worked out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3782
msgid ""
"He witnessed unlikely events unfolding and was completely intrigued by them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3783
msgid ""
"One of his favorite stories was about making financial arrangements to move "
"to Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3784
msgid ""
"He was still weighing his options about moving and was reluctant for several"
" reasons."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3785
msgid ""
"He thought to himself, “Well, if I have $10,000, I’ll go,” feeling he needed"
" extra financial assurance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3786
msgid ""
"Soon he was inwardly prompted to buy some IBM stock options. “I didn’t have "
"the money at all, and no one in his right mind would do anything like this, "
"it was extremely risky."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3787
msgid ""
"But right after I bought them—the same day—the stock began to shoot up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 994
#: sentence:3788
msgid "I made the $10,000 I needed within twenty-four hours.”[106]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 995
#: sentence:3789
msgid "00014.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 996
#: sentence:3790
msgid ""
"Despite his eminence as a professor, Bill always considered himself a "
"student and sought wisdom from a wide range of sources, from the “far-out” "
"to the more traditional."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 996
#: sentence:3791
msgid ""
"He explored anything that could be therapeutic or that facilitated self-"
"discovery."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 996
#: sentence:3792
msgid ""
"In LeRoy Zemke’s personal readings, which Bill found helpful in gaining new "
"perspectives on his unfolding life, he speaks of another aspect of the "
"indigo color in Bill’s aura:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 997
#: sentence:3793
msgid ""
"This is the color of the unknown, the part of you that reaches into the "
"unknown, always seeking to draw in more of what you do not know."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 997
#: sentence:3794
msgid ""
"It is that dimension that is never satisfied, always yearning for more."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 997
#: sentence:3795
msgid ""
"As its external effect, it causes you to search out unusual things, unusual "
"ideas or to attract them into your life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 997
#: sentence:3796
msgid ""
"This causes you to draw unusual friends into your life pattern, unusual "
"people from very different walks of life, some of whom are very incongruous "
"with others, but all of whom have very special, almost what might be called "
"spiritual or holy qualities about them.[107]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 998
#: sentence:3797
msgid ""
"Bill had immersed himself in mystical and metaphysical teachings once the "
"Course began, because he felt certain its premises could not be unique and "
"he was correct—universal wisdom is just that and not the exclusive province "
"of ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 999
#: sentence:3798
msgid ""
"A year or so before he died, Bill and the Lucketts went to see Adele "
"Tinning, the “table tipper.” She was an older woman who lived in a little "
"old house in southern California and was renowned for her ability to make a "
"huge oak table levitate—to vibrate and tap out answers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 999
#: sentence:3799
msgid ""
"She asked Bill to identify who was tipping the table as it spelled out a "
"name that was unfamiliar to all present except Bill—it was Helen’s secret "
"name for him. (I cannot find anyone who knows what that name was.) He was "
"astounded and convinced of the validity of Tinning and her methods."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 999
#: sentence:3800
msgid ""
"He then asked Helen a series of questions, via the table, and received "
"answers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 999
#: sentence:3801
msgid ""
"Clearly, Bill was not shy about privately pursuing the unusual and he loved "
"the unexplainable, the ineffable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 999
#: sentence:3802
msgid ""
"With his usual play on words, he used to joke about trying to “eff” the "
"ineffable, discover the undiscoverable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1000
#: sentence:3803
msgid ""
"Both Bill and Helen sought answers and reassurance from unlikely sources, "
"meeting with two well-known British psychics and visiting Hugh Lynn Cayce in"
" Virginia, just before the Course began and several other times as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1000
#: sentence:3804
msgid ""
"Though Bill was not interested in organized religion, parapsychology and "
"psychic phenomena had long caught his attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1000
#: sentence:3805
msgid ""
"Hugh Lynn had highly recommended the work of Eileen Garrett, the world-"
"famous psychic, and Bill felt a strong intuitive urge to speak with her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1000
#: sentence:3806
msgid ""
"He had heard she never went out publicly, but nevertheless, he had a "
"persistent feeling he was supposed to meet her. “I had also heard she was "
"ill most of the time and impossible to meet,” he recounts, “that she spent a"
" great deal of her time in southern France."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1000
#: sentence:3807
msgid ""
"I thought I would certainly not call her office; it didn’t seem like the "
"thing to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1000
#: sentence:3808
msgid ""
"But there was something in the back of my mind urging me to meet her.”[108]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1001
#: sentence:3809
msgid ""
"Sometime in 1968, he received an unexpected announcement from the American "
"Society for Psychical Research about a lecture on mediumship to be given by "
"experts in the field."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3810
msgid ""
"When I saw this announcement, I thought, “I must go to this,” even though I "
"never went to ASPR meetings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3811
msgid ""
"It seemed strange that I would want to do that, but I thought this was an "
"important occasion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3812
msgid ""
"When I walked in for the meeting, I was aware of something different in the "
"atmosphere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3813
msgid ""
"A number of people came up to me and talked in a way that suggested that "
"they thought I knew something about psychics or that I had psychic "
"abilities."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3814
msgid ""
"People seemed to be reading my aura and there was a lot of strange stuff "
"going on that I wasn’t accustomed to."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3815
msgid ""
"I sat in the back of the hall and during the speaker’s presentation a woman "
"in the front row asked questions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3816
msgid "I thought, “That must be Eileen Garrett,” yet I had never seen her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3817
msgid "I was just sure that this was who it was. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3818
msgid ""
"At the end of the meeting I did something that was very out of character for"
" me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3819
msgid ""
"I went up to her, held out my hand to introduce myself, and said, “Mrs. "
"Garrett, my name is Professor Thetford from Columbia and I think it is very "
"important that I talk to you.” She turned around, looked at me with total "
"attention, held my hand for a moment and said, “Yes, you must come."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1002
#: sentence:3820
msgid "Call and make an appointment.”[109]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1003
#: sentence:3821
msgid ""
"Within a week, to the astonishment of her office staff, Bill had an "
"appointment with the “impossible to meet” Mrs. Garrett and was amazed that "
"it had been so simple."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1003
#: sentence:3822
msgid "His next hurdle was to induce Helen to go with him to meet Garrett."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1003
#: sentence:3823
msgid ""
"She panicked at the idea of seeing her and discussing dissociated states, "
"but ultimately he succeeded in, as he called it, “dragging her down there "
"[to Garrett’s office].”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3824
msgid ""
"When Bill and Helen met with Mrs. Garrett, she was gracious, charming, calm,"
" and very reassuring to Helen, calling her a “fragile little flower” and "
"indicating that she (Eileen) needed no details about the manuscript they "
"referred to, but that she would publish whatever they had taken down because"
" of its source."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3825
msgid "In her mind, there was no question about its authenticity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3826
msgid ""
"Bill said her most important comment was that “if we went in the direction "
"of the Course, if we followed it in our personal lives, we would both be "
"gloriously happy, but if we fought it, we would be sick. She repeated that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3827
msgid ""
"It was obvious that she saw something about the character of the Course even"
" then in 1968.”[110] Bill believed she was the greatest living psychic, and "
"for her to confirm its legitimacy and to repeatedly emphasize the need to "
"practice it made a strong impression on him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3828
msgid ""
"He was deeply reassured because he and Helen could talk to so few people "
"about their extraordinary project."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3829
msgid ""
"In retrospect, their meeting Eileen seems destined, just as was mine with "
"Bill and the process was so similar."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1004
#: sentence:3830
msgid ""
"We cannot avoid meeting those who are to be in our lives, no matter how "
"convoluted the process of our coming together may seem."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1005
#: sentence:3831
msgid ""
"Another confirming experience for Bill occurred in London and involved the "
"famous English psychic, Ronald Beasley."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1005
#: sentence:3832
msgid "Beasley read auras, the energy field that we are and emanate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1005
#: sentence:3833
msgid ""
"He commented that Bill’s and Helen’s auras were remarkably similar, a very "
"unusual situation, and told them personal information he could not have "
"known, which they found most impressive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1005
#: sentence:3834
msgid ""
"Beasley concluded by saying they were wasting their time, “You shouldn’t be "
"involved in the university life; you should be involved in healing.”[111]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1006
#: sentence:3835
msgid ""
"Since the Course was clearly about both healing and teaching, Bill sought "
"more information about unusual healing practices, just as he investigated "
"various mystical traditions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1006
#: sentence:3836
msgid ""
"He had watched Kathryn Kuhlman, a widely known faith healer, on TV and "
"thought she was a bit hysterical but sincere, prompting him to seek her out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1006
#: sentence:3837
msgid ""
"They managed to acquire front-row tickets for one of her events in New York "
"and were captivated at seeing her in action up close. Bill recounts:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3838
msgid "It was a highly charged emotional atmosphere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3839
msgid ""
"At the beginning, Kathryn came out on stage and went through a warm-up "
"period."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3840
msgid ""
"She was really coquettish and, to my mind, inappropriate, especially for her"
" age."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3841
msgid ""
"She wore a white dress and made little jokes, gradually warming up her "
"audience."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3842
msgid "This went on for a while, then gradually something began to happen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3843
msgid "She became more serious and started talking about the power of spirit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3844
msgid "I was aware of the moment when things clicked—changed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3845
msgid "She became quite different, another consciousness had taken over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3846
msgid "That was presumably what she was waiting for."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3847
msgid ""
"It takes enormous courage to get up before thousands of people and wait for "
"that to happen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3848
msgid "When it happened, there was a feeling of authenticity about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3849
msgid ""
"She was no longer this sort of silly, somewhat hysterical woman, but a power"
" and spirit that somehow came through."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3850
msgid ""
"When she started calling out healings in various parts of the audience, "
"people would come down and line up."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3851
msgid "It was amazing; she would just touch people and they would fall over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3852
msgid "This went on for hours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3853
msgid "Time didn’t seem to make any difference."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3854
msgid "None of it seemed contrived; it was all quite startling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3855
msgid ""
"Some of it may have been suggestion, but I don’t think it was all "
"suggestion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3856
msgid ""
"It’s easy to dismiss this kind of thing, but Helen was very moved by it, "
"too."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3857
msgid ""
"Helen even dropped all of her blasé defensiveness, and I was very touched."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3858
msgid "We felt a tremendous spiritual power that was generated somehow."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3859
msgid ""
"Kathryn was acting as a common battery, I guess; she was the focal point of "
"this energy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3860
msgid "It was very, very impressive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1007
#: sentence:3861
msgid ""
"It went on all day, so by the time we left I felt both exhilarated and "
"drained.[112]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1008
#: sentence:3862
msgid ""
"If Bill sought out-of-the-ordinary experiences, the reverse was also true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1008
#: sentence:3863
msgid ""
"Cal Hatcher, Bill’s confidant as the Course was being scribed, recalled an "
"incident. “Father Ben” in this tale was Bill’s graduate student who arranged"
" the first meeting between Helen, Bill, and Ken Wapnick."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3864
msgid ""
"Ben had come up to Columbia and taken his doctorate under Bill in "
"psychology."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3865
msgid "Ben was confessing to Cardinal Cook."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3866
msgid ""
"He was a character to me, and would come up there in his long brown robes "
"with his cross swinging on him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3867
msgid ""
"My office was on the first floor at Columbia Presbyterian [Hospital] and "
"sometimes he’d throw little pebbles at the window to get my attention."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3868
msgid "One day he came by and was throwing pebbles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3869
msgid ""
"There was a little concrete ledge there and an iron fence all around the "
"office building I was in."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3870
msgid ""
"I raised the window and Father Ben was standing out there with these two "
"ladies in habits, nuns."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3871
msgid ""
"He said, “I want you to meet a friend of mine.” I invited them to come in to"
" talk. “We don’t have time,” he said, “but this is Mother Teresa and this is"
" sister So-and-So.” Well, I didn’t know who Mother Teresa was, but my "
"assistant, who was Catholic, said to me, “You dim-witted Protestant, you "
"wouldn’t know anything.” So Mother Teresa was there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3872
msgid ""
"She was short, and so was standing up on the concrete ledge with the other "
"sister."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3873
msgid ""
"We were just talking back and forth, and they were on their way to see Bill "
"and Helen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1009
#: sentence:3874
msgid ""
"The famous Mother Teresa from India was on her way to visit Bill and Helen! "
"[113]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1010
#: sentence:3875
msgid ""
"Bill said that while they were transcribing the Course, he had prayed that "
"he might meet a living teacher, someone who embodied these teachings of "
"love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1010
#: sentence:3876
msgid ""
"He had been “led” to a book about Mother Teresa, and shortly after, "
"circumstances conspired to facilitate a meeting with her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1010
#: sentence:3877
msgid ""
"She was then establishing a branch of her order in the South Bronx, the "
"worst of all crime-ridden poverty areas in New York."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1010
#: sentence:3878
msgid "He was invited to meet her there and of that invitation, Bill said,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3879
msgid ""
"Initially, I felt apprehensive about actually having my prayers answered, "
"since I was not sure that I was up to meeting a living saint."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3880
msgid ""
"However, when this tiny woman graciously met us with palms extended, I felt "
"an almost instantaneous sense of relief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3881
msgid "It seemed as if I had always known her."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3882
msgid ""
"Completely selfless and without pretense, she radiated the joy of total "
"spiritual commitment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3883
msgid ""
"Later, when she turned to me and said, “Doctor, wouldn’t you like to come to"
" India?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3884
msgid ""
"There is so much you could do to help the poor,” I felt an almost "
"irresistible impulse to answer, “Yes!” . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1011
#: sentence:3885
msgid ""
"To me, her life is a demonstration of the importance of total dedication and"
" complete consistency on the spiritual path.[114]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1012
#: sentence:3886
msgid ""
"Later, she came to see Bill and Helen; they visited on more than one "
"occasion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1012
#: sentence:3887
msgid ""
"As Tammy Cohen conducted interviews about Bill and the Course et al. in the "
"mid 1990s, several would begin a sentence with, “Bill was no saint, but . . "
".” and proceed to comment on his gentle ways, his generosity of spirit, or "
"his refusal to indulge in character assassination."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1012
#: sentence:3888
msgid ""
"Those I interviewed or others who knew him in California never included the "
"initial qualifying phrase, but mentioned only his positive traits."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1012
#: sentence:3889
msgid ""
"His westward move proved to be a specific line of demarcation in how most "
"people saw him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1012
#: sentence:3890
msgid ""
"It also marks that time when, perhaps guided by the several meetings he had "
"with Mother Teresa, he lived more and more that “total dedication and "
"complete consistency.” Years later, Roger Walsh commented,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1013
#: sentence:3891
msgid ""
"There will doubtless be mythologies that try to make a saint out of Bill and"
" perhaps other Course founders."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1013
#: sentence:3892
msgid ""
"If we mean by “saint” someone who has resolved all their psychological and "
"spiritual difficulties, then Bill was certainly no saint and never pretended"
" to be."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1013
#: sentence:3893
msgid ""
"However, he was someone who worked as hard as possible to have a full "
"spiritual life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1013
#: sentence:3894
msgid "Perhaps, in the end, that’s a more realistic view of what a saint is."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1013
#: sentence:3895
msgid ""
"But labels aside, Bill was clearly a model of sincerity and integrity, and "
"who can even guess how many millions of people his life will touch?[115]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1014
#: sentence:3896
msgid ""
"Bill’s guidance was as clear about saying no as saying yes. Layle Luckett "
"remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3897
msgid ""
"A great learning for me was in being less directive and less controlling."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3898
msgid "Bill wasn’t a guy you could control."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3899
msgid "We used to go out almost every night."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3900
msgid "He had a very powerful intuition and sometimes he would balk."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3901
msgid "He would open the door and just say no, he wasn’t going."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3902
msgid "We knew not to push."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1015
#: sentence:3903
msgid ""
"For sure, when he said he wouldn’t go, we should have stopped in our tracks,"
" because it would be the worst play you ever saw.[116]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1016
#: sentence:3904
msgid ""
"His close associates knew about his inner inquiry for any decision, large or"
" small."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1016
#: sentence:3905
msgid ""
"When anyone made a request that he felt was not for him, Bill usually "
"modeled the ideal response, simply saying, “No, that doesn’t work for me,” "
"with no need to justify, explain, or make excuses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1016
#: sentence:3906
msgid ""
"He made it clear there was nothing personal in refusing, it was simply his "
"guidance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3907
msgid ""
"Another legendary talent was Bill’s ability to get tickets to any event he "
"chose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3908
msgid ""
"Stories abound about all the times he showed up at an opera, play, or other "
"special event, and someone would always sell or give him a ticket(s)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3909
msgid ""
"Almost everyone who knew him well observed this remarkable skill in "
"action—and it was a very specific action."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3910
msgid ""
"He never had subscriptions to the Metropolitan Opera while he lived in New "
"York but always attended whatever he wanted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3911
msgid ""
"He was likely to note that at 7:12 p.m. it would be time to go to the box "
"office to get tickets."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3912
msgid ""
"He always seemed to have a precise sense about when to go on his ticket-"
"acquiring quest; and he wouldn’t get just any tickets but the ones he "
"preferred."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1017
#: sentence:3913
msgid ""
"As with all of us, the more something happens, the more we trust the process"
" and the more frequently it occurs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1018
#: sentence:3914
msgid ""
"Pat Hopkins recalls a special trip to New York with Bill to visit some of "
"his old haunts:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1019
#: sentence:3915
msgid ""
"The highlight of the trip for both of us, however, was hearing Jessye Norman"
" sing her Metropolitan Opera debut in Berlioz’s Les Troyens."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1019
#: sentence:3916
msgid ""
"Bill worked the magic he was famous for among his friends by somehow "
"managing to obtain center-aisle orchestra seats to a sold-out performance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1019
#: sentence:3917
msgid ""
"No matter how popular the event, or how long he waited to purchase the "
"tickets, I never saw Bill fail to get excellent seats for anything he wanted"
" to hear or see, anytime he wanted to go. It was absolutely amazing!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1019
#: sentence:3918
msgid ""
"He used to tell me it was God’s reward for being willing to help bring the "
"Course though."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1019
#: sentence:3919
msgid ""
"Even though he always laughed when he said this, I’m not at all sure he was "
"joking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3920
msgid ""
"On that particular occasion, we had been sitting in our hotel room reading "
"the morning newspaper when Bill suddenly said, “I think we should go down to"
" Lincoln Center about 2:30 this afternoon and look around.” Not a word was "
"said about opera tickets—we already knew there were none available—and Bill "
"was never one to state the obvious."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3921
msgid ""
"So we had some lunch and went down to Lincoln Center a little before two."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3922
msgid ""
"We strolled around looking at the Chagall murals and some photographs and "
"musical scores on display in the opera hall."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3923
msgid ""
"I didn’t even realize Bill was gone until I turned around at one point to "
"say something to him and saw him walking toward me from across the room."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3924
msgid ""
"He had a gleeful expression on his face and I knew that he had done it "
"again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3925
msgid ""
"Sure enough, in his hand were two center-aisle orchestra tickets for that "
"evening’s performance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3926
msgid "It was a thrilling performance! . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3927
msgid ""
"I remember looking at Bill during a particularly moving aria and realizing "
"we were both in a kind of altered state."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1020
#: sentence:3928
msgid "It was a transcendent, joyful occasion, one I’ll never forget.[117]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1021
#: sentence:3929
msgid "Another example involved Ice Capades tickets."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1021
#: sentence:3930
msgid ""
"Jack Luckett had bought three tickets sometime in advance of a particular "
"performance, only to find they would be out of town."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1021
#: sentence:3931
msgid "He gave them to Bill, who then invited a couple to go with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1021
#: sentence:3932
msgid ""
"As it turned out, another friend was going to be in town at that time and "
"Bill invited him also."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1021
#: sentence:3933
msgid ""
"His initial invitee reminded Bill that he had only three tickets, but he "
"reassured him that was no problem, all four would go. Jack recounts:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3934
msgid "They drove to the sports arena with only three tickets."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3935
msgid ""
"There were thousands of people surrounding this place, and they were walking"
" across the parking lot when a man on a bicycle comes riding toward them, "
"riding through all the people, through all the cars and right up to them. . "
". ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3936
msgid ""
"Bill said, “Do you have a ticket for me?” And the guy answered, “Yes.” Bill "
"asked him how much it was and the man mentioned an amount."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3937
msgid ""
"Bill reached into his side coat pocket and pulled out the money and handed "
"it to him—the exact amount."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3938
msgid ""
"It was not the amount of the ticket, but to the dollar, he had the amount "
"the guy was asking for the ticket."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3939
msgid ""
"As he handed it to him, he said, “Thank you, I was waiting for this,” put "
"the ticket in his pocket, and they went in."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1022
#: sentence:3940
msgid ""
"As it turned out, this fourth seat was very close to where they were sitting"
" in that huge sports arena.[118]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3941
msgid ""
"Though it may sound trivial, the same dynamic applied to parking spaces."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3942
msgid ""
"Ease in finding parking spaces per se is hardly cause for celebration, but "
"the state of mind it reveals is."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3943
msgid ""
"I was with Bill more than once when we needed to find a space in a very "
"crowded area."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3944
msgid ""
"As we approached, I would suggest we start looking and Bill would say, “No, "
"there’ll be a parking space waiting.” One time near a crowded plaza, a "
"vacant spot appeared right across from our destination—it was as if it was "
"invisible to all the others looking for one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3945
msgid ""
"That often occurred for Bill; he was intuitive and open to such things and "
"took great delight in their happening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3946
msgid ""
"Although he knew very well that miracles arise from a miraculous state of "
"mind, he wasn’t always there; he wasn’t constant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1023
#: sentence:3947
msgid "But when he knew he was “on,” it always worked. Hugh remembers,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1024
#: sentence:3948
msgid ""
"And yet he didn’t think he’d led a charmed life or had special powers and "
"was just as aware when things didn’t work out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1024
#: sentence:3949
msgid ""
"It’s not like he thought there was someone making everything smooth for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1024
#: sentence:3950
msgid ""
"He did not subscribe to a race of chosen ones, and the whole subject of "
"manifesting—that somehow our spiritual path gives us powers ordinary mortals"
" don’t have—whereby the Holy Spirit opens personal doors so you get the "
"right job, the right car, money, success, and parking spaces was immensely "
"amusing to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1024
#: sentence:3951
msgid ""
"We shared a tremendous amount of humor about all this . . . and he delighted"
" in talking about it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1024
#: sentence:3952
msgid "It was part of his open-mindedness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1024
#: sentence:3953
msgid ""
"Despite his being somewhat cynical about our personal ability to manipulate "
"the world, he was completely open to psychic phenomena that show the "
"unreality of the world, which is not quite the same thing.[119]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3954
msgid ""
"If intuition worked while he was “on” and not at other times, he was very "
"happy that Helen’s intuition was not always reliable."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3955
msgid ""
"One unusual challenge that weighed on him in his first years away from New "
"York was Helen’s prediction, made around the time ACIM was first published, "
"about when both she and Bill would die; she saw the date on her own "
"tombstone (she was off by a year) and indicated Bill would follow her within"
" a year of her passing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3956
msgid ""
"Since she had died in February 1981, everyone, certainly Bill, felt some "
"apprehension as the anniversary date approached."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3957
msgid ""
"It came and went without incident, and everyone let out a collective sigh of"
" relief; Bill survived Helen by seven and a half years."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3958
msgid ""
"Ken Wapnick has noted she could be notoriously wrong when she had a personal"
" investment in a prediction."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3959
msgid ""
"That was her psychic facility misfiring, rather than the Voice that authored"
" ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1025
#: sentence:3960
msgid ""
"Only with nonspecific, nonpersonal Course material was she always absolutely"
" clear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3961
msgid ""
"Even though Bill had followed his guidance or intuition about moving to "
"Tiburon, that didn’t imply his time there would be the proverbial bed of "
"roses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3962
msgid ""
"It was simply the locale for his next round of inner growth and releasing "
"defenses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3963
msgid ""
"He mused, “I guess too, sometimes, we also really have to go to the ultimate"
" despair in order to break through; at least I do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3964
msgid ""
"It seems to be the way it went, and that may be the only way I can learn."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3965
msgid "I felt I had to struggle with everything, including the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3966
msgid ""
"It was very hard to be on this path without the notion of struggle, which "
"seemed so predominant, but I loosened up a bit.”[120] All learning isn’t "
"difficult or painful of necessity, only resistance makes it seem so."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1026
#: sentence:3967
msgid ""
"Along with the more challenging situations, Bill also had some wonderful, "
"happy times in Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1027
#: sentence:3968
msgid ""
"A friend of mine coined the phrase, “trading up to grace,” to describe the "
"process of relinquishing the ego."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1027
#: sentence:3969
msgid ""
"Bill was increasingly able to set aside the distractions of the world and "
"his own illusions; he moved steadily toward his goal—peace of mind—through "
"each opportunity to let go of fear and, indeed, trade up to grace."
msgstr ""

