#. Paragraph 1150
#: sentence:4102
msgid "Chapter 22"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1151
#: sentence:4103
msgid ""
"In 1982, as Bill recovered from his near-fatal heart episode, his friendship"
" with Pat Hopkins continued to deepen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1151
#: sentence:4104
msgid ""
"Pat remembers from that time, “Sometimes I would join him and Jules for "
"dinner and our conversation would continue through the evening hours."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1151
#: sentence:4105
msgid ""
"It was obvious that our friendship was becoming more intimate, but it did "
"not feel like falling-in-love romance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1151
#: sentence:4106
msgid ""
"Rather, it was more a recognition of something I do not know how to "
"describe, something that gave us both comfort and a deep sense of "
"kinship.”[1]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1152
#: sentence:4107
msgid ""
"I find it fascinating that so many people referred to that feeling with "
"Bill; they variously likened it to a sense of kinship, being part of a "
"family, an indescribable connection, recognizing an old friend or even one’s"
" self, or a feeling of coming Home—nothing words can accurately convey."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1152
#: sentence:4108
msgid ""
"Incidentally, it’s reassuring to know that no matter who you’re with, the "
"feeling of “being included in the family” increases as you practice "
"forgiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1153
#: sentence:4109
msgid "In late spring, Bill suggested they become housemates."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1153
#: sentence:4110
msgid ""
"Pat had a long daily commute to Tiburon from Santa Rosa, her home at the "
"time, and Bill recognized his need for companionship, so for both practical "
"and emotional reasons it seemed a perfect fit."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1153
#: sentence:4111
msgid ""
"From a broader perspective, it was also a perfect opportunity for both of "
"them to continue to acknowledge some unfinished issues and to choose to let "
"them go."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1153
#: sentence:4112
msgid ""
"The Course is crystal clear that the purpose of all relationships is our "
"healing, whether we ever come to that awareness or not, and this one was no "
"exception."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4113
msgid "Pat and Bill had much in common."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4114
msgid ""
"They both loved classical music—Mozart for Bill and a more balanced "
"repertoire for Pat—and it was the centerpiece of their respective lives, "
"second in importance only to their spiritual practice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4115
msgid ""
"Both were also very bright, intellectually gifted, and loved reading and "
"discussing what they read, including much mystical and spiritual literature."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4116
msgid ""
"They also shared a common sense of the absurd and had many a good laugh over"
" the local “soap operas” within their community."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4117
msgid ""
"As a primary focus from 1982–1985, Bill, Pat, and Jerry spent a great deal "
"of time together writing Good-bye to Guilt, attending the daily 9 a.m. "
"meetings, interacting with their friends whose common bond was the Course, "
"and attending to the business of the Center for Attitudinal Healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4118
msgid "All three were on its board of directors."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4119
msgid ""
"During times when not serving on the board, Pat was a consultant to the "
"center and later a temporary acting director."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1154
#: sentence:4120
msgid ""
"She also helped Jerry establish an ancillary organization, the Foundation "
"for Spiritual Alternatives, so as she said, she was the “ham in the "
"Bill/Jerry sandwich.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1155
#: sentence:4121
msgid ""
"In preparation for moving in together, Bill had opened a box of memorabilia "
"and, with some resistance, looked through it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4122
msgid ""
"I found samples of absolutely everything, like reprints of old papers going "
"back over thirty years and a report I had written when I was studying "
"brainwashing. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4123
msgid ""
"I also found a certificate that the War Department presented to me for my "
"work on the atomic bomb, as well as some scattered personal notes from the "
"Course that Helen and I had taken out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4124
msgid ""
"There were also some old birthday cards that Helen had written and pictures "
"of both my parents."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4125
msgid ""
"It was a review of “This Is Your Life” going back to the middle 1940s, all "
"jammed in a box."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4126
msgid "I found my reaction very strange."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4127
msgid "I was sad and obviously had resistance to looking."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4128
msgid "I threw out a lot of it in preparation for the move."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4129
msgid ""
"So in cleaning house, I reviewed all the madness that one accumulates. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1156
#: sentence:4130
msgid ""
"House cleaning is good, but I have the feeling that there is something that "
"I don’t want to look at or something is missing.[2]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4131
msgid ""
"In his relationship with Pat, Bill would continue that housecleaning, moving"
" yet another step toward his liberation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4132
msgid ""
"Despite all they had in common and their great admiration for one another, "
"Pat indicated that “nevertheless, living together did not always go smoothly"
" for us” and that their time together was “the best of times and the worst "
"of times, to quote Dickens.”[3] This is exactly what one might expect from a"
" relationship so important to their mutual growth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4133
msgid ""
"I’ve always thought we learn our lessons with our closest friends, who agree"
" at some level to be the mirror to our own fears, though at the time it can "
"feel decidedly unfriendly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4134
msgid ""
"The people we live with provide the setup for deep and essential work, if we"
" choose."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4135
msgid ""
"Bill followed his own unique path to waking up as he built and maintained "
"various relationships throughout his life that delivered exactly what he was"
" willing to deal with at any given moment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4136
msgid ""
"The introduction to the Course text says, “Free will does not mean that you "
"can establish the curriculum."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4137
msgid ""
"It means only that you can elect what you want to take at a given time.”[4] "
"We do have to unlearn our fear and guilt."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4138
msgid ""
"We can drag our feet or dedicate ourselves in a cooperative manner to "
"discovering those beliefs masking as truths."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4139
msgid ""
"Clearly, Bill and Pat’s relationship had the same purpose: mutual healing, "
"regardless of whatever reasons or needs seemed to draw them together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4140
msgid ""
"Bob Howe recalled, “I remember sitting down there in his condominium when "
"Pat was living with him and they were arguing about which way the toilet "
"paper should be on the holder. And the paper towels."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4141
msgid ""
"Each one had their own inner secrecy and you kinda knew they had their own "
"thoughts, their own way of doing what they wanted to do, and how they wanted"
" to do it.”[5] They were perfect companions for the work at hand, and their "
"time together was an essential part of his curriculum (and hers), a "
"releasing, clearing, and burning away of old grievances and outworn beliefs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1157
#: sentence:4142
msgid "Regarding that curriculum, Pat reminisces:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1158
#: sentence:4143
msgid ""
"As the surviving co-scribe of the Course, I believe Bill felt an enormous "
"responsibility, I would almost call it a burden, to be both modest, which "
"was his nature, and to do everything he could to live and exemplify it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1158
#: sentence:4144
msgid ""
"I still feel that Bill felt very strongly that he was holding the iconic, "
"the symbolic, essence of the Course after Helen died."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1158
#: sentence:4145
msgid ""
"While he did extraordinarily well with not being inflated by those "
"projections, I think he still felt them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1158
#: sentence:4146
msgid ""
"At times, I felt this cost him enormously in terms of his own personal life;"
" he was very divided between a fulfilled personal life and what he felt he "
"needed to be for the Course, putting certain constraints on our "
"relationship, as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1159
#: sentence:4147
msgid ""
"It is hard to know, however, whether this sense of constraint I felt came "
"solely from Bill’s desire not to compromise the Course in any way, or from "
"the guardedness he felt compelled to maintain most of his life about his "
"homosexuality.[6]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1160
#: sentence:4148
msgid ""
"I believe that beyond guardedness about being gay and resistance to the "
"iconic role he felt he should fill, Bill simply had an internal sense of "
"constraint from birth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1160
#: sentence:4149
msgid ""
"Jaison Kayn picked up on that when he visited Pat and Bill shortly after "
"they had moved in together:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4150
msgid ""
"The only time I ever saw Bill a little nonplussed was when I went to see "
"them just after they started living together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4151
msgid ""
"Pat and Bill were standing in the kitchen of his apartment and I was close "
"by in the adjacent dining nook."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4152
msgid "All of a sudden the room was filled with soft rose-pink energy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4153
msgid ""
"I saw it everywhere and felt it inside myself, as well. It was astounding!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4154
msgid ""
"Fortunately, I had had an experience of this just the week before and knew "
"what it meant."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4155
msgid "It was the presence of love urging us to open to expansion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4156
msgid ""
"Before I could stop myself, I felt the energy move me into the room and open"
" my mouth."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4157
msgid ""
"I started telling Bill to trust getting closer to Pat, which for me "
"was—well, I never say things like that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4158
msgid ""
"I could feel this sweet rose-energy presence saying to them, “You have "
"something important to do together.” Bill was clearly nervous and upset."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4159
msgid ""
"I think he felt inadequate and overwhelmed, but I could tell that he knew he"
" was being given a gift he could trust."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4160
msgid "It was about their hearts joining."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4161
msgid ""
"It was clear that their hearts were on the verge of joining into some "
"remarkable commitment that neither of them had experienced before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4162
msgid ""
"I don’t know if he saw the energy, too, but I certainly felt it and Pat "
"seemed grateful because she knew."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4163
msgid "Her heart was ready to give him whatever she possibly could."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1161
#: sentence:4164
msgid ""
"For Bill, it was like asking a person to step off the curb blindly, knowing "
"that rush-hour traffic was about to begin, yet also knowing the danger he "
"felt was his own fear and that he would somehow be okay.[7]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1162
#: sentence:4165
msgid ""
"Robert Rosenthal speaks for many in seeing their relationship as imperative "
"to Bill’s stepping forward."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1163
#: sentence:4166
msgid ""
"I think when Pat Hopkins moved in with him, that was Bill’s attempt, at a "
"deep psychological and even psycho-spiritual level, to move through his "
"grief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1163
#: sentence:4167
msgid ""
"And maybe not just the grief from Helen, though that was the most "
"significant, but a deeper, lifetimes-long grief. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1164
#: sentence:4168
msgid ""
"I think that he and Pat had an old connection, that they had agreed to come "
"together at that time so she could help him get through his fear and grief."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1164
#: sentence:4169
msgid ""
"Bill was the happiest I had ever seen him with Pat, at least in the "
"beginning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1164
#: sentence:4170
msgid ""
"I believe their relationship allowed him to move beyond his unfulfilled "
"expectations about Helen.[8]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4171
msgid ""
"As an interesting aspect of Bill’s multitasking talents, or perhaps of his "
"“don’t fence me in” proclivity, Bill established new, significant "
"relationships and maintained others while he and Pat lived together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4172
msgid ""
"About the time Bill and Pat were becoming better acquainted, he met "
"Carlagaye Olson."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4173
msgid ""
"They became close friends and their Thursday “play-days” with Jules were "
"noted earlier in terms of the healing Bill often seemed to precipitate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4174
msgid ""
"Bill and Carlagaye occasionally got together on weekends, when her husband "
"Steve also joined them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4175
msgid ""
"When Catherine Prescott moved to town in 1984, she and Bill also became very"
" close."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4176
msgid ""
"At first, he saw her regularly in her professional therapeutic role, but "
"that ultimately morphed into a more personal relationship, as well."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1165
#: sentence:4177
msgid ""
"Bill’s other meaningful relationships created a win/win situation, as Pat "
"also cherished having her own space."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1166
#: sentence:4178
msgid ""
"Those of us from out of town also maintained our friendships with Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1166
#: sentence:4179
msgid ""
"He and I got together on my visits to Tiburon as well as periodically "
"talking on the phone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1166
#: sentence:4180
msgid ""
"His original core group in Tiburon remained central to his life in "
"California, and his capacity to genuinely care for many individuals at the "
"same time was very deep and remained to the end of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1166
#: sentence:4181
msgid ""
"Bill could be with a person, in love, rather than being “in love” with a "
"person, and each relationship seemed to foster another important aspect of "
"his self-discovery."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4182
msgid ""
"As Pat and Bill began their fourth year sharing an apartment, both were "
"often gone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4183
msgid ""
"In 1985, Pat started traveling to do research for the book she co-authored "
"with Sherry Anderson, The Feminine Face of God, and ultimately moved into "
"her own apartment in January 1986.[9] Bill was spending perhaps a third of "
"his time in La Jolla, visiting there from 1982–1986 on an increasingly "
"regular basis."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4184
msgid ""
"Several months after they moved in together, Bill and Pat had gone to La "
"Jolla, and after that Bill made extended visits, sometimes with Pat and "
"sometimes alone."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4185
msgid ""
"They had discovered a quiet, well-run motel, and either he or they stayed in"
" the same room on each trip."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4186
msgid ""
"He loved the greater ease of the southern California lifestyle and "
"established a pattern of going there for at least three weeks, then "
"returning to Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4187
msgid ""
"After several weeks, he started to feel a bit lonely and less energized, so "
"he would head back south."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4188
msgid ""
"He talked about vacillating between Tiburon and La Jolla, or more "
"humorously, teetering away from Tiburon and leaning toward La Jolla."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4189
msgid "Clearly, something was drawing him there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1167
#: sentence:4190
msgid ""
"It would be the last venue for his healing, representing a major "
"breakthrough—an outward sign of another significant step in his evolution."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1168
#: sentence:4191
msgid ""
"Robert Rosenthal recalled, “I think the next important transition for Bill "
"was when it became clear that the relationship with Pat was not going to "
"work out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1168
#: sentence:4192
msgid ""
"From the way I understood it, Bill really wasn’t capable of a full sexual "
"relationship with a woman."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1168
#: sentence:4193
msgid ""
"And so the relationship, as close as it was, was always left incomplete—a "
"halfway relationship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1168
#: sentence:4194
msgid ""
"Celibacy may have worked okay for him, but probably not for her.”[10] From "
"Pat’s perspective on their time together, “We were like family, but not "
"sisterly-brotherly, and we were partners, but not in the traditional sense "
"of the word."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1168
#: sentence:4195
msgid ""
"To this day, I don’t know how to describe our relationship.”[11] She also "
"told me, “I know it was hugely and immensely important; I would say that "
"both our lives were significantly enriched, but I couldn’t give "
"specifics.”[12]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1169
#: sentence:4196
msgid ""
"Hugh remembers getting together with them after they stopped being "
"housemates:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1170
#: sentence:4197
msgid ""
"Well, he saw the humor in it [their learning experiences] and at the same "
"time I think it [times of not getting along] was distressing to him, but he "
"didn’t hang on to it. Neither of them did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1170
#: sentence:4198
msgid "They had been very close friends and became very close friends again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1170
#: sentence:4199
msgid ""
"They would tell many funny stories about what had happened when they were "
"together and what went on in that apartment; it was just a riot![13]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1171
#: sentence:4200
msgid "He also observed, as Bill was vacillating about his move,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1172
#: sentence:4201
msgid ""
"He was several years making that decision [to go to La Jolla], which was a "
"very deep one."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1172
#: sentence:4202
msgid ""
"It was on his mind for a long time, and I’m certain that at that point he "
"saw his own ego clearly, which was sort of the eastern, sophisticated, New "
"York professor, classical music, classical education- type thing, which he "
"shared with everyone else he was surrounded by there, with the exception of "
"Jerry. [Jerry was California born and bred and attended medical school at "
"Stanford.] But Pat, Jules, Frances, Roger, and Judy shared his same "
"worldview."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1172
#: sentence:4203
msgid "That was the unconscious part of Bill’s ego in the beginning."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1172
#: sentence:4204
msgid ""
"In other words, he just presumed everyone would love Mozart and opera; that "
"was a given or a fact."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1172
#: sentence:4205
msgid ""
"His whole personality, that whole eastern thing, was quite unlike this "
"lighthearted self."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1173
#: sentence:4206
msgid ""
"My understanding in conversations, and from my own observation, was that he "
"saw that in order to let go of his ego he was going to have to turn it "
"upside down."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1173
#: sentence:4207
msgid "He would have to stand it on its head."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1173
#: sentence:4208
msgid ""
"He was going to have to get out of this situation and put himself in a "
"completely different, nonintellectual environment, which he did."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1173
#: sentence:4209
msgid ""
"He had a tremendous capacity for acceptance and was able to accept and enjoy"
" it immensely; that’s when his ego dissolved at a remarkably fast rate.[14]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1174
#: sentence:4210
msgid ""
"Gayle Prather additionally noted: “He did agonize over that decision to move"
" to southern California."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1174
#: sentence:4211
msgid ""
"I guess it was because, basically, he really was going to be saying good-bye"
" to his past because everybody, despite how he or she may or may not have "
"felt about it, deferred to Bill as the patriarch."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1174
#: sentence:4212
msgid ""
"He was the head of the family, and I don’t think he could shake that role as"
" long as he was in Tiburon.”[15]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1175
#: sentence:4213
msgid "Bill and Judy - ACIM 10th anniversary 1986"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4214
msgid "Bill’s situation was transparent to everyone watching him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4215
msgid ""
"Many echoed Hugh’s and Gayle’s comments, recognizing the heavy intellectual "
"emphasis in Tiburon, his attempts to escape it, and his inability to take "
"his next step until he was out of that environment entirely."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4216
msgid ""
"In his own way, he was dissociating himself from normal rules of behavior, "
"of self- and other kinds of evaluation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4217
msgid ""
"He had told his stories long enough and had chosen not to pursue a more "
"public or authoritative role with the Course, nor a more conventional, "
"professional career."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4218
msgid "In terms of an outward focus, he had done what he came to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4219
msgid ""
"Also, Roger Walsh felt that part of the pull to La Jolla was to be with "
"people, primarily the Lucketts, who solely devoted themselves to practicing "
"ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1176
#: sentence:4220
msgid ""
"Although his Tiburon friends were all Course students, they had divided "
"loyalties, including careers, organizations, family responsibilities, or "
"other worldly matters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1177
#: sentence:4221
msgid "Chapter 23"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1178
#: sentence:4222
msgid "In October 1986, Bill moved permanently to La Jolla."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1178
#: sentence:4223
msgid ""
"He had released much in Tiburon and done a marvelous job, as Frances Vaughan"
" stated earlier, of learning to “take up no space,” inserting virtually no "
"“personality noise.” However, not wanting to be egocentric can sometimes be "
"a cover for emotional repression; he retained some old inhibitions and "
"defense patterns when it came to self-expression."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1178
#: sentence:4224
msgid ""
"La Jolla was about sorting this out so he could more easily express his "
"loving, gracious energy without reservation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1178
#: sentence:4225
msgid ""
"He knew, as did those close to him, that the healing uniquely possible "
"through his friends in southern California would be the major focus of the "
"rest of his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1178
#: sentence:4226
msgid "Forgiveness was still “job one.”"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1179
#: sentence:4227
msgid ""
"Bill’s companions—better called playmates—for “letting go on the fast track”"
" were his close friends, Jack and Layle Luckett, whom he had been visiting "
"since the early 1980s."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1179
#: sentence:4228
msgid ""
"They met in Tiburon in 1978, when Jack was director of the Center for "
"Attitudinal Healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1179
#: sentence:4229
msgid ""
"After a short while, the couple felt drawn to the San Diego area and "
"relocated there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1179
#: sentence:4230
msgid ""
"The Lucketts served as Bill’s gateway to the joyous part of himself, because"
" they were certifiably the most lighthearted of his companions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1179
#: sentence:4231
msgid ""
"The label applied to them was “wild and carefree,” and almost literally arm "
"in arm, the three of them traveled the last part of Bill’s path together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1180
#: sentence:4232
msgid "Wild and carefree?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1180
#: sentence:4233
msgid ""
"Here was a couple with unlikely credentials for being Bill’s playmates."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1180
#: sentence:4234
msgid ""
"When they met Bill, Layle was teaching MBA students in San Francisco and "
"working on her Ph.D.; Jack was a retired Marine colonel, also retired from "
"careers as a criminal lawyer and assistant district attorney in Los Angeles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1180
#: sentence:4235
msgid "They were devoted ACIM students and loved music and the theater."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1180
#: sentence:4236
msgid ""
"Who could be more suited to assist Bill move from an academic/intellectual "
"orientation to its opposite end of the spectrum than ones who had already "
"done so themselves?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1181
#: sentence:4237
msgid ""
"If San Diego was as far from New York as one can get in this country, so was"
" life under the Lucketts’ tutelage."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1181
#: sentence:4238
msgid ""
"They were the perfect catalysts for Bill in tying up loose ends, moving "
"toward greater openness and freedom, and releasing what yet weighed him "
"down."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1181
#: sentence:4239
msgid ""
"He relaxed and enjoyed life in La Jolla, loved the lighter atmosphere and "
"just being a regular member of the “Garden,” the Lucketts’ ACIM group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1181
#: sentence:4240
msgid ""
"A local friend found a condo for him, and Jules and Carlagaye moved his "
"possessions and set things up there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1181
#: sentence:4241
msgid ""
"His friends carefully watched his comings and goings to La Jolla, weighing "
"in with observations about what would be his last and final move, and "
"unanimously approving it, as if anyone else’s opinion mattered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1181
#: sentence:4242
msgid "Bill was following his famous right-on intuition."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1182
#: sentence:4243
msgid "Pat’s observation echoed those opinions:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1183
#: sentence:4244
msgid ""
"What I did feel was that he was reliving the childhood he hadn’t been able "
"to have."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1183
#: sentence:4245
msgid ""
"I thought that was terrific—doing such goofy and uncharacteristic things "
"that he wouldn’t have been able to do in the Bay area because of inhibition "
"and projections, too many roles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1183
#: sentence:4246
msgid ""
"The Lucketts were such a wild and carefree couple; they were fabulous for "
"him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1183
#: sentence:4247
msgid ""
"I think his homosexuality had much more spaciousness there, going to places "
"where I think he felt in the company of his own.[16]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1184
#: sentence:4248
msgid ""
"The “company of his own” referred not only to the myriad new friends and "
"acquaintances from dozens of ACIM groups, but to the gay community there and"
" its much more open atmosphere. Jack commented:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4249
msgid ""
"We always had a strong gay contingent in our groups and we took Bill to many"
" ACIM/gay meetings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4250
msgid "We also observed him with his own gay friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4251
msgid ""
"As you know, Bill possessed a quiet but intense magnetism that impressed and"
" attracted women as well as men."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4252
msgid "He was uniformly cordial and warm to men, women, straight, or gay."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4253
msgid "He was not at ease with children or loudmouths."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4254
msgid ""
"He was a celebrity in the gay male community, because of what he had "
"accomplished in life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4255
msgid ""
"He did not try to impress or boast regardless of who he was introduced to."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4256
msgid "That was part of his unique charm."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4257
msgid ""
"When we were with Bill and a male friend on a date, going to the theatre, "
"the circus, or dinner, he was always very attentive and super concerned that"
" his escort was treated well and had a good time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4258
msgid ""
"Bill had many gay friends but few, what we would call today, close "
"relationships."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4259
msgid ""
"His past lovers as well as casual friends were loyal and respectful right to"
" the end."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1185
#: sentence:4260
msgid "How lucky we all were to share part of the life of a real avatar.[17]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1186
#: sentence:4261
msgid ""
"Because it is unusual, a number of others also mentioned that Bill remained "
"friends with and was revered by past lovers and intimate associates."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1186
#: sentence:4262
msgid ""
"It’s almost as if he lived parallel lives—his straight life and his gay "
"one—with very little overlap."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1186
#: sentence:4263
msgid ""
"He was known to have a dozen or so gay friends in La Jolla with whom he "
"spent more time, but no one knows any names or details."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1186
#: sentence:4264
msgid ""
"Judy remembers that he never hid his homosexuality from any of her family "
"nor from Helen’s, but publicly he was very discreet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1187
#: sentence:4265
msgid ""
"Long before Bill moved to La Jolla permanently, he attended ACIM groups "
"there, both the Lucketts’ and several others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1187
#: sentence:4266
msgid "At first, Bill didn’t actively share, but gradually he joined in."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1187
#: sentence:4267
msgid ""
"Even though he had been mostly an observer in many activities throughout his"
" life, here he really started to play and participate, and he got such a "
"kick out of it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1187
#: sentence:4268
msgid ""
"Some members of the Garden group were dancers, and they finally persuaded "
"him to join in the dancing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1187
#: sentence:4269
msgid ""
"He had danced some in his youth but not often as an adult, and then only "
"under very private circumstances with very close friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1188
#: sentence:4270
msgid ""
"Jack forbade attendees to ask Bill anything about the scribing the Course, "
"as that trapped him in his past, but they could ask him anything about his "
"current life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1188
#: sentence:4271
msgid ""
"Treating him like anyone else was a stretch for everyone; however, when Jack"
" set those limits, Bill relaxed and became increasingly available and "
"confident."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1188
#: sentence:4272
msgid ""
"In addition to dancers, there were a number of singers in the group and that"
" encouraged him to experiment both with reading and later singing Course "
"selections. According to Jack,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4273
msgid ""
"When he started reading the Course in the first person, everyone else was "
"freed up to do it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4274
msgid ""
"He started singing the Course and that just broke a dam; it was a very big "
"moment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4275
msgid "He really joined the group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4276
msgid "People realized they could just walk up and hug him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4277
msgid "He was no longer just a quiet figure that had all the authority."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4278
msgid "He was Billy, nobody special, a member of the group."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4279
msgid ""
"He still had the authority, but it was more accessible; he was just one of "
"us and that is what he wanted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4280
msgid "He did not want to be above or below, in front of or behind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4281
msgid "It was, I think, a major healing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1189
#: sentence:4282
msgid ""
"There was a very playful little kid in there, one who hadn’t played, and "
"this part of him had a chance to come out in a safe space.[18]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1190
#: sentence:4283
msgid ""
"Bill learned more about how to express his perspectives on everything; for "
"him, all subjects offered something lovely."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1190
#: sentence:4284
msgid ""
"Friends in Tiburon and beyond, who kept a watchful eye, noticed his gradual "
"but steady unburdening."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1190
#: sentence:4285
msgid "What a treat for those who participated in Bill’s unfolding!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1190
#: sentence:4286
msgid ""
"One fortunate Garden participant, Jim Jeffries, remembered Bill’s "
"generosity, recounting that on one occasion Bill unexpectedly pressed "
"something into his hand as the meeting concluded and said, “The Holy Spirit "
"directed me to give this to you.” When Jim got in his car, he looked and "
"there was a fifty-dollar bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1190
#: sentence:4287
msgid ""
"From then on, Jim called him “Fifty-Dollar Bill,” delighting him with the "
"pun."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1191
#: sentence:4288
msgid ""
"Sometimes disagreements arose about what a passage meant and Bill would not "
"join those debates."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1191
#: sentence:4289
msgid ""
"Jack remembers, “So as a being of pure love, which is really what he was, . "
". . he did not feel that he had to tell other people how, because he knew "
"they needed to do it in their own way and not to rely on others."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1191
#: sentence:4290
msgid ""
"He never took on the teacher/guru role, but was always in a supportive role."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1191
#: sentence:4291
msgid ""
"He supported everyone . . . and he was never threatening—never, never, "
"never.”[19]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1192
#: sentence:4292
msgid ""
"One particular incident about Bill’s giving advice, however, has literally "
"traveled around the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1192
#: sentence:4293
msgid ""
"I have heard this story retold in a number of ways, and it has also returned"
" to Jack and Layle in somewhat altered form."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1192
#: sentence:4294
msgid "Here is the actual eyewitness account."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4295
msgid ""
"We had a friend, Wayne Germaine, a very sweet person, who moderated a small "
"ACIM beginner’s group—maybe a half dozen people—at his home on Tuesday "
"nights."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4296
msgid ""
"Bill would go to that meeting, I think to support Wayne, although, oddly "
"enough, there were many meetings he wouldn’t touch with a ten-foot pole."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4297
msgid "He wouldn’t moderate, wouldn’t say a word."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4298
msgid ""
"Wayne told Bill, in a conversation away from the meeting and in a totally "
"different social context, “I don’t know how to handle this situation."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4299
msgid ""
"It’s come up two or three times and it’s baffling me. [This incident "
"occurred at one of the few meetings Bill had missed.] Somebody will say "
"something about the Course and then someone will say something that’s the "
"opposite, and then they will start arguing and I’m not supposed to correct "
"my brother."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4300
msgid ""
"I don’t want to have fights in my group, but I don’t know how to handle "
"these aggressive people who are arguing about the meaning of the Course.” "
"Bill simply looked at him and said, “Tell them to tear out the page."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1193
#: sentence:4301
msgid "There is nothing in this world worth arguing over.”[20]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1194
#: sentence:4302
msgid ""
"Quite a statement from a man who had argued with Helen so vehemently for so "
"many years! Layle continued,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1195
#: sentence:4303
msgid ""
"We started laughing when this issue came up because we knew one of the guys "
"[provoking the argument]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1195
#: sentence:4304
msgid ""
"We didn’t know the new person, but the other one was a regular in our group,"
" a person who was extremely adamant about his position and how something had"
" to be done."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1195
#: sentence:4305
msgid ""
"Bill and Jack and I knew him very well, and Bill was howling because he knew"
" this guy would get into an argument with somebody instantly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1195
#: sentence:4306
msgid ""
"This was after maybe six years of our facilitating meetings every day, so we"
" knew how to cope with this, but it caught Wayne unaware."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1195
#: sentence:4307
msgid ""
"It was Wayne’s sweetness to admit, in the first place, that he just couldn’t"
" cope with the argument, and Bill’s answer was absolutely priceless."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1195
#: sentence:4308
msgid "It came out so quickly with no forethought whatsoever.[21]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1196
#: sentence:4309
msgid ""
"This story has captured people’s imagination, as this King Solomon-type "
"wisdom was so typical of Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1196
#: sentence:4310
msgid ""
"His message was to follow the Course, don’t put it on a pedestal, and don’t "
"deify it or make it a holy text."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1196
#: sentence:4311
msgid ""
"He did not rigidly worship the literal meaning of ACIM, although he "
"understood it profoundly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1196
#: sentence:4312
msgid ""
"Speaking of the worshipping issue, Jack recalls a time when a short person "
"used the text for a footstool."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1196
#: sentence:4313
msgid ""
"Some visiting students of another ACIM teacher were distressed at what they "
"considered a lack of respect for the sacred book."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1196
#: sentence:4314
msgid ""
"All teachers have their own style, which is perfect for their students, but "
"the style in La Jolla’s Garden group was definitely not to worship the "
"Course, but to steadily practice its teachings."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1197
#: sentence:4315
msgid ""
"A rumor circulated during Bill’s early time in La Jolla that reinforced the "
"Lucketts’ “wild and carefree” reputation; it held that he attended nude ACIM"
" meetings at their home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1197
#: sentence:4316
msgid ""
"This was an exaggeration as there never were nude meetings in the Garden "
"groups, so named because they took place in the enclosed back patio of the "
"Lucketts’ beach cottage, which was made of concrete and often very warm. "
"Jack recounts,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4317
msgid ""
"We were right across the street from the beach, so many students swam before"
" or after the meetings and wore bathing suits during our two- to three-hour "
"meetings. They were sunbathing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4318
msgid ""
"A major issue arose when a couple of the younger women wanted to remove "
"their bra tops to get an even suntan."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4319
msgid "Older members objected because it would be undignified."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4320
msgid ""
"I stopped the action, we held hands in a circle, asking the Holy Spirit to "
"guide us, and after fifteen minutes of meditation, addressed the issue "
"specifically in ACIM terms."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4321
msgid ""
"We had a great discussion covering ego, judgment, fear, true vision, equal "
"treatment of both sexes, and our true nature."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4322
msgid ""
"At the end of that discussion, a young lady said, “If ‘I am not a body."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4323
msgid ""
"I am free’ [one of the workbook lessons], what can a mere strip of cloth "
"mean to me?” We then took a vote and decided that if, in the privacy of our "
"meetings, any woman wished to be topless like the men, she could, but it was"
" not required."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1198
#: sentence:4324
msgid ""
"This went on for a while—some did, some didn’t—it actually wasn’t a big "
"deal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1199
#: sentence:4325
msgid ""
"Some of the 60,000 attendees that came to teach us [the Course states that "
"we are all teachers to one another] were lawyers, doctors, ordained "
"ministers, Catholic priests and nuns, La Jolla matrons, university "
"professors, nurses, teachers, businessmen, airline pilots, military—both "
"active duty and retired—the luminaries of ACIM except for Helen, working "
"people and retired ones, people living in their cars, and patients sent by "
"psychologists."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1199
#: sentence:4326
msgid ""
"Out of this stimulating mix, no one ever questioned the early days’ practice"
" of some girls going topless."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1199
#: sentence:4327
msgid ""
"In the 2,160 consecutive meetings with thousands of participants, not "
"allowing smoking was a much larger issue.[22]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1200
#: sentence:4328
msgid ""
"Although the truth is not as exotic as the fiction about the Garden groups, "
"the meetings certainly were a vast leap from his days at Columbia and a "
"marvelous opportunity to be part of the Course’s influence as it spread "
"across the country and throughout the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1200
#: sentence:4329
msgid ""
"In addition, Bill attended a number of other ACIM groups in the area and "
"made a host of new friends in the process."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1200
#: sentence:4330
msgid ""
"He was presented with other opportunities for friendly outreach beyond the "
"Course community."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1200
#: sentence:4331
msgid ""
"How could it be otherwise with Jack and Layle as guides? They took him "
"everywhere."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1200
#: sentence:4332
msgid ""
"Almost every night they went to restaurants, movies, dinners, and "
"entertainment of every conceivable kind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1200
#: sentence:4333
msgid "Jack commented on his preferences:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4334
msgid ""
"Bill loved films; he preferred foreign and art films and also liked drama, "
"historical pieces, and adult comedies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4335
msgid ""
"Under no circumstances would he attend sci-fi, action, war, western, or "
"vampire flicks, or stupid comedies."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4336
msgid "His favorite movie was Amadeus, which he viewed several times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4337
msgid "We had season tickets to most live-theater houses."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4338
msgid "Bill liked the theater but had hard and fast rules about going."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4339
msgid ""
"He insisted on an aisle seat and the play had to have an intermission (he "
"opined that having no intermission meant the play was no good and everyone "
"would leave if given a chance)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4340
msgid ""
"In addition to opera and classical concerts, Bill also loved the circus, ice"
" shows, and jazz concerts."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1201
#: sentence:4341
msgid ""
"We all had annual tickets to Sea World and often attended their night "
"spectacles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1202
#: sentence:4342
msgid "As you know, Bill was very well read."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1202
#: sentence:4343
msgid ""
"During our time together he read the New York Times front to back, but he "
"was done with his book and magazine reading."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1202
#: sentence:4344
msgid ""
"We lived very close to the La Jolla library (Layle and I always had books "
"out) and had several excellent bookstores nearby, but Bill wasn’t "
"interested."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1202
#: sentence:4345
msgid "He read the Course daily, usually with me, and that was it.[23]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1203
#: sentence:4346
msgid ""
"They soon realized that Bill was not used to interacting with others in a "
"restaurant, despite all his years of eating out. (Regarding food "
"preferences, Bill would eat anything; no special diets for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1203
#: sentence:4347
msgid ""
"His colleagues at Columbia said he routinely ordered cake and ice cream for "
"lunch!) Layle tended to engage with the wait staff, and following her lead, "
"Bill started talking with them more and thoroughly enjoyed becoming "
"acquainted with them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1203
#: sentence:4348
msgid ""
"At his favorite places, the staff began to call him by name, and he would "
"chat away with them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1203
#: sentence:4349
msgid ""
"Pretty soon word went out that he was available for socializing and that the"
" best venue for this was to invite him to breakfast."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1203
#: sentence:4350
msgid ""
"I can personally attest to his greater participation, because my husband and"
" I went many places with him on our last visit to La Jolla, and he was well "
"known at all the restaurants we visited."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1204
#: sentence:4351
msgid ""
"To continue broadening his range of experience, the Lucketts took Bill to a "
"nightclub, where he had never been before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1204
#: sentence:4352
msgid ""
"For most of his life, he might have felt that was somehow beneath him and "
"not necessary for his growth, but by the mid 1980s he was up for anything!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1204
#: sentence:4353
msgid ""
"They also took him to improv places with stand-up comedians. Jack remembers "
"one occasion:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4354
msgid ""
"So here we were sitting in this Improv, talking about ACIM, and the girl who"
" had seated us said that she had been in the Course."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4355
msgid ""
"Two other waitresses came over and one of them was part-time in Hare "
"Krishna, while the other was a born-again Christian. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4356
msgid "Layle was pinning these tiny hearts on people."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4357
msgid "We all came together and I had everyone hold hands."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4358
msgid "This is a nightclub, mind you!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4359
msgid ""
"We all said a prayer, asking that everybody who was going to be on the stage"
" that night would provide healing for everyone in the audience, that they "
"would heal something in us that we didn’t understand or had rejected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4360
msgid "And they all joined in, very willingly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1205
#: sentence:4361
msgid ""
"It was not inappropriate at all, and Bill said, “You know, one of the things"
" I have learned from being with you, Jack, is that the spiritual movement is"
" happening everywhere if you take it with you, if you let the light "
"shine.”[24]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1206
#: sentence:4362
msgid ""
"They also took him to a late-night version of the Rocky Horror Picture Show,"
" where devotees come dressed as the characters."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1206
#: sentence:4363
msgid ""
"Knowing the lines, they stood down in front acting out the parts and the "
"entire audience spoke the words as the movie unfolded."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1206
#: sentence:4364
msgid ""
"Some might call the diehard participants outcasts, certainly not the kind of"
" folks Bill would have encountered in his sophisticated New York or northern"
" California worlds, but here was a place where they could fully join and "
"participate."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1206
#: sentence:4365
msgid ""
"Bill was fascinated; remember he was unused to participating and Layle said "
"they all felt like fifteen again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1206
#: sentence:4366
msgid ""
"Bill just laughed and laughed, having one of the best times of his life. "
"Jack observed,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4367
msgid ""
"He had a marvelously developed sense of humor and the quality I’m certain "
"all masters have, of not being pretentious and of being able to see the "
"beauty in all forms of life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4368
msgid "He could see the kids joining."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4369
msgid ""
"He could see them in costume, letting the other sides of themselves come "
"out."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4370
msgid ""
"He could see all of us laughing together at the silliness of the whole "
"thing. He caught it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4371
msgid ""
"Some people are full of religiosity and they fully approve of everything "
"that seems to fall within their scope of standards, but are certain that "
"anything that falls outside that scope has some evil attached to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4372
msgid "That was not Bill’s way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4373
msgid "His way was to be like Jesus, as I understand Jesus."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1207
#: sentence:4374
msgid "He saw the beauty in all aspects of humanity.[25]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4375
msgid ""
"Another sign of his freedom was when we went to see an ACIM “gardener” [a "
"participant in the ACIM Garden group] in a home-grown play."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4376
msgid ""
"It turned out to be held in the back room of a biker bar with the toughest-"
"looking guys you can imagine!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4377
msgid ""
"Billy just walked through smiling and waving to everyone as if this were his"
" usual routine."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4378
msgid ""
"Also, around Bill’s birthday in 1988, a handsome young sailor came to the "
"Garden."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4379
msgid ""
"They struck up an instant relationship, one so close that Billy actually "
"acceded to driving up to Los Angeles with this guy in his red Jeep just for "
"lunch!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4380
msgid "Can you imagine him so loose?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1208
#: sentence:4381
msgid ""
"This was a big deal; he wanted everyone to see him riding around in a "
"Jeep.[26]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4382
msgid "And the loosening continued."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4383
msgid ""
"Late one night as the three of them were returning from the theater, Bill, "
"out of the blue, started to sing parodies about the Course, changing the "
"lyrics of the first lines of well-known songs."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4384
msgid ""
"Jack also knew a lot of music, so he chimed in immediately with the next "
"line."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4385
msgid ""
"They alternated singing these lines from songs, creating an abbreviated, "
"funny version of the Course history."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4386
msgid ""
"For fifteen minutes, they invented hilarious new words, feeding off each "
"other’s creativity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4387
msgid ""
"Jack said Bill got so tickled and laughed so hard, it was just wonderful, "
"another great release for him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4388
msgid ""
"Bill had made up some musical parodies with Helen in New York, but this was "
"the expanded version and yet another marker of his disappearing barriers and"
" inhibitions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4389
msgid ""
"Jack referred to his time in LaJolla as “an out-reaching, people-oriented, "
"heart-opening experiential phase."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1209
#: sentence:4390
msgid "To his credit he participted with verve and charm.”[27]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4391
msgid ""
"My husband Bob and I saw Bill for the last time on a visit to La Jolla in "
"April 1987."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4392
msgid ""
"For several nonstop days, we attended ACIM Garden meetings with him, a daily"
" routine, and it was great seeing him in his new “natural habitat.” We went "
"to some of his favorite haunts, spent much time at his home, walked through "
"the nearby park, and accompanied him to the first public viewing of the "
"video, The Story of A Course In Miracles; it was scheduled, “by coincidence”"
" for its premiere one evening while we were there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4393
msgid ""
"He was a bit nervous about everyone else watching him on film while he, too,"
" watched but it seemed a relatively minor issue."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4394
msgid ""
"This video documents the history of A Course In Miracles with Bill’s "
"firsthand narration and skillful use of pictures of Helen, including "
"excerpts read from her diaries."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4395
msgid ""
"It was an unexpected treat for Bob and me to observe Bill watching himself "
"on screen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4396
msgid ""
"Afterward, he asked for feedback about several aspects of the production, "
"and we assured him that both the video and his presentation were right on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4397
msgid ""
"It was a delight to be with him as he jumped another hurdle about being "
"publicly noticed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4398
msgid ""
"I thought he had grown so much and was more casual, relaxed, and open than "
"ever before."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4399
msgid "He was more expressive generally and seemed very happy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1210
#: sentence:4400
msgid ""
"In the year following our visit, we spoke periodically on the phone, and I "
"was deeply satisfied to know that all was right with his world and getting "
"better all the time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1211
#: sentence:4401
msgid "Our last time together in La Jolla 1987"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1212
#: sentence:4402
msgid ""
"In April 1988, when asked how he would like to celebrate his upcoming sixty-"
"fifth birthday, Bill replied that he wanted absolutely nothing, no party; he"
" was still a little shy about people focusing attention on him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1212
#: sentence:4403
msgid "The Garden group paid no attention and had one anyway."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1212
#: sentence:4404
msgid ""
"On short notice, word of this momentous birthday celebration spread, and "
"around seventy people bearing covered dishes and cakes decorated all sorts "
"of ways—several sporting the ACIM cover—showed up to honor him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1213
#: sentence:4405
msgid "He received meaningful gifts from the Foundation for Inner Peace."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1213
#: sentence:4406
msgid ""
"Judy Whitson had assembled sections from all the foreign translations then "
"in progress and put them in a black thesis binder identical to those that "
"held the early typescripts of ACIM."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1213
#: sentence:4407
msgid ""
"In addition, Judy created a large scrapbook filled with cards, greetings, "
"and photos from his friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1213
#: sentence:4408
msgid ""
"These displays of affection meant so much to him, and he was touched and "
"thrilled by the scrapbook, also a bit embarrassed and overwhelmed (rather "
"than “underwhelmed” as he liked to joke)."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1214
#: sentence:4409
msgid ""
"Someone suggested that Bill circle the garden and allow each person to "
"express gratitude for his presence and for bringing ACIM into being. Jack "
"reminisced,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1215
#: sentence:4410
msgid ""
"Well, there is no way he would have allowed it before that day, because he "
"would have disappeared."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1215
#: sentence:4411
msgid "He would not have put up with it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1215
#: sentence:4412
msgid ""
"So the first person really poured out his heart, “Billy, thank you for this "
"and this and this.” Billy reached over and just melted him in a hug that "
"lasted for at least a minute, just pulled him into him . . . and held him "
"silently."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1215
#: sentence:4413
msgid ""
"Then he went to the next person, and we spent the day doing this, each "
"person acknowledging him fully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1215
#: sentence:4414
msgid ""
"He put up with it, and he gave a one-minute, or longer, hug to everyone.[28]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1216
#: sentence:4415
msgid ""
"When it was Jack’s turn, he joked with him as was their custom, and put a "
"large crown of blown-up balloons on Bill’s head, calling him the “crown "
"prince” of A Course In Miracles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1216
#: sentence:4416
msgid "Remarkably, he surrendered to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1217
#: sentence:4417
msgid ""
"And so he could accept this rather foolish and bizarre-looking crown, and he"
" laughed, smiled, and said again, “I’m too old not to be flexible,” and that"
" was his great lesson."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1217
#: sentence:4418
msgid ""
"And always the great punster, he often said later, I am, “flexi-Bill.” [That"
" name derived from a song written by Libby McGuire entitled, “Flexi-"
"Billy-T.”] . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1217
#: sentence:4419
msgid ""
"And he later confided that he had had the fullest experience of love, beyond"
" anything he had ever allowed himself with anybody on this planet. He felt "
"completely loved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1217
#: sentence:4420
msgid "He would not have accepted that before this time in his life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1217
#: sentence:4421
msgid "He would not have understood it, . . . but he finally got it.[29]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1218
#: sentence:4422
msgid ""
"65th birthday with gift of ACIM translations from Foundation for Inner Peace"
" 1988"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1219
#: sentence:4423
msgid ""
"In response to Bill’s joyful pronouncement about his flexibility, Whit "
"Whitson wrote,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1220
#: sentence:4424
msgid ""
"I believe he was saying that he had finally torn down the psychological "
"boundaries by which he had defined himself for a lifetime."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1220
#: sentence:4425
msgid ""
"In so doing, he had forgiven himself for all the judgments with which he had"
" imprisoned his closest friends and colleagues in his own perceptions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1220
#: sentence:4426
msgid ""
"It was as if he had finally liberated himself from the crises of his long "
"journey of self-definition. Finally, he was free.[30]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1221
#: sentence:4427
msgid ""
"When I asked Jack about Bill’s evolution once he moved to La Jolla, he "
"replied:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4428
msgid ""
"As far as I could see, Bill had full spiritual depth the day I met him and "
"that did not change."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4429
msgid ""
"His social skills, his relaxing, his ease with others changed considerably, "
"even dramatically, after he moved to San Diego, becoming part and parcel of "
"the wild group we had down there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4430
msgid "He really felt at home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4431
msgid "When he was up in the Bay area, they called him Dr. Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4432
msgid "Who the hell wants to be a Dr. Bill, anyway?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4433
msgid "We stopped that right away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1222
#: sentence:4434
msgid "He was just Bill [or Billy] and a member of the group.[31]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1223
#: sentence:4435
msgid ""
"Secondly, Bill, the human, took the Course, turned his life around, and "
"became the humble, modest, perfect, enlightened teacher of the Course by his"
" conduct, by his being, and by his grace, gentleness, and love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1223
#: sentence:4436
msgid ""
"Even if he had never helped bring us the Course, and I had just met this "
"man, I would still honor his most beautiful life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1223
#: sentence:4437
msgid ""
"And he’s still operating because his energies are still with us, surrounding"
" us.[32]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4438
msgid ""
"While basking in the glow of his newfound freedom and finally allowing "
"himself to be fully loved, remnants of his past tugged at him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4439
msgid ""
"In March 1988, out of the blue, Bill contacted his old friend Jo, his "
"girlfriend from college days, to wish her happy birthday and to invite her "
"out for a birthday dinner."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4440
msgid "She was recently widowed and they rekindled their old friendship."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4441
msgid ""
"They had met only twice since college, once in the late 1970s when Bill was "
"in San Diego, her home at that time, and once when she was in Tiburon about "
"four years later."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4442
msgid ""
"According to Jo, they had a truly marvelous time and got together several "
"times during the following three months."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4443
msgid ""
"In midsummer, with an extended business trip to New Zealand coming up, Jo "
"had to make arrangements for her rental property out in the desert while she"
" was gone; she invited Bill to drive out with her and he happily accepted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1224
#: sentence:4444
msgid ""
"Jo reminisced about all the fun they had had together as pals, before Bill "
"gave her his fraternity pin:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1225
#: sentence:4445
msgid ""
"We used to sit on the bench at his piano, which he could play beautifully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1225
#: sentence:4446
msgid "He could sing beautifully, too. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1225
#: sentence:4447
msgid "We used to sing things like Danny Boy and The Desert Song."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4448
msgid ""
"So it was funny some fifty years later when we were driving up to the desert"
" and he broke out in this song and we sang together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4449
msgid "It was really neat, just like old times, . . . a delightful weekend."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4450
msgid ""
"There was nothing [romantic] between us, yet he seemed so much at home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4451
msgid "It was like he was really at peace with himself. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4452
msgid ""
"So we agreed we were just really great old friends, and I realized at that "
"time, that’s it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4453
msgid ""
"It was kind of interesting because on that trip he gave me a copy of his "
"book, Choose Once Again, and I think there’s a message there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1226
#: sentence:4454
msgid "Like I had to choose once again, somebody, but not him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1227
#: sentence:4455
msgid ""
"But I have to say that even though I’d known Bill since kindergarten, he was"
" still somewhat of an enigma to me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1227
#: sentence:4456
msgid ""
"Yet he really opened up to me, more than ever before, that last time we were"
" together in the desert."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1227
#: sentence:4457
msgid "We were closer than ever before as just good friends."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1228
#: sentence:4458
msgid ""
"The one thing that was interesting, too, and he was almost secretive about "
"this, is that he said, “I’m really going to be more of a risk taker,” "
"although he didn’t explain what that meant. . . . “I’ve got a lot of plans "
"and I’ve made up my mind."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1228
#: sentence:4459
msgid ""
"I think I’ve protected myself too much all my life; I’m going to be more of "
"a risk taker.” That last week he was so relaxed and confident."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1228
#: sentence:4460
msgid ""
"It was like, “I’ve finally arrived and I really have it all together now.” I"
" was really looking forward to seeing him again."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1229
#: sentence:4461
msgid ""
"When we parted [two days later], he told me he was going to try to get to "
"New Zealand while I was there, since I was going to be there a whole year."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1229
#: sentence:4462
msgid ""
"I said, “Great, as soon as I get there and find out what my address is I’ll "
"write you.” [Soon after], I left for New Zealand and he left for San "
"Francisco that same day.[33]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1230
#: sentence:4463
msgid ""
"Jo indicated they each knew, though didn’t say, that this was really the "
"last good-bye."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4464
msgid ""
"By all accounts from many witnesses, by the end of his earthly life Bill had"
" become playful, participating, flexible, light, joyous, and free—aware of "
"his true identity."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4465
msgid ""
"Many people had served him throughout his life as he owned his shadow side, "
"and ownership allowed his fears to fade away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4466
msgid ""
"Much of his humor stemmed from recognizing fear’s lack of substance and the "
"absurdity of taking ourselves so seriously. “This is the way salvation "
"works."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4467
msgid ""
"As you step back, the light in you steps forward and encompasses the world."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4468
msgid "It heralds not the end of sin in punishment and death."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4469
msgid ""
"In lightness and in laughter is sin gone, because its quaint absurdity is "
"seen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1231
#: sentence:4470
msgid ""
"It is a foolish thought, a silly dream, not frightening, ridiculous perhaps,"
" but who would waste an instant in approach to God Himself for such a "
"senseless whim?”[34]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4471
msgid ""
"At long last, Bill became aware that he no longer needed to escape from "
"anyone or anything, but could simply set aside any upset as a nightmare "
"without appeal."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4472
msgid "He chose not to be imprisoned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4473
msgid ""
"In all ways, large and small, his loving presence eclipsed his fearful, "
"self-serving thoughts."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4474
msgid ""
"He reached the point where there was little more for him to say, because "
"knowing was so deeply embedded in his psyche."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4475
msgid ""
"He had allowed grievances and old habit patterns to be dissolved, and now "
"experienced the truth of his being."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4476
msgid "Talk would only trivialize it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4477
msgid ""
"In adopting the goal of a better way to live, he instantly found himself on "
"a path with no exit point, leading straight to the heart of love itself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1232
#: sentence:4478
msgid "What he had admired in Mother Teresa, he had become."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1233
#: sentence:4479
msgid ""
"Now, many years later, with so many sharing their unique perspectives of "
"him, no more hiding is possible."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1233
#: sentence:4480
msgid ""
"The enigmatic, secretive, and compartmentalized Bill finally stands revealed"
" for all to see."
msgstr ""

