#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4520
msgid ""
"On the last weekend Bill and Jo spent together, he had declared his "
"intention to take more risks, expand his reach, and be ever more true to "
"himself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4521
msgid "The time for wearing a mask was over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4522
msgid ""
"My favorite mantra is, “When all else fails, tell the truth,” and Bill now "
"adopted this fully."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4523
msgid ""
"We have been conditioned to do everything else but that, having learned our "
"manipulating and negotiating skills at a very early age."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4524
msgid ""
"As with all of us, Bill’s imprisonment began in childhood; with each "
"grievance he collected, another imaginary bar was installed, creating the "
"subjective experience of an unshared, lonely prison."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4525
msgid ""
"But with each choice to change his mind, a bar vanished, and he felt more "
"powerful, integrated, secure, confident, and able to access his inborn "
"wisdom."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1271
#: sentence:4526
msgid ""
"He was in charge of the prison doors and could use his talents to gain his "
"freedom."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4527
msgid "Abilities must be developed before you can use them."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4528
msgid ""
"This is not true of anything that God created, but it is the kindest "
"solution possible for what you made."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4529
msgid ""
"In an impossible situation, you can develop your abilities to the point "
"where they can get you out of it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4530
msgid ""
"You have a Guide to how to develop them, but you have no commander except "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4531
msgid ""
"This leaves you in charge of the Kingdom, with both a Guide to find it and a"
" means to keep it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4532
msgid ""
"You have a model to follow who will strengthen your command, and never "
"detract from it in any way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1272
#: sentence:4533
msgid ""
"You therefore retain the central place in your imagined enslavement, which "
"in itself demonstrates that you are not enslaved.[1]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1273
#: sentence:4534
msgid "Bill was always forthright about needing help with wanting to forgive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1273
#: sentence:4535
msgid ""
"Lukewarm to the idea at first, he developed a zeal for leaving no grievance "
"unaddressed as the years passed and his understanding grew."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1273
#: sentence:4536
msgid ""
"When he recognized that his own ego thoughts enslaved him, his final biggest"
" “risk” was deciding to let them all go."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1273
#: sentence:4537
msgid ""
"He often said that his major prayer was “Help!” or the expanded version, "
"“Help me do this!” It was no more specific than that, regarding either the "
"subject or object of his prayer."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1273
#: sentence:4538
msgid ""
"The Lucketts said that occasionally, while they shared a home with Bill, "
"they could hear him earnestly praying, “Help me do this!” His deepest desire"
" was to completely forgive everyone and everything."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1273
#: sentence:4539
msgid ""
"In her book, You Are That, the American teacher Gangaji describes what we "
"set in motion with the simple prayer, “Help”:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4540
msgid "Help is here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4541
msgid "You are never separate from help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4542
msgid "Anytime you ask for help, help presents itself."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4543
msgid "It is beautifully humbling to ask for help."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4544
msgid "It is good to give up your idea of independence."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4545
msgid ""
"Just say “Please help,” and you will see instantly that every enlightened "
"being in every realm, known and unknown, from all the dimensions, charted "
"and uncharted, is immediately supporting, helping, reminding, pushing, "
"pulling, embracing, holding, shaking or doing whatever is needed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4546
msgid "Your plea for help cuts through all past arrogance."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1274
#: sentence:4547
msgid ""
"You are helped immediately because you are calling to the truth of "
"yourself.[2]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1275
#: sentence:4548
msgid "A Course In Miracles echoes this:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1276
#: sentence:4549
msgid ""
"Everyone here has entered darkness, yet no one has entered it alone. . . ."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1276
#: sentence:4550
msgid ""
"For he has come with Heaven’s Help within him, ready to lead him out of "
"darkness into light at any time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1276
#: sentence:4551
msgid ""
"The time he chooses can be any time, for help is there, awaiting but his "
"choice."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1276
#: sentence:4552
msgid ""
"And when he chooses to avail himself of what is given him, then will he see "
"each situation that he thought before was means to justify his anger turned "
"to an event which justifies his love."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1276
#: sentence:4553
msgid ""
"He will hear plainly that the calls to war he heard before are really calls "
"to peace.[3]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1277
#: sentence:4554
msgid "Asking for help turns out to be the best insurance policy around!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1278
#: sentence:4555
msgid ""
"In February 1988, Bill experienced some bronchial difficulty, which required"
" postponing a planned trip to Tiburon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1278
#: sentence:4556
msgid ""
"For several years, he had had occasional incidents of atrial fibrillation, "
"an arrhythmia of the heart not uncommon in older people but more dangerous "
"for him, as his heart had been compromised by the rheumatic fever he "
"developed as a child."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1278
#: sentence:4557
msgid ""
"Throughout his adult life he had irregular heartbeat episodes that he "
"basically ignored; he was very casual about body-related issues except for "
"the carotid artery blockage in 1981, which demanded attention and, "
"ultimately, two surgeries."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1278
#: sentence:4558
msgid ""
"Jack noted Bill’s flu-like symptoms and, aware of his chronic heart "
"condition, asked if his affairs were in order and/or if he would like help "
"with his will or other related paperwork."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1278
#: sentence:4559
msgid ""
"Bill thanked him and laughed, reassuring him, “Don’t worry, it’s all done "
"and, by the way, when my time comes, I’m going to Judy."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1278
#: sentence:4560
msgid ""
"Judy’s in charge and will know what to do.” Jack commented about his health:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4561
msgid ""
"After his near fatal heart attack in 1981, Bill was always aware that the "
"angel of death was on his left shoulder."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4562
msgid "He had constant heart fibrillations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4563
msgid ""
"We took him to the emergency room at Scripps Hospital more than once for "
"fibrillations."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4564
msgid "He was having some signs that his work was done."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4565
msgid ""
"He did not make a big thing of this publicly, but he knew his life was in "
"danger at all times."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4566
msgid ""
"This was one reason he asked Layle and me to live with him; he wanted others"
" around if help was needed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1279
#: sentence:4567
msgid ""
"He strove to live fully and experience all he could before he left. He was "
"very brave.[4]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1280
#: sentence:4568
msgid ""
"Although many were completely surprised at Bill’s passing, others were "
"apparently prescient close to the end."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1280
#: sentence:4569
msgid ""
"Driving around a bend in the road (in April, his next-to-last trip to "
"Tiburon), Diane Cirincione was surprised to see Bill standing there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1280
#: sentence:4570
msgid "He smiled, she stopped the car and got out to visit with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1281
#: sentence:4571
msgid ""
"When I first saw him, I had this strange feeling—it was so wonderful to see "
"him there, but in a very special way."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1281
#: sentence:4572
msgid ""
"As I got in the car at the end of our conversation, he leaned through the "
"window and gave me another hug."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1281
#: sentence:4573
msgid ""
"I pulled away slowly, looking in the mirror as he stood there watching the "
"car."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1281
#: sentence:4574
msgid ""
"I was amazed to find myself thinking, very consciously, “If this is the last"
" time I ever see Bill, that will be okay.” I felt so good, totally "
"fulfilled, and when I heard that he had died, that picture of him looking at"
" me through the window, accompanied by that strange thought, immediately "
"flashed through my mind.[5]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1282
#: sentence:4575
msgid ""
"Pat Hopkins also had a very telling dream three weeks before Bill’s passing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1282
#: sentence:4576
msgid ""
"Excerpts cited from that dream reveal the magnitude of Bill’s transformation"
" and the universal availability of that information in the one mind we all "
"share."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4577
msgid ""
"In the dream, his friend, Calvin Hatcher, the only other administrator at "
"Columbia who knew at the time what he and Helen were up to, had taken Bill "
"and me to an opera in New York City."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4578
msgid ""
"For whatever reason, our tickets were split and Bill was sitting two or "
"three rows in front of me; Calvin and Judy were in my row and farther down "
"the line was Frances [Vaughan]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4579
msgid ""
"About the time people would be reading their program notes, some ladies came"
" through; if you were at a ballgame you would say they were hotdog and beer "
"hawkers."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4580
msgid ""
"But these were very straight, ethereal-looking, ballerina-type ladies and "
"they were handing out chocolate sundaes, for which Bill had a particular "
"fondness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4581
msgid ""
"Not only were there chocolate sundaes, but those coffee-crunch things you "
"could put on top, which he also loved."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4582
msgid ""
"I thought this was very strange, but they were very good and I noticed that "
"he was eating his."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4583
msgid ""
"About the time you would expect the overture to begin, Bill stood up from "
"his chair, turned around to face us, and said, “I have come full circle in "
"my life."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4584
msgid ""
"All the things that I didn’t understand, all the things I was afraid to say,"
" I now want to share with you.” He proceeded to give the most exquisite, "
"simple, eloquent speech that moved absolutely everybody."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4585
msgid ""
"Knowing how he hated to speak in public and the anxiety it caused him, the "
"relaxation with which he delivered this truth of his life was an incredible "
"thing to behold."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4586
msgid ""
"When he was finished, Frances, Judy, Calvin, and I looked at each other and "
"said we thought we knew Bill, but this was a totally new dimension of this "
"person that we all loved so much."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4587
msgid ""
"Nobody applauded but when he finished, everybody stood up with tears running"
" down their cheeks."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4588
msgid ""
"The house was filled and people started to gather in small clumps or groups "
"and began to tell each other the truth of their lives with the same utter "
"defenselessness, vulnerability, and trust that he had exhibited when he "
"stood and talked with us."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4589
msgid ""
"I saw Bill beaming down on absolutely everyone at what he had set in motion."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4590
msgid "That was the end of the dream."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4591
msgid "The next morning when I awakened, I was in a joyful state."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4592
msgid ""
"I knew that Bill had come to something in his life that was totally freeing,"
" absolutely new, and the achievement of a lifetime."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4593
msgid ""
"Naturally, my ego got involved and wondered if it was my own projection, so "
"I waited eagerly for his next visit to share the dream with him, to see for "
"myself whether or not it was true."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1283
#: sentence:4594
msgid "As we now know, it was a dream but it was also true.[6]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1284
#: sentence:4595
msgid ""
"Hugh noted that, although he never talked to him about this specifically, he"
" thought Bill understood that the greatest thing we can do for the world is "
"to awaken individually."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1284
#: sentence:4596
msgid ""
"He and Gayle strongly felt he did awaken by the end of his earthly life, and"
" accomplished it in a relatively short period of time. He observed:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1285
#: sentence:4597
msgid ""
"At the end of his life, Bill was going around telling everybody not to take "
"this Course so seriously, not that one doesn’t revere or appreciate it, just"
" don’t make it into such a rigid, deadly thing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1285
#: sentence:4598
msgid ""
"He still had his little soap operas with extensive travel plans on the "
"drawing board, other relationship and living arrangement offers on the "
"table, and then there was the real Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1285
#: sentence:4599
msgid ""
"Toward the end, he got into that wonderful state of mind where he could "
"awaken; you could see it all so clearly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1285
#: sentence:4600
msgid ""
"He was smart enough not to get involved back in the world, a perfect time "
"for him to leave.[7]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1286
#: sentence:4601
msgid ""
"After he passed, I asked Gayle what confirmed for her that he really had "
"awakened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1286
#: sentence:4602
msgid ""
"She answered, “A great burst of joy came to me during his memorial "
"service.”[8]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1287
#: sentence:4603
msgid "Chapter 25"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1288
#: sentence:4604
msgid ""
"As the daily ACIM transcription process stretched into months, then years, "
"Bill and Helen had mused about whether it would ever end, and if so, how "
"they might know that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1288
#: sentence:4605
msgid ""
"At first, they thought it would be only a few pages long, but as it "
"continued to unfold, it became clear it was a much longer work."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1288
#: sentence:4606
msgid ""
"Now, four decades later, we can say offhandedly, “Oh yes, the Course "
"consists of a text, a workbook, and teacher’s manual,” but they had no way "
"of knowing that early on."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1288
#: sentence:4607
msgid ""
"When they inquired, the inner Voice told them they would recognize the end "
"of dictation (of the text) when they heard the word Amen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1288
#: sentence:4608
msgid ""
"I am consistently moved to tears, imagining that October morning in 1968, "
"when Helen slowly read the words, “And now we say Amen,” the first sentence "
"in the final paragraph of the text."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4609
msgid "And as for Bill, now we say Amen."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4610
msgid ""
"Those who knew and loved him during the California chapter of his life "
"watched his steady transformation unfold—sometimes barely perceptible, "
"sometimes in sudden leaps, occasionally with some discomfort, but always "
"modestly—as his initial small willingness to practice forgiveness grew into "
"a serious commitment."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4611
msgid ""
"Once he made that commitment to practice complete forgiveness, he never "
"really wavered."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4612
msgid ""
"Everyone noticed the steady dissolution of his ego, that process markedly "
"accelerating after he moved to La Jolla."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4613
msgid ""
"His prayers for help, indeed, were granted, and one day Bill simply woke up,"
" walked out of “prison,” and declared his own independence on July 4, 1988."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4614
msgid ""
"No one who knew him believed the date was a coincidence; in retrospect, "
"everyone laughed about it, affirming the perfection of his last few days."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4615
msgid "Bill, who so loved to play with words, was playing with dates."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1289
#: sentence:4616
msgid "In the end, all grievances were healed and “flexi-Bill” was free."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1290
#: sentence:4617
msgid "00033.jpg"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1291
#: sentence:4618
msgid ""
"For what would be his final visit to Tiburon, Bill planned to arrive on July"
" 3rd to join the holiday festivities at the Whitson household."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1291
#: sentence:4619
msgid ""
"Just before leaving, he and Catherine Prescott discussed getting together, "
"as was their custom on his occasional trips up from La Jolla."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1291
#: sentence:4620
msgid ""
"With uncharacteristic fervor, Bill insisted that they have dinner with Jerry"
" the night of the third."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1291
#: sentence:4621
msgid ""
"Since she planned to leave for Hawaii the next day, she responded, “No, it’s"
" not worth it, Bill; I’ll see you when I get back.” In retrospect, she found"
" it amazing that he kept saying, “No, no, I have to see you before you go!” "
"She agreed to dinner, somewhat reluctantly, because she had an early morning"
" departure and many last-minute chores still to do."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4622
msgid ""
"Jerry picked Bill up at the San Francisco airport the morning of July 3, and"
" on the drive north to Tiburon, they found themselves ensnarled in a huge "
"traffic jam."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4623
msgid ""
"The drive usually takes about an hour but on this day it was closer to three"
" and a half hours, which Jerry later recalled as a real blessing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4624
msgid ""
"Spending that much time with Bill was such a treat for him. “Bill was in a "
"very playful, joyful mood, very light."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4625
msgid "I never saw him so exuberant; his humor was amazing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4626
msgid "He was walking very lightly and kind of playing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4627
msgid "You know how he liked to play on words."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4628
msgid "I was really happy to see him lighter, not taking life seriously."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1292
#: sentence:4629
msgid ""
"I absolutely remember telling him how wonderful it was to see his joy and "
"what a great decision it had been to go down there [to La Jolla].”[9]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1293
#: sentence:4630
msgid ""
"Judy Whitson recounts, as if it were yesterday, the sequence of events that "
"unfolded in Bill’s astonishing final days:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4631
msgid "The whole story of his last two days was all one piece."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4632
msgid ""
"I was expecting him for the weekend, as it was the Fourth of July, and I had"
" invited thirty-six people to greet him and have an outdoor meal on the deck"
" with fireworks and all."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4633
msgid ""
"Jerry picked him up at the airport to bring him to our house for lunch, "
"which I had ready about 12:30, expecting them by 1:00 p.m. It passed, then "
"1:30, 2:00; they weren’t there and I was getting a little miffed!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4634
msgid "This was before cell phones."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4635
msgid "Finally, around 3:00 they walked in and what I saw was so unexpected."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4636
msgid ""
"Jerry looked kind of sheepish and Bill was smiling as if he were onstage."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4637
msgid ""
"He was lifting up his arms in the air with grace—I never thought of Bill as "
"a graceful person—and doing a little jig as he walked in the door."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4638
msgid ""
"Then he kissed me and said, “You won’t believe what happened, you won’t "
"believe what happened!” I said, “What?” still a little miffed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4639
msgid ""
"He said, “We had terrible, terrible traffic and Jerry didn’t get angry "
"once!” I looked at Jerry and he sort of shrugged, smiling his little "
"embarrassed smile because that remark meant that he usually did get annoyed "
"at traffic."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1294
#: sentence:4640
msgid ""
"But Bill felt something had happened and was commenting on the difference, "
"“We had such a wonderful talk, a really wonderful connection.” He was very "
"much aware that it was different with Jerry, and oh, my goodness, he was "
"dancing, literally dancing into our house![10]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1295
#: sentence:4641
msgid ""
"The Course states unequivocally that as we change our thoughts, their outer "
"counterparts—the details of our daily lives, including others’ behavior—will"
" change automatically."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1295
#: sentence:4642
msgid ""
"Since Bill had clearly made a major shift in his thinking, he naturally saw "
"things differently, experiencing everyone around him—in this case Jerry—as "
"more loving, open, and intensely satisfying."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1295
#: sentence:4643
msgid "Of course, such healing is mutual—the ultimate win/win situation!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1295
#: sentence:4644
msgid ""
"Jerry and Bill made their arrangements for the evening and Jerry left. Judy "
"continued,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4645
msgid ""
"Bill was still “tripping the light fantastic” all around the living room, "
"though there was no music playing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4646
msgid ""
"I asked what he was doing and he answered, “Oh, I feel so flexible, I feel "
"so flexible!” I asked if he would like to sit down to have lunch and he "
"replied, “Alright,” but he was blithe, that is the only word I can think of."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4647
msgid "It was a very different Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4648
msgid ""
"He was just happy, but the happiness was not “good mood” happiness, rather a"
" joy that was radiating through the body. His spirit was transcendent."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4649
msgid ""
"Watching him as I served him lunch (there was the watcher part and the doer "
"part of me), the watcher thought something strange was going on here."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4650
msgid ""
"I wondered if he was on something, thinking some medication had him stoned."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4651
msgid ""
"I asked him what he was taking these days and he laughed, saying, “No, no, "
"I’m just feeling so good, so free, so complete!” When I asked if he meant "
"“relationship complete,” he answered that he was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4652
msgid ""
"So, playing the role of the sister, I started quizzing him about them, "
"beginning with Ken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4653
msgid ""
"Bill said he had spoken with Ken a few months before, telling him that "
"anything he had ever held against him was his own misperception and how "
"terribly sorry he was."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4654
msgid ""
"He was honest with Ken about the times he had resented him, his judgments "
"about him, and his resistance to being friends with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1296
#: sentence:4655
msgid ""
"He said the grievances were all gone, absolutely gone in his mind, that he "
"didn’t see him that way anymore and asked for forgiveness.[11]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1297
#: sentence:4656
msgid ""
"The conversation with Ken took place, to be precise, in February on Ken’s "
"birthday."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1297
#: sentence:4657
msgid ""
"Jack Luckett confirmed the circumstances from his own perspective, as he had"
" overheard Bill’s side of the phone call."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1298
#: sentence:4658
msgid ""
"Bill normally got up earlier than I did, and he would have clippings from "
"the newspaper set out on the coffee table for us to talk about when I joined"
" him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1298
#: sentence:4659
msgid ""
"On this day, as every morning, Layle was out doing her yoga and Bill and I "
"were drinking coffee, chatting about those articles."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1298
#: sentence:4660
msgid ""
"Unexpectedly, he got up in the middle of a discussion, dialed the phone, and"
" spoke to Ken, among other things wishing him a happy birthday."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1298
#: sentence:4661
msgid ""
"When he hung up I told him I was listening to the tone of his voice and that"
" it was so clear to me he had totally forgiven Ken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1298
#: sentence:4662
msgid "He answered that it was, indeed, true.[12]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1299
#: sentence:4663
msgid "Ken corroborated the story."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1299
#: sentence:4664
msgid ""
"He said the conversation was a short one, but Bill was very warm and sincere"
" and that it felt genuine to him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1299
#: sentence:4665
msgid ""
"He didn’t remember the exact words, but Bill did apologize, saying something"
" like he had no right to judge or know what Ken should be doing or might do,"
" that anything he did was fine with him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1299
#: sentence:4666
msgid ""
"A month or so after the call, Ken spoke with him again, asking Bill to "
"attend the grand opening in August of the retreat center in Roscoe, New "
"York, which he and his wife Gloria were starting."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1299
#: sentence:4667
msgid "Bill agreed to join them there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1300
#: sentence:4668
msgid "Judy continued questioning Bill about his relationships:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1301
#: sentence:4669
msgid ""
"Then I went through a list of about eight people where I knew the "
"relationships had been sticky ones and with every one of them he was "
"beaming."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1301
#: sentence:4670
msgid ""
"I got to the one I thought might be extremely embarrassing, asking about Jo,"
" his first girlfriend."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1301
#: sentence:4671
msgid ""
"He knew what I meant and said they had gone away together two weekends "
"before to her condo out in the desert [near San Diego]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1301
#: sentence:4672
msgid ""
"When I inquired, he said he had finally told her and it was clear, although "
"they discussed his visiting her in New Zealand once she got settled."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1301
#: sentence:4673
msgid "Bill and I never actually discussed the fact that he was homosexual."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1301
#: sentence:4674
msgid "It wasn’t as if I didn’t know, we just didn’t discuss it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1302
#: sentence:4675
msgid ""
"Then I asked him about Helen, because that was the big one. “Funny you "
"should ask that,” he answered, “because the other night I had a dream where "
"I saw her as the priestess [representing an important aspect of Helen’s "
"nonphysical function, one she had many dreams and visions about]."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1302
#: sentence:4676
msgid ""
"She was holding out her hands to me and glowing, with such a sweet smile on "
"her face.” It seemed that, indeed, there was nothing left undone, so I gave "
"him a hug, saying, “Well, you are free, you’ve done your homework.” He "
"smiled, just a big grin, and said, “Yes, I have!”[13]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1303
#: sentence:4677
msgid ""
"As planned, Jerry came for Bill later that evening, then they collected "
"Catherine to join them for dinner. “Bill was so happy and excited,” she "
"recounted. “He played out this romantic thing with me even though there was "
"nothing to it."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1303
#: sentence:4678
msgid "I was his ‘girlfriend,’ but not really."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1303
#: sentence:4679
msgid ""
"Nothing ever happened, but I think he liked to play this knight in shining "
"armor and be kind of chivalrous.”[14] She said he was ebullient and joyful "
"as he danced around; his dancing apparently hadn’t stopped when he left the "
"Whitsons’ home."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1304
#: sentence:4680
msgid ""
"The trio ordered fish, and when it arrived already filleted, Catherine said,"
" “I looked down at it and had a feeling, a psychic hit, right then that "
"something was going to happen because it looked like a dead body!”[15] Often"
" throughout the meal Bill would hug her, saying, “Well, there must have been"
" some reason I was supposed to see you tonight, right?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1304
#: sentence:4681
msgid "It had to be tonight.”[16]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1305
#: sentence:4682
msgid "Meanwhile, Catherine noted,"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1306
#: sentence:4683
msgid ""
"I had this fish and a feeling in the pit in my stomach, but never did I "
"think it was related to Bill, never."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1306
#: sentence:4684
msgid ""
"His energy, his frequency, was vibrating at such an incredibly high rate he "
"swept me into it, like going up in a hot-air balloon."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1306
#: sentence:4685
msgid ""
"He was saying all the way home from the restaurant, “There’s no baggage; I’m"
" cleaned out, in and out; I’m complete with everyone.” On arriving home, "
"while Jerry waited in the car, he kissed me, danced around in the street, "
"and the last thing he said was, “See, there had to be a reason that I saw "
"you tonight."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1306
#: sentence:4686
msgid ""
"Tonight’s the night.” But I had this clutching feeling, and the tape playing"
" on my stereo when I walked in was called “Walk and Talk Like Angels.”[17]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1307
#: sentence:4687
msgid ""
"While Catherine pondered her strange feelings, Jerry returned Bill to the "
"Whitsons,’ where the three of them talked a bit about the evening, and then,"
" still playful and elated, Bill retired to bed."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1307
#: sentence:4688
msgid ""
"Whit corroborated Judy’s accounting of the day, “On that last night he was "
"very light, literally dancing around, and I’d never seen him do that."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1307
#: sentence:4689
msgid ""
"He was very joyful, up on tiptoes as if he were going to lift off.”[18] He "
"noted, as did everyone else who saw him those last couple of days, that a "
"substantive shift had occurred."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1307
#: sentence:4690
msgid ""
"Bill seemed to have cut loose all the anchors—professional ones related to "
"his scientific persona, as well as his personal ones, the struggles and "
"disappointments."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1308
#: sentence:4691
msgid ""
"The next morning, while serving Bill breakfast, Judy commented about its "
"being the Fourth of July, and he said, “Yes, it’s my independence day!” She "
"asked if he still felt free, and he reiterated, “Yes, I’m so flexible!” He "
"and Whit had talked about the meaning of flexible as a term from the "
"PAS—flexibility not of the body but of the personality."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1308
#: sentence:4692
msgid ""
"He had gone from being restricted, reserved, and inflexible to expansive, "
"flowing, and inclusive."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1308
#: sentence:4693
msgid ""
"He also offered his private conviction to Whit that the PAS was still the "
"most powerful and advanced psychological tool for describing human behavior "
"and that only a few people really understood it. Judy’s chronicle continues:"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4694
msgid ""
"Bill knew I was having a large group over for the holiday; the tables were "
"all set up and I had a refrigerator full of food."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4695
msgid ""
"After breakfast I decided, however, that I had to go to the market and get "
"some more chicken."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4696
msgid ""
"Bill insisted I already had enough, but I said, “Yes, but I’m a Jewish "
"mother and have to have extra.” He then announced that he was going for a "
"walk [as was his daily custom], would meet me at the supermarket, and then "
"drive home with me."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4697
msgid ""
"Since I didn’t really have time to shop, needing to tend to the barbecue and"
" other last-minute details, I must have responded with a funny look."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4698
msgid "He apparently noticed that because he said, “Don’t worry, dear."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4699
msgid ""
"If I’m not there when you’re ready to leave, go home without me.” I put my "
"arms around him, hugged him really tight, and said, “Bill, I’m never going "
"home without you!” thinking only from the Course frame of reference of our "
"returning Home together."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4700
msgid ""
"He seemed perfectly fine, and I didn’t connect his comment with any feeling "
"of foreboding, certainly nothing like death!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1309
#: sentence:4701
msgid "He just patted me on the head."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4702
msgid ""
"Bill walked out the door to take his stroll while I went downstairs, "
"collected my shopping list, and maybe five minutes later, got in the car and"
" drove a few feet."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4703
msgid "And there was Bill, lying on the ground, the paramedics already there."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4704
msgid ""
"My next-door neighbor, a surgeon—God bless him—had been clipping his bushes "
"in the front yard."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4705
msgid ""
"He saw Bill go down, ran to his car maybe three yards away, grabbed his "
"medical kit, called the paramedics, and in seconds was by his side."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4706
msgid ""
"The whole idea of Bill dying right then and there—my mind raced thinking "
"about his being alone, all that one thinks when something like that happens."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4707
msgid "If I had come out three minutes earlier, could I have saved him?"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4708
msgid ""
"But the doctor was in total control, and I’ll never forget his kindness."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4709
msgid ""
"He wanted to know what medicines he might have been on, so I ran to the "
"house, brought out his shaving kit, and he started going through it while "
"still holding Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4710
msgid ""
"The paramedics wanted to give him oxygen, but the doctor said he was already"
" gone, dead before his head hit the road."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1310
#: sentence:4711
msgid ""
"There was considerable blood because he hit the ground so hard, but the "
"doctor thought the cause of death was his heart “blowing out.” That, of "
"course, is not a medical term, but it did describe the situation.[19]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1311
#: sentence:4712
msgid ""
"The autopsy later confirmed that part of Bill’s heart had, indeed, exploded "
"and that he had left suddenly and painlessly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1312
#: sentence:4713
msgid ""
"Whit and I accompanied Bill’s body to the hospital, where he was placed in a"
" room to be checked over."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1312
#: sentence:4714
msgid ""
"I called Jerry, Roger and Frances, and after they arrived, we all stayed in "
"the room with him for about an hour just saying good-bye, reciting some of "
"our favorite quotes from the Course, touching and petting and loving him."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1312
#: sentence:4715
msgid ""
"The only picture I carry in my mind is one of love, his face showing total "
"peace, as he lay on that table."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1312
#: sentence:4716
msgid "After all, it was Bill’s independence day."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4717
msgid ""
"On the way back, I had to go by to tell my mom, who lived a few minutes "
"away."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4718
msgid "She loved Bill, and they were very, very close."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4719
msgid ""
"Of course, she had to know. “Does this mean we aren’t going to have his "
"party?” she inquired."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4720
msgid ""
"We looked at each other and only then did I realize people would be at our "
"house in an hour."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4721
msgid ""
"Some lived far away and there was no way to stop them from coming, so we "
"agreed we would celebrate Bill, as that’s what he would have wanted."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4722
msgid ""
"As they arrived, I told each guest about his sudden passing, and of course, "
"all were tremendously saddened."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4723
msgid "But we did, indeed, celebrate Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4724
msgid ""
"After dinner, with ringside seats from the deck of our house, we watched "
"those remarkable Fourth of July fireworks, especially gorgeous that night "
"all over San Francisco, no fog or anything."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1313
#: sentence:4725
msgid "And all I could think of was Bill going out in a blaze of glory![20]"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1314
#: sentence:4726
msgid ""
"Despite their surprise and grief, many were so amused that Bill left on the "
"Fourth of July—so like him to take even his own dying process "
"lightheartedly."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1314
#: sentence:4727
msgid ""
"Some might have found Bill’s friends a curious lot, as amid the shock of his"
" sudden death, one could hear expressions of elation and delight; “Oh, my "
"God, he did it! He did it!"
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1314
#: sentence:4728
msgid ""
"He’s the first person to finish the Course, really finish the Course!”—not "
"unlike adoring fans cheering their star quarterback over the goal line."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1315
#: sentence:4729
msgid ""
"Bill’s memorial service was held outdoors on July 8, 1988, at the "
"Congregational Church in Tiburon. “Panis Angelicus,” one of his favorite "
"pieces, commenced the program."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1315
#: sentence:4730
msgid ""
"Then followed a passage from a tape Bill had created a short while before, "
"perhaps not consciously aware it would be used as his last good-bye."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1315
#: sentence:4731
msgid ""
"Listening to his beautiful voice, everyone was deeply moved by his final "
"blessing."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1315
#: sentence:4732
msgid ""
"Tammy, Judy’s daughter, chose to be at the crematorium rather than at the "
"church so he would not be “alone”; she later confirmed that his body was "
"cremated at the exact moment his taped reading was played."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1315
#: sentence:4733
msgid ""
"An intuitive, tuned-in young woman, she testified that she and Bill "
"“watched” the service remotely and that he was laughing the whole time."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1316
#: sentence:4734
msgid "Thus ends the earthly sojourn of Bill Thetford."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1316
#: sentence:4735
msgid ""
"The calling card found in his wallet had only Bill Thetford printed on it. "
"Just plain Bill."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1316
#: sentence:4736
msgid ""
"He asked for the Course; he received it and used it, willingly stripping "
"himself of his persona, psychological armoring, prestige, unhelpful habits, "
"and presumptions."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1316
#: sentence:4737
msgid ""
"Throughout the process, he danced, laughed and struggled, joked, despaired "
"and supported, loved, feared and prayed, and steadily forgave his way to the"
" end, soaring to a glorious finale worthy of the grandest of operas he so "
"adored."
msgstr ""

#. Paragraph 1316
#: sentence:4738
msgid ""
"And memories of Bill have settled with everlasting comfort into the hearts "
"of all who knew, loved, and were touched by this most gracious friend."
msgstr ""

